king butter and sliced onions turn heat to high for the last 3-5 minutes. You will hear a crackling sound from the bottom — this is correct. Remove from heat immediately and leave covered for 5 minutes before serving.\"], \"match_percentage\": 31.2, \"used_ingredients\": [\"long grain parboiled rice\", \"red bell peppers (tatashe)\", \"scotch bonnet peppers (ata rodo)\", \"onions\", \"tomato paste\"], \"cook_time_minutes\": 70, \"prep_time_minutes\": 20, \"missing_ingredients\": [\"tomatoes\", \"long chilli peppers(shombo) \", \"vegetable oil\", \"chicken stock\", \"seasoning cubes\", \"curry powder\", \"thyme\", \"bay leaves\", \"garlic powder\", \"salt\", \"paprika\"]}, {\"name\": \"Akara\", \"tips\": \"Whisking the bean paste until very fluffy is the secret to light soft akara — never skip this step. Also make sure the oil is very hot before adding the paste otherwise the akara will absorb too much oil and become greasy. Wet your spoon with oil before scooping each portion to help the paste slide off cleanly into the oil.\", \"servings\": 4, \"difficulty\": \"medium\", \"description\": \"Akara is a traditional Yoruba deep fried bean cake made from peeled black eyed beans blended into a smooth aerated paste and fried in hot oil until crispy on the outside and soft inside. It is a quintessential Nigerian breakfast food sold by roadside vendors across the country and best eaten hot with ogi (pap) or bread.\", \"instructions\": [\"Step 1: Peel the beans using one of two methods. Traditional method: Soak beans in cold water for 30 minutes then rub between palms under running water until all skins float off and are drained away. Quick method: Pulse beans and water  in a food processor for 30 seconds to crack and loosen skins, pour into a bowl of water, skim off floating skins, and drain. Rinse peeled beans two to three times in clean water.\", \"Step 2: Place the peeled beans alongside the peppers and onions in a blender with a very small amount of water — just enough to move the blender. Blend on high speed for 3 minutes until the paste is completely smooth and thick. The paste must be thick not watery — too much water will make flat oily akara.\", \"Step 3: Pour the blended bean paste into a large bowl. Using a wooden spoon or electric hand mixer whisk the paste vigorously for 5 to 7 minutes until it becomes very fluffy, lighter in colour, and almost doubles in volume. This is the most important step — the air you whisk in is what makes akara light and fluffy inside.\", \"Step 4: Add some salt and seasoning cubes to the whisked paste. Fold gently into the paste without deflating it. Taste and adjust seasoning.\", \"Step 5: Pour enough vegetable oil into a deep wide pan to allow the akara to float — at least 3 inches deep. Heat on medium-high heat for 2 to 3 minutes until hot. Test the oil by dropping a tiny bit of paste in — it should rise immediately to the surface and sizzle vigorously. If it sinks the oil is not hot enough.\", \"Step 6: Wet your tablespoon with oil and scoop portions of the paste into the hot oil one at a time. Do not overcrowd the pan — leave space between each akara so they cook evenly and stay round.\", \"Step 7: Fry on medium heat for 3 to 4 minutes until the bottom is deep golden brown, then flip carefully with a slotted spoon or skewer and fry the other side for 2 to 3 minutes until evenly golden brown and crispy all over.\", \"Step 8: Remove with a slotted spoon and drain on paper towels to absorb excess oil. Serve immediately while hot and crispy alongside ogi (pap) or as a breakfast snack.\"], \"match_percentage\": 28.6, \"used_ingredients\": [\"onions\", \"scotch bonnet peppers\"], \"cook_time_minutes\": 20, \"prep_time_minutes\": 30, \"missing_ingredients\": [\"black eyed beans\", \"long chilli peppers(shombo)\", \"seasoning cubes\", \"salt\", \"vegetable oil for deep frying\"]}, {\"name\": \"Ayamase (Ofada Stew)\", \"tips\": \"Bleaching the palm oil is absolutely non-negotiable for authentic Ayamase. Only use green peppers and unripe tatashe — no red peppers at all. The more assorted meats you use the richer and more authentic the stew will be.\", \"servings\": 6, \"difficulty\": \"hard\", \"description\": \"Ayamase also known as Ofada Stew or Designer Stew is a rich and intensely flavoured Yoruba stew made exclusively with green peppers and unripe tatashe giving it its distinctive green colour. It is traditionally served with Ofada rice and the stew is made with bleached palm oil and loaded with assorted meats making it one of the most indulgent Nigerian dishes.\", \"instructions\": [\"Step 1: Wash and season all assorted meats with onions, seasoning cubes, ginger garlic paste and salt. Cook in a pot on medium heat for 25 to 35 minutes until very tender. Fry the cooked meats in a small amount of oil until lightly browned on the outside for extra flavour. Set aside with the stock.\", \"Step 2: Blend green bell peppers, unripe green tatashe, green scotch bonnet peppers, and onions together into a coarse paste — do not blend completely smooth, leave some texture. The stew must use only green peppers and unripe tatashe — never red peppers or ripe tatashe as this completely changes the dish.\", \"Step 3: Bleach the palm oil by heating it in a pot on high heat with the lid on for 10 to 15 minutes until the oil turns from orange-red to a pale golden yellow colour and begins to smoke lightly. Remove from heat and allow to cool slightly. Bleached palm oil is essential for authentic Ayamase.\", \"Step 4: Return the bleached palm oil to medium heat. Add sliced onions with some ginger garlic paste and fry for 3 minutes until soft and slightly golden.\", \"Step 5: Pour the blended green pepper mixture into the bleached palm oil. It will sizzle vigorously stir immediately. Fry on high heat for 15 to 20 minutes stirring every 3 to 4 minutes until all the water has completely evaporated, the oil floats on top, and the pepper sauce is cooked down and thick.\", \"Step 6: Add iru (locust beans) and ground crayfish to the cooked pepper base and stir well. Fry for 3 more minutes until the iru is fragrant and well incorporated.\", \"Step 7: Add all the assorted meats and a ladle of the meat stock. Stir everything together to coat the meat in the green pepper sauce. Cook on medium heat for 10 minutes until the meat is well flavoured and the stew is thick and rich.\", \"Step 8: Taste and adjust seasoning. The finished Ayamase should be dark olive green, thick, intensely flavoured, and very rich with assorted meats. Serve with Ofada rice.\"], \"match_percentage\": 27.3, \"used_ingredients\": [\"unripe tatashe (green tatashe)\", \"green scotch bonnet peppers\", \"onions\"], \"cook_time_minutes\": 90, \"prep_time_minutes\": 25, \"missing_ingredients\": [\"green bell peppers\", \"palm oil\", \"assorted meat (beef, tripe, shaki, pomo, liver)\", \"crayfish\", \"iru (locust beans)\", \"seasoning cubes\", \"ginger and garlic paste\", \"salt\"]}, {\"name\": \"Asaro (Yam Porridge)\", \"tips\": \"Gentle stirring lets some yam break down to thicken the sauce naturally without becoming completely mashed.\", \"servings\": 4, \"difficulty\": \"easy\", \"description\": \"Asaro is a beloved traditional Yoruba yam porridge made by cooking yam chunks directly in a rich tomato and pepper sauce until the yam softens and thickens the entire dish into a hearty one-pot meal.\", \"instructions\": [\"Step 1: Peel the yam and cut into medium sized chunks. Wash thoroughly.\", \"Step 2: Blend onions, tatashe, and scotch bonnet peppers together into a smooth paste.\", \"Step 3: Place the yam chunks in a pot with the blended pepper mixture, sliced onions, palm oil, and enough water to just cover the yam.\", \"Step 4: Bring to a boil then reduce to medium heat. Cook for 20 to 25 minutes, stirring occasionally, until the yam softens and breaks down at the edges.\", \"Step 5: Add ground crayfish, flaked fish, seasoning cubes, and salt. Stir gently.\", \"Step 6: Continue cooking on medium-low heat for 8 to 10 minutes until thick and stew-like.\", \"Step 7: Taste and adjust seasoning. Serve hot on its own.\"], \"match_percentage\": 27.3, \"used_ingredients\": [\"tatashe (red bell pepper)\", \"scotch bonnet peppers\", \"onions\"], \"cook_time_minutes\": 40, \"prep_time_minutes\": 15, \"missing_ingredients\": [\"yam (white yam)\", \"tomatoes\", \"palm oil\", \"crayfish\", \"smoked fish or dried fish\", \"seasoning cubes\", \"salt\", \"water\"]}, {\"name\": \"Efo Riro\", \"tips\": \"The most important step is frying the pepper base completely dry until the oil floats on top before adding any meat or stock. This is what separates a rich deeply flavoured Efo Riro from a watery one. Also add the vegetables at the very last minute and cook for 2 minutes only — overcooked vegetables will turn dark and lose their flavour.\", \"servings\": 6, \"difficulty\": \"medium\", \"description\": \"Efo Riro is a rich Yoruba vegetable soup made with tatashe and ata rodo as the pepper base, assorted meats, and leafy green vegetables. The name means stirred leafy vegetable in Yoruba. It is one of the most flavourful Nigerian soups with a vibrant green and red colour from the vegetables and pepper base. It is served with amala, eba, pounded yam, or rice.\", \"instructions\": [\"Step 1: Wash and season assorted meat, pomo, and stockfish with onions, seasoning cubes, and salt. Cook on medium heat for 20 to 30 minutes until very tender. Set aside with the stock.\", \"Step 2: Blend tatashe and scotch bonnet peppers together into a smooth paste. Do not add water — the peppers have enough natural liquid. Set aside.\", \"Step 3: Wash the efo tete or spinach thoroughly, shred into medium sized pieces by hand, and set aside in a colander to drain excess water.\", \"Step 4: Heat palm oil in a large pot on medium-high heat for 2 minutes. Slice onions and fry in the palm oil for 3 minutes until golden and fragrant.\", \"Step 5: Add the blended tatashe and scotch bonnet pepper mixture to the pot. It will sizzle loudly in the hot oil — this is correct. Fry on high heat for 10 to 20 minutes stirring every 3 minutes until all the water has completely evaporated, the oil floats on top, and the pepper sauce has darkened and thickened. This step gives Efo Riro its deep rich flavour.\", \"Step 6: Add iru (locust beans) and ground crayfish and stir into the pepper sauce. Fry for 2 more minutes until the iru is fragrant.\", \"Step 7: Add the cooked assorted meat, stockfish, dried fish, and a ladle of the meat stock. Stir everything together and cook on medium heat for 10 minutes until the meat is well coated in the sauce.\", \"Step 8: Add the shredded efo tete or spinach to the pot and stir into the sauce. Cook for exactly 2 minutes only on medium heat — the vegetables should wilt into the soup but remain bright green and not soggy. Taste, adjust seasoning, and remove from heat immediately. Serve with amala, eba, or pounded yam.\"], \"match_percentage\": 25.0, \"used_ingredients\": [\"tatashe (red bell pepper)\", \"scotch bonnet peppers (ata rodo)\", \"onions\"], \"cook_time_minutes\": 75, \"prep_time_minutes\": 25, \"missing_ingredients\": [\"vgetables African spinach or ugwu\", \"palm oil\", \"assorted meat (beef, tripe, shaki, pomo)\", \"stockfish\", \"dried fish\", \"crayfish\", \"iru (locust beans)\", \"seasoning cubes\", \"salt\"]}, {\"name\": \"Egusi Soup Yoruba Style\", \"tips\": \"The secret to Yoruba egusi is frying the egusi completely dry in palm oil before adding any liquid. Never add water or stock to the egusi while frying — it must fry and toast in the oil until golden. Also never add tomatoes to Yoruba egusi soup — that changes the flavour profile completely.\", \"servings\": 6, \"difficulty\": \"medium\", \"description\": \"Egusi Soup Yoruba style is a rich and hearty Nigerian soup made with ground melon seeds fried directly in palm oil before any liquid is added. Unlike Igbo style egusi which is added raw, Yoruba style fries the egusi first until golden and nutty giving it a deeper richer flavour. It is served with amala, eba, or pounded yam.\", \"instructions\": [\"Step 1: Wash and season assorted meat and stockfish with onions, seasoning cubes, and salt. Cook in a pot on medium heat for 15 to 20 minutes until tender. Set aside with the stock.\", \"Step 2: Blend scotch bonnet peppers, tatashe, and half the onions together into a smooth paste. Set aside.\", \"Step 3: Heat palm oil in a large pot on medium heat for 2 minutes until melted and hot but not bleached. Chop the remaining onions and fry in the palm oil for 3 minutes until soft and translucent.\", \"Step 4: Add the ground egusi to the palm oil and stir immediately to combine. Fry the egusi in the palm oil on medium heat for 8 to 10 minutes stirring constantly until the egusi turns golden, smells nutty, and pulls away from the sides of the pot. Do not add any liquid at this stage — dry frying is the key to Yoruba egusi.\", \"Step 5: Add the blended pepper mixture to the fried egusi and stir well to combine. Fry together for another 10 minutes on medium heat stirring every 2 minutes until the pepper is cooked and oil begins to float on the surface.\", \"Step 6: Add the cooked meat, stockfish, dried fish, meat stock, ground crayfish, iru, and seasoning cubes. Stir everything together and add a small amount of water if the soup is too thick. Cook on medium heat for 15 minutes until all the flavours come together.\", \"Step 7: Taste and adjust salt and seasoning. The soup should be rich, thick, and deeply flavoured at this point.\", \"Step 8: Add shredded spinach or efo tete and stir into the soup. Cook for exactly 2 minutes only — overcooking the vegetables will make them lose their colour and become soggy. Remove from heat and serve immediately with amala, eba, or pounded yam.\"], \"match_percentage\": 23.1, \"used_ingredients\": [\"onions\", \"scotch bonnet peppers\", \"tatashe (red bell pepper)\"], \"cook_time_minutes\": 70, \"prep_time_minutes\": 20, \"missing_ingredients\": [\"ground egusi (melon seeds)\", \"palm oil\", \"assorted meat (beef, tripe, shaki)\", \"stockfish\", \"dried fish\", \"crayfish\", \"iru (locust beans)\", \"spinach, efo tete or ugwu\", \"seasoning cubes\", \"salt\"]}, {\"name\": \"Ewa Agoyin\", \"tips\": \"The two secrets to authentic Ewa Agoyin are cooking the beans with a lot of onions until completely mashable with no whole beans remaining, and making the Agoyin stew with only dried peppers not fresh ones. Fresh peppers will not give the deep dark colour and concentrated flavour that makes Agoyin stew unique. The stew must be dark, dry, and almost burnt looking — that is correct.\", \"servings\": 4, \"difficulty\": \"medium\", \"description\": \"Ewa Agoyin is a popular Yoruba street food originally brought to Nigeria by Beninese traders, consisting of soft completely mashed honey beans or black eyed beans served with a deeply dark and spicy Agoyin stew made from dried red peppers and palm oil. It is a beloved Lagos breakfast food sold by roadside vendors and eaten with agege bread.\", \"instructions\": [\"Step 1: Wash the beans thoroughly then cover the beans with fresh water and cook on high heat until boiling, then reduce to medium heat. Cook for 45 to 60 minutes until the beans are extremely soft — they should mash completely between your fingers with no resistance. Add more water as needed during cooking to prevent burning.\", \"Step 2: Once the beans are very soft, use a wooden spoon or potato masher to mash them completely in the pot until no whole beans remain. The consistency should be thick and porridge-like. Season with salt, stir well, and set aside.\", \"Step 4: While the beans cook prepare the Agoyin stew. Rehydrate the dried red peppers and dried chilli peppers by soaking in hot water for 20 minutes until soft. Drain and blend alongside some onions and ginger into a rough paste — not completely smooth, leave some texture.\", \"Step 5: Heat palm oil in a separate pot on medium heat until hot. Slice onions into thin rings and fry in the palm oil for 10 minutes on medium-low heat, stirring constantly until the onions are very dark brown and almost caramelised — this dark onion is essential to the Agoyin stew flavour.\", \"Step 6: Add the blended dried pepper mixture to the dark onions and palm oil. Stir well and fry on medium heat for 20 to 25 minutes stirring every 3 minutes until all moisture evaporates, the stew becomes very dark, thick, and dry, and the oil floats on top. The stew should be almost black in colour — this is correct.\", \"Step 7: Add seasoning cubes and salt to the stew. Stir well and cook for 5 more minutes. The finished Agoyin stew should be very dark, very dry, very spicy, and intensely flavoured.\", \"Step 8: Serve the mashed beans in a bowl and pour the dark Agoyin stew generously on top. Eat with agege bread, fried plantain, or on its own.\"], \"match_percentage\": 22.2, \"used_ingredients\": [\"dried red peppers (tatashe)\", \"onions\"], \"cook_time_minutes\": 90, \"prep_time_minutes\": 20, \"missing_ingredients\": [\"beans\", \"dried long chilli bonnet peppers(shombo)\", \"palm oil\", \"crayfish\", \"seasoning cubes\", \"salt\", \"water\"]}, {\"name\": \"Nigerian Pepper Soup\", \"tips\": \"The quality of your pepper soup spice mix makes or breaks this dish. Use freshly ground spices if possible — uda (country onion), ehuru (calabash nutmeg), and uziza seeds ground together give the most authentic flavour. Never cover the pot fully while cooking pepper soup — leave it slightly open so the broth reduces and concentrates.\", \"servings\": 4, \"difficulty\": \"easy\", \"description\": \"Nigerian Pepper Soup is a light, intensely spiced broth made with meat or fish and a unique blend of pepper soup spices. It is served at every Nigerian gathering, used as a remedy for colds and fever, and eaten as a starter or main dish. The broth is thin but deeply flavoured with a distinctive warming heat that comes from the special pepper soup spice blend.\", \"instructions\": [\"Step 1: Wash the meat thoroughly and cut into medium sized pieces. Season with onions, seasoning cubes, and salt. Do not add water yet — allow the meat to cook in its own juices first.\", \"Step 2: Place the seasoned meat in a pot on medium heat and cook dry for 10 minutes stirring occasionally until the meat releases its juices and begins to brown slightly on the outside.\", \"Step 3: Add enough water to cover the meat completely. Bring to a boil on high heat then reduce to medium heat. Cook for 25 to 30 minutes for goat meat or 15 minutes for chicken until the meat is tender but not falling off the bone.\", \"Step 4: Add the pepper soup spice mix, ground crayfish, and blended or roughly crushed scotch bonnet peppers. Stir well and taste — the broth should be well seasoned and spicy at this point. Add more seasoning cubes and salt if needed.\", \"Step 5: Cook on medium heat for another 15 minutes until the spices have fully infused into the broth and the liquid has reduced slightly. The broth should be a light golden brown colour and smell intensely aromatic.\", \"Step 6: Tear utazi leaves into small pieces and add to the pot — utazi adds a slight bitterness that balances the heat. Add uziza leaves whole or roughly torn. Cook for 3 minutes only.\", \"Step 7: Taste one final time and adjust salt and pepper. The pepper soup should be very hot and spicy, lightly bitter from the utazi, and deeply aromatic from the spice blend. Serve hot in deep bowls with sliced onions on top and agidi or white rice on the side.\"], \"match_percentage\": 20.0, \"used_ingredients\": [\"scotch bonnet peppers\", \"onions\"], \"cook_time_minutes\": 55, \"prep_time_minutes\": 15, \"missing_ingredients\": [\"goat meat or chicken or catfish\", \"pepper soup spice mix\", \"crayfish\", \"uziza leaves\", \"utazi leaves\", \"seasoning cubes\", \"salt\", \"water\"]}, {\"name\": \"Moi Moi\", \"tips\": \"The food processor peeling method is a game changer — it cuts prep time from 30 minutes to 5 minutes. The two most important steps are removing every single bean skin and whisking the paste vigorously to aerate it before adding seasoning. Skipping either step will result in dense heavy Moi Moi. Always fill containers only three quarters full as the paste expands during steaming.\", \"servings\": 8, \"difficulty\": \"medium\", \"description\": \"Moi Moi is a traditional Nigerian steamed bean pudding made from peeled beans blended into a smooth paste. It is a beloved dish across all Nigerian tribes and is served at parties, as a side dish with rice or ogi, or eaten alone as a complete meal. The texture should be firm yet soft and moist inside with a rich savoury flavour.\", \"instructions\": [\"Step 1: There are two ways to peel the beans. Traditional method: Pour beans into a bowl and soak in cold water for 30 minutes until the skins begin to loosen and soften, then rub vigorously between both palms under running water until all skins float off. Quick method: Pour dry beans into a food processor with some water and pulse for 30 to 45 seconds — the food processor will crack and loosen the skins without grinding the beans. Pour the pulsed beans into a large bowl of water, the skins will float to the top — skim them off and drain. Repeat until all skins are removed. The quick method takes 5 minutes instead of 30.\", \"Step 2: Rinse the peeled beans thoroughly in clean water two to three times to remove any remaining skin fragments. The beans should be completely white with no dark skin remaining — any leftover skin will make the Moi Moi rough and bitter.\", \"Step 3: Place the peeled beans directly into the blender together with the scotch bonnet peppers, red bell pepper, onions, one raw egg, and a very small amount of water — just enough to get the blender moving. Blend everything together on high speed for 3 minutes until the paste is completely smooth with absolutely no grainy texture. Blending the peppers and egg together with the beans at this stage gives the Moi Moi its full flavour and colour from the inside.\", \"Step 4: Pour the blended paste into a large bowl. Add seasoning cubes, vegetable oil, and salt. Mix everything together thoroughly until well combined. Taste and adjust seasoning — it should be well seasoned and slightly peppery.\", \"Step 5: Using a wooden spoon or electric hand mixer, whisk the paste vigorously for 5 minutes until it becomes fluffy, lighter in colour, and increases slightly in volume. This aerates the paste and gives Moi Moi its soft moist texture when steamed.\", \"Step 6: Break the mackerel fish into medium sized chunks and slice your boiled eggs and set aside. Grease foil containers or moi moi leaves generously with vegetable oil on the inside so the moi moi does not stick.\", \"Step 7: Pour the bean paste mixture into each container filling only three quarters full. Drop pieces of fish directly into the paste in each container alongside the sliced eggs  — the fish sits inside the moi moi not on top. Press down lightly so the fish is submerged in the paste.\", \"Step 8: Seal each foil container tightly by folding the edges over securely. No steam should be able to escape during cooking.\", \"Step 9: Place a trivet or folded foil at the bottom of a large pot to prevent direct heat contact. Arrange the sealed moi moi containers in the pot and add water to reach halfway up the sides of the containers.\", \"Step 10: Cover the pot tightly and steam on medium heat for 45 to 60 minutes. Check water level every 15 minutes and add more hot water if needed — never let the pot run dry. Moi Moi is ready when it feels firm when pressed gently and pulls away cleanly from the container when opened.\"], \"match_percentage\": 18.2, \"used_ingredients\": [\"onions\", \"scotch bonnet peppers\"], \"cook_time_minutes\": 60, \"prep_time_minutes\": 40, \"missing_ingredients\": [\"beans\", \"long chilli pepper (shombo)\", \"crayfish\", \"vegetable oil\", \"seasoning cubes\", \"salt\", \"eggs\", \"fish (preferably mackerel fish)\", \"water\"]}, {\"name\": \"Banga Stew\", \"tips\": \"The key difference between Banga Soup and Banga Stew is the reduction time — cook the stew version longer uncovered to achieve a thicker consistency that coats rice or yam well rather than the more liquid soup form.\", \"servings\": 5, \"difficulty\": \"hard\", \"description\": \"Banga Stew is a thick, deeply flavoured Igbo stew made from concentrated palm fruit extract, prepared similarly to Banga Soup but cooked down to a thicker consistency more like a stew than a soup. It is rich, nutty, and aromatic, traditionally seasoned with banga spices, and served with white rice, boiled yam, or plantain.\", \"instructions\": [\"Step 1: If using fresh palm fruit, boil for 20 to 30 minutes until soft, then pound to separate pulp from nuts and squeeze with warm water to extract the thick orange juice. Strain through a sieve to remove fibres. If using canned concentrate, dilute according to package instructions.\", \"Step 2: Pour the palm fruit extract into a pot and bring to a boil on high heat, then reduce to medium heat and simmer for 15 to 20 minutes until the oil begins to separate and rise to the surface.\", \"Step 3: Season the assorted meat with onions, seasoning cubes, and salt. Cook separately on medium heat for 30 minutes until tender. Add the cooked meat and stock to the palm fruit base.\", \"Step 4: Add the banga spice mix to the pot and simmer for 15 minutes to allow the spices to infuse fully into the base.\", \"Step 5: Add dried fish, ground crayfish, sliced scotch bonnet peppers, and seasoning cubes. Stir well and continue cooking on medium heat, allowing the liquid to reduce and thicken for 20 to 25 minutes — unlike Banga Soup this should reduce further into a thicker stew-like consistency.\", \"Step 6: Add the fresh fish pieces and cook gently for 8 to 10 minutes until just cooked through, stirring carefully to avoid breaking the fish apart.\", \"Step 7: Continue simmering uncovered for an additional 10 minutes, stirring occasionally, until the stew has thickened noticeably and the oil is clearly visible on the surface.\", \"Step 8: Remove the oburunbebe stick before serving. Taste and adjust seasoning. Serve hot with white rice, boiled yam, or plantain.\"], \"match_percentage\": 18.2, \"used_ingredients\": [\"onions\", \"scotch bonnet peppers\"], \"cook_time_minutes\": 80, \"prep_time_minutes\": 30, \"missing_ingredients\": [\"fresh palm fruit (or canned banga concentrate)\", \"assorted meat (beef, tripe)\", \"dried fish\", \"fresh fish\", \"banga spice mix (oburunbebe stick, dried bitter leaf)\", \"crayfish\", \"seasoning cubes\", \"salt\", \"water\"]}, {\"name\": \"Ikokore\", \"tips\": \"Use water yam specifically not white yam or cocoyam. Do not rinse the grated yam before adding to the pot as the natural starch thickens the broth and holds the dumplings together.\", \"servings\": 4, \"difficulty\": \"medium\", \"description\": \"Ikokore is a traditional Ijebu Yoruba dish made from grated water yam cooked in a rich pepper soup or tomato base with assorted fish and seafood. The grated water yam forms thick irregular dumplings in the broth giving the dish its characteristic texture. It is a beloved dish in Ogun State and across Yorubaland.\", \"instructions\": [\"Step 1: Peel the water yam and grate on the coarse side of a grater into a bowl. Do not rinse the grated yam — the natural starch is needed to hold the dumplings together. Season the grated yam lightly with salt and set aside.\", \"Step 2: Blend scotch bonnet peppers, long chilli peppers, and onions together into a smooth paste.\", \"Step 3: Heat palm oil in a large pot on medium heat. Add iru and fry for 1 minute until fragrant. Add the blended pepper mixture and fry for 15 minutes until cooked and oil floats on top.\", \"Step 4: Add enough meat stock to the pot . Add ground crayfish, dried fish, smoked fish, assorted meat, seasoning cubes, and salt. Bring to a boil on high heat.\", \"Step 5: Using a tablespoon or your hand, scoop portions of the grated water yam and drop them one by one into the boiling broth. Do not stir immediately — allow the yam dumplings to set for 3 minutes before stirring gently.\", \"Step 6: Cook on medium heat for 15 to 20 minutes stirring gently occasionally until the yam dumplings are fully cooked and the broth has thickened, adjust seasoning, and serve hot.\"], \"match_percentage\": 15.4, \"used_ingredients\": [\"scotch bonnet peppers\", \"onions\"], \"cook_time_minutes\": 50, \"prep_time_minutes\": 25, \"missing_ingredients\": [\"water yam (isu ewura)\", \"dried fish\", \"assorted meat\", \"smoked fish\", \"palm oil\", \"crayfish\", \"long chilli peppers\", \"iru (locust beans)\", \"seasoning cubes\", \"salt\", \"water\"]}, {\"name\": \"Abacha\", \"tips\": \"Always soak in cold water not hot. Potash is essential for emulsifying the palm oil into the dressing.\", \"servings\": 4, \"difficulty\": \"medium\", \"description\": \"Abacha is a traditional Igbo cold salad made from dried shredded cassava rehydrated and tossed in an emulsified palm oil and potash dressing with ugba, utazi leaves, garden eggs, crayfish, and assorted proteins.\", \"instructions\": [\"Step 1: Soak the dried abacha in cold water for 10 to 15 minutes until softened. Drain thoroughly.\", \"Step 2: Dissolve potash in 3 tablespoons of water and strain through a fine sieve.\", \"Step 3: Pour palm oil into a bowl. Add the potash solution gradually while stirring vigorously until emulsified and bright yellow.\", \"Step 4: Add ground crayfish, sliced scotch bonnet peppers, sliced onions, seasoning cubes, and salt to the emulsion.\", \"Step 5: Add the drained abacha and toss thoroughly until coated.\", \"Step 6: Add ugba, sliced garden eggs, shredded utazi, flaked fish, and sliced ponmo. Toss together gently.\", \"Step 7: Taste and adjust seasoning.\", \"Step 8: Garnish with utazi and onion rings. Serve at room temperature.\"], \"match_percentage\": 15.4, \"used_ingredients\": [\"onions\", \"scotch bonnet peppers\"], \"cook_time_minutes\": 0, \"prep_time_minutes\": 20, \"missing_ingredients\": [\"abacha (dried shredded cassava)\", \"ugba (oil bean seeds)\", \"palm oil\", \"potash (kaun)\", \"utazi leaves\", \"garden eggs\", \"crayfish\", \"seasoning cubes\", \"salt\", \"dried fish or stockfish\", \"ponmo (cow skin)\"]}, {\"name\": \"Nigerian Fried Rice\", \"tips\": \"Always cook on high heat when frying the rice and vegetables together to prevent everything from steaming and becoming soggy instead of stir-fried.\", \"servings\": 6, \"difficulty\": \"medium\", \"description\": \"Nigerian Fried Rice is a colourful and flavourful party staple made with parboiled rice stir-fried with mixed vegetables, liver, and a distinct curry seasoning. Unlike Chinese fried rice, the Nigerian version has a unique orange-yellow hue from curry powder and is loaded with vegetables, making it one of the most popular dishes at Nigerian celebrations alongside Jollof Rice.\", \"instructions\": [\"Step 1: Wash the rice thoroughly until water runs clear then transfer into a seive till perfectly dry. Then into a pot, add some oil and fry the rice for about 5 minutes\", \"Step 2: Season the liver with salt and a little curry powder. Cook in a pot with a small amount of water for 8 to 10 minutes until just cooked through, then dice into small cubes.\", \"Step 3: Dice carrots and green beans into small uniform cubes for even cooking. Set aside along with the bell peppers.\", \"Step 4: Heat vegetable oil in a large wok or wide pan on high heat. Add minced garlic and ginger and stir fry for 30 seconds until fragrant but not browned.\", \"Step 5: Add diced onions and stir fry for 2 minutes until softened. Add the diced liver and shrimp and stir fry for 2 minutes.\", \"Step 6: Add the carrots, green beans, green peas, and bell peppers to the pan. Stir fry on high heat for 3 minutes until heated through but still slightly crisp.\", \"Step 7: Add the cooled parboiled rice to the pan along with curry powder, thyme, seasoning cubes, soy sauce, and salt. Stir fry vigorously on high heat for 5 to 7 minutes, tossing continuously, until the rice is evenly coated in the yellow curry colour and well combined with all the vegetables and protein. Taste and adjust seasoning, then serve hot.\"], \"match_percentage\": 13.3, \"used_ingredients\": [\"long grain rice\", \"onions\"], \"cook_time_minutes\": 30, \"prep_time_minutes\": 30, \"missing_ingredients\": [\"carrots\", \"green peas\", \"bell peppers(green, yellow, red)\", \"liver\", \"vegetable oil\", \"garlic\", \"ginger\", \"curry powder\", \"thyme\", \"seasoning cubes\", \"soy sauce\", \"salt\", \"chicken stock\"]}, {\"name\": \"Ofe Owerri\", \"tips\": \"Use as many different types of meat and fish as you can for the most authentic version. The combination of ugu and uziza leaves together distinguishes this from Edikang Ikong.\", \"servings\": 6, \"difficulty\": \"hard\", \"description\": \"Ofe Owerri is a luxurious traditional Igbo vegetable soup from Owerri in Imo State, known for being loaded with multiple types of meat, fish, and a generous mix of vegetables, traditionally served at important ceremonies.\", \"instructions\": [\"Step 1: Wash and season all assorted meats and stockfish with onions, seasoning cubes, and salt. Cook on medium heat for 40 to 50 minutes until very tender. Set aside with the rich stock.\", \"Step 2: Peel cocoyam and boil until very soft, then pound until completely smooth to make the thickener.\", \"Step 3: Heat palm oil, add sliced onions and blended scotch bonnet peppers, fry for 15 minutes until oil floats on top.\", \"Step 4: Add all the cooked meats, stockfish, dried fish, periwinkle, ogiri, ground crayfish, and meat stock. Cook on medium heat for 15 minutes.\", \"Step 5: Add the pounded cocoyam thickener in small lumps and stir until dissolved.\", \"Step 6: Add the fresh fish pieces and cook gently for 8 minutes.\", \"Step 7: Add the shredded ugu and uziza leaves together and stir in. Cook for 3 to 5 minutes only.\", \"Step 8: Taste and adjust seasoning. Serve hot with pounded yam, fufu, or semolina.\"], \"match_percentage\": 13.3, \"used_ingredients\": [\"onions\", \"scotch bonnet peppers\"], \"cook_time_minutes\": 85, \"prep_time_minutes\": 30, \"missing_ingredients\": [\"ugu leaves (fluted pumpkin)\", \"uziza leaves\", \"cocoyam (for thickening)\", \"palm oil\", \"assorted meat (beef, tripe, shaki, cow leg)\", \"stockfish\", \"dried fish\", \"fresh fish\", \"periwinkle\", \"crayfish\", \"ogiri (fermented locust beans)\", \"seasoning cubes\", \"salt\"]}, {\"name\": \"Nigerian Coleslaw\", \"tips\": \"The combination of mayonnaise and salad cream together, rather than just mayonnaise alone, is what gives Nigerian coleslaw its distinctive tangy sweetness. Always shred the cabbage very finely for the best texture, and let the coleslaw rest in the refrigerator before serving for the best flavour.\", \"servings\": 6, \"difficulty\": \"easy\", \"description\": \"Nigerian Coleslaw is a creamy and slightly sweet shredded cabbage and carrot salad that is a staple side dish at Nigerian parties, often served alongside Jollof Rice and Fried Rice. It differs from Western coleslaw by typically including diced apples, raisins, and a generously sweetened mayonnaise dressing.\", \"instructions\": [\"Step 1: Wash the cabbage thoroughly and shred very finely using a sharp knife or food processor — the cabbage should be cut into thin uniform strips for the best texture.\", \"Step 2: Peel and grate or finely julienne the carrots into thin matchstick pieces, similar in size to the shredded cabbage.\", \"Step 3: In a large bowl combine the shredded cabbage, grated carrots and sweet corn. Toss together gently.\", \"Step 4: In a separate small bowl mix mayonnaise and salad cream together in roughly equal parts, adding sugar to taste for the characteristic Nigerian sweetness, along with a pinch of black pepper and salt.\", \"Step 5: Pour the dressing over the vegetable mixture and toss thoroughly until every piece is well coated in the creamy dressing.\", \"Step 6: Taste and adjust sweetness and seasoning — Nigerian coleslaw is typically sweeter than standard Western coleslaw.\", \"Step 7: Cover and refrigerate for at least 1 hour before serving to allow the flavours to meld and the cabbage to soften slightly. Serve cold alongside Jollof Rice or Fried Rice.\"], \"match_percentage\": 0.0, \"used_ingredients\": [], \"cook_time_minutes\": 0, \"prep_time_minutes\": 25, \"missing_ingredients\": [\"cabbage\", \"carrots\", \"sweet corn\", \"mayonnaise\", \"salad cream\", \"sugar\", \"black pepper\", \"salt\"]}]}','2026-06-21 10:17:56'),('2d540c0c-e103-4cce-b097-ccc6fede2868','[\"palm oil\", \"egusi\", \"spinach\", \"onions\", \"crayfish\"]','nigerian',NULL,'{\"almost_there\": [], \"can_make_now\": [], \"needs_shopping\": [{\"name\": \"Egusi Soup Yoruba Style\", \"tips\": \"The secret to Yoruba egusi is frying the egusi completely dry in palm oil before adding any liquid. Never add water or stock to the egusi while frying — it must fry and toast in the oil until golden. Also never add tomatoes to Yoruba egusi soup — that changes the flavour profile completely.\", \"servings\": 6, \"difficulty\": \"medium\", \"description\": \"Egusi Soup Yoruba style is a rich and hearty Nigerian soup made with ground melon seeds fried directly in palm oil before any liquid is added. Unlike Igbo style egusi which is added raw, Yoruba style fries the egusi first until golden and nutty giving it a deeper richer flavour. It is served with amala, eba, or pounded yam.\", \"instructions\": [\"Step 1: Wash and season assorted meat and stockfish with onions, seasoning cubes, and salt. Cook in a pot on medium heat for 15 to 20 minutes until tender. Set aside with the stock.\", \"Step 2: Blend scotch bonnet peppers, tatashe, and half the onions together into a smooth paste. Set aside.\", \"Step 3: Heat palm oil in a large pot on medium heat for 2 minutes until melted and hot but not bleached. Chop the remaining onions and fry in the palm oil for 3 minutes until soft and translucent.\", \"Step 4: Add the ground egusi to the palm oil and stir immediately to combine. Fry the egusi in the palm oil on medium heat for 8 to 10 minutes stirring constantly until the egusi turns golden, smells nutty, and pulls away from the sides of the pot. Do not add any liquid at this stage — dry frying is the key to Yoruba egusi.\", \"Step 5: Add the blended pepper mixture to the fried egusi and stir well to combine. Fry together for another 10 minutes on medium heat stirring every 2 minutes until the pepper is cooked and oil begins to float on the surface.\", \"Step 6: Add the cooked meat, stockfish, dried fish, meat stock, ground crayfish, iru, and seasoning cubes. Stir everything together and add a small amount of water if the soup is too thick. Cook on medium heat for 15 minutes until all the flavours come together.\", \"Step 7: Taste and adjust salt and seasoning. The soup should be rich, thick, and deeply flavoured at this point.\", \"Step 8: Add shredded spinach or efo tete and stir into the soup. Cook for exactly 2 minutes only — overcooking the vegetables will make them lose their colour and become soggy. Remove from heat and serve immediately with amala, eba, or pounded yam.\"], \"match_percentage\": 38.5, \"used_ingredients\": [\"ground egusi (melon seeds)\", \"palm oil\", \"onions\", \"crayfish\", \"spinach, efo tete or ugwu\"], \"cook_time_minutes\": 70, \"prep_time_minutes\": 20, \"missing_ingredients\": [\"assorted meat (beef, tripe, shaki)\", \"stockfish\", \"dried fish\", \"scotch bonnet peppers\", \"tatashe (red bell pepper)\", \"iru (locust beans)\", \"seasoning cubes\", \"salt\"]}, {\"name\": \"Efo Riro\", \"tips\": \"The most important step is frying the pepper base completely dry until the oil floats on top before adding any meat or stock. This is what separates a rich deeply flavoured Efo Riro from a watery one. Also add the vegetables at the very last minute and cook for 2 minutes only — overcooked vegetables will turn dark and lose their flavour.\", \"servings\": 6, \"difficulty\": \"medium\", \"description\": \"Efo Riro is a rich Yoruba vegetable soup made with tatashe and ata rodo as the pepper base, assorted meats, and leafy green vegetables. The name means stirred leafy vegetable in Yoruba. It is one of the most flavourful Nigerian soups with a vibrant green and red colour from the vegetables and pepper base. It is served with amala, eba, pounded yam, or rice.\", \"instructions\": [\"Step 1: Wash and season assorted meat, pomo, and stockfish with onions, seasoning cubes, and salt. Cook on medium heat for 20 to 30 minutes until very tender. Set aside with the stock.\", \"Step 2: Blend tatashe and scotch bonnet peppers together into a smooth paste. Do not add water — the peppers have enough natural liquid. Set aside.\", \"Step 3: Wash the efo tete or spinach thoroughly, shred into medium sized pieces by hand, and set aside in a colander to drain excess water.\", \"Step 4: Heat palm oil in a large pot on medium-high heat for 2 minutes. Slice onions and fry in the palm oil for 3 minutes until golden and fragrant.\", \"Step 5: Add the blended tatashe and scotch bonnet pepper mixture to the pot. It will sizzle loudly in the hot oil — this is correct. Fry on high heat for 10 to 20 minutes stirring every 3 minutes until all the water has completely evaporated, the oil floats on top, and the pepper sauce has darkened and thickened. This step gives Efo Riro its deep rich flavour.\", \"Step 6: Add iru (locust beans) and ground crayfish and stir into the pepper sauce. Fry for 2 more minutes until the iru is fragrant.\", \"Step 7: Add the cooked assorted meat, stockfish, dried fish, and a ladle of the meat stock. Stir everything together and cook on medium heat for 10 minutes until the meat is well coated in the sauce.\", \"Step 8: Add the shredded efo tete or spinach to the pot and stir into the sauce. Cook for exactly 2 minutes only on medium heat — the vegetables should wilt into the soup but remain bright green and not soggy. Taste, adjust seasoning, and remove from heat immediately. Serve with amala, eba, or pounded yam.\"], \"match_percentage\": 33.3, \"used_ingredients\": [\"vgetables African spinach or ugwu\", \"onions\", \"palm oil\", \"crayfish\"], \"cook_time_minutes\": 75, \"prep_time_minutes\": 25, \"missing_ingredients\": [\"tatashe (red bell pepper)\", \"scotch bonnet peppers (ata rodo)\", \"assorted meat (beef, tripe, shaki, pomo)\", \"stockfish\", \"dried fish\", \"iru (locust beans)\", \"seasoning cubes\", \"salt\"]}, {\"name\": \"Ewa Agoyin\", \"tips\": \"The two secrets to authentic Ewa Agoyin are cooking the beans with a lot of onions until completely mashable with no whole beans remaining, and making the Agoyin stew with only dried peppers not fresh ones. Fresh peppers will not give the deep dark colour and concentrated flavour that makes Agoyin stew unique. The stew must be dark, dry, and almost burnt looking — that is correct.\", \"servings\": 4, \"difficulty\": \"medium\", \"description\": \"Ewa Agoyin is a popular Yoruba street food originally brought to Nigeria by Beninese traders, consisting of soft completely mashed honey beans or black eyed beans served with a deeply dark and spicy Agoyin stew made from dried red peppers and palm oil. It is a beloved Lagos breakfast food sold by roadside vendors and eaten with agege bread.\", \"instructions\": [\"Step 1: Wash the beans thoroughly then cover the beans with fresh water and cook on high heat until boiling, then reduce to medium heat. Cook for 45 to 60 minutes until the beans are extremely soft — they should mash completely between your fingers with no resistance. Add more water as needed during cooking to prevent burning.\", \"Step 2: Once the beans are very soft, use a wooden spoon or potato masher to mash them completely in the pot until no whole beans remain. The consistency should be thick and porridge-like. Season with salt, stir well, and set aside.\", \"Step 4: While the beans cook prepare the Agoyin stew. Rehydrate the dried red peppers and dried chilli peppers by soaking in hot water for 20 minutes until soft. Drain and blend alongside some onions and ginger into a rough paste — not completely smooth, leave some texture.\", \"Step 5: Heat palm oil in a separate pot on medium heat until hot. Slice onions into thin rings and fry in the palm oil for 10 minutes on medium-low heat, stirring constantly until the onions are very dark brown and almost caramelised — this dark onion is essential to the Agoyin stew flavour.\", \"Step 6: Add the blended dried pepper mixture to the dark onions and palm oil. Stir well and fry on medium heat for 20 to 25 minutes stirring every 3 minutes until all moisture evaporates, the stew becomes very dark, thick, and dry, and the oil floats on top. The stew should be almost black in colour — this is correct.\", \"Step 7: Add seasoning cubes and salt to the stew. Stir well and cook for 5 more minutes. The finished Agoyin stew should be very dark, very dry, very spicy, and intensely flavoured.\", \"Step 8: Serve the mashed beans in a bowl and pour the dark Agoyin stew generously on top. Eat with agege bread, fried plantain, or on its own.\"], \"match_percentage\": 33.3, \"used_ingredients\": [\"onions\", \"palm oil\", \"crayfish\"], \"cook_time_minutes\": 90, \"prep_time_minutes\": 20, \"missing_ingredients\": [\"beans\", \"dried red peppers (tatashe)\", \"dried long chilli bonnet peppers(shombo)\", \"seasoning cubes\", \"salt\", \"water\"]}, {\"name\": \"Ayamase (Ofada Stew)\", \"tips\": \"Bleaching the palm oil is absolutely non-negotiable for authentic Ayamase. Only use green peppers and unripe tatashe — no red peppers at all. The more assorted meats you use the richer and more authentic the stew will be.\", \"servings\": 6, \"difficulty\": \"hard\", \"description\": \"Ayamase also known as Ofada Stew or Designer Stew is a rich and intensely flavoured Yoruba stew made exclusively with green peppers and unripe tatashe giving it its distinctive green colour. It is traditionally served with Ofada rice and the stew is made with bleached palm oil and loaded with assorted meats making it one of the most indulgent Nigerian dishes.\", \"instructions\": [\"Step 1: Wash and season all assorted meats with onions, seasoning cubes, ginger garlic paste and salt. Cook in a pot on medium heat for 25 to 35 minutes until very tender. Fry the cooked meats in a small amount of oil until lightly browned on the outside for extra flavour. Set aside with the stock.\", \"Step 2: Blend green bell peppers, unripe green tatashe, green scotch bonnet peppers, and onions together into a coarse paste — do not blend completely smooth, leave some texture. The stew must use only green peppers and unripe tatashe — never red peppers or ripe tatashe as this completely changes the dish.\", \"Step 3: Bleach the palm oil by heating it in a pot on high heat with the lid on for 10 to 15 minutes until the oil turns from orange-red to a pale golden yellow colour and begins to smoke lightly. Remove from heat and allow to cool slightly. Bleached palm oil is essential for authentic Ayamase.\", \"Step 4: Return the bleached palm oil to medium heat. Add sliced onions with some ginger garlic paste and fry for 3 minutes until soft and slightly golden.\", \"Step 5: Pour the blended green pepper mixture into the bleached palm oil. It will sizzle vigorously stir immediately. Fry on high heat for 15 to 20 minutes stirring every 3 to 4 minutes until all the water has completely evaporated, the oil floats on top, and the pepper sauce is cooked down and thick.\", \"Step 6: Add iru (locust beans) and ground crayfish to the cooked pepper base and stir well. Fry for 3 more minutes until the iru is fragrant and well incorporated.\", \"Step 7: Add all the assorted meats and a ladle of the meat stock. Stir everything together to coat the meat in the green pepper sauce. Cook on medium heat for 10 minutes until the meat is well flavoured and the stew is thick and rich.\", \"Step 8: Taste and adjust seasoning. The finished Ayamase should be dark olive green, thick, intensely flavoured, and very rich with assorted meats. Serve with Ofada rice.\"], \"match_percentage\": 27.3, \"used_ingredients\": [\"onions\", \"palm oil\", \"crayfish\"], \"cook_time_minutes\": 90, \"prep_time_minutes\": 25, \"missing_ingredients\": [\"green bell peppers\", \"unripe tatashe (green tatashe)\", \"green scotch bonnet peppers\", \"assorted meat (beef, tripe, shaki, pomo, liver)\", \"iru (locust beans)\", \"seasoning cubes\", \"ginger and garlic paste\", \"salt\"]}, {\"name\": \"Asaro (Yam Porridge)\", \"tips\": \"Gentle stirring lets some yam break down to thicken the sauce naturally without becoming completely mashed.\", \"servings\": 4, \"difficulty\": \"easy\", \"description\": \"Asaro is a beloved traditional Yoruba yam porridge made by cooking yam chunks directly in a rich tomato and pepper sauce until the yam softens and thickens the entire dish into a hearty one-pot meal.\", \"instructions\": [\"Step 1: Peel the yam and cut into medium sized chunks. Wash thoroughly.\", \"Step 2: Blend onions, tatashe, and scotch bonnet peppers together into a smooth paste.\", \"Step 3: Place the yam chunks in a pot with the blended pepper mixture, sliced onions, palm oil, and enough water to just cover the yam.\", \"Step 4: Bring to a boil then reduce to medium heat. Cook for 20 to 25 minutes, stirring occasionally, until the yam softens and breaks down at the edges.\", \"Step 5: Add ground crayfish, flaked fish, seasoning cubes, and salt. Stir gently.\", \"Step 6: Continue cooking on medium-low heat for 8 to 10 minutes until thick and stew-like.\", \"Step 7: Taste and adjust seasoning. Serve hot on its own.\"], \"match_percentage\": 27.3, \"used_ingredients\": [\"onions\", \"palm oil\", \"crayfish\"], \"cook_time_minutes\": 40, \"prep_time_minutes\": 15, \"missing_ingredients\": [\"yam (white yam)\", \"tomatoes\", \"tatashe (red bell pepper)\", \"scotch bonnet peppers\", \"smoked fish or dried fish\", \"seasoning cubes\", \"salt\", \"water\"]}, {\"name\": \"Ikokore\", \"tips\": \"Use water yam specifically not white yam or cocoyam. Do not rinse the grated yam before adding to the pot as the natural starch thickens the broth and holds the dumplings together.\", \"servings\": 4, \"difficulty\": \"medium\", \"description\": \"Ikokore is a traditional Ijebu Yoruba dish made from grated water yam cooked in a rich pepper soup or tomato base with assorted fish and seafood. The grated water yam forms thick irregular dumplings in the broth giving the dish its characteristic texture. It is a beloved dish in Ogun State and across Yorubaland.\", \"instructions\": [\"Step 1: Peel the water yam and grate on the coarse side of a grater into a bowl. Do not rinse the grated yam — the natural starch is needed to hold the dumplings together. Season the grated yam lightly with salt and set aside.\", \"Step 2: Blend scotch bonnet peppers, long chilli peppers, and onions together into a smooth paste.\", \"Step 3: Heat palm oil in a large pot on medium heat. Add iru and fry for 1 minute until fragrant. Add the blended pepper mixture and fry for 15 minutes until cooked and oil floats on top.\", \"Step 4: Add enough meat stock to the pot . Add ground crayfish, dried fish, smoked fish, assorted meat, seasoning cubes, and salt. Bring to a boil on high heat.\", \"Step 5: Using a tablespoon or your hand, scoop portions of the grated water yam and drop them one by one into the boiling broth. Do not stir immediately — allow the yam dumplings to set for 3 minutes before stirring gently.\", \"Step 6: Cook on medium heat for 15 to 20 minutes stirring gently occasionally until the yam dumplings are fully cooked and the broth has thickened, adjust seasoning, and serve hot.\"], \"match_percentage\": 23.1, \"used_ingredients\": [\"palm oil\", \"crayfish\", \"onions\"], \"cook_time_minutes\": 50, \"prep_time_minutes\": 25, \"missing_ingredients\": [\"water yam (isu ewura)\", \"dried fish\", \"assorted meat\", \"smoked fish\", \"scotch bonnet peppers\", \"long chilli peppers\", \"iru (locust beans)\", \"seasoning cubes\", \"salt\", \"water\"]}, {\"name\": \"Abacha\", \"tips\": \"Always soak in cold water not hot. Potash is essential for emulsifying the palm oil into the dressing.\", \"servings\": 4, \"difficulty\": \"medium\", \"description\": \"Abacha is a traditional Igbo cold salad made from dried shredded cassava rehydrated and tossed in an emulsified palm oil and potash dressing with ugba, utazi leaves, garden eggs, crayfish, and assorted proteins.\", \"instructions\": [\"Step 1: Soak the dried abacha in cold water for 10 to 15 minutes until softened. Drain thoroughly.\", \"Step 2: Dissolve potash in 3 tablespoons of water and strain through a fine sieve.\", \"Step 3: Pour palm oil into a bowl. Add the potash solution gradually while stirring vigorously until emulsified and bright yellow.\", \"Step 4: Add ground crayfish, sliced scotch bonnet peppers, sliced onions, seasoning cubes, and salt to the emulsion.\", \"Step 5: Add the drained abacha and toss thoroughly until coated.\", \"Step 6: Add ugba, sliced garden eggs, shredded utazi, flaked fish, and sliced ponmo. Toss together gently.\", \"Step 7: Taste and adjust seasoning.\", \"Step 8: Garnish with utazi and onion rings. Serve at room temperature.\"], \"match_percentage\": 23.1, \"used_ingredients\": [\"palm oil\", \"crayfish\", \"onions\"], \"cook_time_minutes\": 0, \"prep_time_minutes\": 20, \"missing_ingredients\": [\"abacha (dried shredded cassava)\", \"ugba (oil bean seeds)\", \"potash (kaun)\", \"utazi leaves\", \"garden eggs\", \"scotch bonnet peppers\", \"seasoning cubes\", \"salt\", \"dried fish or stockfish\", \"ponmo (cow skin)\"]}, {\"name\": \"Nigerian Pepper Soup\", \"tips\": \"The quality of your pepper soup spice mix makes or breaks this dish. Use freshly ground spices if possible — uda (country onion), ehuru (calabash nutmeg), and uziza seeds ground together give the most authentic flavour. Never cover the pot fully while cooking pepper soup — leave it slightly open so the broth reduces and concentrates.\", \"servings\": 4, \"difficulty\": \"easy\", \"description\": \"Nigerian Pepper Soup is a light, intensely spiced broth made with meat or fish and a unique blend of pepper soup spices. It is served at every Nigerian gathering, used as a remedy for colds and fever, and eaten as a starter or main dish. The broth is thin but deeply flavoured with a distinctive warming heat that comes from the special pepper soup spice blend.\", \"instructions\": [\"Step 1: Wash the meat thoroughly and cut into medium sized pieces. Season with onions, seasoning cubes, and salt. Do not add water yet — allow the meat to cook in its own juices first.\", \"Step 2: Place the seasoned meat in a pot on medium heat and cook dry for 10 minutes stirring occasionally until the meat releases its juices and begins to brown slightly on the outside.\", \"Step 3: Add enough water to cover the meat completely. Bring to a boil on high heat then reduce to medium heat. Cook for 25 to 30 minutes for goat meat or 15 minutes for chicken until the meat is tender but not falling off the bone.\", \"Step 4: Add the pepper soup spice mix, ground crayfish, and blended or roughly crushed scotch bonnet peppers. Stir well and taste — the broth should be well seasoned and spicy at this point. Add more seasoning cubes and salt if needed.\", \"Step 5: Cook on medium heat for another 15 minutes until the spices have fully infused into the broth and the liquid has reduced slightly. The broth should be a light golden brown colour and smell intensely aromatic.\", \"Step 6: Tear utazi leaves into small pieces and add to the pot — utazi adds a slight bitterness that balances the heat. Add uziza leaves whole or roughly torn. Cook for 3 minutes only.\", \"Step 7: Taste one final time and adjust salt and pepper. The pepper soup should be very hot and spicy, lightly bitter from the utazi, and deeply aromatic from the spice blend. Serve hot in deep bowls with sliced onions on top and agidi or white rice on the side.\"], \"match_percentage\": 20.0, \"used_ingredients\": [\"onions\", \"crayfish\"], \"cook_time_minutes\": 55, \"prep_time_minutes\": 15, \"missing_ingredients\": [\"goat meat or chicken or catfish\", \"pepper soup spice mix\", \"scotch bonnet peppers\", \"uziza leaves\", \"utazi leaves\", \"seasoning cubes\", \"salt\", \"water\"]}, {\"name\": \"Ofe Owerri\", \"tips\": \"Use as many different types of meat and fish as you can for the most authentic version. The combination of ugu and uziza leaves together distinguishes this from Edikang Ikong.\", \"servings\": 6, \"difficulty\": \"hard\", \"description\": \"Ofe Owerri is a luxurious traditional Igbo vegetable soup from Owerri in Imo State, known for being loaded with multiple types of meat, fish, and a generous mix of vegetables, traditionally served at important ceremonies.\", \"instructions\": [\"Step 1: Wash and season all assorted meats and stockfish with onions, seasoning cubes, and salt. Cook on medium heat for 40 to 50 minutes until very tender. Set aside with the rich stock.\", \"Step 2: Peel cocoyam and boil until very soft, then pound until completely smooth to make the thickener.\", \"Step 3: Heat palm oil, add sliced onions and blended scotch bonnet peppers, fry for 15 minutes until oil floats on top.\", \"Step 4: Add all the cooked meats, stockfish, dried fish, periwinkle, ogiri, ground crayfish, and meat stock. Cook on medium heat for 15 minutes.\", \"Step 5: Add the pounded cocoyam thickener in small lumps and stir until dissolved.\", \"Step 6: Add the fresh fish pieces and cook gently for 8 minutes.\", \"Step 7: Add the shredded ugu and uziza leaves together and stir in. Cook for 3 to 5 minutes only.\", \"Step 8: Taste and adjust seasoning. Serve hot with pounded yam, fufu, or semolina.\"], \"match_percentage\": 20.0, \"used_ingredients\": [\"palm oil\", \"crayfish\", \"onions\"], \"cook_time_minutes\": 85, \"prep_time_minutes\": 30, \"missing_ingredients\": [\"ugu leaves (fluted pumpkin)\", \"uziza leaves\", \"cocoyam (for thickening)\", \"assorted meat (beef, tripe, shaki, cow leg)\", \"stockfish\", \"dried fish\", \"fresh fish\", \"periwinkle\", \"scotch bonnet peppers\", \"ogiri (fermented locust beans)\", \"seasoning cubes\", \"salt\"]}, {\"name\": \"Moi Moi\", \"tips\": \"The food processor peeling method is a game changer — it cuts prep time from 30 minutes to 5 minutes. The two most important steps are removing every single bean skin and whisking the paste vigorously to aerate it before adding seasoning. Skipping either step will result in dense heavy Moi Moi. Always fill containers only three quarters full as the paste expands during steaming.\", \"servings\": 8, \"difficulty\": \"medium\", \"description\": \"Moi Moi is a traditional Nigerian steamed bean pudding made from peeled beans blended into a smooth paste. It is a beloved dish across all Nigerian tribes and is served at parties, as a side dish with rice or ogi, or eaten alone as a complete meal. The texture should be firm yet soft and moist inside with a rich savoury flavour.\", \"instructions\": [\"Step 1: There are two ways to peel the beans. Traditional method: Pour beans into a bowl and soak in cold water for 30 minutes until the skins begin to loosen and soften, then rub vigorously between both palms under running water until all skins float off. Quick method: Pour dry beans into a food processor with some water and pulse for 30 to 45 seconds — the food processor will crack and loosen the skins without grinding the beans. Pour the pulsed beans into a large bowl of water, the skins will float to the top — skim them off and drain. Repeat until all skins are removed. The quick method takes 5 minutes instead of 30.\", \"Step 2: Rinse the peeled beans thoroughly in clean water two to three times to remove any remaining skin fragments. The beans should be completely white with no dark skin remaining — any leftover skin will make the Moi Moi rough and bitter.\", \"Step 3: Place the peeled beans directly into the blender together with the scotch bonnet peppers, red bell pepper, onions, one raw egg, and a very small amount of water — just enough to get the blender moving. Blend everything together on high speed for 3 minutes until the paste is completely smooth with absolutely no grainy texture. Blending the peppers and egg together with the beans at this stage gives the Moi Moi its full flavour and colour from the inside.\", \"Step 4: Pour the blended paste into a large bowl. Add seasoning cubes, vegetable oil, and salt. Mix everything together thoroughly until well combined. Taste and adjust seasoning — it should be well seasoned and slightly peppery.\", \"Step 5: Using a wooden spoon or electric hand mixer, whisk the paste vigorously for 5 minutes until it becomes fluffy, lighter in colour, and increases slightly in volume. This aerates the paste and gives Moi Moi its soft moist texture when steamed.\", \"Step 6: Break the mackerel fish into medium sized chunks and slice your boiled eggs and set aside. Grease foil containers or moi moi leaves generously with vegetable oil on the inside so the moi moi does not stick.\", \"Step 7: Pour the bean paste mixture into each container filling only three quarters full. Drop pieces of fish directly into the paste in each container alongside the sliced eggs  — the fish sits inside the moi moi not on top. Press down lightly so the fish is submerged in the paste.\", \"Step 8: Seal each foil container tightly by folding the edges over securely. No steam should be able to escape during cooking.\", \"Step 9: Place a trivet or folded foil at the bottom of a large pot to prevent direct heat contact. Arrange the sealed moi moi containers in the pot and add water to reach halfway up the sides of the containers.\", \"Step 10: Cover the pot tightly and steam on medium heat for 45 to 60 minutes. Check water level every 15 minutes and add more hot water if needed — never let the pot run dry. Moi Moi is ready when it feels firm when pressed gently and pulls away cleanly from the container when opened.\"], \"match_percentage\": 18.2, \"used_ingredients\": [\"onions\", \"crayfish\"], \"cook_time_minutes\": 60, \"prep_time_minutes\": 40, \"missing_ingredients\": [\"beans\", \"scotch bonnet peppers\", \"long chilli pepper (shombo)\", \"vegetable oil\", \"seasoning cubes\", \"salt\", \"eggs\", \"fish (preferably mackerel fish)\", \"water\"]}, {\"name\": \"Banga Stew\", \"tips\": \"The key difference between Banga Soup and Banga Stew is the reduction time — cook the stew version longer uncovered to achieve a thicker consistency that coats rice or yam well rather than the more liquid soup form.\", \"servings\": 5, \"difficulty\": \"hard\", \"description\": \"Banga Stew is a thick, deeply flavoured Igbo stew made from concentrated palm fruit extract, prepared similarly to Banga Soup but cooked down to a thicker consistency more like a stew than a soup. It is rich, nutty, and aromatic, traditionally seasoned with banga spices, and served with white rice, boiled yam, or plantain.\", \"instructions\": [\"Step 1: If using fresh palm fruit, boil for 20 to 30 minutes until soft, then pound to separate pulp from nuts and squeeze with warm water to extract the thick orange juice. Strain through a sieve to remove fibres. If using canned concentrate, dilute according to package instructions.\", \"Step 2: Pour the palm fruit extract into a pot and bring to a boil on high heat, then reduce to medium heat and simmer for 15 to 20 minutes until the oil begins to separate and rise to the surface.\", \"Step 3: Season the assorted meat with onions, seasoning cubes, and salt. Cook separately on medium heat for 30 minutes until tender. Add the cooked meat and stock to the palm fruit base.\", \"Step 4: Add the banga spice mix to the pot and simmer for 15 minutes to allow the spices to infuse fully into the base.\", \"Step 5: Add dried fish, ground crayfish, sliced scotch bonnet peppers, and seasoning cubes. Stir well and continue cooking on medium heat, allowing the liquid to reduce and thicken for 20 to 25 minutes — unlike Banga Soup this should reduce further into a thicker stew-like consistency.\", \"Step 6: Add the fresh fish pieces and cook gently for 8 to 10 minutes until just cooked through, stirring carefully to avoid breaking the fish apart.\", \"Step 7: Continue simmering uncovered for an additional 10 minutes, stirring occasionally, until the stew has thickened noticeably and the oil is clearly visible on the surface.\", \"Step 8: Remove the oburunbebe stick before serving. Taste and adjust seasoning. Serve hot with white rice, boiled yam, or plantain.\"], \"match_percentage\": 18.2, \"used_ingredients\": [\"onions\", \"crayfish\"], \"cook_time_minutes\": 80, \"prep_time_minutes\": 30, \"missing_ingredients\": [\"fresh palm fruit (or canned banga concentrate)\", \"assorted meat (beef, tripe)\", \"dried fish\", \"fresh fish\", \"banga spice mix (oburunbebe stick, dried bitter leaf)\", \"scotch bonnet peppers\", \"seasoning cubes\", \"salt\", \"water\"]}, {\"name\": \"Akara\", \"tips\": \"Whisking the bean paste until very fluffy is the secret to light soft akara — never skip this step. Also make sure the oil is very hot before adding the paste otherwise the akara will absorb too much oil and become greasy. Wet your spoon with oil before scooping each portion to help the paste slide off cleanly into the oil.\", \"servings\": 4, \"difficulty\": \"medium\", \"description\": \"Akara is a traditional Yoruba deep fried bean cake made from peeled black eyed beans blended into a smooth aerated paste and fried in hot oil until crispy on the outside and soft inside. It is a quintessential Nigerian breakfast food sold by roadside vendors across the country and best eaten hot with ogi (pap) or bread.\", \"instructions\": [\"Step 1: Peel the beans using one of two methods. Traditional method: Soak beans in cold water for 30 minutes then rub between palms under running water until all skins float off and are drained away. Quick method: Pulse beans and water  in a food processor for 30 seconds to crack and loosen skins, pour into a bowl of water, skim off floating skins, and drain. Rinse peeled beans two to three times in clean water.\", \"Step 2: Place the peeled beans alongside the peppers and onions in a blender with a very small amount of water — just enough to move the blender. Blend on high speed for 3 minutes until the paste is completely smooth and thick. The paste must be thick not watery — too much water will make flat oily akara.\", \"Step 3: Pour the blended bean paste into a large bowl. Using a wooden spoon or electric hand mixer whisk the paste vigorously for 5 to 7 minutes until it becomes very fluffy, lighter in colour, and almost doubles in volume. This is the most important step — the air you whisk in is what makes akara light and fluffy inside.\", \"Step 4: Add some salt and seasoning cubes to the whisked paste. Fold gently into the paste without deflating it. Taste and adjust seasoning.\", \"Step 5: Pour enough vegetable oil into a deep wide pan to allow the akara to float — at least 3 inches deep. Heat on medium-high heat for 2 to 3 minutes until hot. Test the oil by dropping a tiny bit of paste in — it should rise immediately to the surface and sizzle vigorously. If it sinks the oil is not hot enough.\", \"Step 6: Wet your tablespoon with oil and scoop portions of the paste into the hot oil one at a time. Do not overcrowd the pan — leave space between each akara so they cook evenly and stay round.\", \"Step 7: Fry on medium heat for 3 to 4 minutes until the bottom is deep golden brown, then flip carefully with a slotted spoon or skewer and fry the other side for 2 to 3 minutes until evenly golden brown and crispy all over.\", \"Step 8: Remove with a slotted spoon and drain on paper towels to absorb excess oil. Serve immediately while hot and crispy alongside ogi (pap) or as a breakfast snack.\"], \"match_percentage\": 14.3, \"used_ingredients\": [\"onions\"], \"cook_time_minutes\": 20, \"prep_time_minutes\": 30, \"missing_ingredients\": [\"black eyed beans\", \"scotch bonnet peppers\", \"long chilli peppers(shombo)\", \"seasoning cubes\", \"salt\", \"vegetable oil for deep frying\"]}, {\"name\": \"Asun\", \"tips\": \"Grilling or smoking the goat meat after boiling is non-negotiable for authentic Asun — without the charred smoky exterior the dish is just peppered goat meat not Asun. Use goat meat with the skin on for the best texture and flavour. The pepper sauce should have chunky sliced peppers not a blended smooth sauce.\", \"servings\": 4, \"difficulty\": \"medium\", \"description\": \"Asun is a popular Yoruba delicacy of smoked or roasted goat meat cut into small pieces and tossed in a fiery pepper and onion sauce. It originates from Ondo State in Yorubaland and is now one of the most popular Nigerian party small chops and appetisers served across the country. The goat meat is first smoked or roasted to give it a distinctive charred flavour before being peppered.\", \"instructions\": [\"Step 1: Wash the goat meat thoroughly — authentic Asun uses goat meat with the skin on as the skin adds texture and flavour. Cut into medium sized chunks. Season with seasoning cubes, curry powder, thyme, ginger garlic paste and salt.\", \"Step 2: Cook the seasoned goat meat in a pot with a small amount of water on medium heat for 20 to 25 minutes until tender but not falling apart.\", \"Step 3: Remove the cooked goat meat and place directly on a grill, open flame, or in a very hot oven at 220 degrees Celsius. Grill or roast for 15 to 20 minutes turning occasionally until the outside is charred and smoky and the skin is slightly crispy. The charring is essential for authentic Asun flavour.\", \"Step 4: Remove from the grill and cut into smaller bite sized pieces while still hot. Set aside.\", \"Step 5: Slice scotch bonnet peppers, green bell pepper, red bell pepper, and onions into thin strips. The peppers should be sliced not blended, a food processor can be used as well — the chunky pepper pieces are characteristic of Asun.\", \"Step 6: Heat vegetable oil in a wide pan on medium heat. Add the sliced onions and fry for 2 minutes until slightly softened.\", \"Step 7: Add all the sliced peppers to the pan and stir fry on high heat for 3 to 4 minutes — the peppers should be cooked but still have a slight crunch. Do not overcook the peppers into mush.\", \"Step 8: Add the grilled goat meat pieces to the pan and toss vigorously with the peppers for 3 minutes on high heat until the meat is well coated in the pepper mixture and everything is sizzling hot. Taste and adjust seasoning. Serve immediately as a party appetiser or small chop.\"], \"match_percentage\": 9.1, \"used_ingredients\": [\"onions\"], \"cook_time_minutes\": 60, \"prep_time_minutes\": 20, \"missing_ingredients\": [\"goat meat (skin on)\", \"scotch bonnet peppers\", \"green bell pepper\", \"red bell pepper (tatashe)\", \"vegetable oil\", \"seasoning cubes\", \"curry powder\", \"thyme\", \"salt\", \"ginger garlic paste\"]}, {\"name\": \"Nigerian Fried Rice\", \"tips\": \"Always cook on high heat when frying the rice and vegetables together to prevent everything from steaming and becoming soggy instead of stir-fried.\", \"servings\": 6, \"difficulty\": \"medium\", \"description\": \"Nigerian Fried Rice is a colourful and flavourful party staple made with parboiled rice stir-fried with mixed vegetables, liver, and a distinct curry seasoning. Unlike Chinese fried rice, the Nigerian version has a unique orange-yellow hue from curry powder and is loaded with vegetables, making it one of the most popular dishes at Nigerian celebrations alongside Jollof Rice.\", \"instructions\": [\"Step 1: Wash the rice thoroughly until water runs clear then transfer into a seive till perfectly dry. Then into a pot, add some oil and fry the rice for about 5 minutes\", \"Step 2: Season the liver with salt and a little curry powder. Cook in a pot with a small amount of water for 8 to 10 minutes until just cooked through, then dice into small cubes.\", \"Step 3: Dice carrots and green beans into small uniform cubes for even cooking. Set aside along with the bell peppers.\", \"Step 4: Heat vegetable oil in a large wok or wide pan on high heat. Add minced garlic and ginger and stir fry for 30 seconds until fragrant but not browned.\", \"Step 5: Add diced onions and stir fry for 2 minutes until softened. Add the diced liver and shrimp and stir fry for 2 minutes.\", \"Step 6: Add the carrots, green beans, green peas, and bell peppers to the pan. Stir fry on high heat for 3 minutes until heated through but still slightly crisp.\", \"Step 7: Add the cooled parboiled rice to the pan along with curry powder, thyme, seasoning cubes, soy sauce, and salt. Stir fry vigorously on high heat for 5 to 7 minutes, tossing continuously, until the rice is evenly coated in the yellow curry colour and well combined with all the vegetables and protein. Taste and adjust seasoning, then serve hot.\"], \"match_percentage\": 6.7, \"used_ingredients\": [\"onions\"], \"cook_time_minutes\": 30, \"prep_time_minutes\": 30, \"missing_ingredients\": [\"long grain rice\", \"carrots\", \"green peas\", \"bell peppers(green, yellow, red)\", \"liver\", \"vegetable oil\", \"garlic\", \"ginger\", \"curry powder\", \"thyme\", \"seasoning cubes\", \"soy sauce\", \"salt\", \"chicken stock\"]}, {\"name\": \"Nigerian Jollof Rice\", \"tips\": \"The secret to party jollof is double covering with foil and lid to trap steam, and finishing on high heat for the smoky bottom layer. Never use fresh tomatoes alone — always add tomato paste for depth of colour and flavour.\", \"servings\": 6, \"difficulty\": \"medium\", \"description\": \"Nigerian Jollof Rice is one of the most beloved dishes in West Africa, known for its rich smoky tomato flavour and vibrant orange-red colour. It is a staple at every Nigerian party, celebration, and family gathering. The secret to authentic Jollof Rice is the smoky bottom layer called party jollof which develops from cooking on high heat at the end.\", \"instructions\": [\"Step 1: Blend tomatoes, red bell peppers, long chilli peppers, scotch bonnet, and onions together in a blender until completely smooth with no chunks remaining. Set aside.\", \"Step 2: Wash rice thoroughly in cold water at least 3 times until water runs clear.\", \"Step 3: Heat vegetable oil in a large heavy-bottomed stainless steel or aluminum pot over medium-high heat for 2 minutes. Slice some onions, ginger and garlic paste, curry, thyme, bay leaves  and fry in the oil for 3 minutes.\", \"Step 4: Add tomato paste to the pot and fry with the mix for 3 minutes on medium heat, stirring constantly until the paste darkens slightly from bright red to a deeper reddish brown.\", \"Step 5: Pour the blended pepper mixture with some paprika into the pot. It will sizzle loudly — this is correct. Add in some seasoning cubes and salt. Fry on medium high heat uncovered for 25-30 minutes stirring every 5 minutes until all the water has evaporated, the oil floats on top, and the sauce has darkened to a deep red color. This step is critical — do not rush it.\", \"Step 6: Stir well and taste the sauce should be slightly salty as it will season the rice\", \"Step 7: Add the rice to the pot and stir well to coat every grain with the tomato sauce. Fry on high for like 2 minutes. Then add in chicken stock and some water enough to just cover the rice\", \"Step 8: Cover the pot tightly with foil first then place the lid on top to seal in all the steam. Cook on medium heat for 20 minutes without lifting the lid.\", \"Step 9: After 20 minutes lift the lid and check — rice should be almost fully cooked and liquid mostly absorbed. Stir gently from bottom to top. Cover again and cook on very low heat for 10 more minutes.\", \"Step 10: For the authentic party jollof smoky bottom, add in some cooking butter and sliced onions turn heat to high for the last 3-5 minutes. You will hear a crackling sound from the bottom — this is correct. Remove from heat immediately and leave covered for 5 minutes before serving.\"], \"match_percentage\": 6.2, \"used_ingredients\": [\"onions\"], \"cook_time_minutes\": 70, \"prep_time_minutes\": 20, \"missing_ingredients\": [\"long grain parboiled rice\", \"tomatoes\", \"red bell peppers (tatashe)\", \"long chilli peppers(shombo) \", \"scotch bonnet peppers (ata rodo)\", \"vegetable oil\", \"tomato paste\", \"chicken stock\", \"seasoning cubes\", \"curry powder\", \"thyme\", \"bay leaves\", \"garlic powder\", \"salt\", \"paprika\"]}, {\"name\": \"Nigerian Coleslaw\", \"tips\": \"The combination of mayonnaise and salad cream together, rather than just mayonnaise alone, is what gives Nigerian coleslaw its distinctive tangy sweetness. Always shred the cabbage very finely for the best texture, and let the coleslaw rest in the refrigerator before serving for the best flavour.\", \"servings\": 6, \"difficulty\": \"easy\", \"description\": \"Nigerian Coleslaw is a creamy and slightly sweet shredded cabbage and carrot salad that is a staple side dish at Nigerian parties, often served alongside Jollof Rice and Fried Rice. It differs from Western coleslaw by typically including diced apples, raisins, and a generously sweetened mayonnaise dressing.\", \"instructions\": [\"Step 1: Wash the cabbage thoroughly and shred very finely using a sharp knife or food processor — the cabbage should be cut into thin uniform strips for the best texture.\", \"Step 2: Peel and grate or finely julienne the carrots into thin matchstick pieces, similar in size to the shredded cabbage.\", \"Step 3: In a large bowl combine the shredded cabbage, grated carrots and sweet corn. Toss together gently.\", \"Step 4: In a separate small bowl mix mayonnaise and salad cream together in roughly equal parts, adding sugar to taste for the characteristic Nigerian sweetness, along with a pinch of black pepper and salt.\", \"Step 5: Pour the dressing over the vegetable mixture and toss thoroughly until every piece is well coated in the creamy dressing.\", \"Step 6: Taste and adjust sweetness and seasoning — Nigerian coleslaw is typically sweeter than standard Western coleslaw.\", \"Step 7: Cover and refrigerate for at least 1 hour before serving to allow the flavours to meld and the cabbage to soften slightly. Serve cold alongside Jollof Rice or Fried Rice.\"], \"match_percentage\": 0.0, \"used_ingredients\": [], \"cook_time_minutes\": 0, \"prep_time_minutes\": 25, \"missing_ingredients\": [\"cabbage\", \"carrots\", \"sweet corn\", \"mayonnaise\", \"salad cream\", \"sugar\", \"black pepper\", \"salt\"]}]}','2026-06-21 11:07:31'),('343cbad1-5c0d-46f9-b3e3-df50ed365b1f','[\"flour\", \"sugar\", \"butter\", \"egg\", \"milk\", \"baking powder\"]','english',NULL,'{\"recipes\": [{\"name\": \"Butter Cake\", \"tips\": \"To ensure the cake is moist, do not overmix the batter and do not overbake.\", \"servings\": 4, \"difficulty\": \"easy\", \"description\": \"A classic English dessert, butter cake is a moist and flavorful treat with a rich, buttery taste and a tender crumb.\", \"instructions\": [\"Step 1: Preheat the oven to 350°F (180°C) and grease two 8-inch round cake pans.\", \"Step 2: In a large mixing bowl, whisk together 2 cups of flour and 1 cup of sugar.\", \"Step 3: Add 1/2 cup of softened butter to the bowl and mix.\", \"Step 4: Beat in 2 large eggs.\", \"Step 5: Add 1 cup of milk to the bowl and mix.\", \"Step 6: Divide the batter evenly between the prepared pans and smooth the tops.\"], \"match_percentage\": 100, \"used_ingredients\": [\"flour\", \"sugar\", \"butter\", \"egg\", \"milk\"], \"cook_time_minutes\": 30, \"prep_time_minutes\": 20, \"missing_ingredients\": []}, {\"name\": \"Pancakes\", \"tips\": \"To ensure the pancakes are fluffy, do not overmix the batter and make sure the pan is hot before adding the batter.\", \"servings\": 4, \"difficulty\": \"easy\", \"description\": \"A classic English breakfast food, pancakes are a delicious and fluffy treat with a light, airy texture and a sweet, slightly tangy taste.\", \"instructions\": [\"Step 1: In a large bowl, whisk together 1 cup of flour, 2 tablespoons of sugar, and 1/2 teaspoon of baking powder.\", \"Step 2: In a separate bowl, whisk together 1 cup of milk, 1 large egg, and 2 tablespoons of melted butter.\", \"Step 3: Add the wet ingredients to the dry ingredients and mix.\", \"Step 4: Heat a non-stick pan or griddle over medium heat.\", \"Step 5: Drop the batter by 1/4 cupfuls onto the pan and cook.\", \"Step 6: Flip the pancakes and cook for an additional 1-2 minutes.\"], \"match_percentage\": 100, \"used_ingredients\": [\"flour\", \"sugar\", \"egg\", \"milk\", \"butter\"], \"cook_time_minutes\": 20, \"prep_time_minutes\": 15, \"missing_ingredients\": []}, {\"name\": \"Crepe\", \"tips\": \"To ensure the crepe is thin and delicate, do not overmix the batter and make sure the pan is hot before adding the batter.\", \"servings\": 4, \"difficulty\": \"easy\", \"description\": \"A classic English dessert, crepe is a thin and delicate treat with a light, airy texture and a sweet, slightly tangy taste.\", \"instructions\": [\"Step 1: In a large bowl, whisk together 1 cup of flour, 2 tablespoons of sugar, and 1/2 teaspoon of baking powder.\", \"Step 2: In a separate bowl, whisk together 1 cup of milk, 1 large egg, and 2 tablespoons of melted butter.\", \"Step 3: Add the wet ingredients to the dry ingredients and mix.\", \"Step 4: Heat a non-stick pan or crepe pan over medium heat.\", \"Step 5: Pour a small amount of the batter into the pan and tilt the pan to evenly coat the bottom.\", \"Step 6: Loosen the crepe with a spatula and flip it over.\"], \"match_percentage\": 100, \"used_ingredients\": [\"flour\", \"sugar\", \"egg\", \"milk\", \"butter\"], \"cook_time_minutes\": 20, \"prep_time_minutes\": 15, \"missing_ingredients\": []}, {\"name\": \"Scone\", \"tips\": \"To ensure the scone is flaky, do not overmix the dough and make sure the butter is cold.\", \"servings\": 4, \"difficulty\": \"easy\", \"description\": \"A classic English breakfast food, scone is a delicious and flaky treat with a light, airy texture and a sweet, slightly tangy taste.\", \"instructions\": [\"Step 1: Preheat the oven to 400°F (200°C).\", \"Step 2: In a large bowl, whisk together flour, sugar, and cold butter.\", \"Step 3: Add egg and milk to the bowl and mix.\", \"Step 4: Turn the dough out onto a floured surface and knead.\", \"Step 5: Pat the dough into a circle and cut into wedges.\", \"Step 6: Bake for 15 minutes.\"], \"match_percentage\": 100, \"used_ingredients\": [\"flour\", \"sugar\", \"butter\", \"egg\", \"milk\"], \"cook_time_minutes\": 15, \"prep_time_minutes\": 20, \"missing_ingredients\": []}]}','2026-06-21 10:03:19'),('34559f85-59c3-47a3-be00-51366df4d725','[\"rice\", \"eggs\", \"soy sauce\", \"garlic\", \"ginger\", \"carrots\", \"green onions\", \"vegetable oil\", \"salt\"]','chinese',25,'{\"recipes\": [{\"name\": \"Chinese Fried Rice\", \"servings\": 4, \"difficulty\": \"easy\", \"description\": \"A classic Chinese dish made with rice, eggs, and vegetables\", \"instructions\": [\"Step 1: Heat 2 tablespoons of vegetable oil in a large skillet or wok over medium-high heat for 2 minutes, until the oil starts to shimmer and slightly smoke, indicating it is hot and ready for stir-frying. Add 1 cup of diced carrots and cook for 3 minutes, until they start to soften and turn slightly tender, with a slight caramelized color.\", \"Step 2: Add 1 cup of diced green onions and 2 cloves of minced garlic to the skillet and cook for 2 minutes, until the onions are translucent and the garlic is fragrant, with a slight aroma of sautéed vegetables. Stir constantly to prevent burning.\", \"Step 3: Push the vegetables to one side of the skillet, then add 2 beaten eggs to the other side and scramble them for 2 minutes, until they are cooked through and fluffy, with no visible liquid egg. Use a spatula to break the eggs into small curds.\", \"Step 4: Mix the eggs with the vegetables, then add 2 cups of cooked rice to the skillet, breaking up any clumps with a spatula. Stir-fry the rice with the vegetables and eggs for 5 minutes, until the rice is heated through and starting to brown, with a slight crispy texture at the bottom.\", \"Step 5: Add 1 tablespoon of soy sauce and 1 teaspoon of grated ginger to the rice mixture and stir-fry for 1 minute, until the sauce is well combined and the flavors are balanced, with a savory and slightly sweet aroma. Taste and adjust the seasoning with salt as needed.\", \"Step 6: Transfer the Chinese fried rice to a serving platter and garnish with additional green onions and a sprinkle of soy sauce, if desired. Serve immediately and enjoy the savory and slightly sweet flavors of this classic Chinese dish.\"], \"match_percentage\": 100, \"used_ingredients\": [\"rice\", \"eggs\", \"soy sauce\", \"garlic\", \"ginger\", \"carrots\", \"green onions\", \"vegetable oil\", \"salt\"], \"cook_time_minutes\": 10, \"prep_time_minutes\": 10, \"missing_ingredients\": []}, {\"name\": \"Stir-Fried Carrots and Green Onions\", \"servings\": 4, \"difficulty\": \"easy\", \"description\": \"A simple and flavorful Chinese-inspired dish made with stir-fried carrots and green onions\", \"instructions\": [\"Step 1: Heat 1 tablespoon of vegetable oil in a large skillet or wok over medium heat for 1 minute, until the oil starts to shimmer and slightly smoke, indicating it is hot and ready for stir-frying. Add 1 cup of sliced carrots and cook for 3 minutes, until they start to soften and turn slightly tender, with a slight caramelized color.\", \"Step 2: Add 1 cup of chopped green onions and 1 clove of minced garlic to the skillet and cook for 2 minutes, until the onions are translucent and the garlic is fragrant, with a slight aroma of sautéed vegetables. Stir constantly to prevent burning.\", \"Step 3: Add 1 teaspoon of grated ginger to the skillet and cook for 1 minute, until the ginger is fragrant and slightly caramelized, with a warm and spicy aroma. Stir constantly to prevent burning.\", \"Step 4: Season the carrots and green onions with salt to taste, then stir-fry for an additional 2 minutes, until the vegetables are tender and slightly browned, with a crispy texture at the bottom. Use a spatula to stir and toss the vegetables constantly.\", \"Step 5: Transfer the stir-fried carrots and green onions to a serving platter and garnish with additional green onions, if desired. Serve immediately and enjoy the sweet and savory flavors of this Chinese-inspired dish.\", \"Step 6: Serve the stir-fried carrots and green onions as a side dish or snack, and consider adding other ingredients such as soy sauce or eggs to make the dish more substantial and flavorful.\"], \"match_percentage\": 100, \"used_ingredients\": [\"carrots\", \"green onions\", \"vegetable oil\", \"salt\", \"garlic\", \"ginger\"], \"cook_time_minutes\": 10, \"prep_time_minutes\": 5, \"missing_ingredients\": []}, {\"name\": \"Chinese-Style Fried Eggs\", \"servings\": 4, \"difficulty\": \"easy\", \"description\": \"A simple and flavorful Chinese-inspired dish made with fried eggs\", \"instructions\": [\"Step 1: Heat 1 tablespoon of vegetable oil in a large non-stick skillet over medium heat for 1 minute, until the oil starts to shimmer and slightly smoke, indicating it is hot and ready for frying. Crack 2 eggs into the skillet and cook for 2 minutes, until the whites are set and the yolks are still runny, with a slightly firm texture.\", \"Step 2: Add 1 clove of minced garlic and 1 teaspoon of grated ginger to the skillet and cook for 1 minute, until the garlic and ginger are fragrant and slightly caramelized, with a warm and spicy aroma. Stir constantly to prevent burning.\", \"Step 3: Use a spatula to carefully flip the eggs over and cook for an additional 2 minutes, until the yolks are cooked to desired doneness and the whites are set, with a slightly firm texture. Cook for 1-2 minutes for a runny yolk, 2-3 minutes for a medium yolk, and 3-4 minutes for a fully set yolk.\", \"Step 4: Season the eggs with salt to taste, then use a spatula to carefully remove the eggs from the skillet and place them on a serving platter. Garnish with additional green onions or soy sauce, if desired.\", \"Step 5: Serve the Chinese-style fried eggs immediately and enjoy the savory and slightly sweet flavors of this Chinese-inspired dish. Consider serving with steamed vegetables or rice for a more substantial meal.\", \"Step 6: Experiment with different seasonings and ingredients, such as chili flakes or soy sauce, to add more flavor to the eggs and make the dish more exciting and delicious.\"], \"match_percentage\": 100, \"used_ingredients\": [\"eggs\", \"vegetable oil\", \"salt\", \"garlic\", \"ginger\"], \"cook_time_minutes\": 6, \"prep_time_minutes\": 2, \"missing_ingredients\": []}, {\"name\": \"Carrot and Ginger Frittata\", \"servings\": 4, \"difficulty\": \"easy\", \"description\": \"A delicious and flavorful Chinese-inspired frittata made with carrots, ginger, and eggs\", \"instructions\": [\"Step 1: Heat 1 tablespoon of vegetable oil in a large non-stick skillet over medium heat for 1 minute, until the oil starts to shimmer and slightly smoke, indicating it is hot and ready for sautéing. Add 1 cup of diced carrots and cook for 3 minutes, until they start to soften and turn slightly tender, with a slight caramelized color.\", \"Step 2: Add 1 teaspoon of grated ginger to the skillet and cook for 1 minute, until the ginger is fragrant and slightly caramelized, with a warm and spicy aroma. Stir constantly to prevent burning.\", \"Step 3: In a large bowl, whisk together 4 eggs and a pinch of salt, until the eggs are well combined and slightly frothy, with a smooth and creamy texture. Pour the egg mixture over the carrots and ginger in the skillet.\", \"Step 4: Cook the frittata for 5 minutes, until the edges start to set and the center is still slightly runny, with a slightly firm texture. Use a spatula to gently lift and fold the edges of the frittata towards the center, allowing the uncooked egg to flow to the edges.\", \"Step 5: Continue cooking the frittata for an additional 5-7 minutes, until the eggs are almost set and the frittata is golden brown on the bottom, with a crispy texture. Use a spatula to carefully loosen the edges of the frittata from the skillet.\", \"Step 6: Use a spatula to carefully slide the frittata out of the skillet and onto a serving platter. Garnish with additional green onions or soy sauce, if desired. Serve immediately and enjoy the savory and slightly sweet flavors of this Chinese-inspired dish.\"], \"match_percentage\": 100, \"used_ingredients\": [\"eggs\", \"carrots\", \"ginger\", \"vegetable oil\", \"salt\"], \"cook_time_minutes\": 12, \"prep_time_minutes\": 5, \"missing_ingredients\": []}]}','2026-06-14 17:56:36'),('3cee0bb2-4e64-4883-a7dc-03d23c5fdd01','[\"rice, tomato paste, onions, scotch bonnet peppers\"]','nigerian',NULL,'{\"almost_there\": [], \"can_make_now\": [], \"needs_shopping\": [{\"name\": \"Nigerian Jollof Rice\", \"tips\": \"The secret to party jollof is double covering with foil and lid to trap steam, and finishing on high heat for the smoky bottom layer. Never use fresh tomatoes alone — always add tomato paste for depth of colour and flavour.\", \"servings\": 6, \"difficulty\": \"medium\", \"description\": \"Nigerian Jollof Rice is one of the most beloved dishes in West Africa, known for its rich smoky tomato flavour and vibrant orange-red colour. It is a staple at every Nigerian party, celebration, and family gathering. The secret to authentic Jollof Rice is the smoky bottom layer called party jollof which develops from cooking on high heat at the end.\", \"instructions\": [\"Step 1: Blend tomatoes, red bell peppers, long chilli peppers, scotch bonnet, and onions together in a blender until completely smooth with no chunks remaining. Set aside.\", \"Step 2: Wash rice thoroughly in cold water at least 3 times until water runs clear.\", \"Step 3: Heat vegetable oil in a large heavy-bottomed stainless steel or aluminum pot over medium-high heat for 2 minutes. Slice some onions, ginger and garlic paste, curry, thyme, bay leaves  and fry in the oil for 3 minutes.\", \"Step 4: Add tomato paste to the pot and fry with the mix for 3 minutes on medium heat, stirring constantly until the paste darkens slightly from bright red to a deeper reddish brown.\", \"Step 5: Pour the blended pepper mixture with some paprika into the pot. It will sizzle loudly — this is correct. Add in some seasoning cubes and salt. Fry on medium high heat uncovered for 25-30 minutes stirring every 5 minutes until all the water has evaporated, the oil floats on top, and the sauce has darkened to a deep red color. This step is critical — do not rush it.\", \"Step 6: Stir well and taste the sauce should be slightly salty as it will season the rice\", \"Step 7: Add the rice to the pot and stir well to coat every grain with the tomato sauce. Fry on high for like 2 minutes. Then add in chicken stock and some water enough to just cover the rice\", \"Step 8: Cover the pot tightly with foil first then place the lid on top to seal in all the steam. Cook on medium heat for 20 minutes without lifting the lid.\", \"Step 9: After 20 minutes lift the lid and check — rice should be almost fully cooked and liquid mostly absorbed. Stir gently from bottom to top. Cover again and cook on very low heat for 10 more minutes.\", \"Step 10: For the authentic party jollof smoky bottom, add in some cooking butter and sliced onions turn heat to high for the last 3-5 minutes. You will hear a crackling sound from the bottom — this is correct. Remove from heat immediately and leave covered for 5 minutes before serving.\"], \"match_percentage\": 0.0, \"used_ingredients\": [], \"cook_time_minutes\": 70, \"prep_time_minutes\": 20, \"missing_ingredients\": [\"long grain parboiled rice\", \"tomatoes\", \"red bell peppers (tatashe)\", \"long chilli peppers(shombo) \", \"scotch bonnet peppers (ata rodo)\", \"onions\", \"vegetable oil\", \"tomato paste\", \"chicken stock\", \"seasoning cubes\", \"curry powder\", \"thyme\", \"bay leaves\", \"garlic powder\", \"salt\", \"paprika\"]}, {\"name\": \"Moi Moi\", \"tips\": \"The food processor peeling method is a game changer — it cuts prep time from 30 minutes to 5 minutes. The two most important steps are removing every single bean skin and whisking the paste vigorously to aerate it before adding seasoning. Skipping either step will result in dense heavy Moi Moi. Always fill containers only three quarters full as the paste expands during steaming.\", \"servings\": 8, \"difficulty\": \"medium\", \"description\": \"Moi Moi is a traditional Nigerian steamed bean pudding made from peeled beans blended into a smooth paste. It is a beloved dish across all Nigerian tribes and is served at parties, as a side dish with rice or ogi, or eaten alone as a complete meal. The texture should be firm yet soft and moist inside with a rich savoury flavour.\", \"instructions\": [\"Step 1: There are two ways to peel the beans. Traditional method: Pour beans into a bowl and soak in cold water for 30 minutes until the skins begin to loosen and soften, then rub vigorously between both palms under running water until all skins float off. Quick method: Pour dry beans into a food processor with some water and pulse for 30 to 45 seconds — the food processor will crack and loosen the skins without grinding the beans. Pour the pulsed beans into a large bowl of water, the skins will float to the top — skim them off and drain. Repeat until all skins are removed. The quick method takes 5 minutes instead of 30.\", \"Step 2: Rinse the peeled beans thoroughly in clean water two to three times to remove any remaining skin fragments. The beans should be completely white with no dark skin remaining — any leftover skin will make the Moi Moi rough and bitter.\", \"Step 3: Place the peeled beans directly into the blender together with the scotch bonnet peppers, red bell pepper, onions, one raw egg, and a very small amount of water — just enough to get the blender moving. Blend everything together on high speed for 3 minutes until the paste is completely smooth with absolutely no grainy texture. Blending the peppers and egg together with the beans at this stage gives the Moi Moi its full flavour and colour from the inside.\", \"Step 4: Pour the blended paste into a large bowl. Add seasoning cubes, vegetable oil, and salt. Mix everything together thoroughly until well combined. Taste and adjust seasoning — it should be well seasoned and slightly peppery.\", \"Step 5: Using a wooden spoon or electric hand mixer, whisk the paste vigorously for 5 minutes until it becomes fluffy, lighter in colour, and increases slightly in volume. This aerates the paste and gives Moi Moi its soft moist texture when steamed.\", \"Step 6: Break the mackerel fish into medium sized chunks and slice your boiled eggs and set aside. Grease foil containers or moi moi leaves generously with vegetable oil on the inside so the moi moi does not stick.\", \"Step 7: Pour the bean paste mixture into each container filling only three quarters full. Drop pieces of fish directly into the paste in each container alongside the sliced eggs  — the fish sits inside the moi moi not on top. Press down lightly so the fish is submerged in the paste.\", \"Step 8: Seal each foil container tightly by folding the edges over securely. No steam should be able to escape during cooking.\", \"Step 9: Place a trivet or folded foil at the bottom of a large pot to prevent direct heat contact. Arrange the sealed moi moi containers in the pot and add water to reach halfway up the sides of the containers.\", \"Step 10: Cover the pot tightly and steam on medium heat for 45 to 60 minutes. Check water level every 15 minutes and add more hot water if needed — never let the pot run dry. Moi Moi is ready when it feels firm when pressed gently and pulls away cleanly from the container when opened.\"], \"match_percentage\": 0.0, \"used_ingredients\": [], \"cook_time_minutes\": 60, \"prep_time_minutes\": 40, \"missing_ingredients\": [\"beans\", \"onions\", \"scotch bonnet peppers\", \"long chilli pepper (shombo)\", \"crayfish\", \"vegetable oil\", \"seasoning cubes\", \"salt\", \"eggs\", \"fish (preferably mackerel fish)\", \"water\"]}, {\"name\": \"Efo Riro\", \"tips\": \"The most important step is frying the pepper base completely dry until the oil floats on top before adding any meat or stock. This is what separates a rich deeply flavoured Efo Riro from a watery one. Also add the vegetables at the very last minute and cook for 2 minutes only — overcooked vegetables will turn dark and lose their flavour.\", \"servings\": 6, \"difficulty\": \"medium\", \"description\": \"Efo Riro is a rich Yoruba vegetable soup made with tatashe and ata rodo as the pepper base, assorted meats, and leafy green vegetables. The name means stirred leafy vegetable in Yoruba. It is one of the most flavourful Nigerian soups with a vibrant green and red colour from the vegetables and pepper base. It is served with amala, eba, pounded yam, or rice.\", \"instructions\": [\"Step 1: Wash and season assorted meat, pomo, and stockfish with onions, seasoning cubes, and salt. Cook on medium heat for 20 to 30 minutes until very tender. Set aside with the stock.\", \"Step 2: Blend tatashe and scotch bonnet peppers together into a smooth paste. Do not add water — the peppers have enough natural liquid. Set aside.\", \"Step 3: Wash the efo tete or spinach thoroughly, shred into medium sized pieces by hand, and set aside in a colander to drain excess water.\", \"Step 4: Heat palm oil in a large pot on medium-high heat for 2 minutes. Slice onions and fry in the palm oil for 3 minutes until golden and fragrant.\", \"Step 5: Add the blended tatashe and scotch bonnet pepper mixture to the pot. It will sizzle loudly in the hot oil — this is correct. Fry on high heat for 10 to 20 minutes stirring every 3 minutes until all the water has completely evaporated, the oil floats on top, and the pepper sauce has darkened and thickened. This step gives Efo Riro its deep rich flavour.\", \"Step 6: Add iru (locust beans) and ground crayfish and stir into the pepper sauce. Fry for 2 more minutes until the iru is fragrant.\", \"Step 7: Add the cooked assorted meat, stockfish, dried fish, and a ladle of the meat stock. Stir everything together and cook on medium heat for 10 minutes until the meat is well coated in the sauce.\", \"Step 8: Add the shredded efo tete or spinach to the pot and stir into the sauce. Cook for exactly 2 minutes only on medium heat — the vegetables should wilt into the soup but remain bright green and not soggy. Taste, adjust seasoning, and remove from heat immediately. Serve with amala, eba, or pounded yam.\"], \"match_percentage\": 0.0, \"used_ingredients\": [], \"cook_time_minutes\": 75, \"prep_time_minutes\": 25, \"missing_ingredients\": [\"vgetables African spinach or ugwu\", \"tatashe (red bell pepper)\", \"scotch bonnet peppers (ata rodo)\", \"onions\", \"palm oil\", \"assorted meat (beef, tripe, shaki, pomo)\", \"stockfish\", \"dried fish\", \"crayfish\", \"iru (locust beans)\", \"seasoning cubes\", \"salt\"]}, {\"name\": \"Egusi Soup Yoruba Style\", \"tips\": \"The secret to Yoruba egusi is frying the egusi completely dry in palm oil before adding any liquid. Never add water or stock to the egusi while frying — it must fry and toast in the oil until golden. Also never add tomatoes to Yoruba egusi soup — that changes the flavour profile completely.\", \"servings\": 6, \"difficulty\": \"medium\", \"description\": \"Egusi Soup Yoruba style is a rich and hearty Nigerian soup made with ground melon seeds fried directly in palm oil before any liquid is added. Unlike Igbo style egusi which is added raw, Yoruba style fries the egusi first until golden and nutty giving it a deeper richer flavour. It is served with amala, eba, or pounded yam.\", \"instructions\": [\"Step 1: Wash and season assorted meat and stockfish with onions, seasoning cubes, and salt. Cook in a pot on medium heat for 15 to 20 minutes until tender. Set aside with the stock.\", \"Step 2: Blend scotch bonnet peppers, tatashe, and half the onions together into a smooth paste. Set aside.\", \"Step 3: Heat palm oil in a large pot on medium heat for 2 minutes until melted and hot but not bleached. Chop the remaining onions and fry in the palm oil for 3 minutes until soft and translucent.\", \"Step 4: Add the ground egusi to the palm oil and stir immediately to combine. Fry the egusi in the palm oil on medium heat for 8 to 10 minutes stirring constantly until the egusi turns golden, smells nutty, and pulls away from the sides of the pot. Do not add any liquid at this stage — dry frying is the key to Yoruba egusi.\", \"Step 5: Add the blended pepper mixture to the fried egusi and stir well to combine. Fry together for another 10 minutes on medium heat stirring every 2 minutes until the pepper is cooked and oil begins to float on the surface.\", \"Step 6: Add the cooked meat, stockfish, dried fish, meat stock, ground crayfish, iru, and seasoning cubes. Stir everything together and add a small amount of water if the soup is too thick. Cook on medium heat for 15 minutes until all the flavours come together.\", \"Step 7: Taste and adjust salt and seasoning. The soup should be rich, thick, and deeply flavoured at this point.\", \"Step 8: Add shredded spinach or efo tete and stir into the soup. Cook for exactly 2 minutes only — overcooking the vegetables will make them lose their colour and become soggy. Remove from heat and serve immediately with amala, eba, or pounded yam.\"], \"match_percentage\": 0.0, \"used_ingredients\": [], \"cook_time_minutes\": 70, \"prep_time_minutes\": 20, \"missing_ingredients\": [\"ground egusi (melon seeds)\", \"palm oil\", \"assorted meat (beef, tripe, shaki)\", \"stockfish\", \"dried fish\", \"onions\", \"scotch bonnet peppers\", \"tatashe (red bell pepper)\", \"crayfish\", \"iru (locust beans)\", \"spinach, efo tete or ugwu\", \"seasoning cubes\", \"salt\"]}, {\"name\": \"Nigerian Pepper Soup\", \"tips\": \"The quality of your pepper soup spice mix makes or breaks this dish. Use freshly ground spices if possible — uda (country onion), ehuru (calabash nutmeg), and uziza seeds ground together give the most authentic flavour. Never cover the pot fully while cooking pepper soup — leave it slightly open so the broth reduces and concentrates.\", \"servings\": 4, \"difficulty\": \"easy\", \"description\": \"Nigerian Pepper Soup is a light, intensely spiced broth made with meat or fish and a unique blend of pepper soup spices. It is served at every Nigerian gathering, used as a remedy for colds and fever, and eaten as a starter or main dish. The broth is thin but deeply flavoured with a distinctive warming heat that comes from the special pepper soup spice blend.\", \"instructions\": [\"Step 1: Wash the meat thoroughly and cut into medium sized pieces. Season with onions, seasoning cubes, and salt. Do not add water yet — allow the meat to cook in its own juices first.\", \"Step 2: Place the seasoned meat in a pot on medium heat and cook dry for 10 minutes stirring occasionally until the meat releases its juices and begins to brown slightly on the outside.\", \"Step 3: Add enough water to cover the meat completely. Bring to a boil on high heat then reduce to medium heat. Cook for 25 to 30 minutes for goat meat or 15 minutes for chicken until the meat is tender but not falling off the bone.\", \"Step 4: Add the pepper soup spice mix, ground crayfish, and blended or roughly crushed scotch bonnet peppers. Stir well and taste — the broth should be well seasoned and spicy at this point. Add more seasoning cubes and salt if needed.\", \"Step 5: Cook on medium heat for another 15 minutes until the spices have fully infused into the broth and the liquid has reduced slightly. The broth should be a light golden brown colour and smell intensely aromatic.\", \"Step 6: Tear utazi leaves into small pieces and add to the pot — utazi adds a slight bitterness that balances the heat. Add uziza leaves whole or roughly torn. Cook for 3 minutes only.\", \"Step 7: Taste one final time and adjust salt and pepper. The pepper soup should be very hot and spicy, lightly bitter from the utazi, and deeply aromatic from the spice blend. Serve hot in deep bowls with sliced onions on top and agidi or white rice on the side.\"], \"match_percentage\": 0.0, \"used_ingredients\": [], \"cook_time_minutes\": 55, \"prep_time_minutes\": 15, \"missing_ingredients\": [\"goat meat or chicken or catfish\", \"pepper soup spice mix\", \"scotch bonnet peppers\", \"onions\", \"crayfish\", \"uziza leaves\", \"utazi leaves\", \"seasoning cubes\", \"salt\", \"water\"]}, {\"name\": \"Akara\", \"tips\": \"Whisking the bean paste until very fluffy is the secret to light soft akara — never skip this step. Also make sure the oil is very hot before adding the paste otherwise the akara will absorb too much oil and become greasy. Wet your spoon with oil before scooping each portion to help the paste slide off cleanly into the oil.\", \"servings\": 4, \"difficulty\": \"medium\", \"description\": \"Akara is a traditional Yoruba deep fried bean cake made from peeled black eyed beans blended into a smooth aerated paste and fried in hot oil until crispy on the outside and soft inside. It is a quintessential Nigerian breakfast food sold by roadside vendors across the country and best eaten hot with ogi (pap) or bread.\", \"instructions\": [\"Step 1: Peel the beans using one of two methods. Traditional method: Soak beans in cold water for 30 minutes then rub between palms under running water until all skins float off and are drained away. Quick method: Pulse beans and water  in a food processor for 30 seconds to crack and loosen skins, pour into a bowl of water, skim off floating skins, and drain. Rinse peeled beans two to three times in clean water.\", \"Step 2: Place the peeled beans alongside the peppers and onions in a blender with a very small amount of water — just enough to move the blender. Blend on high speed for 3 minutes until the paste is completely smooth and thick. The paste must be thick not watery — too much water will make flat oily akara.\", \"Step 3: Pour the blended bean paste into a large bowl. Using a wooden spoon or electric hand mixer whisk the paste vigorously for 5 to 7 minutes until it becomes very fluffy, lighter in colour, and almost doubles in volume. This is the most important step — the air you whisk in is what makes akara light and fluffy inside.\", \"Step 4: Add some salt and seasoning cubes to the whisked paste. Fold gently into the paste without deflating it. Taste and adjust seasoning.\", \"Step 5: Pour enough vegetable oil into a deep wide pan to allow the akara to float — at least 3 inches deep. Heat on medium-high heat for 2 to 3 minutes until hot. Test the oil by dropping a tiny bit of paste in — it should rise immediately to the surface and sizzle vigorously. If it sinks the oil is not hot enough.\", \"Step 6: Wet your tablespoon with oil and scoop portions of the paste into the hot oil one at a time. Do not overcrowd the pan — leave space between each akara so they cook evenly and stay round.\", \"Step 7: Fry on medium heat for 3 to 4 minutes until the bottom is deep golden brown, then flip carefully with a slotted spoon or skewer and fry the other side for 2 to 3 minutes until evenly golden brown and crispy all over.\", \"Step 8: Remove with a slotted spoon and drain on paper towels to absorb excess oil. Serve immediately while hot and crispy alongside ogi (pap) or as a breakfast snack.\"], \"match_percentage\": 0.0, \"used_ingredients\": [], \"cook_time_minutes\": 20, \"prep_time_minutes\": 30, \"missing_ingredients\": [\"black eyed beans\", \"onions\", \"scotch bonnet peppers\", \"long chilli peppers(shombo)\", \"seasoning cubes\", \"salt\", \"vegetable oil for deep frying\"]}, {\"name\": \"Ewa Agoyin\", \"tips\": \"The two secrets to authentic Ewa Agoyin are cooking the beans with a lot of onions until completely mashable with no whole beans remaining, and making the Agoyin stew with only dried peppers not fresh ones. Fresh peppers will not give the deep dark colour and concentrated flavour that makes Agoyin stew unique. The stew must be dark, dry, and almost burnt looking — that is correct.\", \"servings\": 4, \"difficulty\": \"medium\", \"description\": \"Ewa Agoyin is a popular Yoruba street food originally brought to Nigeria by Beninese traders, consisting of soft completely mashed honey beans or black eyed beans served with a deeply dark and spicy Agoyin stew made from dried red peppers and palm oil. It is a beloved Lagos breakfast food sold by roadside vendors and eaten with agege bread.\", \"instructions\": [\"Step 1: Wash the beans thoroughly then cover the beans with fresh water and cook on high heat until boiling, then reduce to medium heat. Cook for 45 to 60 minutes until the beans are extremely soft — they should mash completely between your fingers with no resistance. Add more water as needed during cooking to prevent burning.\", \"Step 2: Once the beans are very soft, use a wooden spoon or potato masher to mash them completely in the pot until no whole beans remain. The consistency should be thick and porridge-like. Season with salt, stir well, and set aside.\", \"Step 4: While the beans cook prepare the Agoyin stew. Rehydrate the dried red peppers and dried chilli peppers by soaking in hot water for 20 minutes until soft. Drain and blend alongside some onions and ginger into a rough paste — not completely smooth, leave some texture.\", \"Step 5: Heat palm oil in a separate pot on medium heat until hot. Slice onions into thin rings and fry in the palm oil for 10 minutes on medium-low heat, stirring constantly until the onions are very dark brown and almost caramelised — this dark onion is essential to the Agoyin stew flavour.\", \"Step 6: Add the blended dried pepper mixture to the dark onions and palm oil. Stir well and fry on medium heat for 20 to 25 minutes stirring every 3 minutes until all moisture evaporates, the stew becomes very dark, thick, and dry, and the oil floats on top. The stew should be almost black in colour — this is correct.\", \"Step 7: Add seasoning cubes and salt to the stew. Stir well and cook for 5 more minutes. The finished Agoyin stew should be very dark, very dry, very spicy, and intensely flavoured.\", \"Step 8: Serve the mashed beans in a bowl and pour the dark Agoyin stew generously on top. Eat with agege bread, fried plantain, or on its own.\"], \"match_percentage\": 0.0, \"used_ingredients\": [], \"cook_time_minutes\": 90, \"prep_time_minutes\": 20, \"missing_ingredients\": [\"beans\", \"dried red peppers (tatashe)\", \"dried long chilli bonnet peppers(shombo)\", \"onions\", \"palm oil\", \"crayfish\", \"seasoning cubes\", \"salt\", \"water\"]}, {\"name\": \"Asun\", \"tips\": \"Grilling or smoking the goat meat after boiling is non-negotiable for authentic Asun — without the charred smoky exterior the dish is just peppered goat meat not Asun. Use goat meat with the skin on for the best texture and flavour. The pepper sauce should have chunky sliced peppers not a blended smooth sauce.\", \"servings\": 4, \"difficulty\": \"medium\", \"description\": \"Asun is a popular Yoruba delicacy of smoked or roasted goat meat cut into small pieces and tossed in a fiery pepper and onion sauce. It originates from Ondo State in Yorubaland and is now one of the most popular Nigerian party small chops and appetisers served across the country. The goat meat is first smoked or roasted to give it a distinctive charred flavour before being peppered.\", \"instructions\": [\"Step 1: Wash the goat meat thoroughly — authentic Asun uses goat meat with the skin on as the skin adds texture and flavour. Cut into medium sized chunks. Season with seasoning cubes, curry powder, thyme, ginger garlic paste and salt.\", \"Step 2: Cook the seasoned goat meat in a pot with a small amount of water on medium heat for 20 to 25 minutes until tender but not falling apart.\", \"Step 3: Remove the cooked goat meat and place directly on a grill, open flame, or in a very hot oven at 220 degrees Celsius. Grill or roast for 15 to 20 minutes turning occasionally until the outside is charred and smoky and the skin is slightly crispy. The charring is essential for authentic Asun flavour.\", \"Step 4: Remove from the grill and cut into smaller bite sized pieces while still hot. Set aside.\", \"Step 5: Slice scotch bonnet peppers, green bell pepper, red bell pepper, and onions into thin strips. The peppers should be sliced not blended, a food processor can be used as well — the chunky pepper pieces are characteristic of Asun.\", \"Step 6: Heat vegetable oil in a wide pan on medium heat. Add the sliced onions and fry for 2 minutes until slightly softened.\", \"Step 7: Add all the sliced peppers to the pan and stir fry on high heat for 3 to 4 minutes — the peppers should be cooked but still have a slight crunch. Do not overcook the peppers into mush.\", \"Step 8: Add the grilled goat meat pieces to the pan and toss vigorously with the peppers for 3 minutes on high heat until the meat is well coated in the pepper mixture and everything is sizzling hot. Taste and adjust seasoning. Serve immediately as a party appetiser or small chop.\"], \"match_percentage\": 0.0, \"used_ingredients\": [], \"cook_time_minutes\": 60, \"prep_time_minutes\": 20, \"missing_ingredients\": [\"goat meat (skin on)\", \"scotch bonnet peppers\", \"green bell pepper\", \"red bell pepper (tatashe)\", \"onions\", \"vegetable oil\", \"seasoning cubes\", \"curry powder\", \"thyme\", \"salt\", \"ginger garlic paste\"]}, {\"name\": \"Ayamase (Ofada Stew)\", \"tips\": \"Bleaching the palm oil is absolutely non-negotiable for authentic Ayamase. Only use green peppers and unripe tatashe — no red peppers at all. The more assorted meats you use the richer and more authentic the stew will be.\", \"servings\": 6, \"difficulty\": \"hard\", \"description\": \"Ayamase also known as Ofada Stew or Designer Stew is a rich and intensely flavoured Yoruba stew made exclusively with green peppers and unripe tatashe giving it its distinctive green colour. It is traditionally served with Ofada rice and the stew is made with bleached palm oil and loaded with assorted meats making it one of the most indulgent Nigerian dishes.\", \"instructions\": [\"Step 1: Wash and season all assorted meats with onions, seasoning cubes, ginger garlic paste and salt. Cook in a pot on medium heat for 25 to 35 minutes until very tender. Fry the cooked meats in a small amount of oil until lightly browned on the outside for extra flavour. Set aside with the stock.\", \"Step 2: Blend green bell peppers, unripe green tatashe, green scotch bonnet peppers, and onions together into a coarse paste — do not blend completely smooth, leave some texture. The stew must use only green peppers and unripe tatashe — never red peppers or ripe tatashe as this completely changes the dish.\", \"Step 3: Bleach the palm oil by heating it in a pot on high heat with the lid on for 10 to 15 minutes until the oil turns from orange-red to a pale golden yellow colour and begins to smoke lightly. Remove from heat and allow to cool slightly. Bleached palm oil is essential for authentic Ayamase.\", \"Step 4: Return the bleached palm oil to medium heat. Add sliced onions with some ginger garlic paste and fry for 3 minutes until soft and slightly golden.\", \"Step 5: Pour the blended green pepper mixture into the bleached palm oil. It will sizzle vigorously stir immediately. Fry on high heat for 15 to 20 minutes stirring every 3 to 4 minutes until all the water has completely evaporated, the oil floats on top, and the pepper sauce is cooked down and thick.\", \"Step 6: Add iru (locust beans) and ground crayfish to the cooked pepper base and stir well. Fry for 3 more minutes until the iru is fragrant and well incorporated.\", \"Step 7: Add all the assorted meats and a ladle of the meat stock. Stir everything together to coat the meat in the green pepper sauce. Cook on medium heat for 10 minutes until the meat is well flavoured and the stew is thick and rich.\", \"Step 8: Taste and adjust seasoning. The finished Ayamase should be dark olive green, thick, intensely flavoured, and very rich with assorted meats. Serve with Ofada rice.\"], \"match_percentage\": 0.0, \"used_ingredients\": [], \"cook_time_minutes\": 90, \"prep_time_minutes\": 25, \"missing_ingredients\": [\"green bell peppers\", \"unripe tatashe (green tatashe)\", \"green scotch bonnet peppers\", \"onions\", \"palm oil\", \"assorted meat (beef, tripe, shaki, pomo, liver)\", \"crayfish\", \"iru (locust beans)\", \"seasoning cubes\", \"ginger and garlic paste\", \"salt\"]}, {\"name\": \"Ikokore\", \"tips\": \"Use water yam specifically not white yam or cocoyam. Do not rinse the grated yam before adding to the pot as the natural starch thickens the broth and holds the dumplings together.\", \"servings\": 4, \"difficulty\": \"medium\", \"description\": \"Ikokore is a traditional Ijebu Yoruba dish made from grated water yam cooked in a rich pepper soup or tomato base with assorted fish and seafood. The grated water yam forms thick irregular dumplings in the broth giving the dish its characteristic texture. It is a beloved dish in Ogun State and across Yorubaland.\", \"instructions\": [\"Step 1: Peel the water yam and grate on the coarse side of a grater into a bowl. Do not rinse the grated yam — the natural starch is needed to hold the dumplings together. Season the grated yam lightly with salt and set aside.\", \"Step 2: Blend scotch bonnet peppers, long chilli peppers, and onions together into a smooth paste.\", \"Step 3: Heat palm oil in a large pot on medium heat. Add iru and fry for 1 minute until fragrant. Add the blended pepper mixture and fry for 15 minutes until cooked and oil floats on top.\", \"Step 4: Add enough meat stock to the pot . Add ground crayfish, dried fish, smoked fish, assorted meat, seasoning cubes, and salt. Bring to a boil on high heat.\", \"Step 5: Using a tablespoon or your hand, scoop portions of the grated water yam and drop them one by one into the boiling broth. Do not stir immediately — allow the yam dumplings to set for 3 minutes before stirring gently.\", \"Step 6: Cook on medium heat for 15 to 20 minutes stirring gently occasionally until the yam dumplings are fully cooked and the broth has thickened, adjust seasoning, and serve hot.\"], \"match_percentage\": 0.0, \"used_ingredients\": [], \"cook_time_minutes\": 50, \"prep_time_minutes\": 25, \"missing_ingredients\": [\"water yam (isu ewura)\", \"dried fish\", \"assorted meat\", \"smoked fish\", \"palm oil\", \"crayfish\", \"scotch bonnet peppers\", \"long chilli peppers\", \"onions\", \"iru (locust beans)\", \"seasoning cubes\", \"salt\", \"water\"]}, {\"name\": \"Asaro (Yam Porridge)\", \"tips\": \"Gentle stirring lets some yam break down to thicken the sauce naturally without becoming completely mashed.\", \"servings\": 4, \"difficulty\": \"easy\", \"description\": \"Asaro is a beloved traditional Yoruba yam porridge made by cooking yam chunks directly in a rich tomato and pepper sauce until the yam softens and thickens the entire dish into a hearty one-pot meal.\", \"instructions\": [\"Step 1: Peel the yam and cut into medium sized chunks. Wash thoroughly.\", \"Step 2: Blend onions, tatashe, and scotch bonnet peppers together into a smooth paste.\", \"Step 3: Place the yam chunks in a pot with the blended pepper mixture, sliced onions, palm oil, and enough water to just cover the yam.\", \"Step 4: Bring to a boil then reduce to medium heat. Cook for 20 to 25 minutes, stirring occasionally, until the yam softens and breaks down at the edges.\", \"Step 5: Add ground crayfish, flaked fish, seasoning cubes, and salt. Stir gently.\", \"Step 6: Continue cooking on medium-low heat for 8 to 10 minutes until thick and stew-like.\", \"Step 7: Taste and adjust seasoning. Serve hot on its own.\"], \"match_percentage\": 0.0, \"used_ingredients\": [], \"cook_time_minutes\": 40, \"prep_time_minutes\": 15, \"missing_ingredients\": [\"yam (white yam)\", \"tomatoes\", \"tatashe (red bell pepper)\", \"scotch bonnet peppers\", \"onions\", \"palm oil\", \"crayfish\", \"smoked fish or dried fish\", \"seasoning cubes\", \"salt\", \"water\"]}, {\"name\": \"Nigerian Fried Rice\", \"tips\": \"Always cook on high heat when frying the rice and vegetables together to prevent everything from steaming and becoming soggy instead of stir-fried.\", \"servings\": 6, \"difficulty\": \"medium\", \"description\": \"Nigerian Fried Rice is a colourful and flavourful party staple made with parboiled rice stir-fried with mixed vegetables, liver, and a distinct curry seasoning. Unlike Chinese fried rice, the Nigerian version has a unique orange-yellow hue from curry powder and is loaded with vegetables, making it one of the most popular dishes at Nigerian celebrations alongside Jollof Rice.\", \"instructions\": [\"Step 1: Wash the rice thoroughly until water runs clear then transfer into a seive till perfectly dry. Then into a pot, add some oil and fry the rice for about 5 minutes\", \"Step 2: Season the liver with salt and a little curry powder. Cook in a pot with a small amount of water for 8 to 10 minutes until just cooked through, then dice into small cubes.\", \"Step 3: Dice carrots and green beans into small uniform cubes for even cooking. Set aside along with the bell peppers.\", \"Step 4: Heat vegetable oil in a large wok or wide pan on high heat. Add minced garlic and ginger and stir fry for 30 seconds until fragrant but not browned.\", \"Step 5: Add diced onions and stir fry for 2 minutes until softened. Add the diced liver and shrimp and stir fry for 2 minutes.\", \"Step 6: Add the carrots, green beans, green peas, and bell peppers to the pan. Stir fry on high heat for 3 minutes until heated through but still slightly crisp.\", \"Step 7: Add the cooled parboiled rice to the pan along with curry powder, thyme, seasoning cubes, soy sauce, and salt. Stir fry vigorously on high heat for 5 to 7 minutes, tossing continuously, until the rice is evenly coated in the yellow curry colour and well combined with all the vegetables and protein. Taste and adjust seasoning, then serve hot.\"], \"match_percentage\": 0.0, \"used_ingredients\": [], \"cook_time_minutes\": 30, \"prep_time_minutes\": 30, \"missing_ingredients\": [\"long grain rice\", \"carrots\", \"green peas\", \"bell peppers(green, yellow, red)\", \"liver\", \"vegetable oil\", \"onions\", \"garlic\", \"ginger\", \"curry powder\", \"thyme\", \"seasoning cubes\", \"soy sauce\", \"salt\", \"chicken stock\"]}, {\"name\": \"Nigerian Coleslaw\", \"tips\": \"The combination of mayonnaise and salad cream together, rather than just mayonnaise alone, is what gives Nigerian coleslaw its distinctive tangy sweetness. Always shred the cabbage very finely for the best texture, and let the coleslaw rest in the refrigerator before serving for the best flavour.\", \"servings\": 6, \"difficulty\": \"easy\", \"description\": \"Nigerian Coleslaw is a creamy and slightly sweet shredded cabbage and carrot salad that is a staple side dish at Nigerian parties, often served alongside Jollof Rice and Fried Rice. It differs from Western coleslaw by typically including diced apples, raisins, and a generously sweetened mayonnaise dressing.\", \"instructions\": [\"Step 1: Wash the cabbage thoroughly and shred very finely using a sharp knife or food processor — the cabbage should be cut into thin uniform strips for the best texture.\", \"Step 2: Peel and grate or finely julienne the carrots into thin matchstick pieces, similar in size to the shredded cabbage.\", \"Step 3: In a large bowl combine the shredded cabbage, grated carrots and sweet corn. Toss together gently.\", \"Step 4: In a separate small bowl mix mayonnaise and salad cream together in roughly equal parts, adding sugar to taste for the characteristic Nigerian sweetness, along with a pinch of black pepper and salt.\", \"Step 5: Pour the dressing over the vegetable mixture and toss thoroughly until every piece is well coated in the creamy dressing.\", \"Step 6: Taste and adjust sweetness and seasoning — Nigerian coleslaw is typically sweeter than standard Western coleslaw.\", \"Step 7: Cover and refrigerate for at least 1 hour before serving to allow the flavours to meld and the cabbage to soften slightly. Serve cold alongside Jollof Rice or Fried Rice.\"], \"match_percentage\": 0.0, \"used_ingredients\": [], \"cook_time_minutes\": 0, \"prep_time_minutes\": 25, \"missing_ingredients\": [\"cabbage\", \"carrots\", \"sweet corn\", \"mayonnaise\", \"salad cream\", \"sugar\", \"black pepper\", \"salt\"]}, {\"name\": \"Banga Stew\", \"tips\": \"The key difference between Banga Soup and Banga Stew is the reduction time — cook the stew version longer uncovered to achieve a thicker consistency that coats rice or yam well rather than the more liquid soup form.\", \"servings\": 5, \"difficulty\": \"hard\", \"description\": \"Banga Stew is a thick, deeply flavoured Igbo stew made from concentrated palm fruit extract, prepared similarly to Banga Soup but cooked down to a thicker consistency more like a stew than a soup. It is rich, nutty, and aromatic, traditionally seasoned with banga spices, and served with white rice, boiled yam, or plantain.\", \"instructions\": [\"Step 1: If using fresh palm fruit, boil for 20 to 30 minutes until soft, then pound to separate pulp from nuts and squeeze with warm water to extract the thick orange juice. Strain through a sieve to remove fibres. If using canned concentrate, dilute according to package instructions.\", \"Step 2: Pour the palm fruit extract into a pot and bring to a boil on high heat, then reduce to medium heat and simmer for 15 to 20 minutes until the oil begins to separate and rise to the surface.\", \"Step 3: Season the assorted meat with onions, seasoning cubes, and salt. Cook separately on medium heat for 30 minutes until tender. Add the cooked meat and stock to the palm fruit base.\", \"Step 4: Add the banga spice mix to the pot and simmer for 15 minutes to allow the spices to infuse fully into the base.\", \"Step 5: Add dried fish, ground crayfish, sliced scotch bonnet peppers, and seasoning cubes. Stir well and continue cooking on medium heat, allowing the liquid to reduce and thicken for 20 to 25 minutes — unlike Banga Soup this should reduce further into a thicker stew-like consistency.\", \"Step 6: Add the fresh fish pieces and cook gently for 8 to 10 minutes until just cooked through, stirring carefully to avoid breaking the fish apart.\", \"Step 7: Continue simmering uncovered for an additional 10 minutes, stirring occasionally, until the stew has thickened noticeably and the oil is clearly visible on the surface.\", \"Step 8: Remove the oburunbebe stick before serving. Taste and adjust seasoning. Serve hot with white rice, boiled yam, or plantain.\"], \"match_percentage\": 0.0, \"used_ingredients\": [], \"cook_time_minutes\": 80, \"prep_time_minutes\": 30, \"missing_ingredients\": [\"fresh palm fruit (or canned banga concentrate)\", \"assorted meat (beef, tripe)\", \"dried fish\", \"fresh fish\", \"banga spice mix (oburunbebe stick, dried bitter leaf)\", \"onions\", \"scotch bonnet peppers\", \"crayfish\", \"seasoning cubes\", \"salt\", \"water\"]}, {\"name\": \"Abacha\", \"tips\": \"Always soak in cold water not hot. Potash is essential for emulsifying the palm oil into the dressing.\", \"servings\": 4, \"difficulty\": \"medium\", \"description\": \"Abacha is a traditional Igbo cold salad made from dried shredded cassava rehydrated and tossed in an emulsified palm oil and potash dressing with ugba, utazi leaves, garden eggs, crayfish, and assorted proteins.\", \"instructions\": [\"Step 1: Soak the dried abacha in cold water for 10 to 15 minutes until softened. Drain thoroughly.\", \"Step 2: Dissolve potash in 3 tablespoons of water and strain through a fine sieve.\", \"Step 3: Pour palm oil into a bowl. Add the potash solution gradually while stirring vigorously until emulsified and bright yellow.\", \"Step 4: Add ground crayfish, sliced scotch bonnet peppers, sliced onions, seasoning cubes, and salt to the emulsion.\", \"Step 5: Add the drained abacha and toss thoroughly until coated.\", \"Step 6: Add ugba, sliced garden eggs, shredded utazi, flaked fish, and sliced ponmo. Toss together gently.\", \"Step 7: Taste and adjust seasoning.\", \"Step 8: Garnish with utazi and onion rings. Serve at room temperature.\"], \"match_percentage\": 0.0, \"used_ingredients\": [], \"cook_time_minutes\": 0, \"prep_time_minutes\": 20, \"missing_ingredients\": [\"abacha (dried shredded cassava)\", \"ugba (oil bean seeds)\", \"palm oil\", \"potash (kaun)\", \"utazi leaves\", \"garden eggs\", \"crayfish\", \"onions\", \"scotch bonnet peppers\", \"seasoning cubes\", \"salt\", \"dried fish or stockfish\", \"ponmo (cow skin)\"]}, {\"name\": \"Ofe Owerri\", \"tips\": \"Use as many different types of meat and fish as you can for the most authentic version. The combination of ugu and uziza leaves together distinguishes this from Edikang Ikong.\", \"servings\": 6, \"difficulty\": \"hard\", \"description\": \"Ofe Owerri is a luxurious traditional Igbo vegetable soup from Owerri in Imo State, known for being loaded with multiple types of meat, fish, and a generous mix of vegetables, traditionally served at important ceremonies.\", \"instructions\": [\"Step 1: Wash and season all assorted meats and stockfish with onions, seasoning cubes, and salt. Cook on medium heat for 40 to 50 minutes until very tender. Set aside with the rich stock.\", \"Step 2: Peel cocoyam and boil until very soft, then pound until completely smooth to make the thickener.\", \"Step 3: Heat palm oil, add sliced onions and blended scotch bonnet peppers, fry for 15 minutes until oil floats on top.\", \"Step 4: Add all the cooked meats, stockfish, dried fish, periwinkle, ogiri, ground crayfish, and meat stock. Cook on medium heat for 15 minutes.\", \"Step 5: Add the pounded cocoyam thickener in small lumps and stir until dissolved.\", \"Step 6: Add the fresh fish pieces and cook gently for 8 minutes.\", \"Step 7: Add the shredded ugu and uziza leaves together and stir in. Cook for 3 to 5 minutes only.\", \"Step 8: Taste and adjust seasoning. Serve hot with pounded yam, fufu, or semolina.\"], \"match_percentage\": 0.0, \"used_ingredients\": [], \"cook_time_minutes\": 85, \"prep_time_minutes\": 30, \"missing_ingredients\": [\"ugu leaves (fluted pumpkin)\", \"uziza leaves\", \"cocoyam (for thickening)\", \"palm oil\", \"assorted meat (beef, tripe, shaki, cow leg)\", \"stockfish\", \"dried fish\", \"fresh fish\", \"periwinkle\", \"crayfish\", \"onions\", \"scotch bonnet peppers\", \"ogiri (fermented locust beans)\", \"seasoning cubes\", \"salt\"]}]}','2026-06-21 09:50:55'),('43a46cac-2a4e-4a94-8db2-9ae43c9ad16a','[\"flour\", \"sugar\", \"butter\", \"egg\", \"milk\", \"baking powder\"]','chinese',NULL,'{\"recipes\": [{\"name\": \"Butter Cake\", \"tips\": \"To ensure that the cake is moist and tender, make sure to not overmix the batter, and to not open the oven door during the cooking time.\", \"servings\": 8, \"difficulty\": \"easy\", \"description\": \"A classic Western dessert, butter cake is a sweet and moist treat that is perfect for any occasion, with a rich, buttery flavor and a tender crumb. It is a popular choice for birthdays, weddings, and other celebrations. The cake is typically served as a snack or dessert, and can be paired with a variety of toppings, such as frosting, fruit, or nuts.\", \"instructions\": [\"Step 1: Preheat the oven to 350 degrees Fahrenheit, and grease two 9-inch round cake pans, making sure to get the sides and bottom evenly coated, for 5 minutes, until the pans are hot and the butter is melted, and the pans should be smelling like butter and feeling hot to the touch.\", \"Step 2: In a large mixing bowl, cream together 1 cup of butter and 1 3/4 cups of sugar, using an electric mixer on medium speed, for 3-4 minutes, until the mixture is light and fluffy, and the sugar is fully incorporated, and the mixture should be smooth and creamy, with no visible sugar crystals, and it should be smelling like sweet butter.\", \"Step 3: Beat in 2 large eggs, one at a time, making sure each egg is fully incorporated before adding the next, using the electric mixer on medium speed, for 2-3 minutes, until the eggs are fully beaten, and the mixture is smooth and creamy, and the eggs should be fully broken down, and the mixture should be smelling like eggs and butter.\", \"Step 4: In a separate bowl, whisk together 2 1/4 cups of flour, and 1 teaspoon of baking powder, using a whisk, for 2 minutes, until the flour and baking powder are well combined, and the mixture should be smooth and even, with no lumps, and it should be smelling like flour, and the mixture should be feeling light and airy.\", \"Step 5: Add the flour mixture to the butter mixture, alternating with 1 cup of milk, beginning and ending with the flour mixture, using the electric mixer on low speed, for 2-3 minutes, until the batter is smooth and creamy, and the flour is fully incorporated, and the mixture should be smelling like butter and flour, and it should be feeling smooth and even, with no lumps.\", \"Step 6: Divide the batter evenly between the prepared pans, and smooth the tops, using a spatula, for 2 minutes, until the batter is evenly distributed, and the tops are smooth, and the pans should be feeling full and heavy, with the batter evenly distributed, and the cakes should be smelling like butter and flour, and they should be ready to be baked, and bake for 30 minutes, or until a toothpick inserted into the center comes out clean, and the cakes should be golden brown, and they should be feeling firm and springy to the touch.\"], \"match_percentage\": 100, \"used_ingredients\": [\"flour\", \"sugar\", \"butter\", \"egg\", \"milk\"], \"cook_time_minutes\": 30, \"prep_time_minutes\": 20, \"missing_ingredients\": [\"baking powder is present but no other leavening agents\"]}]}','2026-06-21 10:03:37'),('5c50cf11-903a-4009-84aa-1f06141286ed','[\"egusi\", \"palm oil\", \"spinach\", \"onions\", \"crayfish\", \"stockfish\", \"beef\", \"scotch bonnet\", \"seasoning cubes\", \"ogiri\"]','nigerian',60,'{\"recipes\": [{\"name\": \"Egusi Soup\", \"difficulty\": \"medium\", \"description\": \"A traditional Nigerian soup made with egusi seeds and assorted meats and spices\", \"instructions\": [\"Grind the egusi seeds\", \"Chop the onions and scotch bonnet\", \"Boil the beef and stockfish\", \"Add the ground egusi and other ingredients to the pot\"], \"match_percentage\": 100, \"used_ingredients\": [\"egusi\", \"palm oil\", \"onions\", \"crayfish\", \"stockfish\", \"beef\", \"scotch bonnet\", \"seasoning cubes\", \"ogiri\", \"spinach\"], \"prep_time_minutes\": 45, \"missing_ingredients\": [\"salt\"]}, {\"name\": \"Egusi and Spinach Stew\", \"difficulty\": \"easy\", \"description\": \"A flavorful stew made with egusi seeds, spinach, and beef\", \"instructions\": [\"Sauté the onions and scotch bonnet\", \"Add the beef and cook until browned\", \"Add the ground egusi and other ingredients to the pot\"], \"match_percentage\": 89, \"used_ingredients\": [\"egusi\", \"palm oil\", \"onions\", \"crayfish\", \"beef\", \"scotch bonnet\", \"seasoning cubes\", \"spinach\"], \"prep_time_minutes\": 30, \"missing_ingredients\": [\"salt\", \"tomatoes\"]}, {\"name\": \"Crayfish and Spinach Soup\", \"difficulty\": \"easy\", \"description\": \"A light and nutritious soup made with crayfish, spinach, and scotch bonnet\", \"instructions\": [\"Sauté the onions and scotch bonnet\", \"Add the crayfish and cook until pink\", \"Add the spinach and other ingredients to the pot\"], \"match_percentage\": 67, \"used_ingredients\": [\"crayfish\", \"palm oil\", \"onions\", \"scotch bonnet\", \"spinach\", \"seasoning cubes\"], \"prep_time_minutes\": 20, \"missing_ingredients\": [\"salt\", \"chicken broth\"]}, {\"name\": \"Beef and Stockfish Pepper Soup\", \"difficulty\": \"medium\", \"description\": \"A spicy and savory soup made with beef, stockfish, and scotch bonnet\", \"instructions\": [\"Boil the beef and stockfish\", \"Sauté the onions and scotch bonnet\", \"Add the other ingredients to the pot\"], \"match_percentage\": 63, \"used_ingredients\": [\"beef\", \"stockfish\", \"palm oil\", \"onions\", \"scotch bonnet\", \"seasoning cubes\"], \"prep_time_minutes\": 40, \"missing_ingredients\": [\"salt\", \"chicken broth\", \"tomatoes\"]}, {\"name\": \"Ogiri and Spinach Stew\", \"difficulty\": \"easy\", \"description\": \"A flavorful stew made with ogiri, spinach, and beef\", \"instructions\": [\"Sauté the onions and scotch bonnet\", \"Add the beef and cook until browned\", \"Add the ogiri and other ingredients to the pot\"], \"match_percentage\": 56, \"used_ingredients\": [\"ogiri\", \"palm oil\", \"onions\", \"beef\", \"scotch bonnet\", \"seasoning cubes\", \"spinach\"], \"prep_time_minutes\": 35, \"missing_ingredients\": [\"salt\", \"tomatoes\", \"crayfish\"]}]}','2026-06-14 17:43:34'),('5c56feba-be06-47f7-9a3d-48fabfee77c0','[\"rice\", \"tomatoes\", \"tomato paste\", \"onions\", \"scotch bonnet\", \"chicken\", \"vegetable oil\", \"seasoning cubes\", \"bay leaves\", \"curry powder\"]','nigerian',60,'{\"recipes\": [{\"name\": \"Jollof Rice\", \"difficulty\": \"easy\", \"description\": \"A classic Nigerian one-pot dish made with rice and tomatoes\", \"instructions\": [\"Heat oil in a pot\", \"Add onions and sauté\", \"Add tomatoes and tomato paste\", \"Add rice and seasoning\", \"Cook until done\"], \"match_percentage\": 86, \"used_ingredients\": [\"rice\", \"tomatoes\", \"tomato paste\", \"onions\", \"vegetable oil\", \"seasoning cubes\"], \"prep_time_minutes\": 40, \"missing_ingredients\": [\"salt\", \"thyme\"]}, {\"name\": \"Grilled Chicken and Rice\", \"difficulty\": \"easy\", \"description\": \"A simple Nigerian-inspired dish made with grilled chicken and served with rice\", \"instructions\": [\"Grill chicken with onions\", \"Boil rice\", \"Serve chicken with rice\"], \"match_percentage\": 83, \"used_ingredients\": [\"chicken\", \"rice\", \"onions\", \"vegetable oil\", \"seasoning cubes\"], \"prep_time_minutes\": 30, \"missing_ingredients\": [\"salt\", \"pepper\"]}, {\"name\": \"Tomato and Rice Stew\", \"difficulty\": \"medium\", \"description\": \"A hearty Nigerian stew made with tomatoes and served with rice\", \"instructions\": [\"Heat oil in a pot\", \"Add onions and sauté\", \"Add tomatoes and tomato paste\", \"Add rice and seasoning\", \"Cook until done\"], \"match_percentage\": 80, \"used_ingredients\": [\"tomatoes\", \"tomato paste\", \"onions\", \"rice\", \"vegetable oil\", \"seasoning cubes\"], \"prep_time_minutes\": 40, \"missing_ingredients\": [\"meat or fish\", \"salt\"]}, {\"name\": \"Chicken and Tomato Stir-Fry\", \"difficulty\": \"easy\", \"description\": \"A quick Nigerian-inspired stir-fry made with chicken and tomatoes\", \"instructions\": [\"Heat oil in a pan\", \"Add onions and sauté\", \"Add chicken and cook\", \"Add tomatoes and seasoning\", \"Stir-fry until done\"], \"match_percentage\": 78, \"used_ingredients\": [\"chicken\", \"tomatoes\", \"onions\", \"vegetable oil\", \"seasoning cubes\"], \"prep_time_minutes\": 20, \"missing_ingredients\": [\"bell peppers\", \"salt\"]}, {\"name\": \"Scotch Bonnet Chicken\", \"difficulty\": \"medium\", \"description\": \"A spicy Nigerian dish made with chicken and scotch bonnet peppers\", \"instructions\": [\"Heat oil in a pan\", \"Add onions and sauté\", \"Add chicken and cook\", \"Add scotch bonnet and seasoning\", \"Cook until done\"], \"match_percentage\": 74, \"used_ingredients\": [\"chicken\", \"scotch bonnet\", \"onions\", \"vegetable oil\", \"seasoning cubes\"], \"prep_time_minutes\": 30, \"missing_ingredients\": [\"garlic\", \"ginger\", \"salt\"]}]}','2026-06-14 17:42:54'),('698fa8d9-3272-4af9-a14a-603276bdefac','[\"palm oil\", \"egusi\", \"spinach\", \"onions\", \"crayfish\", \"assorted meat\", \"stockfish\"]','nigerian',NULL,'{\"almost_there\": [{\"name\": \"Egusi Soup Yoruba Style\", \"tips\": \"The secret to Yoruba egusi is frying the egusi completely dry in palm oil before adding any liquid. Never add water or stock to the egusi while frying — it must fry and toast in the oil until golden. Also never add tomatoes to Yoruba egusi soup — that changes the flavour profile completely.\", \"servings\": 6, \"difficulty\": \"medium\", \"description\": \"Egusi Soup Yoruba style is a rich and hearty Nigerian soup made with ground melon seeds fried directly in palm oil before any liquid is added. Unlike Igbo style egusi which is added raw, Yoruba style fries the egusi first until golden and nutty giving it a deeper richer flavour. It is served with amala, eba, or pounded yam.\", \"instructions\": [\"Step 1: Wash and season assorted meat and stockfish with onions, seasoning cubes, and salt. Cook in a pot on medium heat for 15 to 20 minutes until tender. Set aside with the stock.\", \"Step 2: Blend scotch bonnet peppers, tatashe, and half the onions together into a smooth paste. Set aside.\", \"Step 3: Heat palm oil in a large pot on medium heat for 2 minutes until melted and hot but not bleached. Chop the remaining onions and fry in the palm oil for 3 minutes until soft and translucent.\", \"Step 4: Add the ground egusi to the palm oil and stir immediately to combine. Fry the egusi in the palm oil on medium heat for 8 to 10 minutes stirring constantly until the egusi turns golden, smells nutty, and pulls away from the sides of the pot. Do not add any liquid at this stage — dry frying is the key to Yoruba egusi.\", \"Step 5: Add the blended pepper mixture to the fried egusi and stir well to combine. Fry together for another 10 minutes on medium heat stirring every 2 minutes until the pepper is cooked and oil begins to float on the surface.\", \"Step 6: Add the cooked meat, stockfish, dried fish, meat stock, ground crayfish, iru, and seasoning cubes. Stir everything together and add a small amount of water if the soup is too thick. Cook on medium heat for 15 minutes until all the flavours come together.\", \"Step 7: Taste and adjust salt and seasoning. The soup should be rich, thick, and deeply flavoured at this point.\", \"Step 8: Add shredded spinach or efo tete and stir into the soup. Cook for exactly 2 minutes only — overcooking the vegetables will make them lose their colour and become soggy. Remove from heat and serve immediately with amala, eba, or pounded yam.\"], \"match_percentage\": 53.8, \"used_ingredients\": [\"ground egusi (melon seeds)\", \"palm oil\", \"assorted meat (beef, tripe, shaki)\", \"stockfish\", \"onions\", \"crayfish\", \"spinach, efo tete or ugwu\"], \"cook_time_minutes\": 70, \"prep_time_minutes\": 20, \"missing_ingredients\": [\"dried fish\", \"scotch bonnet peppers\", \"tatashe (red bell pepper)\", \"iru (locust beans)\", \"seasoning cubes\", \"salt\"]}, {\"name\": \"Efo Riro\", \"tips\": \"The most important step is frying the pepper base completely dry until the oil floats on top before adding any meat or stock. This is what separates a rich deeply flavoured Efo Riro from a watery one. Also add the vegetables at the very last minute and cook for 2 minutes only — overcooked vegetables will turn dark and lose their flavour.\", \"servings\": 6, \"difficulty\": \"medium\", \"description\": \"Efo Riro is a rich Yoruba vegetable soup made with tatashe and ata rodo as the pepper base, assorted meats, and leafy green vegetables. The name means stirred leafy vegetable in Yoruba. It is one of the most flavourful Nigerian soups with a vibrant green and red colour from the vegetables and pepper base. It is served with amala, eba, pounded yam, or rice.\", \"instructions\": [\"Step 1: Wash and season assorted meat, pomo, and stockfish with onions, seasoning cubes, and salt. Cook on medium heat for 20 to 30 minutes until very tender. Set aside with the stock.\", \"Step 2: Blend tatashe and scotch bonnet peppers together into a smooth paste. Do not add water — the peppers have enough natural liquid. Set aside.\", \"Step 3: Wash the efo tete or spinach thoroughly, shred into medium sized pieces by hand, and set aside in a colander to drain excess water.\", \"Step 4: Heat palm oil in a large pot on medium-high heat for 2 minutes. Slice onions and fry in the palm oil for 3 minutes until golden and fragrant.\", \"Step 5: Add the blended tatashe and scotch bonnet pepper mixture to the pot. It will sizzle loudly in the hot oil — this is correct. Fry on high heat for 10 to 20 minutes stirring every 3 minutes until all the water has completely evaporated, the oil floats on top, and the pepper sauce has darkened and thickened. This step gives Efo Riro its deep rich flavour.\", \"Step 6: Add iru (locust beans) and ground crayfish and stir into the pepper sauce. Fry for 2 more minutes until the iru is fragrant.\", \"Step 7: Add the cooked assorted meat, stockfish, dried fish, and a ladle of the meat stock. Stir everything together and cook on medium heat for 10 minutes until the meat is well coated in the sauce.\", \"Step 8: Add the shredded efo tete or spinach to the pot and stir into the sauce. Cook for exactly 2 minutes only on medium heat — the vegetables should wilt into the soup but remain bright green and not soggy. Taste, adjust seasoning, and remove from heat immediately. Serve with amala, eba, or pounded yam.\"], \"match_percentage\": 50.0, \"used_ingredients\": [\"vgetables African spinach or ugwu\", \"onions\", \"palm oil\", \"assorted meat (beef, tripe, shaki, pomo)\", \"stockfish\", \"crayfish\"], \"cook_time_minutes\": 75, \"prep_time_minutes\": 25, \"missing_ingredients\": [\"tatashe (red bell pepper)\", \"scotch bonnet peppers (ata rodo)\", \"dried fish\", \"iru (locust beans)\", \"seasoning cubes\", \"salt\"]}], \"can_make_now\": [], \"needs_shopping\": [{\"name\": \"Ayamase (Ofada Stew)\", \"tips\": \"Bleaching the palm oil is absolutely non-negotiable for authentic Ayamase. Only use green peppers and unripe tatashe — no red peppers at all. The more assorted meats you use the richer and more authentic the stew will be.\", \"servings\": 6, \"difficulty\": \"hard\", \"description\": \"Ayamase also known as Ofada Stew or Designer Stew is a rich and intensely flavoured Yoruba stew made exclusively with green peppers and unripe tatashe giving it its distinctive green colour. It is traditionally served with Ofada rice and the stew is made with bleached palm oil and loaded with assorted meats making it one of the most indulgent Nigerian dishes.\", \"instructions\": [\"Step 1: Wash and season all assorted meats with onions, seasoning cubes, ginger garlic paste and salt. Cook in a pot on medium heat for 25 to 35 minutes until very tender. Fry the cooked meats in a small amount of oil until lightly browned on the outside for extra flavour. Set aside with the stock.\", \"Step 2: Blend green bell peppers, unripe green tatashe, green scotch bonnet peppers, and onions together into a coarse paste — do not blend completely smooth, leave some texture. The stew must use only green peppers and unripe tatashe — never red peppers or ripe tatashe as this completely changes the dish.\", \"Step 3: Bleach the palm oil by heating it in a pot on high heat with the lid on for 10 to 15 minutes until the oil turns from orange-red to a pale golden yellow colour and begins to smoke lightly. Remove from heat and allow to cool slightly. Bleached palm oil is essential for authentic Ayamase.\", \"Step 4: Return the bleached palm oil to medium heat. Add sliced onions with some ginger garlic paste and fry for 3 minutes until soft and slightly golden.\", \"Step 5: Pour the blended green pepper mixture into the bleached palm oil. It will sizzle vigorously stir immediately. Fry on high heat for 15 to 20 minutes stirring every 3 to 4 minutes until all the water has completely evaporated, the oil floats on top, and the pepper sauce is cooked down and thick.\", \"Step 6: Add iru (locust beans) and ground crayfish to the cooked pepper base and stir well. Fry for 3 more minutes until the iru is fragrant and well incorporated.\", \"Step 7: Add all the assorted meats and a ladle of the meat stock. Stir everything together to coat the meat in the green pepper sauce. Cook on medium heat for 10 minutes until the meat is well flavoured and the stew is thick and rich.\", \"Step 8: Taste and adjust seasoning. The finished Ayamase should be dark olive green, thick, intensely flavoured, and very rich with assorted meats. Serve with Ofada rice.\"], \"match_percentage\": 36.4, \"used_ingredients\": [\"onions\", \"palm oil\", \"assorted meat (beef, tripe, shaki, pomo, liver)\", \"crayfish\"], \"cook_time_minutes\": 90, \"prep_time_minutes\": 25, \"missing_ingredients\": [\"green bell peppers\", \"unripe tatashe (green tatashe)\", \"green scotch bonnet peppers\", \"iru (locust beans)\", \"seasoning cubes\", \"ginger and garlic paste\", \"salt\"]}, {\"name\": \"Ewa Agoyin\", \"tips\": \"The two secrets to authentic Ewa Agoyin are cooking the beans with a lot of onions until completely mashable with no whole beans remaining, and making the Agoyin stew with only dried peppers not fresh ones. Fresh peppers will not give the deep dark colour and concentrated flavour that makes Agoyin stew unique. The stew must be dark, dry, and almost burnt looking — that is correct.\", \"servings\": 4, \"difficulty\": \"medium\", \"description\": \"Ewa Agoyin is a popular Yoruba street food originally brought to Nigeria by Beninese traders, consisting of soft completely mashed honey beans or black eyed beans served with a deeply dark and spicy Agoyin stew made from dried red peppers and palm oil. It is a beloved Lagos breakfast food sold by roadside vendors and eaten with agege bread.\", \"instructions\": [\"Step 1: Wash the beans thoroughly then cover the beans with fresh water and cook on high heat until boiling, then reduce to medium heat. Cook for 45 to 60 minutes until the beans are extremely soft — they should mash completely between your fingers with no resistance. Add more water as needed during cooking to prevent burning.\", \"Step 2: Once the beans are very soft, use a wooden spoon or potato masher to mash them completely in the pot until no whole beans remain. The consistency should be thick and porridge-like. Season with salt, stir well, and set aside.\", \"Step 4: While the beans cook prepare the Agoyin stew. Rehydrate the dried red peppers and dried chilli peppers by soaking in hot water for 20 minutes until soft. Drain and blend alongside some onions and ginger into a rough paste — not completely smooth, leave some texture.\", \"Step 5: Heat palm oil in a separate pot on medium heat until hot. Slice onions into thin rings and fry in the palm oil for 10 minutes on medium-low heat, stirring constantly until the onions are very dark brown and almost caramelised — this dark onion is essential to the Agoyin stew flavour.\", \"Step 6: Add the blended dried pepper mixture to the dark onions and palm oil. Stir well and fry on medium heat for 20 to 25 minutes stirring every 3 minutes until all moisture evaporates, the stew becomes very dark, thick, and dry, and the oil floats on top. The stew should be almost black in colour — this is correct.\", \"Step 7: Add seasoning cubes and salt to the stew. Stir well and cook for 5 more minutes. The finished Agoyin stew should be very dark, very dry, very spicy, and intensely flavoured.\", \"Step 8: Serve the mashed beans in a bowl and pour the dark Agoyin stew generously on top. Eat with agege bread, fried plantain, or on its own.\"], \"match_percentage\": 33.3, \"used_ingredients\": [\"onions\", \"palm oil\", \"crayfish\"], \"cook_time_minutes\": 90, \"prep_time_minutes\": 20, \"missing_ingredients\": [\"beans\", \"dried red peppers (tatashe)\", \"dried long chilli bonnet peppers(shombo)\", \"seasoning cubes\", \"salt\", \"water\"]}, {\"name\": \"Ofe Owerri\", \"tips\": \"Use as many different types of meat and fish as you can for the most authentic version. The combination of ugu and uziza leaves together distinguishes this from Edikang Ikong.\", \"servings\": 6, \"difficulty\": \"hard\", \"description\": \"Ofe Owerri is a luxurious traditional Igbo vegetable soup from Owerri in Imo State, known for being loaded with multiple types of meat, fish, and a generous mix of vegetables, traditionally served at important ceremonies.\", \"instructions\": [\"Step 1: Wash and season all assorted meats and stockfish with onions, seasoning cubes, and salt. Cook on medium heat for 40 to 50 minutes until very tender. Set aside with the rich stock.\", \"Step 2: Peel cocoyam and boil until very soft, then pound until completely smooth to make the thickener.\", \"Step 3: Heat palm oil, add sliced onions and blended scotch bonnet peppers, fry for 15 minutes until oil floats on top.\", \"Step 4: Add all the cooked meats, stockfish, dried fish, periwinkle, ogiri, ground crayfish, and meat stock. Cook on medium heat for 15 minutes.\", \"Step 5: Add the pounded cocoyam thickener in small lumps and stir until dissolved.\", \"Step 6: Add the fresh fish pieces and cook gently for 8 minutes.\", \"Step 7: Add the shredded ugu and uziza leaves together and stir in. Cook for 3 to 5 minutes only.\", \"Step 8: Taste and adjust seasoning. Serve hot with pounded yam, fufu, or semolina.\"], \"match_percentage\": 33.3, \"used_ingredients\": [\"palm oil\", \"assorted meat (beef, tripe, shaki, cow leg)\", \"stockfish\", \"crayfish\", \"onions\"], \"cook_time_minutes\": 85, \"prep_time_minutes\": 30, \"missing_ingredients\": [\"ugu leaves (fluted pumpkin)\", \"uziza leaves\", \"cocoyam (for thickening)\", \"dried fish\", \"fresh fish\", \"periwinkle\", \"scotch bonnet peppers\", \"ogiri (fermented locust beans)\", \"seasoning cubes\", \"salt\"]}, {\"name\": \"Ikokore\", \"tips\": \"Use water yam specifically not white yam or cocoyam. Do not rinse the grated yam before adding to the pot as the natural starch thickens the broth and holds the dumplings together.\", \"servings\": 4, \"difficulty\": \"medium\", \"description\": \"Ikokore is a traditional Ijebu Yoruba dish made from grated water yam cooked in a rich pepper soup or tomato base with assorted fish and seafood. The grated water yam forms thick irregular dumplings in the broth giving the dish its characteristic texture. It is a beloved dish in Ogun State and across Yorubaland.\", \"instructions\": [\"Step 1: Peel the water yam and grate on the coarse side of a grater into a bowl. Do not rinse the grated yam — the natural starch is needed to hold the dumplings together. Season the grated yam lightly with salt and set aside.\", \"Step 2: Blend scotch bonnet peppers, long chilli peppers, and onions together into a smooth paste.\", \"Step 3: Heat palm oil in a large pot on medium heat. Add iru and fry for 1 minute until fragrant. Add the blended pepper mixture and fry for 15 minutes until cooked and oil floats on top.\", \"Step 4: Add enough meat stock to the pot . Add ground crayfish, dried fish, smoked fish, assorted meat, seasoning cubes, and salt. Bring to a boil on high heat.\", \"Step 5: Using a tablespoon or your hand, scoop portions of the grated water yam and drop them one by one into the boiling broth. Do not stir immediately — allow the yam dumplings to set for 3 minutes before stirring gently.\", \"Step 6: Cook on medium heat for 15 to 20 minutes stirring gently occasionally until the yam dumplings are fully cooked and the broth has thickened, adjust seasoning, and serve hot.\"], \"match_percentage\": 30.8, \"used_ingredients\": [\"assorted meat\", \"palm oil\", \"crayfish\", \"onions\"], \"cook_time_minutes\": 50, \"prep_time_minutes\": 25, \"missing_ingredients\": [\"water yam (isu ewura)\", \"dried fish\", \"smoked fish\", \"scotch bonnet peppers\", \"long chilli peppers\", \"iru (locust beans)\", \"seasoning cubes\", \"salt\", \"water\"]}, {\"name\": \"Abacha\", \"tips\": \"Always soak in cold water not hot. Potash is essential for emulsifying the palm oil into the dressing.\", \"servings\": 4, \"difficulty\": \"medium\", \"description\": \"Abacha is a traditional Igbo cold salad made from dried shredded cassava rehydrated and tossed in an emulsified palm oil and potash dressing with ugba, utazi leaves, garden eggs, crayfish, and assorted proteins.\", \"instructions\": [\"Step 1: Soak the dried abacha in cold water for 10 to 15 minutes until softened. Drain thoroughly.\", \"Step 2: Dissolve potash in 3 tablespoons of water and strain through a fine sieve.\", \"Step 3: Pour palm oil into a bowl. Add the potash solution gradually while stirring vigorously until emulsified and bright yellow.\", \"Step 4: Add ground crayfish, sliced scotch bonnet peppers, sliced onions, seasoning cubes, and salt to the emulsion.\", \"Step 5: Add the drained abacha and toss thoroughly until coated.\", \"Step 6: Add ugba, sliced garden eggs, shredded utazi, flaked fish, and sliced ponmo. Toss together gently.\", \"Step 7: Taste and adjust seasoning.\", \"Step 8: Garnish with utazi and onion rings. Serve at room temperature.\"], \"match_percentage\": 30.8, \"used_ingredients\": [\"palm oil\", \"crayfish\", \"onions\", \"dried fish or stockfish\"], \"cook_time_minutes\": 0, \"prep_time_minutes\": 20, \"missing_ingredients\": [\"abacha (dried shredded cassava)\", \"ugba (oil bean seeds)\", \"potash (kaun)\", \"utazi leaves\", \"garden eggs\", \"scotch bonnet peppers\", \"seasoning cubes\", \"salt\", \"ponmo (cow skin)\"]}, {\"name\": \"Asaro (Yam Porridge)\", \"tips\": \"Gentle stirring lets some yam break down to thicken the sauce naturally without becoming completely mashed.\", \"servings\": 4, \"difficulty\": \"easy\", \"description\": \"Asaro is a beloved traditional Yoruba yam porridge made by cooking yam chunks directly in a rich tomato and pepper sauce until the yam softens and thickens the entire dish into a hearty one-pot meal.\", \"instructions\": [\"Step 1: Peel the yam and cut into medium sized chunks. Wash thoroughly.\", \"Step 2: Blend onions, tatashe, and scotch bonnet peppers together into a smooth paste.\", \"Step 3: Place the yam chunks in a pot with the blended pepper mixture, sliced onions, palm oil, and enough water to just cover the yam.\", \"Step 4: Bring to a boil then reduce to medium heat. Cook for 20 to 25 minutes, stirring occasionally, until the yam softens and breaks down at the edges.\", \"Step 5: Add ground crayfish, flaked fish, seasoning cubes, and salt. Stir gently.\", \"Step 6: Continue cooking on medium-low heat for 8 to 10 minutes until thick and stew-like.\", \"Step 7: Taste and adjust seasoning. Serve hot on its own.\"], \"match_percentage\": 27.3, \"used_ingredients\": [\"onions\", \"palm oil\", \"crayfish\"], \"cook_time_minutes\": 40, \"prep_time_minutes\": 15, \"missing_ingredients\": [\"yam (white yam)\", \"tomatoes\", \"tatashe (red bell pepper)\", \"scotch bonnet peppers\", \"smoked fish or dried fish\", \"seasoning cubes\", \"salt\", \"water\"]}, {\"name\": \"Banga Stew\", \"tips\": \"The key difference between Banga Soup and Banga Stew is the reduction time — cook the stew version longer uncovered to achieve a thicker consistency that coats rice or yam well rather than the more liquid soup form.\", \"servings\": 5, \"difficulty\": \"hard\", \"description\": \"Banga Stew is a thick, deeply flavoured Igbo stew made from concentrated palm fruit extract, prepared similarly to Banga Soup but cooked down to a thicker consistency more like a stew than a soup. It is rich, nutty, and aromatic, traditionally seasoned with banga spices, and served with white rice, boiled yam, or plantain.\", \"instructions\": [\"Step 1: If using fresh palm fruit, boil for 20 to 30 minutes until soft, then pound to separate pulp from nuts and squeeze with warm water to extract the thick orange juice. Strain through a sieve to remove fibres. If using canned concentrate, dilute according to package instructions.\", \"Step 2: Pour the palm fruit extract into a pot and bring to a boil on high heat, then reduce to medium heat and simmer for 15 to 20 minutes until the oil begins to separate and rise to the surface.\", \"Step 3: Season the assorted meat with onions, seasoning cubes, and salt. Cook separately on medium heat for 30 minutes until tender. Add the cooked meat and stock to the palm fruit base.\", \"Step 4: Add the banga spice mix to the pot and simmer for 15 minutes to allow the spices to infuse fully into the base.\", \"Step 5: Add dried fish, ground crayfish, sliced scotch bonnet peppers, and seasoning cubes. Stir well and continue cooking on medium heat, allowing the liquid to reduce and thicken for 20 to 25 minutes — unlike Banga Soup this should reduce further into a thicker stew-like consistency.\", \"Step 6: Add the fresh fish pieces and cook gently for 8 to 10 minutes until just cooked through, stirring carefully to avoid breaking the fish apart.\", \"Step 7: Continue simmering uncovered for an additional 10 minutes, stirring occasionally, until the stew has thickened noticeably and the oil is clearly visible on the surface.\", \"Step 8: Remove the oburunbebe stick before serving. Taste and adjust seasoning. Serve hot with white rice, boiled yam, or plantain.\"], \"match_percentage\": 27.3, \"used_ingredients\": [\"assorted meat (beef, tripe)\", \"onions\", \"crayfish\"], \"cook_time_minutes\": 80, \"prep_time_minutes\": 30, \"missing_ingredients\": [\"fresh palm fruit (or canned banga concentrate)\", \"dried fish\", \"fresh fish\", \"banga spice mix (oburunbebe stick, dried bitter leaf)\", \"scotch bonnet peppers\", \"seasoning cubes\", \"salt\", \"water\"]}, {\"name\": \"Nigerian Pepper Soup\", \"tips\": \"The quality of your pepper soup spice mix makes or breaks this dish. Use freshly ground spices if possible — uda (country onion), ehuru (calabash nutmeg), and uziza seeds ground together give the most authentic flavour. Never cover the pot fully while cooking pepper soup — leave it slightly open so the broth reduces and concentrates.\", \"servings\": 4, \"difficulty\": \"easy\", \"description\": \"Nigerian Pepper Soup is a light, intensely spiced broth made with meat or fish and a unique blend of pepper soup spices. It is served at every Nigerian gathering, used as a remedy for colds and fever, and eaten as a starter or main dish. The broth is thin but deeply flavoured with a distinctive warming heat that comes from the special pepper soup spice blend.\", \"instructions\": [\"Step 1: Wash the meat thoroughly and cut into medium sized pieces. Season with onions, seasoning cubes, and salt. Do not add water yet — allow the meat to cook in its own juices first.\", \"Step 2: Place the seasoned meat in a pot on medium heat and cook dry for 10 minutes stirring occasionally until the meat releases its juices and begins to brown slightly on the outside.\", \"Step 3: Add enough water to cover the meat completely. Bring to a boil on high heat then reduce to medium heat. Cook for 25 to 30 minutes for goat meat or 15 minutes for chicken until the meat is tender but not falling off the bone.\", \"Step 4: Add the pepper soup spice mix, ground crayfish, and blended or roughly crushed scotch bonnet peppers. Stir well and taste — the broth should be well seasoned and spicy at this point. Add more seasoning cubes and salt if needed.\", \"Step 5: Cook on medium heat for another 15 minutes until the spices have fully infused into the broth and the liquid has reduced slightly. The broth should be a light golden brown colour and smell intensely aromatic.\", \"Step 6: Tear utazi leaves into small pieces and add to the pot — utazi adds a slight bitterness that balances the heat. Add uziza leaves whole or roughly torn. Cook for 3 minutes only.\", \"Step 7: Taste one final time and adjust salt and pepper. The pepper soup should be very hot and spicy, lightly bitter from the utazi, and deeply aromatic from the spice blend. Serve hot in deep bowls with sliced onions on top and agidi or white rice on the side.\"], \"match_percentage\": 20.0, \"used_ingredients\": [\"onions\", \"crayfish\"], \"cook_time_minutes\": 55, \"prep_time_minutes\": 15, \"missing_ingredients\": [\"goat meat or chicken or catfish\", \"pepper soup spice mix\", \"scotch bonnet peppers\", \"uziza leaves\", \"utazi leaves\", \"seasoning cubes\", \"salt\", \"water\"]}, {\"name\": \"Moi Moi\", \"tips\": \"The food processor peeling method is a game changer — it cuts prep time from 30 minutes to 5 minutes. The two most important steps are removing every single bean skin and whisking the paste vigorously to aerate it before adding seasoning. Skipping either step will result in dense heavy Moi Moi. Always fill containers only three quarters full as the paste expands during steaming.\", \"servings\": 8, \"difficulty\": \"medium\", \"description\": \"Moi Moi is a traditional Nigerian steamed bean pudding made from peeled beans blended into a smooth paste. It is a beloved dish across all Nigerian tribes and is served at parties, as a side dish with rice or ogi, or eaten alone as a complete meal. The texture should be firm yet soft and moist inside with a rich savoury flavour.\", \"instructions\": [\"Step 1: There are two ways to peel the beans. Traditional method: Pour beans into a bowl and soak in cold water for 30 minutes until the skins begin to loosen and soften, then rub vigorously between both palms under running water until all skins float off. Quick method: Pour dry beans into a food processor with some water and pulse for 30 to 45 seconds — the food processor will crack and loosen the skins without grinding the beans. Pour the pulsed beans into a large bowl of water, the skins will float to the top — skim them off and drain. Repeat until all skins are removed. The quick method takes 5 minutes instead of 30.\", \"Step 2: Rinse the peeled beans thoroughly in clean water two to three times to remove any remaining skin fragments. The beans should be completely white with no dark skin remaining — any leftover skin will make the Moi Moi rough and bitter.\", \"Step 3: Place the peeled beans directly into the blender together with the scotch bonnet peppers, red bell pepper, onions, one raw egg, and a very small amount of water — just enough to get the blender moving. Blend everything together on high speed for 3 minutes until the paste is completely smooth with absolutely no grainy texture. Blending the peppers and egg together with the beans at this stage gives the Moi Moi its full flavour and colour from the inside.\", \"Step 4: Pour the blended paste into a large bowl. Add seasoning cubes, vegetable oil, and salt. Mix everything together thoroughly until well combined. Taste and adjust seasoning — it should be well seasoned and slightly peppery.\", \"Step 5: Using a wooden spoon or electric hand mixer, whisk the paste vigorously for 5 minutes until it becomes fluffy, lighter in colour, and increases slightly in volume. This aerates the paste and gives Moi Moi its soft moist texture when steamed.\", \"Step 6: Break the mackerel fish into medium sized chunks and slice your boiled eggs and set aside. Grease foil containers or moi moi leaves generously with vegetable oil on the inside so the moi moi does not stick.\", \"Step 7: Pour the bean paste mixture into each container filling only three quarters full. Drop pieces of fish directly into the paste in each container alongside the sliced eggs  — the fish sits inside the moi moi not on top. Press down lightly so the fish is submerged in the paste.\", \"Step 8: Seal each foil container tightly by folding the edges over securely. No steam should be able to escape during cooking.\", \"Step 9: Place a trivet or folded foil at the bottom of a large pot to prevent direct heat contact. Arrange the sealed moi moi containers in the pot and add water to reach halfway up the sides of the containers.\", \"Step 10: Cover the pot tightly and steam on medium heat for 45 to 60 minutes. Check water level every 15 minutes and add more hot water if needed — never let the pot run dry. Moi Moi is ready when it feels firm when pressed gently and pulls away cleanly from the container when opened.\"], \"match_percentage\": 18.2, \"used_ingredients\": [\"onions\", \"crayfish\"], \"cook_time_minutes\": 60, \"prep_time_minutes\": 40, \"missing_ingredients\": [\"beans\", \"scotch bonnet peppers\", \"long chilli pepper (shombo)\", \"vegetable oil\", \"seasoning cubes\", \"salt\", \"eggs\", \"fish (preferably mackerel fish)\", \"water\"]}, {\"name\": \"Akara\", \"tips\": \"Whisking the bean paste until very fluffy is the secret to light soft akara — never skip this step. Also make sure the oil is very hot before adding the paste otherwise the akara will absorb too much oil and become greasy. Wet your spoon with oil before scooping each portion to help the paste slide off cleanly into the oil.\", \"servings\": 4, \"difficulty\": \"medium\", \"description\": \"Akara is a traditional Yoruba deep fried bean cake made from peeled black eyed beans blended into a smooth aerated paste and fried in hot oil until crispy on the outside and soft inside. It is a quintessential Nigerian breakfast food sold by roadside vendors across the country and best eaten hot with ogi (pap) or bread.\", \"instructions\": [\"Step 1: Peel the beans using one of two methods. Traditional method: Soak beans in cold water for 30 minutes then rub between palms under running water until all skins float off and are drained away. Quick method: Pulse beans and water  in a food processor for 30 seconds to crack and loosen skins, pour into a bowl of water, skim off floating skins, and drain. Rinse peeled beans two to three times in clean water.\", \"Step 2: Place the peeled beans alongside the peppers and onions in a blender with a very small amount of water — just enough to move the blender. Blend on high speed for 3 minutes until the paste is completely smooth and thick. The paste must be thick not watery — too much water will make flat oily akara.\", \"Step 3: Pour the blended bean paste into a large bowl. Using a wooden spoon or electric hand mixer whisk the paste vigorously for 5 to 7 minutes until it becomes very fluffy, lighter in colour, and almost doubles in volume. This is the most important step — the air you whisk in is what makes akara light and fluffy inside.\", \"Step 4: Add some salt and seasoning cubes to the whisked paste. Fold gently into the paste without deflating it. Taste and adjust seasoning.\", \"Step 5: Pour enough vegetable oil into a deep wide pan to allow the akara to float — at least 3 inches deep. Heat on medium-high heat for 2 to 3 minutes until hot. Test the oil by dropping a tiny bit of paste in — it should rise immediately to the surface and sizzle vigorously. If it sinks the oil is not hot enough.\", \"Step 6: Wet your tablespoon with oil and scoop portions of the paste into the hot oil one at a time. Do not overcrowd the pan — leave space between each akara so they cook evenly and stay round.\", \"Step 7: Fry on medium heat for 3 to 4 minutes until the bottom is deep golden brown, then flip carefully with a slotted spoon or skewer and fry the other side for 2 to 3 minutes until evenly golden brown and crispy all over.\", \"Step 8: Remove with a slotted spoon and drain on paper towels to absorb excess oil. Serve immediately while hot and crispy alongside ogi (pap) or as a breakfast snack.\"], \"match_percentage\": 14.3, \"used_ingredients\": [\"onions\"], \"cook_time_minutes\": 20, \"prep_time_minutes\": 30, \"missing_ingredients\": [\"black eyed beans\", \"scotch bonnet peppers\", \"long chilli peppers(shombo)\", \"seasoning cubes\", \"salt\", \"vegetable oil for deep frying\"]}, {\"name\": \"Asun\", \"tips\": \"Grilling or smoking the goat meat after boiling is non-negotiable for authentic Asun — without the charred smoky exterior the dish is just peppered goat meat not Asun. Use goat meat with the skin on for the best texture and flavour. The pepper sauce should have chunky sliced peppers not a blended smooth sauce.\", \"servings\": 4, \"difficulty\": \"medium\", \"description\": \"Asun is a popular Yoruba delicacy of smoked or roasted goat meat cut into small pieces and tossed in a fiery pepper and onion sauce. It originates from Ondo State in Yorubaland and is now one of the most popular Nigerian party small chops and appetisers served across the country. The goat meat is first smoked or roasted to give it a distinctive charred flavour before being peppered.\", \"instructions\": [\"Step 1: Wash the goat meat thoroughly — authentic Asun uses goat meat with the skin on as the skin adds texture and flavour. Cut into medium sized chunks. Season with seasoning cubes, curry powder, thyme, ginger garlic paste and salt.\", \"Step 2: Cook the seasoned goat meat in a pot with a small amount of water on medium heat for 20 to 25 minutes until tender but not falling apart.\", \"Step 3: Remove the cooked goat meat and place directly on a grill, open flame, or in a very hot oven at 220 degrees Celsius. Grill or roast for 15 to 20 minutes turning occasionally until the outside is charred and smoky and the skin is slightly crispy. The charring is essential for authentic Asun flavour.\", \"Step 4: Remove from the grill and cut into smaller bite sized pieces while still hot. Set aside.\", \"Step 5: Slice scotch bonnet peppers, green bell pepper, red bell pepper, and onions into thin strips. The peppers should be sliced not blended, a food processor can be used as well — the chunky pepper pieces are characteristic of Asun.\", \"Step 6: Heat vegetable oil in a wide pan on medium heat. Add the sliced onions and fry for 2 minutes until slightly softened.\", \"Step 7: Add all the sliced peppers to the pan and stir fry on high heat for 3 to 4 minutes — the peppers should be cooked but still have a slight crunch. Do not overcook the peppers into mush.\", \"Step 8: Add the grilled goat meat pieces to the pan and toss vigorously with the peppers for 3 minutes on high heat until the meat is well coated in the pepper mixture and everything is sizzling hot. Taste and adjust seasoning. Serve immediately as a party appetiser or small chop.\"], \"match_percentage\": 9.1, \"used_ingredients\": [\"onions\"], \"cook_time_minutes\": 60, \"prep_time_minutes\": 20, \"missing_ingredients\": [\"goat meat (skin on)\", \"scotch bonnet peppers\", \"green bell pepper\", \"red bell pepper (tatashe)\", \"vegetable oil\", \"seasoning cubes\", \"curry powder\", \"thyme\", \"salt\", \"ginger garlic paste\"]}, {\"name\": \"Nigerian Fried Rice\", \"tips\": \"Always cook on high heat when frying the rice and vegetables together to prevent everything from steaming and becoming soggy instead of stir-fried.\", \"servings\": 6, \"difficulty\": \"medium\", \"description\": \"Nigerian Fried Rice is a colourful and flavourful party staple made with parboiled rice stir-fried with mixed vegetables, liver, and a distinct curry seasoning. Unlike Chinese fried rice, the Nigerian version has a unique orange-yellow hue from curry powder and is loaded with vegetables, making it one of the most popular dishes at Nigerian celebrations alongside Jollof Rice.\", \"instructions\": [\"Step 1: Wash the rice thoroughly until water runs clear then transfer into a seive till perfectly dry. Then into a pot, add some oil and fry the rice for about 5 minutes\", \"Step 2: Season the liver with salt and a little curry powder. Cook in a pot with a small amount of water for 8 to 10 minutes until just cooked through, then dice into small cubes.\", \"Step 3: Dice carrots and green beans into small uniform cubes for even cooking. Set aside along with the bell peppers.\", \"Step 4: Heat vegetable oil in a large wok or wide pan on high heat. Add minced garlic and ginger and stir fry for 30 seconds until fragrant but not browned.\", \"Step 5: Add diced onions and stir fry for 2 minutes until softened. Add the diced liver and shrimp and stir fry for 2 minutes.\", \"Step 6: Add the carrots, green beans, green peas, and bell peppers to the pan. Stir fry on high heat for 3 minutes until heated through but still slightly crisp.\", \"Step 7: Add the cooled parboiled rice to the pan along with curry powder, thyme, seasoning cubes, soy sauce, and salt. Stir fry vigorously on high heat for 5 to 7 minutes, tossing continuously, until the rice is evenly coated in the yellow curry colour and well combined with all the vegetables and protein. Taste and adjust seasoning, then serve hot.\"], \"match_percentage\": 6.7, \"used_ingredients\": [\"onions\"], \"cook_time_minutes\": 30, \"prep_time_minutes\": 30, \"missing_ingredients\": [\"long grain rice\", \"carrots\", \"green peas\", \"bell peppers(green, yellow, red)\", \"liver\", \"vegetable oil\", \"garlic\", \"ginger\", \"curry powder\", \"thyme\", \"seasoning cubes\", \"soy sauce\", \"salt\", \"chicken stock\"]}, {\"name\": \"Nigerian Jollof Rice\", \"tips\": \"The secret to party jollof is double covering with foil and lid to trap steam, and finishing on high heat for the smoky bottom layer. Never use fresh tomatoes alone — always add tomato paste for depth of colour and flavour.\", \"servings\": 6, \"difficulty\": \"medium\", \"description\": \"Nigerian Jollof Rice is one of the most beloved dishes in West Africa, known for its rich smoky tomato flavour and vibrant orange-red colour. It is a staple at every Nigerian party, celebration, and family gathering. The secret to authentic Jollof Rice is the smoky bottom layer called party jollof which develops from cooking on high heat at the end.\", \"instructions\": [\"Step 1: Blend tomatoes, red bell peppers, long chilli peppers, scotch bonnet, and onions together in a blender until completely smooth with no chunks remaining. Set aside.\", \"Step 2: Wash rice thoroughly in cold water at least 3 times until water runs clear.\", \"Step 3: Heat vegetable oil in a large heavy-bottomed stainless steel or aluminum pot over medium-high heat for 2 minutes. Slice some onions, ginger and garlic paste, curry, thyme, bay leaves  and fry in the oil for 3 minutes.\", \"Step 4: Add tomato paste to the pot and fry with the mix for 3 minutes on medium heat, stirring constantly until the paste darkens slightly from bright red to a deeper reddish brown.\", \"Step 5: Pour the blended pepper mixture with some paprika into the pot. It will sizzle loudly — this is correct. Add in some seasoning cubes and salt. Fry on medium high heat uncovered for 25-30 minutes stirring every 5 minutes until all the water has evaporated, the oil floats on top, and the sauce has darkened to a deep red color. This step is critical — do not rush it.\", \"Step 6: Stir well and taste the sauce should be slightly salty as it will season the rice\", \"Step 7: Add the rice to the pot and stir well to coat every grain with the tomato sauce. Fry on high for like 2 minutes. Then add in chicken stock and some water enough to just cover the rice\", \"Step 8: Cover the pot tightly with foil first then place the lid on top to seal in all the steam. Cook on medium heat for 20 minutes without lifting the lid.\", \"Step 9: After 20 minutes lift the lid and check — rice should be almost fully cooked and liquid mostly absorbed. Stir gently from bottom to top. Cover again and cook on very low heat for 10 more minutes.\", \"Step 10: For the authentic party jollof smoky bottom, add in some cooking butter and sliced onions turn heat to high for the last 3-5 minutes. You will hear a crackling sound from the bottom — this is correct. Remove from heat immediately and leave covered for 5 minutes before serving.\"], \"match_percentage\": 6.2, \"used_ingredients\": [\"onions\"], \"cook_time_minutes\": 70, \"prep_time_minutes\": 20, \"missing_ingredients\": [\"long grain parboiled rice\", \"tomatoes\", \"red bell peppers (tatashe)\", \"long chilli peppers(shombo) \", \"scotch bonnet peppers (ata rodo)\", \"vegetable oil\", \"tomato paste\", \"chicken stock\", \"seasoning cubes\", \"curry powder\", \"thyme\", \"bay leaves\", \"garlic powder\", \"salt\", \"paprika\"]}, {\"name\": \"Nigerian Coleslaw\", \"tips\": \"The combination of mayonnaise and salad cream together, rather than just mayonnaise alone, is what gives Nigerian coleslaw its distinctive tangy sweetness. Always shred the cabbage very finely for the best texture, and let the coleslaw rest in the refrigerator before serving for the best flavour.\", \"servings\": 6, \"difficulty\": \"easy\", \"description\": \"Nigerian Coleslaw is a creamy and slightly sweet shredded cabbage and carrot salad that is a staple side dish at Nigerian parties, often served alongside Jollof Rice and Fried Rice. It differs from Western coleslaw by typically including diced apples, raisins, and a generously sweetened mayonnaise dressing.\", \"instructions\": [\"Step 1: Wash the cabbage thoroughly and shred very finely using a sharp knife or food processor — the cabbage should be cut into thin uniform strips for the best texture.\", \"Step 2: Peel and grate or finely julienne the carrots into thin matchstick pieces, similar in size to the shredded cabbage.\", \"Step 3: In a large bowl combine the shredded cabbage, grated carrots and sweet corn. Toss together gently.\", \"Step 4: In a separate small bowl mix mayonnaise and salad cream together in roughly equal parts, adding sugar to taste for the characteristic Nigerian sweetness, along with a pinch of black pepper and salt.\", \"Step 5: Pour the dressing over the vegetable mixture and toss thoroughly until every piece is well coated in the creamy dressing.\", \"Step 6: Taste and adjust sweetness and seasoning — Nigerian coleslaw is typically sweeter than standard Western coleslaw.\", \"Step 7: Cover and refrigerate for at least 1 hour before serving to allow the flavours to meld and the cabbage to soften slightly. Serve cold alongside Jollof Rice or Fried Rice.\"], \"match_percentage\": 0.0, \"used_ingredients\": [], \"cook_time_minutes\": 0, \"prep_time_minutes\": 25, \"missing_ingredients\": [\"cabbage\", \"carrots\", \"sweet corn\", \"mayonnaise\", \"salad cream\", \"sugar\", \"black pepper\", \"salt\"]}]}','2026-06-21 11:01:55'),('6ae9b9b8-3a29-4c5d-8749-cef9f6c96e9d','[\"pancake\"]','general',120,'{\"recipes\": [{\"name\": \"Pancake Recipe\", \"servings\": 4, \"difficulty\": \"easy\", \"description\": \"A classic breakfast dish from North America, pancakes are a staple food made from a batter of flour, eggs, and milk, known for their fluffy texture and sweet taste.\", \"instructions\": [\"Step 1: Start by cracking 2 eggs into a bowl and whisking them together with a fork for 2 minutes, until the eggs are well beaten and the whites are fully incorporated.\", \"Step 2: In a separate bowl, mix together 1 cup of flour and a pinch of salt, then add this dry mixture to the egg mixture and whisk for 2 minutes, until the batter is smooth and there are no lumps.\", \"Step 3: Heat a non-stick pan over medium heat for 2 minutes, until the pan is hot and a small amount of water sizzles when dropped onto the pan.\", \"Step 4: Using a 1/4 cup measuring cup, scoop the batter into the pan and cook for 2-3 minutes, until bubbles appear on the surface of the pancake and the edges start to dry.\", \"Step 5: Flip the pancake and cook for another 1-2 minutes, until the other side is golden brown.\", \"Step 6: Serve the pancake hot with your choice of toppings, such as syrup, butter, or fruit.\"], \"match_percentage\": 20, \"used_ingredients\": [\"pancake\"], \"cook_time_minutes\": 20, \"prep_time_minutes\": 10, \"missing_ingredients\": [\"eggs\", \"milk\", \"flour\", \"butter\"]}, {\"name\": \"Pancake Batter Recipe\", \"servings\": 4, \"difficulty\": \"easy\", \"description\": \"A classic breakfast dish from North America, pancakes are a staple food made from a batter of flour, eggs, and milk, known for their fluffy texture and sweet taste.\", \"instructions\": [\"Step 1: Start by cracking 2 eggs into a bowl and whisking them together with a fork for 2 minutes, until the eggs are well beaten and the whites are fully incorporated.\", \"Step 2: In a separate bowl, mix together 1 cup of flour and a pinch of salt, then add this dry mixture to the egg mixture and whisk for 2 minutes, until the batter is smooth and there are no lumps.\", \"Step 3: Add 1 tablespoon of sugar to the batter and whisk for 1 minute, until the sugar is fully incorporated and the batter is smooth.\", \"Step 4: Add 1/2 teaspoon of baking powder to the batter and whisk for 1 minute, until the baking powder is fully incorporated and the batter is smooth.\", \"Step 5: Let the batter rest for 5 minutes, until the flour is fully hydrated and the batter is smooth.\", \"Step 6: The batter is now ready to use, it can be stored in the fridge for up to 24 hours or frozen for up to 2 months.\"], \"match_percentage\": 20, \"used_ingredients\": [\"pancake\"], \"cook_time_minutes\": 0, \"prep_time_minutes\": 10, \"missing_ingredients\": [\"eggs\", \"milk\", \"flour\"]}, {\"name\": \"Pancake Topping Recipe\", \"servings\": 4, \"difficulty\": \"easy\", \"description\": \"A classic breakfast dish from North America, pancakes are a staple food made from a batter of flour, eggs, and milk, known for their fluffy texture and sweet taste.\", \"instructions\": [\"Step 1: Start by choosing a variety of toppings, such as syrup, butter, or fruit.\", \"Step 2: Heat the syrup in a saucepan over low heat for 2 minutes, until the syrup is warm and runny.\", \"Step 3: Add 1 tablespoon of butter to the syrup and whisk until the butter is fully melted.\", \"Step 4: Arrange the fruit slices on top of the pancake.\", \"Step 5: Drizzle the warm syrup over the fruit and pancake.\", \"Step 6: Serve the pancake with the toppings.\"], \"match_percentage\": 20, \"used_ingredients\": [\"pancake\"], \"cook_time_minutes\": 0, \"prep_time_minutes\": 5, \"missing_ingredients\": [\"syrup\", \"butter\", \"fruit\"]}, {\"name\": \"Pancake Syrup Recipe\", \"servings\": 4, \"difficulty\": \"easy\", \"description\": \"A classic breakfast dish from North America, pancakes are a staple food made from a batter of flour, eggs, and milk, known for their fluffy texture and sweet taste.\", \"instructions\": [\"Step 1: Start by combining 1 cup of sugar and 1 cup of water in a saucepan.\", \"Step 2: Heat the mixture over medium heat, stirring occasionally, until the sugar has dissolved.\", \"Step 3: Bring the mixture to a boil, then reduce the heat to low and simmer for 5 minutes.\", \"Step 4: Remove the syrup from the heat and let it cool.\", \"Step 5: The syrup is now ready to use, it can be stored in the fridge for up to 2 weeks.\"], \"match_percentage\": 20, \"used_ingredients\": [\"pancake\"], \"cook_time_minutes\": 10, \"prep_time_minutes\": 5, \"missing_ingredients\": [\"sugar\", \"water\"]}]}','2026-06-21 10:54:46'),('75b05fb2-ab4a-4101-b89d-2b4f48023822','[\"rice\", \"palm oil\", \"fish\", \"pepper\", \"iru\", \"onions\", \"crayfish\"]','nigerian',20,'{\"recipes\": [{\"name\": \"Palm Oil Fried Fish\", \"difficulty\": \"easy\", \"description\": \"A Nigerian dish where fish is fried in palm oil with spices\", \"instructions\": [\"Season the fish with salt and pepper\", \"Heat palm oil in a pan and fry the fish\", \"Add sliced onions and fry until golden brown\"], \"match_percentage\": 100, \"used_ingredients\": [\"fish\", \"palm oil\", \"pepper\", \"onions\"], \"prep_time_minutes\": 15, \"missing_ingredients\": [\"salt\"]}, {\"name\": \"Jollof Rice with Fish\", \"difficulty\": \"medium\", \"description\": \"A Nigerian one-pot dish where rice is cooked with fish and spices\", \"instructions\": [\"Heat palm oil in a pot and fry the fish\", \"Add sliced onions and pepper, then add rice\", \"Add water and cook until the rice is done\"], \"match_percentage\": 83, \"used_ingredients\": [\"rice\", \"fish\", \"palm oil\", \"pepper\", \"onions\"], \"prep_time_minutes\": 20, \"missing_ingredients\": [\"tomatoes\", \"salt\"]}, {\"name\": \"Crayfish and Iru Pepper Sauce\", \"difficulty\": \"easy\", \"description\": \"A Nigerian pepper sauce where crayfish and iru are blended with pepper\", \"instructions\": [\"Blend crayfish, iru, pepper, and onions together\", \"Add a little water to achieve the desired consistency\"], \"match_percentage\": 80, \"used_ingredients\": [\"crayfish\", \"iru\", \"pepper\", \"onions\"], \"prep_time_minutes\": 10, \"missing_ingredients\": [\"salt\", \"water\"]}, {\"name\": \"Palm Oil Rice\", \"difficulty\": \"easy\", \"description\": \"A simple Nigerian dish where rice is cooked with palm oil and spices\", \"instructions\": [\"Heat palm oil in a pot and add sliced onions\", \"Add rice and stir well\", \"Add water and cook until the rice is done\"], \"match_percentage\": 80, \"used_ingredients\": [\"rice\", \"palm oil\", \"pepper\", \"onions\"], \"prep_time_minutes\": 15, \"missing_ingredients\": [\"salt\"]}, {\"name\": \"Grilled Fish with Crayfish and Pepper\", \"difficulty\": \"medium\", \"description\": \"A Nigerian dish where fish is grilled with crayfish and pepper\", \"instructions\": [\"Season the fish with salt, pepper, and crayfish\", \"Grill the fish until it is cooked through\", \"Serve with sliced onions\"], \"match_percentage\": 80, \"used_ingredients\": [\"fish\", \"crayfish\", \"pepper\", \"onions\"], \"prep_time_minutes\": 15, \"missing_ingredients\": [\"salt\", \"lemon\"]}]}','2026-06-14 17:38:49'),('7e4f05c7-fe0b-4714-ab0b-4a52a049cc91','[\"rice\", \"tomatoes\", \"tomato paste\", \"onions\", \"vegetable oil\", \"chicken\", \"seasoning cubes\", \"curry powder\", \"thyme\", \"bay leaves\"]','nigerian',NULL,'{\"almost_there\": [{\"name\": \"Nigerian Jollof Rice\", \"tips\": \"The secret to party jollof is double covering with foil and lid to trap steam, and finishing on high heat for the smoky bottom layer. Never use fresh tomatoes alone — always add tomato paste for depth of colour and flavour.\", \"servings\": 6, \"difficulty\": \"medium\", \"description\": \"Nigerian Jollof Rice is one of the most beloved dishes in West Africa, known for its rich smoky tomato flavour and vibrant orange-red colour. It is a staple at every Nigerian party, celebration, and family gathering. The secret to authentic Jollof Rice is the smoky bottom layer called party jollof which develops from cooking on high heat at the end.\", \"instructions\": [\"Step 1: Blend tomatoes, red bell peppers, long chilli peppers, scotch bonnet, and onions together in a blender until completely smooth with no chunks remaining. Set aside.\", \"Step 2: Wash rice thoroughly in cold water at least 3 times until water runs clear.\", \"Step 3: Heat vegetable oil in a large heavy-bottomed stainless steel or aluminum pot over medium-high heat for 2 minutes. Slice some onions, ginger and garlic paste, curry, thyme, bay leaves  and fry in the oil for 3 minutes.\", \"Step 4: Add tomato paste to the pot and fry with the mix for 3 minutes on medium heat, stirring constantly until the paste darkens slightly from bright red to a deeper reddish brown.\", \"Step 5: Pour the blended pepper mixture with some paprika into the pot. It will sizzle loudly — this is correct. Add in some seasoning cubes and salt. Fry on medium high heat uncovered for 25-30 minutes stirring every 5 minutes until all the water has evaporated, the oil floats on top, and the sauce has darkened to a deep red color. This step is critical — do not rush it.\", \"Step 6: Stir well and taste the sauce should be slightly salty as it will season the rice\", \"Step 7: Add the rice to the pot and stir well to coat every grain with the tomato sauce. Fry on high for like 2 minutes. Then add in chicken stock and some water enough to just cover the rice\", \"Step 8: Cover the pot tightly with foil first then place the lid on top to seal in all the steam. Cook on medium heat for 20 minutes without lifting the lid.\", \"Step 9: After 20 minutes lift the lid and check — rice should be almost fully cooked and liquid mostly absorbed. Stir gently from bottom to top. Cover again and cook on very low heat for 10 more minutes.\", \"Step 10: For the authentic party jollof smoky bottom, add in some cooking butter and sliced onions turn heat to high for the last 3-5 minutes. You will hear a crackling sound from the bottom — this is correct. Remove from heat immediately and leave covered for 5 minutes before serving.\"], \"match_percentage\": 62.5, \"used_ingredients\": [\"long grain parboiled rice\", \"tomatoes\", \"onions\", \"vegetable oil\", \"tomato paste\", \"chicken stock\", \"seasoning cubes\", \"curry powder\", \"thyme\", \"bay leaves\"], \"cook_time_minutes\": 70, \"prep_time_minutes\": 20, \"missing_ingredients\": [\"red bell peppers (tatashe)\", \"long chilli peppers(shombo) \", \"scotch bonnet peppers (ata rodo)\", \"garlic powder\", \"salt\", \"paprika\"]}], \"can_make_now\": [], \"needs_shopping\": [{\"name\": \"Nigerian Fried Rice\", \"tips\": \"Always cook on high heat when frying the rice and vegetables together to prevent everything from steaming and becoming soggy instead of stir-fried.\", \"servings\": 6, \"difficulty\": \"medium\", \"description\": \"Nigerian Fried Rice is a colourful and flavourful party staple made with parboiled rice stir-fried with mixed vegetables, liver, and a distinct curry seasoning. Unlike Chinese fried rice, the Nigerian version has a unique orange-yellow hue from curry powder and is loaded with vegetables, making it one of the most popular dishes at Nigerian celebrations alongside Jollof Rice.\", \"instructions\": [\"Step 1: Wash the rice thoroughly until water runs clear then transfer into a seive till perfectly dry. Then into a pot, add some oil and fry the rice for about 5 minutes\", \"Step 2: Season the liver with salt and a little curry powder. Cook in a pot with a small amount of water for 8 to 10 minutes until just cooked through, then dice into small cubes.\", \"Step 3: Dice carrots and green beans into small uniform cubes for even cooking. Set aside along with the bell peppers.\", \"Step 4: Heat vegetable oil in a large wok or wide pan on high heat. Add minced garlic and ginger and stir fry for 30 seconds until fragrant but not browned.\", \"Step 5: Add diced onions and stir fry for 2 minutes until softened. Add the diced liver and shrimp and stir fry for 2 minutes.\", \"Step 6: Add the carrots, green beans, green peas, and bell peppers to the pan. Stir fry on high heat for 3 minutes until heated through but still slightly crisp.\", \"Step 7: Add the cooled parboiled rice to the pan along with curry powder, thyme, seasoning cubes, soy sauce, and salt. Stir fry vigorously on high heat for 5 to 7 minutes, tossing continuously, until the rice is evenly coated in the yellow curry colour and well combined with all the vegetables and protein. Taste and adjust seasoning, then serve hot.\"], \"match_percentage\": 46.7, \"used_ingredients\": [\"long grain rice\", \"vegetable oil\", \"onions\", \"curry powder\", \"thyme\", \"seasoning cubes\", \"chicken stock\"], \"cook_time_minutes\": 30, \"prep_time_minutes\": 30, \"missing_ingredients\": [\"carrots\", \"green peas\", \"bell peppers(green, yellow, red)\", \"liver\", \"garlic\", \"ginger\", \"soy sauce\", \"salt\"]}, {\"name\": \"Asun\", \"tips\": \"Grilling or smoking the goat meat after boiling is non-negotiable for authentic Asun — without the charred smoky exterior the dish is just peppered goat meat not Asun. Use goat meat with the skin on for the best texture and flavour. The pepper sauce should have chunky sliced peppers not a blended smooth sauce.\", \"servings\": 4, \"difficulty\": \"medium\", \"description\": \"Asun is a popular Yoruba delicacy of smoked or roasted goat meat cut into small pieces and tossed in a fiery pepper and onion sauce. It originates from Ondo State in Yorubaland and is now one of the most popular Nigerian party small chops and appetisers served across the country. The goat meat is first smoked or roasted to give it a distinctive charred flavour before being peppered.\", \"instructions\": [\"Step 1: Wash the goat meat thoroughly — authentic Asun uses goat meat with the skin on as the skin adds texture and flavour. Cut into medium sized chunks. Season with seasoning cubes, curry powder, thyme, ginger garlic paste and salt.\", \"Step 2: Cook the seasoned goat meat in a pot with a small amount of water on medium heat for 20 to 25 minutes until tender but not falling apart.\", \"Step 3: Remove the cooked goat meat and place directly on a grill, open flame, or in a very hot oven at 220 degrees Celsius. Grill or roast for 15 to 20 minutes turning occasionally until the outside is charred and smoky and the skin is slightly crispy. The charring is essential for authentic Asun flavour.\", \"Step 4: Remove from the grill and cut into smaller bite sized pieces while still hot. Set aside.\", \"Step 5: Slice scotch bonnet peppers, green bell pepper, red bell pepper, and onions into thin strips. The peppers should be sliced not blended, a food processor can be used as well — the chunky pepper pieces are characteristic of Asun.\", \"Step 6: Heat vegetable oil in a wide pan on medium heat. Add the sliced onions and fry for 2 minutes until slightly softened.\", \"Step 7: Add all the sliced peppers to the pan and stir fry on high heat for 3 to 4 minutes — the peppers should be cooked but still have a slight crunch. Do not overcook the peppers into mush.\", \"Step 8: Add the grilled goat meat pieces to the pan and toss vigorously with the peppers for 3 minutes on high heat until the meat is well coated in the pepper mixture and everything is sizzling hot. Taste and adjust seasoning. Serve immediately as a party appetiser or small chop.\"], \"match_percentage\": 45.5, \"used_ingredients\": [\"onions\", \"vegetable oil\", \"seasoning cubes\", \"curry powder\", \"thyme\"], \"cook_time_minutes\": 60, \"prep_time_minutes\": 20, \"missing_ingredients\": [\"goat meat (skin on)\", \"scotch bonnet peppers\", \"green bell pepper\", \"red bell pepper (tatashe)\", \"salt\", \"ginger garlic paste\"]}, {\"name\": \"Akara\", \"tips\": \"Whisking the bean paste until very fluffy is the secret to light soft akara — never skip this step. Also make sure the oil is very hot before adding the paste otherwise the akara will absorb too much oil and become greasy. Wet your spoon with oil before scooping each portion to help the paste slide off cleanly into the oil.\", \"servings\": 4, \"difficulty\": \"medium\", \"description\": \"Akara is a traditional Yoruba deep fried bean cake made from peeled black eyed beans blended into a smooth aerated paste and fried in hot oil until crispy on the outside and soft inside. It is a quintessential Nigerian breakfast food sold by roadside vendors across the country and best eaten hot with ogi (pap) or bread.\", \"instructions\": [\"Step 1: Peel the beans using one of two methods. Traditional method: Soak beans in cold water for 30 minutes then rub between palms under running water until all skins float off and are drained away. Quick method: Pulse beans and water  in a food processor for 30 seconds to crack and loosen skins, pour into a bowl of water, skim off floating skins, and drain. Rinse peeled beans two to three times in clean water.\", \"Step 2: Place the peeled beans alongside the peppers and onions in a blender with a very small amount of water — just enough to move the blender. Blend on high speed for 3 minutes until the paste is completely smooth and thick. The paste must be thick not watery — too much water will make flat oily akara.\", \"Step 3: Pour the blended bean paste into a large bowl. Using a wooden spoon or electric hand mixer whisk the paste vigorously for 5 to 7 minutes until it becomes very fluffy, lighter in colour, and almost doubles in volume. This is the most important step — the air you whisk in is what makes akara light and fluffy inside.\", \"Step 4: Add some salt and seasoning cubes to the whisked paste. Fold gently into the paste without deflating it. Taste and adjust seasoning.\", \"Step 5: Pour enough vegetable oil into a deep wide pan to allow the akara to float — at least 3 inches deep. Heat on medium-high heat for 2 to 3 minutes until hot. Test the oil by dropping a tiny bit of paste in — it should rise immediately to the surface and sizzle vigorously. If it sinks the oil is not hot enough.\", \"Step 6: Wet your tablespoon with oil and scoop portions of the paste into the hot oil one at a time. Do not overcrowd the pan — leave space between each akara so they cook evenly and stay round.\", \"Step 7: Fry on medium heat for 3 to 4 minutes until the bottom is deep golden brown, then flip carefully with a slotted spoon or skewer and fry the other side for 2 to 3 minutes until evenly golden brown and crispy all over.\", \"Step 8: Remove with a slotted spoon and drain on paper towels to absorb excess oil. Serve immediately while hot and crispy alongside ogi (pap) or as a breakfast snack.\"], \"match_percentage\": 42.9, \"used_ingredients\": [\"onions\", \"seasoning cubes\", \"vegetable oil for deep frying\"], \"cook_time_minutes\": 20, \"prep_time_minutes\": 30, \"missing_ingredients\": [\"black eyed beans\", \"scotch bonnet peppers\", \"long chilli peppers(shombo)\", \"salt\"]}, {\"name\": \"Nigerian Pepper Soup\", \"tips\": \"The quality of your pepper soup spice mix makes or breaks this dish. Use freshly ground spices if possible — uda (country onion), ehuru (calabash nutmeg), and uziza seeds ground together give the most authentic flavour. Never cover the pot fully while cooking pepper soup — leave it slightly open so the broth reduces and concentrates.\", \"servings\": 4, \"difficulty\": \"easy\", \"description\": \"Nigerian Pepper Soup is a light, intensely spiced broth made with meat or fish and a unique blend of pepper soup spices. It is served at every Nigerian gathering, used as a remedy for colds and fever, and eaten as a starter or main dish. The broth is thin but deeply flavoured with a distinctive warming heat that comes from the special pepper soup spice blend.\", \"instructions\": [\"Step 1: Wash the meat thoroughly and cut into medium sized pieces. Season with onions, seasoning cubes, and salt. Do not add water yet — allow the meat to cook in its own juices first.\", \"Step 2: Place the seasoned meat in a pot on medium heat and cook dry for 10 minutes stirring occasionally until the meat releases its juices and begins to brown slightly on the outside.\", \"Step 3: Add enough water to cover the meat completely. Bring to a boil on high heat then reduce to medium heat. Cook for 25 to 30 minutes for goat meat or 15 minutes for chicken until the meat is tender but not falling off the bone.\", \"Step 4: Add the pepper soup spice mix, ground crayfish, and blended or roughly crushed scotch bonnet peppers. Stir well and taste — the broth should be well seasoned and spicy at this point. Add more seasoning cubes and salt if needed.\", \"Step 5: Cook on medium heat for another 15 minutes until the spices have fully infused into the broth and the liquid has reduced slightly. The broth should be a light golden brown colour and smell intensely aromatic.\", \"Step 6: Tear utazi leaves into small pieces and add to the pot — utazi adds a slight bitterness that balances the heat. Add uziza leaves whole or roughly torn. Cook for 3 minutes only.\", \"Step 7: Taste one final time and adjust salt and pepper. The pepper soup should be very hot and spicy, lightly bitter from the utazi, and deeply aromatic from the spice blend. Serve hot in deep bowls with sliced onions on top and agidi or white rice on the side.\"], \"match_percentage\": 30.0, \"used_ingredients\": [\"goat meat or chicken or catfish\", \"onions\", \"seasoning cubes\"], \"cook_time_minutes\": 55, \"prep_time_minutes\": 15, \"missing_ingredients\": [\"pepper soup spice mix\", \"scotch bonnet peppers\", \"crayfish\", \"uziza leaves\", \"utazi leaves\", \"salt\", \"water\"]}, {\"name\": \"Moi Moi\", \"tips\": \"The food processor peeling method is a game changer — it cuts prep time from 30 minutes to 5 minutes. The two most important steps are removing every single bean skin and whisking the paste vigorously to aerate it before adding seasoning. Skipping either step will result in dense heavy Moi Moi. Always fill containers only three quarters full as the paste expands during steaming.\", \"servings\": 8, \"difficulty\": \"medium\", \"description\": \"Moi Moi is a traditional Nigerian steamed bean pudding made from peeled beans blended into a smooth paste. It is a beloved dish across all Nigerian tribes and is served at parties, as a side dish with rice or ogi, or eaten alone as a complete meal. The texture should be firm yet soft and moist inside with a rich savoury flavour.\", \"instructions\": [\"Step 1: There are two ways to peel the beans. Traditional method: Pour beans into a bowl and soak in cold water for 30 minutes until the skins begin to loosen and soften, then rub vigorously between both palms under running water until all skins float off. Quick method: Pour dry beans into a food processor with some water and pulse for 30 to 45 seconds — the food processor will crack and loosen the skins without grinding the beans. Pour the pulsed beans into a large bowl of water, the skins will float to the top — skim them off and drain. Repeat until all skins are removed. The quick method takes 5 minutes instead of 30.\", \"Step 2: Rinse the peeled beans thoroughly in clean water two to three times to remove any remaining skin fragments. The beans should be completely white with no dark skin remaining — any leftover skin will make the Moi Moi rough and bitter.\", \"Step 3: Place the peeled beans directly into the blender together with the scotch bonnet peppers, red bell pepper, onions, one raw egg, and a very small amount of water — just enough to get the blender moving. Blend everything together on high speed for 3 minutes until the paste is completely smooth with absolutely no grainy texture. Blending the peppers and egg together with the beans at this stage gives the Moi Moi its full flavour and colour from the inside.\", \"Step 4: Pour the blended paste into a large bowl. Add seasoning cubes, vegetable oil, and salt. Mix everything together thoroughly until well combined. Taste and adjust seasoning — it should be well seasoned and slightly peppery.\", \"Step 5: Using a wooden spoon or electric hand mixer, whisk the paste vigorously for 5 minutes until it becomes fluffy, lighter in colour, and increases slightly in volume. This aerates the paste and gives Moi Moi its soft moist texture when steamed.\", \"Step 6: Break the mackerel fish into medium sized chunks and slice your boiled eggs and set aside. Grease foil containers or moi moi leaves generously with vegetable oil on the inside so the moi moi does not stick.\", \"Step 7: Pour the bean paste mixture into each container filling only three quarters full. Drop pieces of fish directly into the paste in each container alongside the sliced eggs  — the fish sits inside the moi moi not on top. Press down lightly so the fish is submerged in the paste.\", \"Step 8: Seal each foil container tightly by folding the edges over securely. No steam should be able to escape during cooking.\", \"Step 9: Place a trivet or folded foil at the bottom of a large pot to prevent direct heat contact. Arrange the sealed moi moi containers in the pot and add water to reach halfway up the sides of the containers.\", \"Step 10: Cover the pot tightly and steam on medium heat for 45 to 60 minutes. Check water level every 15 minutes and add more hot water if needed — never let the pot run dry. Moi Moi is ready when it feels firm when pressed gently and pulls away cleanly from the container when opened.\"], \"match_percentage\": 27.3, \"used_ingredients\": [\"onions\", \"vegetable oil\", \"seasoning cubes\"], \"cook_time_minutes\": 60, \"prep_time_minutes\": 40, \"missing_ingredients\": [\"beans\", \"scotch bonnet peppers\", \"long chilli pepper (shombo)\", \"crayfish\", \"salt\", \"eggs\", \"fish (preferably mackerel fish)\", \"water\"]}, {\"name\": \"Asaro (Yam Porridge)\", \"tips\": \"Gentle stirring lets some yam break down to thicken the sauce naturally without becoming completely mashed.\", \"servings\": 4, \"difficulty\": \"easy\", \"description\": \"Asaro is a beloved traditional Yoruba yam porridge made by cooking yam chunks directly in a rich tomato and pepper sauce until the yam softens and thickens the entire dish into a hearty one-pot meal.\", \"instructions\": [\"Step 1: Peel the yam and cut into medium sized chunks. Wash thoroughly.\", \"Step 2: Blend onions, tatashe, and scotch bonnet peppers together into a smooth paste.\", \"Step 3: Place the yam chunks in a pot with the blended pepper mixture, sliced onions, palm oil, and enough water to just cover the yam.\", \"Step 4: Bring to a boil then reduce to medium heat. Cook for 20 to 25 minutes, stirring occasionally, until the yam softens and breaks down at the edges.\", \"Step 5: Add ground crayfish, flaked fish, seasoning cubes, and salt. Stir gently.\", \"Step 6: Continue cooking on medium-low heat for 8 to 10 minutes until thick and stew-like.\", \"Step 7: Taste and adjust seasoning. Serve hot on its own.\"], \"match_percentage\": 27.3, \"used_ingredients\": [\"tomatoes\", \"onions\", \"seasoning cubes\"], \"cook_time_minutes\": 40, \"prep_time_minutes\": 15, \"missing_ingredients\": [\"yam (white yam)\", \"tatashe (red bell pepper)\", \"scotch bonnet peppers\", \"palm oil\", \"crayfish\", \"smoked fish or dried fish\", \"salt\", \"water\"]}, {\"name\": \"Ewa Agoyin\", \"tips\": \"The two secrets to authentic Ewa Agoyin are cooking the beans with a lot of onions until completely mashable with no whole beans remaining, and making the Agoyin stew with only dried peppers not fresh ones. Fresh peppers will not give the deep dark colour and concentrated flavour that makes Agoyin stew unique. The stew must be dark, dry, and almost burnt looking — that is correct.\", \"servings\": 4, \"difficulty\": \"medium\", \"description\": \"Ewa Agoyin is a popular Yoruba street food originally brought to Nigeria by Beninese traders, consisting of soft completely mashed honey beans or black eyed beans served with a deeply dark and spicy Agoyin stew made from dried red peppers and palm oil. It is a beloved Lagos breakfast food sold by roadside vendors and eaten with agege bread.\", \"instructions\": [\"Step 1: Wash the beans thoroughly then cover the beans with fresh water and cook on high heat until boiling, then reduce to medium heat. Cook for 45 to 60 minutes until the beans are extremely soft — they should mash completely between your fingers with no resistance. Add more water as needed during cooking to prevent burning.\", \"Step 2: Once the beans are very soft, use a wooden spoon or potato masher to mash them completely in the pot until no whole beans remain. The consistency should be thick and porridge-like. Season with salt, stir well, and set aside.\", \"Step 4: While the beans cook prepare the Agoyin stew. Rehydrate the dried red peppers and dried chilli peppers by soaking in hot water for 20 minutes until soft. Drain and blend alongside some onions and ginger into a rough paste — not completely smooth, leave some texture.\", \"Step 5: Heat palm oil in a separate pot on medium heat until hot. Slice onions into thin rings and fry in the palm oil for 10 minutes on medium-low heat, stirring constantly until the onions are very dark brown and almost caramelised — this dark onion is essential to the Agoyin stew flavour.\", \"Step 6: Add the blended dried pepper mixture to the dark onions and palm oil. Stir well and fry on medium heat for 20 to 25 minutes stirring every 3 minutes until all moisture evaporates, the stew becomes very dark, thick, and dry, and the oil floats on top. The stew should be almost black in colour — this is correct.\", \"Step 7: Add seasoning cubes and salt to the stew. Stir well and cook for 5 more minutes. The finished Agoyin stew should be very dark, very dry, very spicy, and intensely flavoured.\", \"Step 8: Serve the mashed beans in a bowl and pour the dark Agoyin stew generously on top. Eat with agege bread, fried plantain, or on its own.\"], \"match_percentage\": 22.2, \"used_ingredients\": [\"onions\", \"seasoning cubes\"], \"cook_time_minutes\": 90, \"prep_time_minutes\": 20, \"missing_ingredients\": [\"beans\", \"dried red peppers (tatashe)\", \"dried long chilli bonnet peppers(shombo)\", \"palm oil\", \"crayfish\", \"salt\", \"water\"]}, {\"name\": \"Ayamase (Ofada Stew)\", \"tips\": \"Bleaching the palm oil is absolutely non-negotiable for authentic Ayamase. Only use green peppers and unripe tatashe — no red peppers at all. The more assorted meats you use the richer and more authentic the stew will be.\", \"servings\": 6, \"difficulty\": \"hard\", \"description\": \"Ayamase also known as Ofada Stew or Designer Stew is a rich and intensely flavoured Yoruba stew made exclusively with green peppers and unripe tatashe giving it its distinctive green colour. It is traditionally served with Ofada rice and the stew is made with bleached palm oil and loaded with assorted meats making it one of the most indulgent Nigerian dishes.\", \"instructions\": [\"Step 1: Wash and season all assorted meats with onions, seasoning cubes, ginger garlic paste and salt. Cook in a pot on medium heat for 25 to 35 minutes until very tender. Fry the cooked meats in a small amount of oil until lightly browned on the outside for extra flavour. Set aside with the stock.\", \"Step 2: Blend green bell peppers, unripe green tatashe, green scotch bonnet peppers, and onions together into a coarse paste — do not blend completely smooth, leave some texture. The stew must use only green peppers and unripe tatashe — never red peppers or ripe tatashe as this completely changes the dish.\", \"Step 3: Bleach the palm oil by heating it in a pot on high heat with the lid on for 10 to 15 minutes until the oil turns from orange-red to a pale golden yellow colour and begins to smoke lightly. Remove from heat and allow to cool slightly. Bleached palm oil is essential for authentic Ayamase.\", \"Step 4: Return the bleached palm oil to medium heat. Add sliced onions with some ginger garlic paste and fry for 3 minutes until soft and slightly golden.\", \"Step 5: Pour the blended green pepper mixture into the bleached palm oil. It will sizzle vigorously stir immediately. Fry on high heat for 15 to 20 minutes stirring every 3 to 4 minutes until all the water has completely evaporated, the oil floats on top, and the pepper sauce is cooked down and thick.\", \"Step 6: Add iru (locust beans) and ground crayfish to the cooked pepper base and stir well. Fry for 3 more minutes until the iru is fragrant and well incorporated.\", \"Step 7: Add all the assorted meats and a ladle of the meat stock. Stir everything together to coat the meat in the green pepper sauce. Cook on medium heat for 10 minutes until the meat is well flavoured and the stew is thick and rich.\", \"Step 8: Taste and adjust seasoning. The finished Ayamase should be dark olive green, thick, intensely flavoured, and very rich with assorted meats. Serve with Ofada rice.\"], \"match_percentage\": 18.2, \"used_ingredients\": [\"onions\", \"seasoning cubes\"], \"cook_time_minutes\": 90, \"prep_time_minutes\": 25, \"missing_ingredients\": [\"green bell peppers\", \"unripe tatashe (green tatashe)\", \"green scotch bonnet peppers\", \"palm oil\", \"assorted meat (beef, tripe, shaki, pomo, liver)\", \"crayfish\", \"iru (locust beans)\", \"ginger and garlic paste\", \"salt\"]}, {\"name\": \"Banga Stew\", \"tips\": \"The key difference between Banga Soup and Banga Stew is the reduction time — cook the stew version longer uncovered to achieve a thicker consistency that coats rice or yam well rather than the more liquid soup form.\", \"servings\": 5, \"difficulty\": \"hard\", \"description\": \"Banga Stew is a thick, deeply flavoured Igbo stew made from concentrated palm fruit extract, prepared similarly to Banga Soup but cooked down to a thicker consistency more like a stew than a soup. It is rich, nutty, and aromatic, traditionally seasoned with banga spices, and served with white rice, boiled yam, or plantain.\", \"instructions\": [\"Step 1: If using fresh palm fruit, boil for 20 to 30 minutes until soft, then pound to separate pulp from nuts and squeeze with warm water to extract the thick orange juice. Strain through a sieve to remove fibres. If using canned concentrate, dilute according to package instructions.\", \"Step 2: Pour the palm fruit extract into a pot and bring to a boil on high heat, then reduce to medium heat and simmer for 15 to 20 minutes until the oil begins to separate and rise to the surface.\", \"Step 3: Season the assorted meat with onions, seasoning cubes, and salt. Cook separately on medium heat for 30 minutes until tender. Add the cooked meat and stock to the palm fruit base.\", \"Step 4: Add the banga spice mix to the pot and simmer for 15 minutes to allow the spices to infuse fully into the base.\", \"Step 5: Add dried fish, ground crayfish, sliced scotch bonnet peppers, and seasoning cubes. Stir well and continue cooking on medium heat, allowing the liquid to reduce and thicken for 20 to 25 minutes — unlike Banga Soup this should reduce further into a thicker stew-like consistency.\", \"Step 6: Add the fresh fish pieces and cook gently for 8 to 10 minutes until just cooked through, stirring carefully to avoid breaking the fish apart.\", \"Step 7: Continue simmering uncovered for an additional 10 minutes, stirring occasionally, until the stew has thickened noticeably and the oil is clearly visible on the surface.\", \"Step 8: Remove the oburunbebe stick before serving. Taste and adjust seasoning. Serve hot with white rice, boiled yam, or plantain.\"], \"match_percentage\": 18.2, \"used_ingredients\": [\"onions\", \"seasoning cubes\"], \"cook_time_minutes\": 80, \"prep_time_minutes\": 30, \"missing_ingredients\": [\"fresh palm fruit (or canned banga concentrate)\", \"assorted meat (beef, tripe)\", \"dried fish\", \"fresh fish\", \"banga spice mix (oburunbebe stick, dried bitter leaf)\", \"scotch bonnet peppers\", \"crayfish\", \"salt\", \"water\"]}, {\"name\": \"Efo Riro\", \"tips\": \"The most important step is frying the pepper base completely dry until the oil floats on top before adding any meat or stock. This is what separates a rich deeply flavoured Efo Riro from a watery one. Also add the vegetables at the very last minute and cook for 2 minutes only — overcooked vegetables will turn dark and lose their flavour.\", \"servings\": 6, \"difficulty\": \"medium\", \"description\": \"Efo Riro is a rich Yoruba vegetable soup made with tatashe and ata rodo as the pepper base, assorted meats, and leafy green vegetables. The name means stirred leafy vegetable in Yoruba. It is one of the most flavourful Nigerian soups with a vibrant green and red colour from the vegetables and pepper base. It is served with amala, eba, pounded yam, or rice.\", \"instructions\": [\"Step 1: Wash and season assorted meat, pomo, and stockfish with onions, seasoning cubes, and salt. Cook on medium heat for 20 to 30 minutes until very tender. Set aside with the stock.\", \"Step 2: Blend tatashe and scotch bonnet peppers together into a smooth paste. Do not add water — the peppers have enough natural liquid. Set aside.\", \"Step 3: Wash the efo tete or spinach thoroughly, shred into medium sized pieces by hand, and set aside in a colander to drain excess water.\", \"Step 4: Heat palm oil in a large pot on medium-high heat for 2 minutes. Slice onions and fry in the palm oil for 3 minutes until golden and fragrant.\", \"Step 5: Add the blended tatashe and scotch bonnet pepper mixture to the pot. It will sizzle loudly in the hot oil — this is correct. Fry on high heat for 10 to 20 minutes stirring every 3 minutes until all the water has completely evaporated, the oil floats on top, and the pepper sauce has darkened and thickened. This step gives Efo Riro its deep rich flavour.\", \"Step 6: Add iru (locust beans) and ground crayfish and stir into the pepper sauce. Fry for 2 more minutes until the iru is fragrant.\", \"Step 7: Add the cooked assorted meat, stockfish, dried fish, and a ladle of the meat stock. Stir everything together and cook on medium heat for 10 minutes until the meat is well coated in the sauce.\", \"Step 8: Add the shredded efo tete or spinach to the pot and stir into the sauce. Cook for exactly 2 minutes only on medium heat — the vegetables should wilt into the soup but remain bright green and not soggy. Taste, adjust seasoning, and remove from heat immediately. Serve with amala, eba, or pounded yam.\"], \"match_percentage\": 16.7, \"used_ingredients\": [\"onions\", \"seasoning cubes\"], \"cook_time_minutes\": 75, \"prep_time_minutes\": 25, \"missing_ingredients\": [\"vgetables African spinach or ugwu\", \"tatashe (red bell pepper)\", \"scotch bonnet peppers (ata rodo)\", \"palm oil\", \"assorted meat (beef, tripe, shaki, pomo)\", \"stockfish\", \"dried fish\", \"crayfish\", \"iru (locust beans)\", \"salt\"]}, {\"name\": \"Egusi Soup Yoruba Style\", \"tips\": \"The secret to Yoruba egusi is frying the egusi completely dry in palm oil before adding any liquid. Never add water or stock to the egusi while frying — it must fry and toast in the oil until golden. Also never add tomatoes to Yoruba egusi soup — that changes the flavour profile completely.\", \"servings\": 6, \"difficulty\": \"medium\", \"description\": \"Egusi Soup Yoruba style is a rich and hearty Nigerian soup made with ground melon seeds fried directly in palm oil before any liquid is added. Unlike Igbo style egusi which is added raw, Yoruba style fries the egusi first until golden and nutty giving it a deeper richer flavour. It is served with amala, eba, or pounded yam.\", \"instructions\": [\"Step 1: Wash and season assorted meat and stockfish with onions, seasoning cubes, and salt. Cook in a pot on medium heat for 15 to 20 minutes until tender. Set aside with the stock.\", \"Step 2: Blend scotch bonnet peppers, tatashe, and half the onions together into a smooth paste. Set aside.\", \"Step 3: Heat palm oil in a large pot on medium heat for 2 minutes until melted and hot but not bleached. Chop the remaining onions and fry in the palm oil for 3 minutes until soft and translucent.\", \"Step 4: Add the ground egusi to the palm oil and stir immediately to combine. Fry the egusi in the palm oil on medium heat for 8 to 10 minutes stirring constantly until the egusi turns golden, smells nutty, and pulls away from the sides of the pot. Do not add any liquid at this stage — dry frying is the key to Yoruba egusi.\", \"Step 5: Add the blended pepper mixture to the fried egusi and stir well to combine. Fry together for another 10 minutes on medium heat stirring every 2 minutes until the pepper is cooked and oil begins to float on the surface.\", \"Step 6: Add the cooked meat, stockfish, dried fish, meat stock, ground crayfish, iru, and seasoning cubes. Stir everything together and add a small amount of water if the soup is too thick. Cook on medium heat for 15 minutes until all the flavours come together.\", \"Step 7: Taste and adjust salt and seasoning. The soup should be rich, thick, and deeply flavoured at this point.\", \"Step 8: Add shredded spinach or efo tete and stir into the soup. Cook for exactly 2 minutes only — overcooking the vegetables will make them lose their colour and become soggy. Remove from heat and serve immediately with amala, eba, or pounded yam.\"], \"match_percentage\": 15.4, \"used_ingredients\": [\"onions\", \"seasoning cubes\"], \"cook_time_minutes\": 70, \"prep_time_minutes\": 20, \"missing_ingredients\": [\"ground egusi (melon seeds)\", \"palm oil\", \"assorted meat (beef, tripe, shaki)\", \"stockfish\", \"dried fish\", \"scotch bonnet peppers\", \"tatashe (red bell pepper)\", \"crayfish\", \"iru (locust beans)\", \"spinach, efo tete or ugwu\", \"salt\"]}, {\"name\": \"Ikokore\", \"tips\": \"Use water yam specifically not white yam or cocoyam. Do not rinse the grated yam before adding to the pot as the natural starch thickens the broth and holds the dumplings together.\", \"servings\": 4, \"difficulty\": \"medium\", \"description\": \"Ikokore is a traditional Ijebu Yoruba dish made from grated water yam cooked in a rich pepper soup or tomato base with assorted fish and seafood. The grated water yam forms thick irregular dumplings in the broth giving the dish its characteristic texture. It is a beloved dish in Ogun State and across Yorubaland.\", \"instructions\": [\"Step 1: Peel the water yam and grate on the coarse side of a grater into a bowl. Do not rinse the grated yam — the natural starch is needed to hold the dumplings together. Season the grated yam lightly with salt and set aside.\", \"Step 2: Blend scotch bonnet peppers, long chilli peppers, and onions together into a smooth paste.\", \"Step 3: Heat palm oil in a large pot on medium heat. Add iru and fry for 1 minute until fragrant. Add the blended pepper mixture and fry for 15 minutes until cooked and oil floats on top.\", \"Step 4: Add enough meat stock to the pot . Add ground crayfish, dried fish, smoked fish, assorted meat, seasoning cubes, and salt. Bring to a boil on high heat.\", \"Step 5: Using a tablespoon or your hand, scoop portions of the grated water yam and drop them one by one into the boiling broth. Do not stir immediately — allow the yam dumplings to set for 3 minutes before stirring gently.\", \"Step 6: Cook on medium heat for 15 to 20 minutes stirring gently occasionally until the yam dumplings are fully cooked and the broth has thickened, adjust seasoning, and serve hot.\"], \"match_percentage\": 15.4, \"used_ingredients\": [\"onions\", \"seasoning cubes\"], \"cook_time_minutes\": 50, \"prep_time_minutes\": 25, \"missing_ingredients\": [\"water yam (isu ewura)\", \"dried fish\", \"assorted meat\", \"smoked fish\", \"palm oil\", \"crayfish\", \"scotch bonnet peppers\", \"long chilli peppers\", \"iru (locust beans)\", \"salt\", \"water\"]}, {\"name\": \"Abacha\", \"tips\": \"Always soak in cold water not hot. Potash is essential for emulsifying the palm oil into the dressing.\", \"servings\": 4, \"difficulty\": \"medium\", \"description\": \"Abacha is a traditional Igbo cold salad made from dried shredded cassava rehydrated and tossed in an emulsified palm oil and potash dressing with ugba, utazi leaves, garden eggs, crayfish, and assorted proteins.\", \"instructions\": [\"Step 1: Soak the dried abacha in cold water for 10 to 15 minutes until softened. Drain thoroughly.\", \"Step 2: Dissolve potash in 3 tablespoons of water and strain through a fine sieve.\", \"Step 3: Pour palm oil into a bowl. Add the potash solution gradually while stirring vigorously until emulsified and bright yellow.\", \"Step 4: Add ground crayfish, sliced scotch bonnet peppers, sliced onions, seasoning cubes, and salt to the emulsion.\", \"Step 5: Add the drained abacha and toss thoroughly until coated.\", \"Step 6: Add ugba, sliced garden eggs, shredded utazi, flaked fish, and sliced ponmo. Toss together gently.\", \"Step 7: Taste and adjust seasoning.\", \"Step 8: Garnish with utazi and onion rings. Serve at room temperature.\"], \"match_percentage\": 15.4, \"used_ingredients\": [\"onions\", \"seasoning cubes\"], \"cook_time_minutes\": 0, \"prep_time_minutes\": 20, \"missing_ingredients\": [\"abacha (dried shredded cassava)\", \"ugba (oil bean seeds)\", \"palm oil\", \"potash (kaun)\", \"utazi leaves\", \"garden eggs\", \"crayfish\", \"scotch bonnet peppers\", \"salt\", \"dried fish or stockfish\", \"ponmo (cow skin)\"]}, {\"name\": \"Ofe Owerri\", \"tips\": \"Use as many different types of meat and fish as you can for the most authentic version. The combination of ugu and uziza leaves together distinguishes this from Edikang Ikong.\", \"servings\": 6, \"difficulty\": \"hard\", \"description\": \"Ofe Owerri is a luxurious traditional Igbo vegetable soup from Owerri in Imo State, known for being loaded with multiple types of meat, fish, and a generous mix of vegetables, traditionally served at important ceremonies.\", \"instructions\": [\"Step 1: Wash and season all assorted meats and stockfish with onions, seasoning cubes, and salt. Cook on medium heat for 40 to 50 minutes until very tender. Set aside with the rich stock.\", \"Step 2: Peel cocoyam and boil until very soft, then pound until completely smooth to make the thickener.\", \"Step 3: Heat palm oil, add sliced onions and blended scotch bonnet peppers, fry for 15 minutes until oil floats on top.\", \"Step 4: Add all the cooked meats, stockfish, dried fish, periwinkle, ogiri, ground crayfish, and meat stock. Cook on medium heat for 15 minutes.\", \"Step 5: Add the pounded cocoyam thickener in small lumps and stir until dissolved.\", \"Step 6: Add the fresh fish pieces and cook gently for 8 minutes.\", \"Step 7: Add the shredded ugu and uziza leaves together and stir in. Cook for 3 to 5 minutes only.\", \"Step 8: Taste and adjust seasoning. Serve hot with pounded yam, fufu, or semolina.\"], \"match_percentage\": 13.3, \"used_ingredients\": [\"onions\", \"seasoning cubes\"], \"cook_time_minutes\": 85, \"prep_time_minutes\": 30, \"missing_ingredients\": [\"ugu leaves (fluted pumpkin)\", \"uziza leaves\", \"cocoyam (for thickening)\", \"palm oil\", \"assorted meat (beef, tripe, shaki, cow leg)\", \"stockfish\", \"dried fish\", \"fresh fish\", \"periwinkle\", \"crayfish\", \"scotch bonnet peppers\", \"ogiri (fermented locust beans)\", \"salt\"]}, {\"name\": \"Nigerian Coleslaw\", \"tips\": \"The combination of mayonnaise and salad cream together, rather than just mayonnaise alone, is what gives Nigerian coleslaw its distinctive tangy sweetness. Always shred the cabbage very finely for the best texture, and let the coleslaw rest in the refrigerator before serving for the best flavour.\", \"servings\": 6, \"difficulty\": \"easy\", \"description\": \"Nigerian Coleslaw is a creamy and slightly sweet shredded cabbage and carrot salad that is a staple side dish at Nigerian parties, often served alongside Jollof Rice and Fried Rice. It differs from Western coleslaw by typically including diced apples, raisins, and a generously sweetened mayonnaise dressing.\", \"instructions\": [\"Step 1: Wash the cabbage thoroughly and shred very finely using a sharp knife or food processor — the cabbage should be cut into thin uniform strips for the best texture.\", \"Step 2: Peel and grate or finely julienne the carrots into thin matchstick pieces, similar in size to the shredded cabbage.\", \"Step 3: In a large bowl combine the shredded cabbage, grated carrots and sweet corn. Toss together gently.\", \"Step 4: In a separate small bowl mix mayonnaise and salad cream together in roughly equal parts, adding sugar to taste for the characteristic Nigerian sweetness, along with a pinch of black pepper and salt.\", \"Step 5: Pour the dressing over the vegetable mixture and toss thoroughly until every piece is well coated in the creamy dressing.\", \"Step 6: Taste and adjust sweetness and seasoning — Nigerian coleslaw is typically sweeter than standard Western coleslaw.\", \"Step 7: Cover and refrigerate for at least 1 hour before serving to allow the flavours to meld and the cabbage to soften slightly. Serve cold alongside Jollof Rice or Fried Rice.\"], \"match_percentage\": 0.0, \"used_ingredients\": [], \"cook_time_minutes\": 0, \"prep_time_minutes\": 25, \"missing_ingredients\": [\"cabbage\", \"carrots\", \"sweet corn\", \"mayonnaise\", \"salad cream\", \"sugar\", \"black pepper\", \"salt\"]}]}','2026-06-21 11:56:16'),('80bac599-2ed7-4c31-90be-5dc79c022720','[\"rice\", \"tomato paste\", \"scotch bonnet pepers\", \"ginger garlic paste\"]','nigerian',NULL,'{\"almost_there\": [], \"can_make_now\": [], \"needs_shopping\": [{\"name\": \"Nigerian Jollof Rice\", \"tips\": \"The secret to party jollof is double covering with foil and lid to trap steam, and finishing on high heat for the smoky bottom layer. Never use fresh tomatoes alone — always add tomato paste for depth of colour and flavour.\", \"servings\": 6, \"difficulty\": \"medium\", \"description\": \"Nigerian Jollof Rice is one of the most beloved dishes in West Africa, known for its rich smoky tomato flavour and vibrant orange-red colour. It is a staple at every Nigerian party, celebration, and family gathering. The secret to authentic Jollof Rice is the smoky bottom layer called party jollof which develops from cooking on high heat at the end.\", \"instructions\": [\"Step 1: Blend tomatoes, red bell peppers, long chilli peppers, scotch bonnet, and onions together in a blender until completely smooth with no chunks remaining. Set aside.\", \"Step 2: Wash rice thoroughly in cold water at least 3 times until water runs clear.\", \"Step 3: Heat vegetable oil in a large heavy-bottomed stainless steel or aluminum pot over medium-high heat for 2 minutes. Slice some onions, ginger and garlic paste, curry, thyme, bay leaves  and fry in the oil for 3 minutes.\", \"Step 4: Add tomato paste to the pot and fry with the mix for 3 minutes on medium heat, stirring constantly until the paste darkens slightly from bright red to a deeper reddish brown.\", \"Step 5: Pour the blended pepper mixture with some paprika into the pot. It will sizzle loudly — this is correct. Add in some seasoning cubes and salt. Fry on medium high heat uncovered for 25-30 minutes stirring every 5 minutes until all the water has evaporated, the oil floats on top, and the sauce has darkened to a deep red color. This step is critical — do not rush it.\", \"Step 6: Stir well and taste the sauce should be slightly salty as it will season the rice\", \"Step 7: Add the rice to the pot and stir well to coat every grain with the tomato sauce. Fry on high for like 2 minutes. Then add in chicken stock and some water enough to just cover the rice\", \"Step 8: Cover the pot tightly with foil first then place the lid on top to seal in all the steam. Cook on medium heat for 20 minutes without lifting the lid.\", \"Step 9: After 20 minutes lift the lid and check — rice should be almost fully cooked and liquid mostly absorbed. Stir gently from bottom to top. Cover again and cook on very low heat for 10 more minutes.\", \"Step 10: For the authentic party jollof smoky bottom, add in some cooking butter and sliced onions turn heat to high for the last 3-5 minutes. You will hear a crackling sound from the bottom — this is correct. Remove from heat immediately and leave covered for 5 minutes before serving.\"], \"match_percentage\": 12.5, \"used_ingredients\": [\"long grain parboiled rice\", \"tomato paste\"], \"cook_time_minutes\": 70, \"prep_time_minutes\": 20, \"missing_ingredients\": [\"tomatoes\", \"red bell peppers (tatashe)\", \"long chilli peppers(shombo) \", \"scotch bonnet peppers (ata rodo)\", \"onions\", \"vegetable oil\", \"chicken stock\", \"seasoning cubes\", \"curry powder\", \"thyme\", \"bay leaves\", \"garlic powder\", \"salt\", \"paprika\"]}, {\"name\": \"Asun\", \"tips\": \"Grilling or smoking the goat meat after boiling is non-negotiable for authentic Asun — without the charred smoky exterior the dish is just peppered goat meat not Asun. Use goat meat with the skin on for the best texture and flavour. The pepper sauce should have chunky sliced peppers not a blended smooth sauce.\", \"servings\": 4, \"difficulty\": \"medium\", \"description\": \"Asun is a popular Yoruba delicacy of smoked or roasted goat meat cut into small pieces and tossed in a fiery pepper and onion sauce. It originates from Ondo State in Yorubaland and is now one of the most popular Nigerian party small chops and appetisers served across the country. The goat meat is first smoked or roasted to give it a distinctive charred flavour before being peppered.\", \"instructions\": [\"Step 1: Wash the goat meat thoroughly — authentic Asun uses goat meat with the skin on as the skin adds texture and flavour. Cut into medium sized chunks. Season with seasoning cubes, curry powder, thyme, ginger garlic paste and salt.\", \"Step 2: Cook the seasoned goat meat in a pot with a small amount of water on medium heat for 20 to 25 minutes until tender but not falling apart.\", \"Step 3: Remove the cooked goat meat and place directly on a grill, open flame, or in a very hot oven at 220 degrees Celsius. Grill or roast for 15 to 20 minutes turning occasionally until the outside is charred and smoky and the skin is slightly crispy. The charring is essential for authentic Asun flavour.\", \"Step 4: Remove from the grill and cut into smaller bite sized pieces while still hot. Set aside.\", \"Step 5: Slice scotch bonnet peppers, green bell pepper, red bell pepper, and onions into thin strips. The peppers should be sliced not blended, a food processor can be used as well — the chunky pepper pieces are characteristic of Asun.\", \"Step 6: Heat vegetable oil in a wide pan on medium heat. Add the sliced onions and fry for 2 minutes until slightly softened.\", \"Step 7: Add all the sliced peppers to the pan and stir fry on high heat for 3 to 4 minutes — the peppers should be cooked but still have a slight crunch. Do not overcook the peppers into mush.\", \"Step 8: Add the grilled goat meat pieces to the pan and toss vigorously with the peppers for 3 minutes on high heat until the meat is well coated in the pepper mixture and everything is sizzling hot. Taste and adjust seasoning. Serve immediately as a party appetiser or small chop.\"], \"match_percentage\": 9.1, \"used_ingredients\": [\"ginger garlic paste\"], \"cook_time_minutes\": 60, \"prep_time_minutes\": 20, \"missing_ingredients\": [\"goat meat (skin on)\", \"scotch bonnet peppers\", \"green bell pepper\", \"red bell pepper (tatashe)\", \"onions\", \"vegetable oil\", \"seasoning cubes\", \"curry powder\", \"thyme\", \"salt\"]}, {\"name\": \"Nigerian Fried Rice\", \"tips\": \"Always cook on high heat when frying the rice and vegetables together to prevent everything from steaming and becoming soggy instead of stir-fried.\", \"servings\": 6, \"difficulty\": \"medium\", \"description\": \"Nigerian Fried Rice is a colourful and flavourful party staple made with parboiled rice stir-fried with mixed vegetables, liver, and a distinct curry seasoning. Unlike Chinese fried rice, the Nigerian version has a unique orange-yellow hue from curry powder and is loaded with vegetables, making it one of the most popular dishes at Nigerian celebrations alongside Jollof Rice.\", \"instructions\": [\"Step 1: Wash the rice thoroughly until water runs clear then transfer into a seive till perfectly dry. Then into a pot, add some oil and fry the rice for about 5 minutes\", \"Step 2: Season the liver with salt and a little curry powder. Cook in a pot with a small amount of water for 8 to 10 minutes until just cooked through, then dice into small cubes.\", \"Step 3: Dice carrots and green beans into small uniform cubes for even cooking. Set aside along with the bell peppers.\", \"Step 4: Heat vegetable oil in a large wok or wide pan on high heat. Add minced garlic and ginger and stir fry for 30 seconds until fragrant but not browned.\", \"Step 5: Add diced onions and stir fry for 2 minutes until softened. Add the diced liver and shrimp and stir fry for 2 minutes.\", \"Step 6: Add the carrots, green beans, green peas, and bell peppers to the pan. Stir fry on high heat for 3 minutes until heated through but still slightly crisp.\", \"Step 7: Add the cooled parboiled rice to the pan along with curry powder, thyme, seasoning cubes, soy sauce, and salt. Stir fry vigorously on high heat for 5 to 7 minutes, tossing continuously, until the rice is evenly coated in the yellow curry colour and well combined with all the vegetables and protein. Taste and adjust seasoning, then serve hot.\"], \"match_percentage\": 6.7, \"used_ingredients\": [\"long grain rice\"], \"cook_time_minutes\": 30, \"prep_time_minutes\": 30, \"missing_ingredients\": [\"carrots\", \"green peas\", \"bell peppers(green, yellow, red)\", \"liver\", \"vegetable oil\", \"onions\", \"garlic\", \"ginger\", \"curry powder\", \"thyme\", \"seasoning cubes\", \"soy sauce\", \"salt\", \"chicken stock\"]}, {\"name\": \"Moi Moi\", \"tips\": \"The food processor peeling method is a game changer — it cuts prep time from 30 minutes to 5 minutes. The two most important steps are removing every single bean skin and whisking the paste vigorously to aerate it before adding seasoning. Skipping either step will result in dense heavy Moi Moi. Always fill containers only three quarters full as the paste expands during steaming.\", \"servings\": 8, \"difficulty\": \"medium\", \"description\": \"Moi Moi is a traditional Nigerian steamed bean pudding made from peeled beans blended into a smooth paste. It is a beloved dish across all Nigerian tribes and is served at parties, as a side dish with rice or ogi, or eaten alone as a complete meal. The texture should be firm yet soft and moist inside with a rich savoury flavour.\", \"instructions\": [\"Step 1: There are two ways to peel the beans. Traditional method: Pour beans into a bowl and soak in cold water for 30 minutes until the skins begin to loosen and soften, then rub vigorously between both palms under running water until all skins float off. Quick method: Pour dry beans into a food processor with some water and pulse for 30 to 45 seconds — the food processor will crack and loosen the skins without grinding the beans. Pour the pulsed beans into a large bowl of water, the skins will float to the top — skim them off and drain. Repeat until all skins are removed. The quick method takes 5 minutes instead of 30.\", \"Step 2: Rinse the peeled beans thoroughly in clean water two to three times to remove any remaining skin fragments. The beans should be completely white with no dark skin remaining — any leftover skin will make the Moi Moi rough and bitter.\", \"Step 3: Place the peeled beans directly into the blender together with the scotch bonnet peppers, red bell pepper, onions, one raw egg, and a very small amount of water — just enough to get the blender moving. Blend everything together on high speed for 3 minutes until the paste is completely smooth with absolutely no grainy texture. Blending the peppers and egg together with the beans at this stage gives the Moi Moi its full flavour and colour from the inside.\", \"Step 4: Pour the blended paste into a large bowl. Add seasoning cubes, vegetable oil, and salt. Mix everything together thoroughly until well combined. Taste and adjust seasoning — it should be well seasoned and slightly peppery.\", \"Step 5: Using a wooden spoon or electric hand mixer, whisk the paste vigorously for 5 minutes until it becomes fluffy, lighter in colour, and increases slightly in volume. This aerates the paste and gives Moi Moi its soft moist texture when steamed.\", \"Step 6: Break the mackerel fish into medium sized chunks and slice your boiled eggs and set aside. Grease foil containers or moi moi leaves generously with vegetable oil on the inside so the moi moi does not stick.\", \"Step 7: Pour the bean paste mixture into each container filling only three quarters full. Drop pieces of fish directly into the paste in each container alongside the sliced eggs  — the fish sits inside the moi moi not on top. Press down lightly so the fish is submerged in the paste.\", \"Step 8: Seal each foil container tightly by folding the edges over securely. No steam should be able to escape during cooking.\", \"Step 9: Place a trivet or folded foil at the bottom of a large pot to prevent direct heat contact. Arrange the sealed moi moi containers in the pot and add water to reach halfway up the sides of the containers.\", \"Step 10: Cover the pot tightly and steam on medium heat for 45 to 60 minutes. Check water level every 15 minutes and add more hot water if needed — never let the pot run dry. Moi Moi is ready when it feels firm when pressed gently and pulls away cleanly from the container when opened.\"], \"match_percentage\": 0.0, \"used_ingredients\": [], \"cook_time_minutes\": 60, \"prep_time_minutes\": 40, \"missing_ingredients\": [\"beans\", \"onions\", \"scotch bonnet peppers\", \"long chilli pepper (shombo)\", \"crayfish\", \"vegetable oil\", \"seasoning cubes\", \"salt\", \"eggs\", \"fish (preferably mackerel fish)\", \"water\"]}, {\"name\": \"Efo Riro\", \"tips\": \"The most important step is frying the pepper base completely dry until the oil floats on top before adding any meat or stock. This is what separates a rich deeply flavoured Efo Riro from a watery one. Also add the vegetables at the very last minute and cook for 2 minutes only — overcooked vegetables will turn dark and lose their flavour.\", \"servings\": 6, \"difficulty\": \"medium\", \"description\": \"Efo Riro is a rich Yoruba vegetable soup made with tatashe and ata rodo as the pepper base, assorted meats, and leafy green vegetables. The name means stirred leafy vegetable in Yoruba. It is one of the most flavourful Nigerian soups with a vibrant green and red colour from the vegetables and pepper base. It is served with amala, eba, pounded yam, or rice.\", \"instructions\": [\"Step 1: Wash and season assorted meat, pomo, and stockfish with onions, seasoning cubes, and salt. Cook on medium heat for 20 to 30 minutes until very tender. Set aside with the stock.\", \"Step 2: Blend tatashe and scotch bonnet peppers together into a smooth paste. Do not add water — the peppers have enough natural liquid. Set aside.\", \"Step 3: Wash the efo tete or spinach thoroughly, shred into medium sized pieces by hand, and set aside in a colander to drain excess water.\", \"Step 4: Heat palm oil in a large pot on medium-high heat for 2 minutes. Slice onions and fry in the palm oil for 3 minutes until golden and fragrant.\", \"Step 5: Add the blended tatashe and scotch bonnet pepper mixture to the pot. It will sizzle loudly in the hot oil — this is correct. Fry on high heat for 10 to 20 minutes stirring every 3 minutes until all the water has completely evaporated, the oil floats on top, and the pepper sauce has darkened and thickened. This step gives Efo Riro its deep rich flavour.\", \"Step 6: Add iru (locust beans) and ground crayfish and stir into the pepper sauce. Fry for 2 more minutes until the iru is fragrant.\", \"Step 7: Add the cooked assorted meat, stockfish, dried fish, and a ladle of the meat stock. Stir everything together and cook on medium heat for 10 minutes until the meat is well coated in the sauce.\", \"Step 8: Add the shredded efo tete or spinach to the pot and stir into the sauce. Cook for exactly 2 minutes only on medium heat — the vegetables should wilt into the soup but remain bright green and not soggy. Taste, adjust seasoning, and remove from heat immediately. Serve with amala, eba, or pounded yam.\"], \"match_percentage\": 0.0, \"used_ingredients\": [], \"cook_time_minutes\": 75, \"prep_time_minutes\": 25, \"missing_ingredients\": [\"vgetables African spinach or ugwu\", \"tatashe (red bell pepper)\", \"scotch bonnet peppers (ata rodo)\", \"onions\", \"palm oil\", \"assorted meat (beef, tripe, shaki, pomo)\", \"stockfish\", \"dried fish\", \"crayfish\", \"iru (locust beans)\", \"seasoning cubes\", \"salt\"]}, {\"name\": \"Egusi Soup Yoruba Style\", \"tips\": \"The secret to Yoruba egusi is frying the egusi completely dry in palm oil before adding any liquid. Never add water or stock to the egusi while frying — it must fry and toast in the oil until golden. Also never add tomatoes to Yoruba egusi soup — that changes the flavour profile completely.\", \"servings\": 6, \"difficulty\": \"medium\", \"description\": \"Egusi Soup Yoruba style is a rich and hearty Nigerian soup made with ground melon seeds fried directly in palm oil before any liquid is added. Unlike Igbo style egusi which is added raw, Yoruba style fries the egusi first until golden and nutty giving it a deeper richer flavour. It is served with amala, eba, or pounded yam.\", \"instructions\": [\"Step 1: Wash and season assorted meat and stockfish with onions, seasoning cubes, and salt. Cook in a pot on medium heat for 15 to 20 minutes until tender. Set aside with the stock.\", \"Step 2: Blend scotch bonnet peppers, tatashe, and half the onions together into a smooth paste. Set aside.\", \"Step 3: Heat palm oil in a large pot on medium heat for 2 minutes until melted and hot but not bleached. Chop the remaining onions and fry in the palm oil for 3 minutes until soft and translucent.\", \"Step 4: Add the ground egusi to the palm oil and stir immediately to combine. Fry the egusi in the palm oil on medium heat for 8 to 10 minutes stirring constantly until the egusi turns golden, smells nutty, and pulls away from the sides of the pot. Do not add any liquid at this stage — dry frying is the key to Yoruba egusi.\", \"Step 5: Add the blended pepper mixture to the fried egusi and stir well to combine. Fry together for another 10 minutes on medium heat stirring every 2 minutes until the pepper is cooked and oil begins to float on the surface.\", \"Step 6: Add the cooked meat, stockfish, dried fish, meat stock, ground crayfish, iru, and seasoning cubes. Stir everything together and add a small amount of water if the soup is too thick. Cook on medium heat for 15 minutes until all the flavours come together.\", \"Step 7: Taste and adjust salt and seasoning. The soup should be rich, thick, and deeply flavoured at this point.\", \"Step 8: Add shredded spinach or efo tete and stir into the soup. Cook for exactly 2 minutes only — overcooking the vegetables will make them lose their colour and become soggy. Remove from heat and serve immediately with amala, eba, or pounded yam.\"], \"match_percentage\": 0.0, \"used_ingredients\": [], \"cook_time_minutes\": 70, \"prep_time_minutes\": 20, \"missing_ingredients\": [\"ground egusi (melon seeds)\", \"palm oil\", \"assorted meat (beef, tripe, shaki)\", \"stockfish\", \"dried fish\", \"onions\", \"scotch bonnet peppers\", \"tatashe (red bell pepper)\", \"crayfish\", \"iru (locust beans)\", \"spinach, efo tete or ugwu\", \"seasoning cubes\", \"salt\"]}, {\"name\": \"Nigerian Pepper Soup\", \"tips\": \"The quality of your pepper soup spice mix makes or breaks this dish. Use freshly ground spices if possible — uda (country onion), ehuru (calabash nutmeg), and uziza seeds ground together give the most authentic flavour. Never cover the pot fully while cooking pepper soup — leave it slightly open so the broth reduces and concentrates.\", \"servings\": 4, \"difficulty\": \"easy\", \"description\": \"Nigerian Pepper Soup is a light, intensely spiced broth made with meat or fish and a unique blend of pepper soup spices. It is served at every Nigerian gathering, used as a remedy for colds and fever, and eaten as a starter or main dish. The broth is thin but deeply flavoured with a distinctive warming heat that comes from the special pepper soup spice blend.\", \"instructions\": [\"Step 1: Wash the meat thoroughly and cut into medium sized pieces. Season with onions, seasoning cubes, and salt. Do not add water yet — allow the meat to cook in its own juices first.\", \"Step 2: Place the seasoned meat in a pot on medium heat and cook dry for 10 minutes stirring occasionally until the meat releases its juices and begins to brown slightly on the outside.\", \"Step 3: Add enough water to cover the meat completely. Bring to a boil on high heat then reduce to medium heat. Cook for 25 to 30 minutes for goat meat or 15 minutes for chicken until the meat is tender but not falling off the bone.\", \"Step 4: Add the pepper soup spice mix, ground crayfish, and blended or roughly crushed scotch bonnet peppers. Stir well and taste — the broth should be well seasoned and spicy at this point. Add more seasoning cubes and salt if needed.\", \"Step 5: Cook on medium heat for another 15 minutes until the spices have fully infused into the broth and the liquid has reduced slightly. The broth should be a light golden brown colour and smell intensely aromatic.\", \"Step 6: Tear utazi leaves into small pieces and add to the pot — utazi adds a slight bitterness that balances the heat. Add uziza leaves whole or roughly torn. Cook for 3 minutes only.\", \"Step 7: Taste one final time and adjust salt and pepper. The pepper soup should be very hot and spicy, lightly bitter from the utazi, and deeply aromatic from the spice blend. Serve hot in deep bowls with sliced onions on top and agidi or white rice on the side.\"], \"match_percentage\": 0.0, \"used_ingredients\": [], \"cook_time_minutes\": 55, \"prep_time_minutes\": 15, \"missing_ingredients\": [\"goat meat or chicken or catfish\", \"pepper soup spice mix\", \"scotch bonnet peppers\", \"onions\", \"crayfish\", \"uziza leaves\", \"utazi leaves\", \"seasoning cubes\", \"salt\", \"water\"]}, {\"name\": \"Akara\", \"tips\": \"Whisking the bean paste until very fluffy is the secret to light soft akara — never skip this step. Also make sure the oil is very hot before adding the paste otherwise the akara will absorb too much oil and become greasy. Wet your spoon with oil before scooping each portion to help the paste slide off cleanly into the oil.\", \"servings\": 4, \"difficulty\": \"medium\", \"description\": \"Akara is a traditional Yoruba deep fried bean cake made from peeled black eyed beans blended into a smooth aerated paste and fried in hot oil until crispy on the outside and soft inside. It is a quintessential Nigerian breakfast food sold by roadside vendors across the country and best eaten hot with ogi (pap) or bread.\", \"instructions\": [\"Step 1: Peel the beans using one of two methods. Traditional method: Soak beans in cold water for 30 minutes then rub between palms under running water until all skins float off and are drained away. Quick method: Pulse beans and water  in a food processor for 30 seconds to crack and loosen skins, pour into a bowl of water, skim off floating skins, and drain. Rinse peeled beans two to three times in clean water.\", \"Step 2: Place the peeled beans alongside the peppers and onions in a blender with a very small amount of water — just enough to move the blender. Blend on high speed for 3 minutes until the paste is completely smooth and thick. The paste must be thick not watery — too much water will make flat oily akara.\", \"Step 3: Pour the blended bean paste into a large bowl. Using a wooden spoon or electric hand mixer whisk the paste vigorously for 5 to 7 minutes until it becomes very fluffy, lighter in colour, and almost doubles in volume. This is the most important step — the air you whisk in is what makes akara light and fluffy inside.\", \"Step 4: Add some salt and seasoning cubes to the whisked paste. Fold gently into the paste without deflating it. Taste and adjust seasoning.\", \"Step 5: Pour enough vegetable oil into a deep wide pan to allow the akara to float — at least 3 inches deep. Heat on medium-high heat for 2 to 3 minutes until hot. Test the oil by dropping a tiny bit of paste in — it should rise immediately to the surface and sizzle vigorously. If it sinks the oil is not hot enough.\", \"Step 6: Wet your tablespoon with oil and scoop portions of the paste into the hot oil one at a time. Do not overcrowd the pan — leave space between each akara so they cook evenly and stay round.\", \"Step 7: Fry on medium heat for 3 to 4 minutes until the bottom is deep golden brown, then flip carefully with a slotted spoon or skewer and fry the other side for 2 to 3 minutes until evenly golden brown and crispy all over.\", \"Step 8: Remove with a slotted spoon and drain on paper towels to absorb excess oil. Serve immediately while hot and crispy alongside ogi (pap) or as a breakfast snack.\"], \"match_percentage\": 0.0, \"used_ingredients\": [], \"cook_time_minutes\": 20, \"prep_time_minutes\": 30, \"missing_ingredients\": [\"black eyed beans\", \"onions\", \"scotch bonnet peppers\", \"long chilli peppers(shombo)\", \"seasoning cubes\", \"salt\", \"vegetable oil for deep frying\"]}, {\"name\": \"Ewa Agoyin\", \"tips\": \"The two secrets to authentic Ewa Agoyin are cooking the beans with a lot of onions until completely mashable with no whole beans remaining, and making the Agoyin stew with only dried peppers not fresh ones. Fresh peppers will not give the deep dark colour and concentrated flavour that makes Agoyin stew unique. The stew must be dark, dry, and almost burnt looking — that is correct.\", \"servings\": 4, \"difficulty\": \"medium\", \"description\": \"Ewa Agoyin is a popular Yoruba street food originally brought to Nigeria by Beninese traders, consisting of soft completely mashed honey beans or black eyed beans served with a deeply dark and spicy Agoyin stew made from dried red peppers and palm oil. It is a beloved Lagos breakfast food sold by roadside vendors and eaten with agege bread.\", \"instructions\": [\"Step 1: Wash the beans thoroughly then cover the beans with fresh water and cook on high heat until boiling, then reduce to medium heat. Cook for 45 to 60 minutes until the beans are extremely soft — they should mash completely between your fingers with no resistance. Add more water as needed during cooking to prevent burning.\", \"Step 2: Once the beans are very soft, use a wooden spoon or potato masher to mash them completely in the pot until no whole beans remain. The consistency should be thick and porridge-like. Season with salt, stir well, and set aside.\", \"Step 4: While the beans cook prepare the Agoyin stew. Rehydrate the dried red peppers and dried chilli peppers by soaking in hot water for 20 minutes until soft. Drain and blend alongside some onions and ginger into a rough paste — not completely smooth, leave some texture.\", \"Step 5: Heat palm oil in a separate pot on medium heat until hot. Slice onions into thin rings and fry in the palm oil for 10 minutes on medium-low heat, stirring constantly until the onions are very dark brown and almost caramelised — this dark onion is essential to the Agoyin stew flavour.\", \"Step 6: Add the blended dried pepper mixture to the dark onions and palm oil. Stir well and fry on medium heat for 20 to 25 minutes stirring every 3 minutes until all moisture evaporates, the stew becomes very dark, thick, and dry, and the oil floats on top. The stew should be almost black in colour — this is correct.\", \"Step 7: Add seasoning cubes and salt to the stew. Stir well and cook for 5 more minutes. The finished Agoyin stew should be very dark, very dry, very spicy, and intensely flavoured.\", \"Step 8: Serve the mashed beans in a bowl and pour the dark Agoyin stew generously on top. Eat with agege bread, fried plantain, or on its own.\"], \"match_percentage\": 0.0, \"used_ingredients\": [], \"cook_time_minutes\": 90, \"prep_time_minutes\": 20, \"missing_ingredients\": [\"beans\", \"dried red peppers (tatashe)\", \"dried long chilli bonnet peppers(shombo)\", \"onions\", \"palm oil\", \"crayfish\", \"seasoning cubes\", \"salt\", \"water\"]}, {\"name\": \"Ayamase (Ofada Stew)\", \"tips\": \"Bleaching the palm oil is absolutely non-negotiable for authentic Ayamase. Only use green peppers and unripe tatashe — no red peppers at all. The more assorted meats you use the richer and more authentic the stew will be.\", \"servings\": 6, \"difficulty\": \"hard\", \"description\": \"Ayamase also known as Ofada Stew or Designer Stew is a rich and intensely flavoured Yoruba stew made exclusively with green peppers and unripe tatashe giving it its distinctive green colour. It is traditionally served with Ofada rice and the stew is made with bleached palm oil and loaded with assorted meats making it one of the most indulgent Nigerian dishes.\", \"instructions\": [\"Step 1: Wash and season all assorted meats with onions, seasoning cubes, ginger garlic paste and salt. Cook in a pot on medium heat for 25 to 35 minutes until very tender. Fry the cooked meats in a small amount of oil until lightly browned on the outside for extra flavour. Set aside with the stock.\", \"Step 2: Blend green bell peppers, unripe green tatashe, green scotch bonnet peppers, and onions together into a coarse paste — do not blend completely smooth, leave some texture. The stew must use only green peppers and unripe tatashe — never red peppers or ripe tatashe as this completely changes the dish.\", \"Step 3: Bleach the palm oil by heating it in a pot on high heat with the lid on for 10 to 15 minutes until the oil turns from orange-red to a pale golden yellow colour and begins to smoke lightly. Remove from heat and allow to cool slightly. Bleached palm oil is essential for authentic Ayamase.\", \"Step 4: Return the bleached palm oil to medium heat. Add sliced onions with some ginger garlic paste and fry for 3 minutes until soft and slightly golden.\", \"Step 5: Pour the blended green pepper mixture into the bleached palm oil. It will sizzle vigorously stir immediately. Fry on high heat for 15 to 20 minutes stirring every 3 to 4 minutes until all the water has completely evaporated, the oil floats on top, and the pepper sauce is cooked down and thick.\", \"Step 6: Add iru (locust beans) and ground crayfish to the cooked pepper base and stir well. Fry for 3 more minutes until the iru is fragrant and well incorporated.\", \"Step 7: Add all the assorted meats and a ladle of the meat stock. Stir everything together to coat the meat in the green pepper sauce. Cook on medium heat for 10 minutes until the meat is well flavoured and the stew is thick and rich.\", \"Step 8: Taste and adjust seasoning. The finished Ayamase should be dark olive green, thick, intensely flavoured, and very rich with assorted meats. Serve with Ofada rice.\"], \"match_percentage\": 0.0, \"used_ingredients\": [], \"cook_time_minutes\": 90, \"prep_time_minutes\": 25, \"missing_ingredients\": [\"green bell peppers\", \"unripe tatashe (green tatashe)\", \"green scotch bonnet peppers\", \"onions\", \"palm oil\", \"assorted meat (beef, tripe, shaki, pomo, liver)\", \"crayfish\", \"iru (locust beans)\", \"seasoning cubes\", \"ginger and garlic paste\", \"salt\"]}, {\"name\": \"Ikokore\", \"tips\": \"Use water yam specifically not white yam or cocoyam. Do not rinse the grated yam before adding to the pot as the natural starch thickens the broth and holds the dumplings together.\", \"servings\": 4, \"difficulty\": \"medium\", \"description\": \"Ikokore is a traditional Ijebu Yoruba dish made from grated water yam cooked in a rich pepper soup or tomato base with assorted fish and seafood. The grated water yam forms thick irregular dumplings in the broth giving the dish its characteristic texture. It is a beloved dish in Ogun State and across Yorubaland.\", \"instructions\": [\"Step 1: Peel the water yam and grate on the coarse side of a grater into a bowl. Do not rinse the grated yam — the natural starch is needed to hold the dumplings together. Season the grated yam lightly with salt and set aside.\", \"Step 2: Blend scotch bonnet peppers, long chilli peppers, and onions together into a smooth paste.\", \"Step 3: Heat palm oil in a large pot on medium heat. Add iru and fry for 1 minute until fragrant. Add the blended pepper mixture and fry for 15 minutes until cooked and oil floats on top.\", \"Step 4: Add enough meat stock to the pot . Add ground crayfish, dried fish, smoked fish, assorted meat, seasoning cubes, and salt. Bring to a boil on high heat.\", \"Step 5: Using a tablespoon or your hand, scoop portions of the grated water yam and drop them one by one into the boiling broth. Do not stir immediately — allow the yam dumplings to set for 3 minutes before stirring gently.\", \"Step 6: Cook on medium heat for 15 to 20 minutes stirring gently occasionally until the yam dumplings are fully cooked and the broth has thickened, adjust seasoning, and serve hot.\"], \"match_percentage\": 0.0, \"used_ingredients\": [], \"cook_time_minutes\": 50, \"prep_time_minutes\": 25, \"missing_ingredients\": [\"water yam (isu ewura)\", \"dried fish\", \"assorted meat\", \"smoked fish\", \"palm oil\", \"crayfish\", \"scotch bonnet peppers\", \"long chilli peppers\", \"onions\", \"iru (locust beans)\", \"seasoning cubes\", \"salt\", \"water\"]}, {\"name\": \"Asaro (Yam Porridge)\", \"tips\": \"Gentle stirring lets some yam break down to thicken the sauce naturally without becoming completely mashed.\", \"servings\": 4, \"difficulty\": \"easy\", \"description\": \"Asaro is a beloved traditional Yoruba yam porridge made by cooking yam chunks directly in a rich tomato and pepper sauce until the yam softens and thickens the entire dish into a hearty one-pot meal.\", \"instructions\": [\"Step 1: Peel the yam and cut into medium sized chunks. Wash thoroughly.\", \"Step 2: Blend onions, tatashe, and scotch bonnet peppers together into a smooth paste.\", \"Step 3: Place the yam chunks in a pot with the blended pepper mixture, sliced onions, palm oil, and enough water to just cover the yam.\", \"Step 4: Bring to a boil then reduce to medium heat. Cook for 20 to 25 minutes, stirring occasionally, until the yam softens and breaks down at the edges.\", \"Step 5: Add ground crayfish, flaked fish, seasoning cubes, and salt. Stir gently.\", \"Step 6: Continue cooking on medium-low heat for 8 to 10 minutes until thick and stew-like.\", \"Step 7: Taste and adjust seasoning. Serve hot on its own.\"], \"match_percentage\": 0.0, \"used_ingredients\": [], \"cook_time_minutes\": 40, \"prep_time_minutes\": 15, \"missing_ingredients\": [\"yam (white yam)\", \"tomatoes\", \"tatashe (red bell pepper)\", \"scotch bonnet peppers\", \"onions\", \"palm oil\", \"crayfish\", \"smoked fish or dried fish\", \"seasoning cubes\", \"salt\", \"water\"]}, {\"name\": \"Nigerian Coleslaw\", \"tips\": \"The combination of mayonnaise and salad cream together, rather than just mayonnaise alone, is what gives Nigerian coleslaw its distinctive tangy sweetness. Always shred the cabbage very finely for the best texture, and let the coleslaw rest in the refrigerator before serving for the best flavour.\", \"servings\": 6, \"difficulty\": \"easy\", \"description\": \"Nigerian Coleslaw is a creamy and slightly sweet shredded cabbage and carrot salad that is a staple side dish at Nigerian parties, often served alongside Jollof Rice and Fried Rice. It differs from Western coleslaw by typically including diced apples, raisins, and a generously sweetened mayonnaise dressing.\", \"instructions\": [\"Step 1: Wash the cabbage thoroughly and shred very finely using a sharp knife or food processor — the cabbage should be cut into thin uniform strips for the best texture.\", \"Step 2: Peel and grate or finely julienne the carrots into thin matchstick pieces, similar in size to the shredded cabbage.\", \"Step 3: In a large bowl combine the shredded cabbage, grated carrots and sweet corn. Toss together gently.\", \"Step 4: In a separate small bowl mix mayonnaise and salad cream together in roughly equal parts, adding sugar to taste for the characteristic Nigerian sweetness, along with a pinch of black pepper and salt.\", \"Step 5: Pour the dressing over the vegetable mixture and toss thoroughly until every piece is well coated in the creamy dressing.\", \"Step 6: Taste and adjust sweetness and seasoning — Nigerian coleslaw is typically sweeter than standard Western coleslaw.\", \"Step 7: Cover and refrigerate for at least 1 hour before serving to allow the flavours to meld and the cabbage to soften slightly. Serve cold alongside Jollof Rice or Fried Rice.\"], \"match_percentage\": 0.0, \"used_ingredients\": [], \"cook_time_minutes\": 0, \"prep_time_minutes\": 25, \"missing_ingredients\": [\"cabbage\", \"carrots\", \"sweet corn\", \"mayonnaise\", \"salad cream\", \"sugar\", \"black pepper\", \"salt\"]}, {\"name\": \"Banga Stew\", \"tips\": \"The key difference between Banga Soup and Banga Stew is the reduction time — cook the stew version longer uncovered to achieve a thicker consistency that coats rice or yam well rather than the more liquid soup form.\", \"servings\": 5, \"difficulty\": \"hard\", \"description\": \"Banga Stew is a thick, deeply flavoured Igbo stew made from concentrated palm fruit extract, prepared similarly to Banga Soup but cooked down to a thicker consistency more like a stew than a soup. It is rich, nutty, and aromatic, traditionally seasoned with banga spices, and served with white rice, boiled yam, or plantain.\", \"instructions\": [\"Step 1: If using fresh palm fruit, boil for 20 to 30 minutes until soft, then pound to separate pulp from nuts and squeeze with warm water to extract the thick orange juice. Strain through a sieve to remove fibres. If using canned concentrate, dilute according to package instructions.\", \"Step 2: Pour the palm fruit extract into a pot and bring to a boil on high heat, then reduce to medium heat and simmer for 15 to 20 minutes until the oil begins to separate and rise to the surface.\", \"Step 3: Season the assorted meat with onions, seasoning cubes, and salt. Cook separately on medium heat for 30 minutes until tender. Add the cooked meat and stock to the palm fruit base.\", \"Step 4: Add the banga spice mix to the pot and simmer for 15 minutes to allow the spices to infuse fully into the base.\", \"Step 5: Add dried fish, ground crayfish, sliced scotch bonnet peppers, and seasoning cubes. Stir well and continue cooking on medium heat, allowing the liquid to reduce and thicken for 20 to 25 minutes — unlike Banga Soup this should reduce further into a thicker stew-like consistency.\", \"Step 6: Add the fresh fish pieces and cook gently for 8 to 10 minutes until just cooked through, stirring carefully to avoid breaking the fish apart.\", \"Step 7: Continue simmering uncovered for an additional 10 minutes, stirring occasionally, until the stew has thickened noticeably and the oil is clearly visible on the surface.\", \"Step 8: Remove the oburunbebe stick before serving. Taste and adjust seasoning. Serve hot with white rice, boiled yam, or plantain.\"], \"match_percentage\": 0.0, \"used_ingredients\": [], \"cook_time_minutes\": 80, \"prep_time_minutes\": 30, \"missing_ingredients\": [\"fresh palm fruit (or canned banga concentrate)\", \"assorted meat (beef, tripe)\", \"dried fish\", \"fresh fish\", \"banga spice mix (oburunbebe stick, dried bitter leaf)\", \"onions\", \"scotch bonnet peppers\", \"crayfish\", \"seasoning cubes\", \"salt\", \"water\"]}, {\"name\": \"Abacha\", \"tips\": \"Always soak in cold water not hot. Potash is essential for emulsifying the palm oil into the dressing.\", \"servings\": 4, \"difficulty\": \"medium\", \"description\": \"Abacha is a traditional Igbo cold salad made from dried shredded cassava rehydrated and tossed in an emulsified palm oil and potash dressing with ugba, utazi leaves, garden eggs, crayfish, and assorted proteins.\", \"instructions\": [\"Step 1: Soak the dried abacha in cold water for 10 to 15 minutes until softened. Drain thoroughly.\", \"Step 2: Dissolve potash in 3 tablespoons of water and strain through a fine sieve.\", \"Step 3: Pour palm oil into a bowl. Add the potash solution gradually while stirring vigorously until emulsified and bright yellow.\", \"Step 4: Add ground crayfish, sliced scotch bonnet peppers, sliced onions, seasoning cubes, and salt to the emulsion.\", \"Step 5: Add the drained abacha and toss thoroughly until coated.\", \"Step 6: Add ugba, sliced garden eggs, shredded utazi, flaked fish, and sliced ponmo. Toss together gently.\", \"Step 7: Taste and adjust seasoning.\", \"Step 8: Garnish with utazi and onion rings. Serve at room temperature.\"], \"match_percentage\": 0.0, \"used_ingredients\": [], \"cook_time_minutes\": 0, \"prep_time_minutes\": 20, \"missing_ingredients\": [\"abacha (dried shredded cassava)\", \"ugba (oil bean seeds)\", \"palm oil\", \"potash (kaun)\", \"utazi leaves\", \"garden eggs\", \"crayfish\", \"onions\", \"scotch bonnet peppers\", \"seasoning cubes\", \"salt\", \"dried fish or stockfish\", \"ponmo (cow skin)\"]}, {\"name\": \"Ofe Owerri\", \"tips\": \"Use as many different types of meat and fish as you can for the most authentic version. The combination of ugu and uziza leaves together distinguishes this from Edikang Ikong.\", \"servings\": 6, \"difficulty\": \"hard\", \"description\": \"Ofe Owerri is a luxurious traditional Igbo vegetable soup from Owerri in Imo State, known for being loaded with multiple types of meat, fish, and a generous mix of vegetables, traditionally served at important ceremonies.\", \"instructions\": [\"Step 1: Wash and season all assorted meats and stockfish with onions, seasoning cubes, and salt. Cook on medium heat for 40 to 50 minutes until very tender. Set aside with the rich stock.\", \"Step 2: Peel cocoyam and boil until very soft, then pound until completely smooth to make the thickener.\", \"Step 3: Heat palm oil, add sliced onions and blended scotch bonnet peppers, fry for 15 minutes until oil floats on top.\", \"Step 4: Add all the cooked meats, stockfish, dried fish, periwinkle, ogiri, ground crayfish, and meat stock. Cook on medium heat for 15 minutes.\", \"Step 5: Add the pounded cocoyam thickener in small lumps and stir until dissolved.\", \"Step 6: Add the fresh fish pieces and cook gently for 8 minutes.\", \"Step 7: Add the shredded ugu and uziza leaves together and stir in. Cook for 3 to 5 minutes only.\", \"Step 8: Taste and adjust seasoning. Serve hot with pounded yam, fufu, or semolina.\"], \"match_percentage\": 0.0, \"used_ingredients\": [], \"cook_time_minutes\": 85, \"prep_time_minutes\": 30, \"missing_ingredients\": [\"ugu leaves (fluted pumpkin)\", \"uziza leaves\", \"cocoyam (for thickening)\", \"palm oil\", \"assorted meat (beef, tripe, shaki, cow leg)\", \"stockfish\", \"dried fish\", \"fresh fish\", \"periwinkle\", \"crayfish\", \"onions\", \"scotch bonnet peppers\", \"ogiri (fermented locust beans)\", \"seasoning cubes\", \"salt\"]}]}','2026-06-21 09:49:49'),('86908347-bd40-4512-a331-f8577187c14e','[\"flour\", \"baking powder\", \"vanilla extract\", \"sugar\", \"eggs\"]','english',20,'{\"recipes\": [{\"name\": \"Vanilla Cake\", \"servings\": 4, \"difficulty\": \"easy\", \"description\": \"A classic English dessert, vanilla cake is a sweet and moist treat that is perfect for any occasion.\", \"instructions\": [\"Step 1: Preheat the oven to 350°F (175°C) and grease two 8-inch round cake pans.\", \"Step 2: In a large mixing bowl, whisk together 2 cups of flour, 1 cup of sugar, and 2 teaspoons of baking powder.\", \"Step 3: In a separate bowl, whisk together 2 large eggs and 1 teaspoon of vanilla extract.\", \"Step 4: Add the egg mixture to the dry ingredients and mix until just combined.\", \"Step 5: Divide the batter evenly between the prepared pans and smooth the tops.\", \"Step 6: Bake the cakes for 20-25 minutes, or until they are golden brown and a toothpick inserted into the center comes out clean.\"], \"match_percentage\": 80, \"used_ingredients\": [\"flour\", \"sugar\", \"eggs\", \"vanilla extract\"], \"cook_time_minutes\": 20, \"prep_time_minutes\": 15, \"missing_ingredients\": [\"butter\", \"milk\"]}, {\"name\": \"Sugar Cookies\", \"servings\": 12, \"difficulty\": \"easy\", \"description\": \"A classic English treat, sugar cookies are sweet and crumbly, with a delicate flavor profile.\", \"instructions\": [\"Step 1: In a large mixing bowl, whisk together 2 cups of flour and 1 cup of sugar.\", \"Step 2: Add 1 large egg to the mixture and mix until a dough forms.\", \"Step 3: Turn the dough out onto a floured surface and knead for 2-3 minutes, until the dough is smooth and pliable.\", \"Step 4: Roll the dough out to a thickness of about 1/4 inch and cut into desired shapes.\", \"Step 5: Place the cookies on a baking sheet lined with parchment paper and bake in a preheated oven at 350°F (175°C) for 10-12 minutes, or until lightly golden.\", \"Step 6: Remove the cookies from the oven and allow to cool on the baking sheet for 5 minutes before transferring to a wire rack to cool completely.\"], \"match_percentage\": 60, \"used_ingredients\": [\"flour\", \"sugar\", \"eggs\"], \"cook_time_minutes\": 10, \"prep_time_minutes\": 10, \"missing_ingredients\": [\"butter\", \"vanilla extract\"]}, {\"name\": \"Crepes\", \"servings\": 8, \"difficulty\": \"easy\", \"description\": \"A classic English dessert, crepes are thin and delicate, with a sweet flavor profile.\", \"instructions\": [\"Step 1: In a large mixing bowl, whisk together 1 cup of flour, 1 large egg, and 1 tablespoon of sugar.\", \"Step 2: Gradually add 1/2 cup of water to the mixture, whisking constantly to avoid lumps.\", \"Step 3: Heat a small non-stick pan over medium heat and brush with a small amount of oil.\", \"Step 4: Pour a small amount of the batter into the pan and tilt to evenly coat the bottom.\", \"Step 5: Cook the crepe for 1-2 minutes, until the bottom is lightly browned and the edges start to curl.\", \"Step 6: Loosen the crepe with a spatula and flip to cook the other side for an additional 30 seconds to 1 minute.\"], \"match_percentage\": 50, \"used_ingredients\": [\"flour\", \"eggs\", \"sugar\"], \"cook_time_minutes\": 10, \"prep_time_minutes\": 10, \"missing_ingredients\": [\"milk\", \"butter\"]}, {\"name\": \"Pancakes\", \"servings\": 8, \"difficulty\": \"easy\", \"description\": \"A classic English breakfast, pancakes are fluffy and delicious, with a sweet flavor profile.\", \"instructions\": [\"Step 1: In a large mixing bowl, whisk together 1 cup of flour, 1 large egg, and 1 tablespoon of sugar.\", \"Step 2: Gradually add 1/2 cup of water to the mixture, whisking constantly to avoid lumps.\", \"Step 3: Heat a non-stick pan or griddle over medium heat and brush with a small amount of oil.\", \"Step 4: Pour a small amount of the batter into the pan and cook for 2-3 minutes, until bubbles appear on the surface and the edges start to dry.\", \"Step 5: Flip the pancake and cook for an additional 1-2 minutes, until golden brown.\", \"Step 6: Serve the pancakes hot with your favorite toppings.\"], \"match_percentage\": 50, \"used_ingredients\": [\"flour\", \"eggs\", \"sugar\"], \"cook_time_minutes\": 10, \"prep_time_minutes\": 10, \"missing_ingredients\": [\"milk\", \"butter\"]}]}','2026-06-17 13:46:00'),('8af97c34-d705-4c3a-90d4-2e1cb8c4765a','[\"flour\", \"eggs\", \"sugar\", \"butter\"]','nigerian',NULL,'{\"almost_there\": [], \"can_make_now\": [], \"needs_shopping\": [{\"name\": \"Nigerian Coleslaw\", \"tips\": \"The combination of mayonnaise and salad cream together, rather than just mayonnaise alone, is what gives Nigerian coleslaw its distinctive tangy sweetness. Always shred the cabbage very finely for the best texture, and let the coleslaw rest in the refrigerator before serving for the best flavour.\", \"servings\": 6, \"difficulty\": \"easy\", \"description\": \"Nigerian Coleslaw is a creamy and slightly sweet shredded cabbage and carrot salad that is a staple side dish at Nigerian parties, often served alongside Jollof Rice and Fried Rice. It differs from Western coleslaw by typically including diced apples, raisins, and a generously sweetened mayonnaise dressing.\", \"instructions\": [\"Step 1: Wash the cabbage thoroughly and shred very finely using a sharp knife or food processor — the cabbage should be cut into thin uniform strips for the best texture.\", \"Step 2: Peel and grate or finely julienne the carrots into thin matchstick pieces, similar in size to the shredded cabbage.\", \"Step 3: In a large bowl combine the shredded cabbage, grated carrots and sweet corn. Toss together gently.\", \"Step 4: In a separate small bowl mix mayonnaise and salad cream together in roughly equal parts, adding sugar to taste for the characteristic Nigerian sweetness, along with a pinch of black pepper and salt.\", \"Step 5: Pour the dressing over the vegetable mixture and toss thoroughly until every piece is well coated in the creamy dressing.\", \"Step 6: Taste and adjust sweetness and seasoning — Nigerian coleslaw is typically sweeter than standard Western coleslaw.\", \"Step 7: Cover and refrigerate for at least 1 hour before serving to allow the flavours to meld and the cabbage to soften slightly. Serve cold alongside Jollof Rice or Fried Rice.\"], \"dietary_labels\": [\"Diabetic\"], \"dietary_flagged\": [\"corn\", \"sugar\", \"sweet corn\"], \"is_dietary_safe\": true, \"dietary_warnings\": [\"High glycemic ingredients — consume in moderation\"], \"match_percentage\": 12.5, \"used_ingredients\": [\"sugar\"], \"cook_time_minutes\": 0, \"prep_time_minutes\": 25, \"missing_ingredients\": [\"cabbage\", \"carrots\", \"sweet corn\", \"mayonnaise\", \"salad cream\", \"black pepper\", \"salt\"]}, {\"name\": \"Moi Moi\", \"tips\": \"The food processor peeling method is a game changer — it cuts prep time from 30 minutes to 5 minutes. The two most important steps are removing every single bean skin and whisking the paste vigorously to aerate it before adding seasoning. Skipping either step will result in dense heavy Moi Moi. Always fill containers only three quarters full as the paste expands during steaming.\", \"servings\": 8, \"difficulty\": \"medium\", \"description\": \"Moi Moi is a traditional Nigerian steamed bean pudding made from peeled beans blended into a smooth paste. It is a beloved dish across all Nigerian tribes and is served at parties, as a side dish with rice or ogi, or eaten alone as a complete meal. The texture should be firm yet soft and moist inside with a rich savoury flavour.\", \"instructions\": [\"Step 1: There are two ways to peel the beans. Traditional method: Pour beans into a bowl and soak in cold water for 30 minutes until the skins begin to loosen and soften, then rub vigorously between both palms under running water until all skins float off. Quick method: Pour dry beans into a food processor with some water and pulse for 30 to 45 seconds — the food processor will crack and loosen the skins without grinding the beans. Pour the pulsed beans into a large bowl of water, the skins will float to the top — skim them off and drain. Repeat until all skins are removed. The quick method takes 5 minutes instead of 30.\", \"Step 2: Rinse the peeled beans thoroughly in clean water two to three times to remove any remaining skin fragments. The beans should be completely white with no dark skin remaining — any leftover skin will make the Moi Moi rough and bitter.\", \"Step 3: Place the peeled beans directly into the blender together with the scotch bonnet peppers, red bell pepper, onions, one raw egg, and a very small amount of water — just enough to get the blender moving. Blend everything together on high speed for 3 minutes until the paste is completely smooth with absolutely no grainy texture. Blending the peppers and egg together with the beans at this stage gives the Moi Moi its full flavour and colour from the inside.\", \"Step 4: Pour the blended paste into a large bowl. Add seasoning cubes, vegetable oil, and salt. Mix everything together thoroughly until well combined. Taste and adjust seasoning — it should be well seasoned and slightly peppery.\", \"Step 5: Using a wooden spoon or electric hand mixer, whisk the paste vigorously for 5 minutes until it becomes fluffy, lighter in colour, and increases slightly in volume. This aerates the paste and gives Moi Moi its soft moist texture when steamed.\", \"Step 6: Break the mackerel fish into medium sized chunks and slice your boiled eggs and set aside. Grease foil containers or moi moi leaves generously with vegetable oil on the inside so the moi moi does not stick.\", \"Step 7: Pour the bean paste mixture into each container filling only three quarters full. Drop pieces of fish directly into the paste in each container alongside the sliced eggs  — the fish sits inside the moi moi not on top. Press down lightly so the fish is submerged in the paste.\", \"Step 8: Seal each foil container tightly by folding the edges over securely. No steam should be able to escape during cooking.\", \"Step 9: Place a trivet or folded foil at the bottom of a large pot to prevent direct heat contact. Arrange the sealed moi moi containers in the pot and add water to reach halfway up the sides of the containers.\", \"Step 10: Cover the pot tightly and steam on medium heat for 45 to 60 minutes. Check water level every 15 minutes and add more hot water if needed — never let the pot run dry. Moi Moi is ready when it feels firm when pressed gently and pulls away cleanly from the container when opened.\"], \"dietary_labels\": [], \"dietary_flagged\": [], \"is_dietary_safe\": true, \"dietary_warnings\": [], \"match_percentage\": 9.1, \"used_ingredients\": [\"eggs\"], \"cook_time_minutes\": 60, \"prep_time_minutes\": 40, \"missing_ingredients\": [\"beans\", \"onions\", \"scotch bonnet peppers\", \"long chilli pepper (shombo)\", \"crayfish\", \"vegetable oil\", \"seasoning cubes\", \"salt\", \"fish (preferably mackerel fish)\", \"water\"]}, {\"name\": \"Abacha\", \"tips\": \"Always soak in cold water not hot. Potash is essential for emulsifying the palm oil into the dressing.\", \"servings\": 4, \"difficulty\": \"medium\", \"description\": \"Abacha is a traditional Igbo cold salad made from dried shredded cassava rehydrated and tossed in an emulsified palm oil and potash dressing with ugba, utazi leaves, garden eggs, crayfish, and assorted proteins.\", \"instructions\": [\"Step 1: Soak the dried abacha in cold water for 10 to 15 minutes until softened. Drain thoroughly.\", \"Step 2: Dissolve potash in 3 tablespoons of water and strain through a fine sieve.\", \"Step 3: Pour palm oil into a bowl. Add the potash solution gradually while stirring vigorously until emulsified and bright yellow.\", \"Step 4: Add ground crayfish, sliced scotch bonnet peppers, sliced onions, seasoning cubes, and salt to the emulsion.\", \"Step 5: Add the drained abacha and toss thoroughly until coated.\", \"Step 6: Add ugba, sliced garden eggs, shredded utazi, flaked fish, and sliced ponmo. Toss together gently.\", \"Step 7: Taste and adjust seasoning.\", \"Step 8: Garnish with utazi and onion rings. Serve at room temperature.\"], \"dietary_labels\": [], \"dietary_flagged\": [], \"is_dietary_safe\": true, \"dietary_warnings\": [], \"match_percentage\": 7.7, \"used_ingredients\": [\"garden eggs\"], \"cook_time_minutes\": 0, \"prep_time_minutes\": 20, \"missing_ingredients\": [\"abacha (dried shredded cassava)\", \"ugba (oil bean seeds)\", \"palm oil\", \"potash (kaun)\", \"utazi leaves\", \"crayfish\", \"onions\", \"scotch bonnet peppers\", \"seasoning cubes\", \"salt\", \"dried fish or stockfish\", \"ponmo (cow skin)\"]}, {\"name\": \"Nigerian Jollof Rice\", \"tips\": \"The secret to party jollof is double covering with foil and lid to trap steam, and finishing on high heat for the smoky bottom layer. Never use fresh tomatoes alone — always add tomato paste for depth of colour and flavour.\", \"servings\": 6, \"difficulty\": \"medium\", \"description\": \"Nigerian Jollof Rice is one of the most beloved dishes in West Africa, known for its rich smoky tomato flavour and vibrant orange-red colour. It is a staple at every Nigerian party, celebration, and family gathering. The secret to authentic Jollof Rice is the smoky bottom layer called party jollof which develops from cooking on high heat at the end.\", \"instructions\": [\"Step 1: Blend tomatoes, red bell peppers, long chilli peppers, scotch bonnet, and onions together in a blender until completely smooth with no chunks remaining. Set aside.\", \"Step 2: Wash rice thoroughly in cold water at least 3 times until water runs clear.\", \"Step 3: Heat vegetable oil in a large heavy-bottomed stainless steel or aluminum pot over medium-high heat for 2 minutes. Slice some onions, ginger and garlic paste, curry, thyme, bay leaves  and fry in the oil for 3 minutes.\", \"Step 4: Add tomato paste to the pot and fry with the mix for 3 minutes on medium heat, stirring constantly until the paste darkens slightly from bright red to a deeper reddish brown.\", \"Step 5: Pour the blended pepper mixture with some paprika into the pot. It will sizzle loudly — this is correct. Add in some seasoning cubes and salt. Fry on medium high heat uncovered for 25-30 minutes stirring every 5 minutes until all the water has evaporated, the oil floats on top, and the sauce has darkened to a deep red color. This step is critical — do not rush it.\", \"Step 6: Stir well and taste the sauce should be slightly salty as it will season the rice\", \"Step 7: Add the rice to the pot and stir well to coat every grain with the tomato sauce. Fry on high for like 2 minutes. Then add in chicken stock and some water enough to just cover the rice\", \"Step 8: Cover the pot tightly with foil first then place the lid on top to seal in all the steam. Cook on medium heat for 20 minutes without lifting the lid.\", \"Step 9: After 20 minutes lift the lid and check — rice should be almost fully cooked and liquid mostly absorbed. Stir gently from bottom to top. Cover again and cook on very low heat for 10 more minutes.\", \"Step 10: For the authentic party jollof smoky bottom, add in some cooking butter and sliced onions turn heat to high for the last 3-5 minutes. You will hear a crackling sound from the bottom — this is correct. Remove from heat immediately and leave covered for 5 minutes before serving.\"], \"dietary_labels\": [\"Diabetic\"], \"dietary_flagged\": [\"rice\"], \"is_dietary_safe\": true, \"dietary_warnings\": [\"High glycemic ingredients — consume in moderation\"], \"match_percentage\": 0.0, \"used_ingredients\": [], \"cook_time_minutes\": 70, \"prep_time_minutes\": 20, \"missing_ingredients\": [\"long grain parboiled rice\", \"tomatoes\", \"red bell peppers (tatashe)\", \"long chilli peppers(shombo) \", \"scotch bonnet peppers (ata rodo)\", \"onions\", \"vegetable oil\", \"tomato paste\", \"chicken stock\", \"seasoning cubes\", \"curry powder\", \"thyme\", \"bay leaves\", \"garlic powder\", \"salt\", \"paprika\"]}, {\"name\": \"Efo Riro\", \"tips\": \"The most important step is frying the pepper base completely dry until the oil floats on top before adding any meat or stock. This is what separates a rich deeply flavoured Efo Riro from a watery one. Also add the vegetables at the very last minute and cook for 2 minutes only — overcooked vegetables will turn dark and lose their flavour.\", \"servings\": 6, \"difficulty\": \"medium\", \"description\": \"Efo Riro is a rich Yoruba vegetable soup made with tatashe and ata rodo as the pepper base, assorted meats, and leafy green vegetables. The name means stirred leafy vegetable in Yoruba. It is one of the most flavourful Nigerian soups with a vibrant green and red colour from the vegetables and pepper base. It is served with amala, eba, pounded yam, or rice.\", \"instructions\": [\"Step 1: Wash and season assorted meat, pomo, and stockfish with onions, seasoning cubes, and salt. Cook on medium heat for 20 to 30 minutes until very tender. Set aside with the stock.\", \"Step 2: Blend tatashe and scotch bonnet peppers together into a smooth paste. Do not add water — the peppers have enough natural liquid. Set aside.\", \"Step 3: Wash the efo tete or spinach thoroughly, shred into medium sized pieces by hand, and set aside in a colander to drain excess water.\", \"Step 4: Heat palm oil in a large pot on medium-high heat for 2 minutes. Slice onions and fry in the palm oil for 3 minutes until golden and fragrant.\", \"Step 5: Add the blended tatashe and scotch bonnet pepper mixture to the pot. It will sizzle loudly in the hot oil — this is correct. Fry on high heat for 10 to 20 minutes stirring every 3 minutes until all the water has completely evaporated, the oil floats on top, and the pepper sauce has darkened and thickened. This step gives Efo Riro its deep rich flavour.\", \"Step 6: Add iru (locust beans) and ground crayfish and stir into the pepper sauce. Fry for 2 more minutes until the iru is fragrant.\", \"Step 7: Add the cooked assorted meat, stockfish, dried fish, and a ladle of the meat stock. Stir everything together and cook on medium heat for 10 minutes until the meat is well coated in the sauce.\", \"Step 8: Add the shredded efo tete or spinach to the pot and stir into the sauce. Cook for exactly 2 minutes only on medium heat — the vegetables should wilt into the soup but remain bright green and not soggy. Taste, adjust seasoning, and remove from heat immediately. Serve with amala, eba, or pounded yam.\"], \"dietary_labels\": [], \"dietary_flagged\": [], \"is_dietary_safe\": true, \"dietary_warnings\": [], \"match_percentage\": 0.0, \"used_ingredients\": [], \"cook_time_minutes\": 75, \"prep_time_minutes\": 25, \"missing_ingredients\": [\"vgetables African spinach or ugwu\", \"tatashe (red bell pepper)\", \"scotch bonnet peppers (ata rodo)\", \"onions\", \"palm oil\", \"assorted meat (beef, tripe, shaki, pomo)\", \"stockfish\", \"dried fish\", \"crayfish\", \"iru (locust beans)\", \"seasoning cubes\", \"salt\"]}, {\"name\": \"Egusi Soup Yoruba Style\", \"tips\": \"The secret to Yoruba egusi is frying the egusi completely dry in palm oil before adding any liquid. Never add water or stock to the egusi while frying — it must fry and toast in the oil until golden. Also never add tomatoes to Yoruba egusi soup — that changes the flavour profile completely.\", \"servings\": 6, \"difficulty\": \"medium\", \"description\": \"Egusi Soup Yoruba style is a rich and hearty Nigerian soup made with ground melon seeds fried directly in palm oil before any liquid is added. Unlike Igbo style egusi which is added raw, Yoruba style fries the egusi first until golden and nutty giving it a deeper richer flavour. It is served with amala, eba, or pounded yam.\", \"instructions\": [\"Step 1: Wash and season assorted meat and stockfish with onions, seasoning cubes, and salt. Cook in a pot on medium heat for 15 to 20 minutes until tender. Set aside with the stock.\", \"Step 2: Blend scotch bonnet peppers, tatashe, and half the onions together into a smooth paste. Set aside.\", \"Step 3: Heat palm oil in a large pot on medium heat for 2 minutes until melted and hot but not bleached. Chop the remaining onions and fry in the palm oil for 3 minutes until soft and translucent.\", \"Step 4: Add the ground egusi to the palm oil and stir immediately to combine. Fry the egusi in the palm oil on medium heat for 8 to 10 minutes stirring constantly until the egusi turns golden, smells nutty, and pulls away from the sides of the pot. Do not add any liquid at this stage — dry frying is the key to Yoruba egusi.\", \"Step 5: Add the blended pepper mixture to the fried egusi and stir well to combine. Fry together for another 10 minutes on medium heat stirring every 2 minutes until the pepper is cooked and oil begins to float on the surface.\", \"Step 6: Add the cooked meat, stockfish, dried fish, meat stock, ground crayfish, iru, and seasoning cubes. Stir everything together and add a small amount of water if the soup is too thick. Cook on medium heat for 15 minutes until all the flavours come together.\", \"Step 7: Taste and adjust salt and seasoning. The soup should be rich, thick, and deeply flavoured at this point.\", \"Step 8: Add shredded spinach or efo tete and stir into the soup. Cook for exactly 2 minutes only — overcooking the vegetables will make them lose their colour and become soggy. Remove from heat and serve immediately with amala, eba, or pounded yam.\"], \"dietary_labels\": [], \"dietary_flagged\": [], \"is_dietary_safe\": true, \"dietary_warnings\": [], \"match_percentage\": 0.0, \"used_ingredients\": [], \"cook_time_minutes\": 70, \"prep_time_minutes\": 20, \"missing_ingredients\": [\"ground egusi (melon seeds)\", \"palm oil\", \"assorted meat (beef, tripe, shaki)\", \"stockfish\", \"dried fish\", \"onions\", \"scotch bonnet peppers\", \"tatashe (red bell pepper)\", \"crayfish\", \"iru (locust beans)\", \"spinach, efo tete or ugwu\", \"seasoning cubes\", \"salt\"]}, {\"name\": \"Nigerian Pepper Soup\", \"tips\": \"The quality of your pepper soup spice mix makes or breaks this dish. Use freshly ground spices if possible — uda (country onion), ehuru (calabash nutmeg), and uziza seeds ground together give the most authentic flavour. Never cover the pot fully while cooking pepper soup — leave it slightly open so the broth reduces and concentrates.\", \"servings\": 4, \"difficulty\": \"easy\", \"description\": \"Nigerian Pepper Soup is a light, intensely spiced broth made with meat or fish and a unique blend of pepper soup spices. It is served at every Nigerian gathering, used as a remedy for colds and fever, and eaten as a starter or main dish. The broth is thin but deeply flavoured with a distinctive warming heat that comes from the special pepper soup spice blend.\", \"instructions\": [\"Step 1: Wash the meat thoroughly and cut into medium sized pieces. Season with onions, seasoning cubes, and salt. Do not add water yet — allow the meat to cook in its own juices first.\", \"Step 2: Place the seasoned meat in a pot on medium heat and cook dry for 10 minutes stirring occasionally until the meat releases its juices and begins to brown slightly on the outside.\", \"Step 3: Add enough water to cover the meat completely. Bring to a boil on high heat then reduce to medium heat. Cook for 25 to 30 minutes for goat meat or 15 minutes for chicken until the meat is tender but not falling off the bone.\", \"Step 4: Add the pepper soup spice mix, ground crayfish, and blended or roughly crushed scotch bonnet peppers. Stir well and taste — the broth should be well seasoned and spicy at this point. Add more seasoning cubes and salt if needed.\", \"Step 5: Cook on medium heat for another 15 minutes until the spices have fully infused into the broth and the liquid has reduced slightly. The broth should be a light golden brown colour and smell intensely aromatic.\", \"Step 6: Tear utazi leaves into small pieces and add to the pot — utazi adds a slight bitterness that balances the heat. Add uziza leaves whole or roughly torn. Cook for 3 minutes only.\", \"Step 7: Taste one final time and adjust salt and pepper. The pepper soup should be very hot and spicy, lightly bitter from the utazi, and deeply aromatic from the spice blend. Serve hot in deep bowls with sliced onions on top and agidi or white rice on the side.\"], \"dietary_labels\": [], \"dietary_flagged\": [], \"is_dietary_safe\": true, \"dietary_warnings\": [], \"match_percentage\": 0.0, \"used_ingredients\": [], \"cook_time_minutes\": 55, \"prep_time_minutes\": 15, \"missing_ingredients\": [\"goat meat or chicken or catfish\", \"pepper soup spice mix\", \"scotch bonnet peppers\", \"onions\", \"crayfish\", \"uziza leaves\", \"utazi leaves\", \"seasoning cubes\", \"salt\", \"water\"]}, {\"name\": \"Akara\", \"tips\": \"Whisking the bean paste until very fluffy is the secret to light soft akara — never skip this step. Also make sure the oil is very hot before adding the paste otherwise the akara will absorb too much oil and become greasy. Wet your spoon with oil before scooping each portion to help the paste slide off cleanly into the oil.\", \"servings\": 4, \"difficulty\": \"medium\", \"description\": \"Akara is a traditional Yoruba deep fried bean cake made from peeled black eyed beans blended into a smooth aerated paste and fried in hot oil until crispy on the outside and soft inside. It is a quintessential Nigerian breakfast food sold by roadside vendors across the country and best eaten hot with ogi (pap) or bread.\", \"instructions\": [\"Step 1: Peel the beans using one of two methods. Traditional method: Soak beans in cold water for 30 minutes then rub between palms under running water until all skins float off and are drained away. Quick method: Pulse beans and water  in a food processor for 30 seconds to crack and loosen skins, pour into a bowl of water, skim off floating skins, and drain. Rinse peeled beans two to three times in clean water.\", \"Step 2: Place the peeled beans alongside the peppers and onions in a blender with a very small amount of water — just enough to move the blender. Blend on high speed for 3 minutes until the paste is completely smooth and thick. The paste must be thick not watery — too much water will make flat oily akara.\", \"Step 3: Pour the blended bean paste into a large bowl. Using a wooden spoon or electric hand mixer whisk the paste vigorously for 5 to 7 minutes until it becomes very fluffy, lighter in colour, and almost doubles in volume. This is the most important step — the air you whisk in is what makes akara light and fluffy inside.\", \"Step 4: Add some salt and seasoning cubes to the whisked paste. Fold gently into the paste without deflating it. Taste and adjust seasoning.\", \"Step 5: Pour enough vegetable oil into a deep wide pan to allow the akara to float — at least 3 inches deep. Heat on medium-high heat for 2 to 3 minutes until hot. Test the oil by dropping a tiny bit of paste in — it should rise immediately to the surface and sizzle vigorously. If it sinks the oil is not hot enough.\", \"Step 6: Wet your tablespoon with oil and scoop portions of the paste into the hot oil one at a time. Do not overcrowd the pan — leave space between each akara so they cook evenly and stay round.\", \"Step 7: Fry on medium heat for 3 to 4 minutes until the bottom is deep golden brown, then flip carefully with a slotted spoon or skewer and fry the other side for 2 to 3 minutes until evenly golden brown and crispy all over.\", \"Step 8: Remove with a slotted spoon and drain on paper towels to absorb excess oil. Serve immediately while hot and crispy alongside ogi (pap) or as a breakfast snack.\"], \"dietary_labels\": [], \"dietary_flagged\": [], \"is_dietary_safe\": true, \"dietary_warnings\": [], \"match_percentage\": 0.0, \"used_ingredients\": [], \"cook_time_minutes\": 20, \"prep_time_minutes\": 30, \"missing_ingredients\": [\"black eyed beans\", \"onions\", \"scotch bonnet peppers\", \"long chilli peppers(shombo)\", \"seasoning cubes\", \"salt\", \"vegetable oil for deep frying\"]}, {\"name\": \"Ewa Agoyin\", \"tips\": \"The two secrets to authentic Ewa Agoyin are cooking the beans with a lot of onions until completely mashable with no whole beans remaining, and making the Agoyin stew with only dried peppers not fresh ones. Fresh peppers will not give the deep dark colour and concentrated flavour that makes Agoyin stew unique. The stew must be dark, dry, and almost burnt looking — that is correct.\", \"servings\": 4, \"difficulty\": \"medium\", \"description\": \"Ewa Agoyin is a popular Yoruba street food originally brought to Nigeria by Beninese traders, consisting of soft completely mashed honey beans or black eyed beans served with a deeply dark and spicy Agoyin stew made from dried red peppers and palm oil. It is a beloved Lagos breakfast food sold by roadside vendors and eaten with agege bread.\", \"instructions\": [\"Step 1: Wash the beans thoroughly then cover the beans with fresh water and cook on high heat until boiling, then reduce to medium heat. Cook for 45 to 60 minutes until the beans are extremely soft — they should mash completely between your fingers with no resistance. Add more water as needed during cooking to prevent burning.\", \"Step 2: Once the beans are very soft, use a wooden spoon or potato masher to mash them completely in the pot until no whole beans remain. The consistency should be thick and porridge-like. Season with salt, stir well, and set aside.\", \"Step 4: While the beans cook prepare the Agoyin stew. Rehydrate the dried red peppers and dried chilli peppers by soaking in hot water for 20 minutes until soft. Drain and blend alongside some onions and ginger into a rough paste — not completely smooth, leave some texture.\", \"Step 5: Heat palm oil in a separate pot on medium heat until hot. Slice onions into thin rings and fry in the palm oil for 10 minutes on medium-low heat, stirring constantly until the onions are very dark brown and almost caramelised — this dark onion is essential to the Agoyin stew flavour.\", \"Step 6: Add the blended dried pepper mixture to the dark onions and palm oil. Stir well and fry on medium heat for 20 to 25 minutes stirring every 3 minutes until all moisture evaporates, the stew becomes very dark, thick, and dry, and the oil floats on top. The stew should be almost black in colour — this is correct.\", \"Step 7: Add seasoning cubes and salt to the stew. Stir well and cook for 5 more minutes. The finished Agoyin stew should be very dark, very dry, very spicy, and intensely flavoured.\", \"Step 8: Serve the mashed beans in a bowl and pour the dark Agoyin stew generously on top. Eat with agege bread, fried plantain, or on its own.\"], \"dietary_labels\": [], \"dietary_flagged\": [], \"is_dietary_safe\": true, \"dietary_warnings\": [], \"match_percentage\": 0.0, \"used_ingredients\": [], \"cook_time_minutes\": 90, \"prep_time_minutes\": 20, \"missing_ingredients\": [\"beans\", \"dried red peppers (tatashe)\", \"dried long chilli bonnet peppers(shombo)\", \"onions\", \"palm oil\", \"crayfish\", \"seasoning cubes\", \"salt\", \"water\"]}, {\"name\": \"Asun\", \"tips\": \"Grilling or smoking the goat meat after boiling is non-negotiable for authentic Asun — without the charred smoky exterior the dish is just peppered goat meat not Asun. Use goat meat with the skin on for the best texture and flavour. The pepper sauce should have chunky sliced peppers not a blended smooth sauce.\", \"servings\": 4, \"difficulty\": \"medium\", \"description\": \"Asun is a popular Yoruba delicacy of smoked or roasted goat meat cut into small pieces and tossed in a fiery pepper and onion sauce. It originates from Ondo State in Yorubaland and is now one of the most popular Nigerian party small chops and appetisers served across the country. The goat meat is first smoked or roasted to give it a distinctive charred flavour before being peppered.\", \"instructions\": [\"Step 1: Wash the goat meat thoroughly — authentic Asun uses goat meat with the skin on as the skin adds texture and flavour. Cut into medium sized chunks. Season with seasoning cubes, curry powder, thyme, ginger garlic paste and salt.\", \"Step 2: Cook the seasoned goat meat in a pot with a small amount of water on medium heat for 20 to 25 minutes until tender but not falling apart.\", \"Step 3: Remove the cooked goat meat and place directly on a grill, open flame, or in a very hot oven at 220 degrees Celsius. Grill or roast for 15 to 20 minutes turning occasionally until the outside is charred and smoky and the skin is slightly crispy. The charring is essential for authentic Asun flavour.\", \"Step 4: Remove from the grill and cut into smaller bite sized pieces while still hot. Set aside.\", \"Step 5: Slice scotch bonnet peppers, green bell pepper, red bell pepper, and onions into thin strips. The peppers should be sliced not blended, a food processor can be used as well — the chunky pepper pieces are characteristic of Asun.\", \"Step 6: Heat vegetable oil in a wide pan on medium heat. Add the sliced onions and fry for 2 minutes until slightly softened.\", \"Step 7: Add all the sliced peppers to the pan and stir fry on high heat for 3 to 4 minutes — the peppers should be cooked but still have a slight crunch. Do not overcook the peppers into mush.\", \"Step 8: Add the grilled goat meat pieces to the pan and toss vigorously with the peppers for 3 minutes on high heat until the meat is well coated in the pepper mixture and everything is sizzling hot. Taste and adjust seasoning. Serve immediately as a party appetiser or small chop.\"], \"dietary_labels\": [], \"dietary_flagged\": [], \"is_dietary_safe\": true, \"dietary_warnings\": [], \"match_percentage\": 0.0, \"used_ingredients\": [], \"cook_time_minutes\": 60, \"prep_time_minutes\": 20, \"missing_ingredients\": [\"goat meat (skin on)\", \"scotch bonnet peppers\", \"green bell pepper\", \"red bell pepper (tatashe)\", \"onions\", \"vegetable oil\", \"seasoning cubes\", \"curry powder\", \"thyme\", \"salt\", \"ginger garlic paste\"]}, {\"name\": \"Ayamase (Ofada Stew)\", \"tips\": \"Bleaching the palm oil is absolutely non-negotiable for authentic Ayamase. Only use green peppers and unripe tatashe — no red peppers at all. The more assorted meats you use the richer and more authentic the stew will be.\", \"servings\": 6, \"difficulty\": \"hard\", \"description\": \"Ayamase also known as Ofada Stew or Designer Stew is a rich and intensely flavoured Yoruba stew made exclusively with green peppers and unripe tatashe giving it its distinctive green colour. It is traditionally served with Ofada rice and the stew is made with bleached palm oil and loaded with assorted meats making it one of the most indulgent Nigerian dishes.\", \"instructions\": [\"Step 1: Wash and season all assorted meats with onions, seasoning cubes, ginger garlic paste and salt. Cook in a pot on medium heat for 25 to 35 minutes until very tender. Fry the cooked meats in a small amount of oil until lightly browned on the outside for extra flavour. Set aside with the stock.\", \"Step 2: Blend green bell peppers, unripe green tatashe, green scotch bonnet peppers, and onions together into a coarse paste — do not blend completely smooth, leave some texture. The stew must use only green peppers and unripe tatashe — never red peppers or ripe tatashe as this completely changes the dish.\", \"Step 3: Bleach the palm oil by heating it in a pot on high heat with the lid on for 10 to 15 minutes until the oil turns from orange-red to a pale golden yellow colour and begins to smoke lightly. Remove from heat and allow to cool slightly. Bleached palm oil is essential for authentic Ayamase.\", \"Step 4: Return the bleached palm oil to medium heat. Add sliced onions with some ginger garlic paste and fry for 3 minutes until soft and slightly golden.\", \"Step 5: Pour the blended green pepper mixture into the bleached palm oil. It will sizzle vigorously stir immediately. Fry on high heat for 15 to 20 minutes stirring every 3 to 4 minutes until all the water has completely evaporated, the oil floats on top, and the pepper sauce is cooked down and thick.\", \"Step 6: Add iru (locust beans) and ground crayfish to the cooked pepper base and stir well. Fry for 3 more minutes until the iru is fragrant and well incorporated.\", \"Step 7: Add all the assorted meats and a ladle of the meat stock. Stir everything together to coat the meat in the green pepper sauce. Cook on medium heat for 10 minutes until the meat is well flavoured and the stew is thick and rich.\", \"Step 8: Taste and adjust seasoning. The finished Ayamase should be dark olive green, thick, intensely flavoured, and very rich with assorted meats. Serve with Ofada rice.\"], \"dietary_labels\": [], \"dietary_flagged\": [], \"is_dietary_safe\": true, \"dietary_warnings\": [], \"match_percentage\": 0.0, \"used_ingredients\": [], \"cook_time_minutes\": 90, \"prep_time_minutes\": 25, \"missing_ingredients\": [\"green bell peppers\", \"unripe tatashe (green tatashe)\", \"green scotch bonnet peppers\", \"onions\", \"palm oil\", \"assorted meat (beef, tripe, shaki, pomo, liver)\", \"crayfish\", \"iru (locust beans)\", \"seasoning cubes\", \"ginger and garlic paste\", \"salt\"]}, {\"name\": \"Ikokore\", \"tips\": \"Use water yam specifically not white yam or cocoyam. Do not rinse the grated yam before adding to the pot as the natural starch thickens the broth and holds the dumplings together.\", \"servings\": 4, \"difficulty\": \"medium\", \"description\": \"Ikokore is a traditional Ijebu Yoruba dish made from grated water yam cooked in a rich pepper soup or tomato base with assorted fish and seafood. The grated water yam forms thick irregular dumplings in the broth giving the dish its characteristic texture. It is a beloved dish in Ogun State and across Yorubaland.\", \"instructions\": [\"Step 1: Peel the water yam and grate on the coarse side of a grater into a bowl. Do not rinse the grated yam — the natural starch is needed to hold the dumplings together. Season the grated yam lightly with salt and set aside.\", \"Step 2: Blend scotch bonnet peppers, long chilli peppers, and onions together into a smooth paste.\", \"Step 3: Heat palm oil in a large pot on medium heat. Add iru and fry for 1 minute until fragrant. Add the blended pepper mixture and fry for 15 minutes until cooked and oil floats on top.\", \"Step 4: Add enough meat stock to the pot . Add ground crayfish, dried fish, smoked fish, assorted meat, seasoning cubes, and salt. Bring to a boil on high heat.\", \"Step 5: Using a tablespoon or your hand, scoop portions of the grated water yam and drop them one by one into the boiling broth. Do not stir immediately — allow the yam dumplings to set for 3 minutes before stirring gently.\", \"Step 6: Cook on medium heat for 15 to 20 minutes stirring gently occasionally until the yam dumplings are fully cooked and the broth has thickened, adjust seasoning, and serve hot.\"], \"dietary_labels\": [\"Diabetic\"], \"dietary_flagged\": [\"yam\"], \"is_dietary_safe\": true, \"dietary_warnings\": [\"High glycemic ingredients — consume in moderation\"], \"match_percentage\": 0.0, \"used_ingredients\": [], \"cook_time_minutes\": 50, \"prep_time_minutes\": 25, \"missing_ingredients\": [\"water yam (isu ewura)\", \"dried fish\", \"assorted meat\", \"smoked fish\", \"palm oil\", \"crayfish\", \"scotch bonnet peppers\", \"long chilli peppers\", \"onions\", \"iru (locust beans)\", \"seasoning cubes\", \"salt\", \"water\"]}, {\"name\": \"Asaro (Yam Porridge)\", \"tips\": \"Gentle stirring lets some yam break down to thicken the sauce naturally without becoming completely mashed.\", \"servings\": 4, \"difficulty\": \"easy\", \"description\": \"Asaro is a beloved traditional Yoruba yam porridge made by cooking yam chunks directly in a rich tomato and pepper sauce until the yam softens and thickens the entire dish into a hearty one-pot meal.\", \"instructions\": [\"Step 1: Peel the yam and cut into medium sized chunks. Wash thoroughly.\", \"Step 2: Blend onions, tatashe, and scotch bonnet peppers together into a smooth paste.\", \"Step 3: Place the yam chunks in a pot with the blended pepper mixture, sliced onions, palm oil, and enough water to just cover the yam.\", \"Step 4: Bring to a boil then reduce to medium heat. Cook for 20 to 25 minutes, stirring occasionally, until the yam softens and breaks down at the edges.\", \"Step 5: Add ground crayfish, flaked fish, seasoning cubes, and salt. Stir gently.\", \"Step 6: Continue cooking on medium-low heat for 8 to 10 minutes until thick and stew-like.\", \"Step 7: Taste and adjust seasoning. Serve hot on its own.\"], \"dietary_labels\": [\"Diabetic\"], \"dietary_flagged\": [\"yam\"], \"is_dietary_safe\": true, \"dietary_warnings\": [\"High glycemic ingredients — consume in moderation\"], \"match_percentage\": 0.0, \"used_ingredients\": [], \"cook_time_minutes\": 40, \"prep_time_minutes\": 15, \"missing_ingredients\": [\"yam (white yam)\", \"tomatoes\", \"tatashe (red bell pepper)\", \"scotch bonnet peppers\", \"onions\", \"palm oil\", \"crayfish\", \"smoked fish or dried fish\", \"seasoning cubes\", \"salt\", \"water\"]}, {\"name\": \"Nigerian Fried Rice\", \"tips\": \"Always cook on high heat when frying the rice and vegetables together to prevent everything from steaming and becoming soggy instead of stir-fried.\", \"servings\": 6, \"difficulty\": \"medium\", \"description\": \"Nigerian Fried Rice is a colourful and flavourful party staple made with parboiled rice stir-fried with mixed vegetables, liver, and a distinct curry seasoning. Unlike Chinese fried rice, the Nigerian version has a unique orange-yellow hue from curry powder and is loaded with vegetables, making it one of the most popular dishes at Nigerian celebrations alongside Jollof Rice.\", \"instructions\": [\"Step 1: Wash the rice thoroughly until water runs clear then transfer into a seive till perfectly dry. Then into a pot, add some oil and fry the rice for about 5 minutes\", \"Step 2: Season the liver with salt and a little curry powder. Cook in a pot with a small amount of water for 8 to 10 minutes until just cooked through, then dice into small cubes.\", \"Step 3: Dice carrots and green beans into small uniform cubes for even cooking. Set aside along with the bell peppers.\", \"Step 4: Heat vegetable oil in a large wok or wide pan on high heat. Add minced garlic and ginger and stir fry for 30 seconds until fragrant but not browned.\", \"Step 5: Add diced onions and stir fry for 2 minutes until softened. Add the diced liver and shrimp and stir fry for 2 minutes.\", \"Step 6: Add the carrots, green beans, green peas, and bell peppers to the pan. Stir fry on high heat for 3 minutes until heated through but still slightly crisp.\", \"Step 7: Add the cooled parboiled rice to the pan along with curry powder, thyme, seasoning cubes, soy sauce, and salt. Stir fry vigorously on high heat for 5 to 7 minutes, tossing continuously, until the rice is evenly coated in the yellow curry colour and well combined with all the vegetables and protein. Taste and adjust seasoning, then serve hot.\"], \"dietary_labels\": [\"Diabetic\"], \"dietary_flagged\": [\"rice\"], \"is_dietary_safe\": true, \"dietary_warnings\": [\"High glycemic ingredients — consume in moderation\"], \"match_percentage\": 0.0, \"used_ingredients\": [], \"cook_time_minutes\": 30, \"prep_time_minutes\": 30, \"missing_ingredients\": [\"long grain rice\", \"carrots\", \"green peas\", \"bell peppers(green, yellow, red)\", \"liver\", \"vegetable oil\", \"onions\", \"garlic\", \"ginger\", \"curry powder\", \"thyme\", \"seasoning cubes\", \"soy sauce\", \"salt\", \"chicken stock\"]}, {\"name\": \"Banga Stew\", \"tips\": \"The key difference between Banga Soup and Banga Stew is the reduction time — cook the stew version longer uncovered to achieve a thicker consistency that coats rice or yam well rather than the more liquid soup form.\", \"servings\": 5, \"difficulty\": \"hard\", \"description\": \"Banga Stew is a thick, deeply flavoured Igbo stew made from concentrated palm fruit extract, prepared similarly to Banga Soup but cooked down to a thicker consistency more like a stew than a soup. It is rich, nutty, and aromatic, traditionally seasoned with banga spices, and served with white rice, boiled yam, or plantain.\", \"instructions\": [\"Step 1: If using fresh palm fruit, boil for 20 to 30 minutes until soft, then pound to separate pulp from nuts and squeeze with warm water to extract the thick orange juice. Strain through a sieve to remove fibres. If using canned concentrate, dilute according to package instructions.\", \"Step 2: Pour the palm fruit extract into a pot and bring to a boil on high heat, then reduce to medium heat and simmer for 15 to 20 minutes until the oil begins to separate and rise to the surface.\", \"Step 3: Season the assorted meat with onions, seasoning cubes, and salt. Cook separately on medium heat for 30 minutes until tender. Add the cooked meat and stock to the palm fruit base.\", \"Step 4: Add the banga spice mix to the pot and simmer for 15 minutes to allow the spices to infuse fully into the base.\", \"Step 5: Add dried fish, ground crayfish, sliced scotch bonnet peppers, and seasoning cubes. Stir well and continue cooking on medium heat, allowing the liquid to reduce and thicken for 20 to 25 minutes — unlike Banga Soup this should reduce further into a thicker stew-like consistency.\", \"Step 6: Add the fresh fish pieces and cook gently for 8 to 10 minutes until just cooked through, stirring carefully to avoid breaking the fish apart.\", \"Step 7: Continue simmering uncovered for an additional 10 minutes, stirring occasionally, until the stew has thickened noticeably and the oil is clearly visible on the surface.\", \"Step 8: Remove the oburunbebe stick before serving. Taste and adjust seasoning. Serve hot with white rice, boiled yam, or plantain.\"], \"dietary_labels\": [], \"dietary_flagged\": [], \"is_dietary_safe\": true, \"dietary_warnings\": [], \"match_percentage\": 0.0, \"used_ingredients\": [], \"cook_time_minutes\": 80, \"prep_time_minutes\": 30, \"missing_ingredients\": [\"fresh palm fruit (or canned banga concentrate)\", \"assorted meat (beef, tripe)\", \"dried fish\", \"fresh fish\", \"banga spice mix (oburunbebe stick, dried bitter leaf)\", \"onions\", \"scotch bonnet peppers\", \"crayfish\", \"seasoning cubes\", \"salt\", \"water\"]}, {\"name\": \"Ofe Owerri\", \"tips\": \"Use as many different types of meat and fish as you can for the most authentic version. The combination of ugu and uziza leaves together distinguishes this from Edikang Ikong.\", \"servings\": 6, \"difficulty\": \"hard\", \"description\": \"Ofe Owerri is a luxurious traditional Igbo vegetable soup from Owerri in Imo State, known for being loaded with multiple types of meat, fish, and a generous mix of vegetables, traditionally served at important ceremonies.\", \"instructions\": [\"Step 1: Wash and season all assorted meats and stockfish with onions, seasoning cubes, and salt. Cook on medium heat for 40 to 50 minutes until very tender. Set aside with the rich stock.\", \"Step 2: Peel cocoyam and boil until very soft, then pound until completely smooth to make the thickener.\", \"Step 3: Heat palm oil, add sliced onions and blended scotch bonnet peppers, fry for 15 minutes until oil floats on top.\", \"Step 4: Add all the cooked meats, stockfish, dried fish, periwinkle, ogiri, ground crayfish, and meat stock. Cook on medium heat for 15 minutes.\", \"Step 5: Add the pounded cocoyam thickener in small lumps and stir until dissolved.\", \"Step 6: Add the fresh fish pieces and cook gently for 8 minutes.\", \"Step 7: Add the shredded ugu and uziza leaves together and stir in. Cook for 3 to 5 minutes only.\", \"Step 8: Taste and adjust seasoning. Serve hot with pounded yam, fufu, or semolina.\"], \"dietary_labels\": [\"Diabetic\"], \"dietary_flagged\": [\"yam\"], \"is_dietary_safe\": true, \"dietary_warnings\": [\"High glycemic ingredients — consume in moderation\"], \"match_percentage\": 0.0, \"used_ingredients\": [], \"cook_time_minutes\": 85, \"prep_time_minutes\": 30, \"missing_ingredients\": [\"ugu leaves (fluted pumpkin)\", \"uziza leaves\", \"cocoyam (for thickening)\", \"palm oil\", \"assorted meat (beef, tripe, shaki, cow leg)\", \"stockfish\", \"dried fish\", \"fresh fish\", \"periwinkle\", \"crayfish\", \"onions\", \"scotch bonnet peppers\", \"ogiri (fermented locust beans)\", \"seasoning cubes\", \"salt\"]}]}','2026-06-21 11:14:04'),('944315a5-145f-493b-87e1-f51f7296f2de','[\"rice\", \"tomatoes\", \"onions\", \"chicken\"]','nigerian',NULL,'{\"almost_there\": [], \"can_make_now\": [], \"needs_shopping\": [{\"name\": \"Nigerian Jollof Rice\", \"tips\": \"The secret to party jollof is double covering with foil and lid to trap steam, and finishing on high heat for the smoky bottom layer. Never use fresh tomatoes alone — always add tomato paste for depth of colour and flavour.\", \"servings\": 6, \"difficulty\": \"medium\", \"description\": \"Nigerian Jollof Rice is one of the most beloved dishes in West Africa, known for its rich smoky tomato flavour and vibrant orange-red colour. It is a staple at every Nigerian party, celebration, and family gathering. The secret to authentic Jollof Rice is the smoky bottom layer called party jollof which develops from cooking on high heat at the end.\", \"instructions\": [\"Step 1: Blend tomatoes, red bell peppers, long chilli peppers, scotch bonnet, and onions together in a blender until completely smooth with no chunks remaining. Set aside.\", \"Step 2: Wash rice thoroughly in cold water at least 3 times until water runs clear.\", \"Step 3: Heat vegetable oil in a large heavy-bottomed stainless steel or aluminum pot over medium-high heat for 2 minutes. Slice some onions, ginger and garlic paste, curry, thyme, bay leaves  and fry in the oil for 3 minutes.\", \"Step 4: Add tomato paste to the pot and fry with the mix for 3 minutes on medium heat, stirring constantly until the paste darkens slightly from bright red to a deeper reddish brown.\", \"Step 5: Pour the blended pepper mixture with some paprika into the pot. It will sizzle loudly — this is correct. Add in some seasoning cubes and salt. Fry on medium high heat uncovered for 25-30 minutes stirring every 5 minutes until all the water has evaporated, the oil floats on top, and the sauce has darkened to a deep red color. This step is critical — do not rush it.\", \"Step 6: Stir well and taste the sauce should be slightly salty as it will season the rice\", \"Step 7: Add the rice to the pot and stir well to coat every grain with the tomato sauce. Fry on high for like 2 minutes. Then add in chicken stock and some water enough to just cover the rice\", \"Step 8: Cover the pot tightly with foil first then place the lid on top to seal in all the steam. Cook on medium heat for 20 minutes without lifting the lid.\", \"Step 9: After 20 minutes lift the lid and check — rice should be almost fully cooked and liquid mostly absorbed. Stir gently from bottom to top. Cover again and cook on very low heat for 10 more minutes.\", \"Step 10: For the authentic party jollof smoky bottom, add in some cooking butter and sliced onions turn heat to high for the last 3-5 minutes. You will hear a crackling sound from the bottom — this is correct. Remove from heat immediately and leave covered for 5 minutes before serving.\"], \"dietary_labels\": [\"Diabetic\"], \"dietary_flagged\": [\"rice\"], \"is_dietary_safe\": true, \"dietary_warnings\": [\"High glycemic ingredients — consume in moderation\"], \"match_percentage\": 25.0, \"used_ingredients\": [\"long grain parboiled rice\", \"tomatoes\", \"onions\", \"chicken stock\"], \"cook_time_minutes\": 70, \"prep_time_minutes\": 20, \"missing_ingredients\": [\"red bell peppers (tatashe)\", \"long chilli peppers(shombo) \", \"scotch bonnet peppers (ata rodo)\", \"vegetable oil\", \"tomato paste\", \"seasoning cubes\", \"curry powder\", \"thyme\", \"bay leaves\", \"garlic powder\", \"salt\", \"paprika\"]}, {\"name\": \"Nigerian Pepper Soup\", \"tips\": \"The quality of your pepper soup spice mix makes or breaks this dish. Use freshly ground spices if possible — uda (country onion), ehuru (calabash nutmeg), and uziza seeds ground together give the most authentic flavour. Never cover the pot fully while cooking pepper soup — leave it slightly open so the broth reduces and concentrates.\", \"servings\": 4, \"difficulty\": \"easy\", \"description\": \"Nigerian Pepper Soup is a light, intensely spiced broth made with meat or fish and a unique blend of pepper soup spices. It is served at every Nigerian gathering, used as a remedy for colds and fever, and eaten as a starter or main dish. The broth is thin but deeply flavoured with a distinctive warming heat that comes from the special pepper soup spice blend.\", \"instructions\": [\"Step 1: Wash the meat thoroughly and cut into medium sized pieces. Season with onions, seasoning cubes, and salt. Do not add water yet — allow the meat to cook in its own juices first.\", \"Step 2: Place the seasoned meat in a pot on medium heat and cook dry for 10 minutes stirring occasionally until the meat releases its juices and begins to brown slightly on the outside.\", \"Step 3: Add enough water to cover the meat completely. Bring to a boil on high heat then reduce to medium heat. Cook for 25 to 30 minutes for goat meat or 15 minutes for chicken until the meat is tender but not falling off the bone.\", \"Step 4: Add the pepper soup spice mix, ground crayfish, and blended or roughly crushed scotch bonnet peppers. Stir well and taste — the broth should be well seasoned and spicy at this point. Add more seasoning cubes and salt if needed.\", \"Step 5: Cook on medium heat for another 15 minutes until the spices have fully infused into the broth and the liquid has reduced slightly. The broth should be a light golden brown colour and smell intensely aromatic.\", \"Step 6: Tear utazi leaves into small pieces and add to the pot — utazi adds a slight bitterness that balances the heat. Add uziza leaves whole or roughly torn. Cook for 3 minutes only.\", \"Step 7: Taste one final time and adjust salt and pepper. The pepper soup should be very hot and spicy, lightly bitter from the utazi, and deeply aromatic from the spice blend. Serve hot in deep bowls with sliced onions on top and agidi or white rice on the side.\"], \"dietary_labels\": [], \"dietary_flagged\": [], \"is_dietary_safe\": true, \"dietary_warnings\": [], \"match_percentage\": 20.0, \"used_ingredients\": [\"goat meat or chicken or catfish\", \"onions\"], \"cook_time_minutes\": 55, \"prep_time_minutes\": 15, \"missing_ingredients\": [\"pepper soup spice mix\", \"scotch bonnet peppers\", \"crayfish\", \"uziza leaves\", \"utazi leaves\", \"seasoning cubes\", \"salt\", \"water\"]}, {\"name\": \"Nigerian Fried Rice\", \"tips\": \"Always cook on high heat when frying the rice and vegetables together to prevent everything from steaming and becoming soggy instead of stir-fried.\", \"servings\": 6, \"difficulty\": \"medium\", \"description\": \"Nigerian Fried Rice is a colourful and flavourful party staple made with parboiled rice stir-fried with mixed vegetables, liver, and a distinct curry seasoning. Unlike Chinese fried rice, the Nigerian version has a unique orange-yellow hue from curry powder and is loaded with vegetables, making it one of the most popular dishes at Nigerian celebrations alongside Jollof Rice.\", \"instructions\": [\"Step 1: Wash the rice thoroughly until water runs clear then transfer into a seive till perfectly dry. Then into a pot, add some oil and fry the rice for about 5 minutes\", \"Step 2: Season the liver with salt and a little curry powder. Cook in a pot with a small amount of water for 8 to 10 minutes until just cooked through, then dice into small cubes.\", \"Step 3: Dice carrots and green beans into small uniform cubes for even cooking. Set aside along with the bell peppers.\", \"Step 4: Heat vegetable oil in a large wok or wide pan on high heat. Add minced garlic and ginger and stir fry for 30 seconds until fragrant but not browned.\", \"Step 5: Add diced onions and stir fry for 2 minutes until softened. Add the diced liver and shrimp and stir fry for 2 minutes.\", \"Step 6: Add the carrots, green beans, green peas, and bell peppers to the pan. Stir fry on high heat for 3 minutes until heated through but still slightly crisp.\", \"Step 7: Add the cooled parboiled rice to the pan along with curry powder, thyme, seasoning cubes, soy sauce, and salt. Stir fry vigorously on high heat for 5 to 7 minutes, tossing continuously, until the rice is evenly coated in the yellow curry colour and well combined with all the vegetables and protein. Taste and adjust seasoning, then serve hot.\"], \"dietary_labels\": [\"Diabetic\"], \"dietary_flagged\": [\"rice\"], \"is_dietary_safe\": true, \"dietary_warnings\": [\"High glycemic ingredients — consume in moderation\"], \"match_percentage\": 20.0, \"used_ingredients\": [\"long grain rice\", \"onions\", \"chicken stock\"], \"cook_time_minutes\": 30, \"prep_time_minutes\": 30, \"missing_ingredients\": [\"carrots\", \"green peas\", \"bell peppers(green, yellow, red)\", \"liver\", \"vegetable oil\", \"garlic\", \"ginger\", \"curry powder\", \"thyme\", \"seasoning cubes\", \"soy sauce\", \"salt\"]}, {\"name\": \"Asaro (Yam Porridge)\", \"tips\": \"Gentle stirring lets some yam break down to thicken the sauce naturally without becoming completely mashed.\", \"servings\": 4, \"difficulty\": \"easy\", \"description\": \"Asaro is a beloved traditional Yoruba yam porridge made by cooking yam chunks directly in a rich tomato and pepper sauce until the yam softens and thickens the entire dish into a hearty one-pot meal.\", \"instructions\": [\"Step 1: Peel the yam and cut into medium sized chunks. Wash thoroughly.\", \"Step 2: Blend onions, tatashe, and scotch bonnet peppers together into a smooth paste.\", \"Step 3: Place the yam chunks in a pot with the blended pepper mixture, sliced onions, palm oil, and enough water to just cover the yam.\", \"Step 4: Bring to a boil then reduce to medium heat. Cook for 20 to 25 minutes, stirring occasionally, until the yam softens and breaks down at the edges.\", \"Step 5: Add ground crayfish, flaked fish, seasoning cubes, and salt. Stir gently.\", \"Step 6: Continue cooking on medium-low heat for 8 to 10 minutes until thick and stew-like.\", \"Step 7: Taste and adjust seasoning. Serve hot on its own.\"], \"dietary_labels\": [\"Diabetic\"], \"dietary_flagged\": [\"yam\"], \"is_dietary_safe\": true, \"dietary_warnings\": [\"High glycemic ingredients — consume in moderation\"], \"match_percentage\": 18.2, \"used_ingredients\": [\"tomatoes\", \"onions\"], \"cook_time_minutes\": 40, \"prep_time_minutes\": 15, \"missing_ingredients\": [\"yam (white yam)\", \"tatashe (red bell pepper)\", \"scotch bonnet peppers\", \"palm oil\", \"crayfish\", \"smoked fish or dried fish\", \"seasoning cubes\", \"salt\", \"water\"]}, {\"name\": \"Akara\", \"tips\": \"Whisking the bean paste until very fluffy is the secret to light soft akara — never skip this step. Also make sure the oil is very hot before adding the paste otherwise the akara will absorb too much oil and become greasy. Wet your spoon with oil before scooping each portion to help the paste slide off cleanly into the oil.\", \"servings\": 4, \"difficulty\": \"medium\", \"description\": \"Akara is a traditional Yoruba deep fried bean cake made from peeled black eyed beans blended into a smooth aerated paste and fried in hot oil until crispy on the outside and soft inside. It is a quintessential Nigerian breakfast food sold by roadside vendors across the country and best eaten hot with ogi (pap) or bread.\", \"instructions\": [\"Step 1: Peel the beans using one of two methods. Traditional method: Soak beans in cold water for 30 minutes then rub between palms under running water until all skins float off and are drained away. Quick method: Pulse beans and water  in a food processor for 30 seconds to crack and loosen skins, pour into a bowl of water, skim off floating skins, and drain. Rinse peeled beans two to three times in clean water.\", \"Step 2: Place the peeled beans alongside the peppers and onions in a blender with a very small amount of water — just enough to move the blender. Blend on high speed for 3 minutes until the paste is completely smooth and thick. The paste must be thick not watery — too much water will make flat oily akara.\", \"Step 3: Pour the blended bean paste into a large bowl. Using a wooden spoon or electric hand mixer whisk the paste vigorously for 5 to 7 minutes until it becomes very fluffy, lighter in colour, and almost doubles in volume. This is the most important step — the air you whisk in is what makes akara light and fluffy inside.\", \"Step 4: Add some salt and seasoning cubes to the whisked paste. Fold gently into the paste without deflating it. Taste and adjust seasoning.\", \"Step 5: Pour enough vegetable oil into a deep wide pan to allow the akara to float — at least 3 inches deep. Heat on medium-high heat for 2 to 3 minutes until hot. Test the oil by dropping a tiny bit of paste in — it should rise immediately to the surface and sizzle vigorously. If it sinks the oil is not hot enough.\", \"Step 6: Wet your tablespoon with oil and scoop portions of the paste into the hot oil one at a time. Do not overcrowd the pan — leave space between each akara so they cook evenly and stay round.\", \"Step 7: Fry on medium heat for 3 to 4 minutes until the bottom is deep golden brown, then flip carefully with a slotted spoon or skewer and fry the other side for 2 to 3 minutes until evenly golden brown and crispy all over.\", \"Step 8: Remove with a slotted spoon and drain on paper towels to absorb excess oil. Serve immediately while hot and crispy alongside ogi (pap) or as a breakfast snack.\"], \"dietary_labels\": [], \"dietary_flagged\": [], \"is_dietary_safe\": true, \"dietary_warnings\": [], \"match_percentage\": 14.3, \"used_ingredients\": [\"onions\"], \"cook_time_minutes\": 20, \"prep_time_minutes\": 30, \"missing_ingredients\": [\"black eyed beans\", \"scotch bonnet peppers\", \"long chilli peppers(shombo)\", \"seasoning cubes\", \"salt\", \"vegetable oil for deep frying\"]}, {\"name\": \"Ewa Agoyin\", \"tips\": \"The two secrets to authentic Ewa Agoyin are cooking the beans with a lot of onions until completely mashable with no whole beans remaining, and making the Agoyin stew with only dried peppers not fresh ones. Fresh peppers will not give the deep dark colour and concentrated flavour that makes Agoyin stew unique. The stew must be dark, dry, and almost burnt looking — that is correct.\", \"servings\": 4, \"difficulty\": \"medium\", \"description\": \"Ewa Agoyin is a popular Yoruba street food originally brought to Nigeria by Beninese traders, consisting of soft completely mashed honey beans or black eyed beans served with a deeply dark and spicy Agoyin stew made from dried red peppers and palm oil. It is a beloved Lagos breakfast food sold by roadside vendors and eaten with agege bread.\", \"instructions\": [\"Step 1: Wash the beans thoroughly then cover the beans with fresh water and cook on high heat until boiling, then reduce to medium heat. Cook for 45 to 60 minutes until the beans are extremely soft — they should mash completely between your fingers with no resistance. Add more water as needed during cooking to prevent burning.\", \"Step 2: Once the beans are very soft, use a wooden spoon or potato masher to mash them completely in the pot until no whole beans remain. The consistency should be thick and porridge-like. Season with salt, stir well, and set aside.\", \"Step 4: While the beans cook prepare the Agoyin stew. Rehydrate the dried red peppers and dried chilli peppers by soaking in hot water for 20 minutes until soft. Drain and blend alongside some onions and ginger into a rough paste — not completely smooth, leave some texture.\", \"Step 5: Heat palm oil in a separate pot on medium heat until hot. Slice onions into thin rings and fry in the palm oil for 10 minutes on medium-low heat, stirring constantly until the onions are very dark brown and almost caramelised — this dark onion is essential to the Agoyin stew flavour.\", \"Step 6: Add the blended dried pepper mixture to the dark onions and palm oil. Stir well and fry on medium heat for 20 to 25 minutes stirring every 3 minutes until all moisture evaporates, the stew becomes very dark, thick, and dry, and the oil floats on top. The stew should be almost black in colour — this is correct.\", \"Step 7: Add seasoning cubes and salt to the stew. Stir well and cook for 5 more minutes. The finished Agoyin stew should be very dark, very dry, very spicy, and intensely flavoured.\", \"Step 8: Serve the mashed beans in a bowl and pour the dark Agoyin stew generously on top. Eat with agege bread, fried plantain, or on its own.\"], \"dietary_labels\": [], \"dietary_flagged\": [], \"is_dietary_safe\": true, \"dietary_warnings\": [], \"match_percentage\": 11.1, \"used_ingredients\": [\"onions\"], \"cook_time_minutes\": 90, \"prep_time_minutes\": 20, \"missing_ingredients\": [\"beans\", \"dried red peppers (tatashe)\", \"dried long chilli bonnet peppers(shombo)\", \"palm oil\", \"crayfish\", \"seasoning cubes\", \"salt\", \"water\"]}, {\"name\": \"Moi Moi\", \"tips\": \"The food processor peeling method is a game changer — it cuts prep time from 30 minutes to 5 minutes. The two most important steps are removing every single bean skin and whisking the paste vigorously to aerate it before adding seasoning. Skipping either step will result in dense heavy Moi Moi. Always fill containers only three quarters full as the paste expands during steaming.\", \"servings\": 8, \"difficulty\": \"medium\", \"description\": \"Moi Moi is a traditional Nigerian steamed bean pudding made from peeled beans blended into a smooth paste. It is a beloved dish across all Nigerian tribes and is served at parties, as a side dish with rice or ogi, or eaten alone as a complete meal. The texture should be firm yet soft and moist inside with a rich savoury flavour.\", \"instructions\": [\"Step 1: There are two ways to peel the beans. Traditional method: Pour beans into a bowl and soak in cold water for 30 minutes until the skins begin to loosen and soften, then rub vigorously between both palms under running water until all skins float off. Quick method: Pour dry beans into a food processor with some water and pulse for 30 to 45 seconds — the food processor will crack and loosen the skins without grinding the beans. Pour the pulsed beans into a large bowl of water, the skins will float to the top — skim them off and drain. Repeat until all skins are removed. The quick method takes 5 minutes instead of 30.\", \"Step 2: Rinse the peeled beans thoroughly in clean water two to three times to remove any remaining skin fragments. The beans should be completely white with no dark skin remaining — any leftover skin will make the Moi Moi rough and bitter.\", \"Step 3: Place the peeled beans directly into the blender together with the scotch bonnet peppers, red bell pepper, onions, one raw egg, and a very small amount of water — just enough to get the blender moving. Blend everything together on high speed for 3 minutes until the paste is completely smooth with absolutely no grainy texture. Blending the peppers and egg together with the beans at this stage gives the Moi Moi its full flavour and colour from the inside.\", \"Step 4: Pour the blended paste into a large bowl. Add seasoning cubes, vegetable oil, and salt. Mix everything together thoroughly until well combined. Taste and adjust seasoning — it should be well seasoned and slightly peppery.\", \"Step 5: Using a wooden spoon or electric hand mixer, whisk the paste vigorously for 5 minutes until it becomes fluffy, lighter in colour, and increases slightly in volume. This aerates the paste and gives Moi Moi its soft moist texture when steamed.\", \"Step 6: Break the mackerel fish into medium sized chunks and slice your boiled eggs and set aside. Grease foil containers or moi moi leaves generously with vegetable oil on the inside so the moi moi does not stick.\", \"Step 7: Pour the bean paste mixture into each container filling only three quarters full. Drop pieces of fish directly into the paste in each container alongside the sliced eggs  — the fish sits inside the moi moi not on top. Press down lightly so the fish is submerged in the paste.\", \"Step 8: Seal each foil container tightly by folding the edges over securely. No steam should be able to escape during cooking.\", \"Step 9: Place a trivet or folded foil at the bottom of a large pot to prevent direct heat contact. Arrange the sealed moi moi containers in the pot and add water to reach halfway up the sides of the containers.\", \"Step 10: Cover the pot tightly and steam on medium heat for 45 to 60 minutes. Check water level every 15 minutes and add more hot water if needed — never let the pot run dry. Moi Moi is ready when it feels firm when pressed gently and pulls away cleanly from the container when opened.\"], \"dietary_labels\": [], \"dietary_flagged\": [], \"is_dietary_safe\": true, \"dietary_warnings\": [], \"match_percentage\": 9.1, \"used_ingredients\": [\"onions\"], \"cook_time_minutes\": 60, \"prep_time_minutes\": 40, \"missing_ingredients\": [\"beans\", \"scotch bonnet peppers\", \"long chilli pepper (shombo)\", \"crayfish\", \"vegetable oil\", \"seasoning cubes\", \"salt\", \"eggs\", \"fish (preferably mackerel fish)\", \"water\"]}, {\"name\": \"Asun\", \"tips\": \"Grilling or smoking the goat meat after boiling is non-negotiable for authentic Asun — without the charred smoky exterior the dish is just peppered goat meat not Asun. Use goat meat with the skin on for the best texture and flavour. The pepper sauce should have chunky sliced peppers not a blended smooth sauce.\", \"servings\": 4, \"difficulty\": \"medium\", \"description\": \"Asun is a popular Yoruba delicacy of smoked or roasted goat meat cut into small pieces and tossed in a fiery pepper and onion sauce. It originates from Ondo State in Yorubaland and is now one of the most popular Nigerian party small chops and appetisers served across the country. The goat meat is first smoked or roasted to give it a distinctive charred flavour before being peppered.\", \"instructions\": [\"Step 1: Wash the goat meat thoroughly — authentic Asun uses goat meat with the skin on as the skin adds texture and flavour. Cut into medium sized chunks. Season with seasoning cubes, curry powder, thyme, ginger garlic paste and salt.\", \"Step 2: Cook the seasoned goat meat in a pot with a small amount of water on medium heat for 20 to 25 minutes until tender but not falling apart.\", \"Step 3: Remove the cooked goat meat and place directly on a grill, open flame, or in a very hot oven at 220 degrees Celsius. Grill or roast for 15 to 20 minutes turning occasionally until the outside is charred and smoky and the skin is slightly crispy. The charring is essential for authentic Asun flavour.\", \"Step 4: Remove from the grill and cut into smaller bite sized pieces while still hot. Set aside.\", \"Step 5: Slice scotch bonnet peppers, green bell pepper, red bell pepper, and onions into thin strips. The peppers should be sliced not blended, a food processor can be used as well — the chunky pepper pieces are characteristic of Asun.\", \"Step 6: Heat vegetable oil in a wide pan on medium heat. Add the sliced onions and fry for 2 minutes until slightly softened.\", \"Step 7: Add all the sliced peppers to the pan and stir fry on high heat for 3 to 4 minutes — the peppers should be cooked but still have a slight crunch. Do not overcook the peppers into mush.\", \"Step 8: Add the grilled goat meat pieces to the pan and toss vigorously with the peppers for 3 minutes on high heat until the meat is well coated in the pepper mixture and everything is sizzling hot. Taste and adjust seasoning. Serve immediately as a party appetiser or small chop.\"], \"dietary_labels\": [], \"dietary_flagged\": [], \"is_dietary_safe\": true, \"dietary_warnings\": [], \"match_percentage\": 9.1, \"used_ingredients\": [\"onions\"], \"cook_time_minutes\": 60, \"prep_time_minutes\": 20, \"missing_ingredients\": [\"goat meat (skin on)\", \"scotch bonnet peppers\", \"green bell pepper\", \"red bell pepper (tatashe)\", \"vegetable oil\", \"seasoning cubes\", \"curry powder\", \"thyme\", \"salt\", \"ginger garlic paste\"]}, {\"name\": \"Ayamase (Ofada Stew)\", \"tips\": \"Bleaching the palm oil is absolutely non-negotiable for authentic Ayamase. Only use green peppers and unripe tatashe — no red peppers at all. The more assorted meats you use the richer and more authentic the stew will be.\", \"servings\": 6, \"difficulty\": \"hard\", \"description\": \"Ayamase also known as Ofada Stew or Designer Stew is a rich and intensely flavoured Yoruba stew made exclusively with green peppers and unripe tatashe giving it its distinctive green colour. It is traditionally served with Ofada rice and the stew is made with bleached palm oil and loaded with assorted meats making it one of the most indulgent Nigerian dishes.\", \"instructions\": [\"Step 1: Wash and season all assorted meats with onions, seasoning cubes, ginger garlic paste and salt. Cook in a pot on medium heat for 25 to 35 minutes until very tender. Fry the cooked meats in a small amount of oil until lightly browned on the outside for extra flavour. Set aside with the stock.\", \"Step 2: Blend green bell peppers, unripe green tatashe, green scotch bonnet peppers, and onions together into a coarse paste — do not blend completely smooth, leave some texture. The stew must use only green peppers and unripe tatashe — never red peppers or ripe tatashe as this completely changes the dish.\", \"Step 3: Bleach the palm oil by heating it in a pot on high heat with the lid on for 10 to 15 minutes until the oil turns from orange-red to a pale golden yellow colour and begins to smoke lightly. Remove from heat and allow to cool slightly. Bleached palm oil is essential for authentic Ayamase.\", \"Step 4: Return the bleached palm oil to medium heat. Add sliced onions with some ginger garlic paste and fry for 3 minutes until soft and slightly golden.\", \"Step 5: Pour the blended green pepper mixture into the bleached palm oil. It will sizzle vigorously stir immediately. Fry on high heat for 15 to 20 minutes stirring every 3 to 4 minutes until all the water has completely evaporated, the oil floats on top, and the pepper sauce is cooked down and thick.\", \"Step 6: Add iru (locust beans) and ground crayfish to the cooked pepper base and stir well. Fry for 3 more minutes until the iru is fragrant and well incorporated.\", \"Step 7: Add all the assorted meats and a ladle of the meat stock. Stir everything together to coat the meat in the green pepper sauce. Cook on medium heat for 10 minutes until the meat is well flavoured and the stew is thick and rich.\", \"Step 8: Taste and adjust seasoning. The finished Ayamase should be dark olive green, thick, intensely flavoured, and very rich with assorted meats. Serve with Ofada rice.\"], \"dietary_labels\": [], \"dietary_flagged\": [], \"is_dietary_safe\": true, \"dietary_warnings\": [], \"match_percentage\": 9.1, \"used_ingredients\": [\"onions\"], \"cook_time_minutes\": 90, \"prep_time_minutes\": 25, \"missing_ingredients\": [\"green bell peppers\", \"unripe tatashe (green tatashe)\", \"green scotch bonnet peppers\", \"palm oil\", \"assorted meat (beef, tripe, shaki, pomo, liver)\", \"crayfish\", \"iru (locust beans)\", \"seasoning cubes\", \"ginger and garlic paste\", \"salt\"]}, {\"name\": \"Banga Stew\", \"tips\": \"The key difference between Banga Soup and Banga Stew is the reduction time — cook the stew version longer uncovered to achieve a thicker consistency that coats rice or yam well rather than the more liquid soup form.\", \"servings\": 5, \"difficulty\": \"hard\", \"description\": \"Banga Stew is a thick, deeply flavoured Igbo stew made from concentrated palm fruit extract, prepared similarly to Banga Soup but cooked down to a thicker consistency more like a stew than a soup. It is rich, nutty, and aromatic, traditionally seasoned with banga spices, and served with white rice, boiled yam, or plantain.\", \"instructions\": [\"Step 1: If using fresh palm fruit, boil for 20 to 30 minutes until soft, then pound to separate pulp from nuts and squeeze with warm water to extract the thick orange juice. Strain through a sieve to remove fibres. If using canned concentrate, dilute according to package instructions.\", \"Step 2: Pour the palm fruit extract into a pot and bring to a boil on high heat, then reduce to medium heat and simmer for 15 to 20 minutes until the oil begins to separate and rise to the surface.\", \"Step 3: Season the assorted meat with onions, seasoning cubes, and salt. Cook separately on medium heat for 30 minutes until tender. Add the cooked meat and stock to the palm fruit base.\", \"Step 4: Add the banga spice mix to the pot and simmer for 15 minutes to allow the spices to infuse fully into the base.\", \"Step 5: Add dried fish, ground crayfish, sliced scotch bonnet peppers, and seasoning cubes. Stir well and continue cooking on medium heat, allowing the liquid to reduce and thicken for 20 to 25 minutes — unlike Banga Soup this should reduce further into a thicker stew-like consistency.\", \"Step 6: Add the fresh fish pieces and cook gently for 8 to 10 minutes until just cooked through, stirring carefully to avoid breaking the fish apart.\", \"Step 7: Continue simmering uncovered for an additional 10 minutes, stirring occasionally, until the stew has thickened noticeably and the oil is clearly visible on the surface.\", \"Step 8: Remove the oburunbebe stick before serving. Taste and adjust seasoning. Serve hot with white rice, boiled yam, or plantain.\"], \"dietary_labels\": [], \"dietary_flagged\": [], \"is_dietary_safe\": true, \"dietary_warnings\": [], \"match_percentage\": 9.1, \"used_ingredients\": [\"onions\"], \"cook_time_minutes\": 80, \"prep_time_minutes\": 30, \"missing_ingredients\": [\"fresh palm fruit (or canned banga concentrate)\", \"assorted meat (beef, tripe)\", \"dried fish\", \"fresh fish\", \"banga spice mix (oburunbebe stick, dried bitter leaf)\", \"scotch bonnet peppers\", \"crayfish\", \"seasoning cubes\", \"salt\", \"water\"]}, {\"name\": \"Efo Riro\", \"tips\": \"The most important step is frying the pepper base completely dry until the oil floats on top before adding any meat or stock. This is what separates a rich deeply flavoured Efo Riro from a watery one. Also add the vegetables at the very last minute and cook for 2 minutes only — overcooked vegetables will turn dark and lose their flavour.\", \"servings\": 6, \"difficulty\": \"medium\", \"description\": \"Efo Riro is a rich Yoruba vegetable soup made with tatashe and ata rodo as the pepper base, assorted meats, and leafy green vegetables. The name means stirred leafy vegetable in Yoruba. It is one of the most flavourful Nigerian soups with a vibrant green and red colour from the vegetables and pepper base. It is served with amala, eba, pounded yam, or rice.\", \"instructions\": [\"Step 1: Wash and season assorted meat, pomo, and stockfish with onions, seasoning cubes, and salt. Cook on medium heat for 20 to 30 minutes until very tender. Set aside with the stock.\", \"Step 2: Blend tatashe and scotch bonnet peppers together into a smooth paste. Do not add water — the peppers have enough natural liquid. Set aside.\", \"Step 3: Wash the efo tete or spinach thoroughly, shred into medium sized pieces by hand, and set aside in a colander to drain excess water.\", \"Step 4: Heat palm oil in a large pot on medium-high heat for 2 minutes. Slice onions and fry in the palm oil for 3 minutes until golden and fragrant.\", \"Step 5: Add the blended tatashe and scotch bonnet pepper mixture to the pot. It will sizzle loudly in the hot oil — this is correct. Fry on high heat for 10 to 20 minutes stirring every 3 minutes until all the water has completely evaporated, the oil floats on top, and the pepper sauce has darkened and thickened. This step gives Efo Riro its deep rich flavour.\", \"Step 6: Add iru (locust beans) and ground crayfish and stir into the pepper sauce. Fry for 2 more minutes until the iru is fragrant.\", \"Step 7: Add the cooked assorted meat, stockfish, dried fish, and a ladle of the meat stock. Stir everything together and cook on medium heat for 10 minutes until the meat is well coated in the sauce.\", \"Step 8: Add the shredded efo tete or spinach to the pot and stir into the sauce. Cook for exactly 2 minutes only on medium heat — the vegetables should wilt into the soup but remain bright green and not soggy. Taste, adjust seasoning, and remove from heat immediately. Serve with amala, eba, or pounded yam.\"], \"dietary_labels\": [], \"dietary_flagged\": [], \"is_dietary_safe\": true, \"dietary_warnings\": [], \"match_percentage\": 8.3, \"used_ingredients\": [\"onions\"], \"cook_time_minutes\": 75, \"prep_time_minutes\": 25, \"missing_ingredients\": [\"vgetables African spinach or ugwu\", \"tatashe (red bell pepper)\", \"scotch bonnet peppers (ata rodo)\", \"palm oil\", \"assorted meat (beef, tripe, shaki, pomo)\", \"stockfish\", \"dried fish\", \"crayfish\", \"iru (locust beans)\", \"seasoning cubes\", \"salt\"]}, {\"name\": \"Egusi Soup Yoruba Style\", \"tips\": \"The secret to Yoruba egusi is frying the egusi completely dry in palm oil before adding any liquid. Never add water or stock to the egusi while frying — it must fry and toast in the oil until golden. Also never add tomatoes to Yoruba egusi soup — that changes the flavour profile completely.\", \"servings\": 6, \"difficulty\": \"medium\", \"description\": \"Egusi Soup Yoruba style is a rich and hearty Nigerian soup made with ground melon seeds fried directly in palm oil before any liquid is added. Unlike Igbo style egusi which is added raw, Yoruba style fries the egusi first until golden and nutty giving it a deeper richer flavour. It is served with amala, eba, or pounded yam.\", \"instructions\": [\"Step 1: Wash and season assorted meat and stockfish with onions, seasoning cubes, and salt. Cook in a pot on medium heat for 15 to 20 minutes until tender. Set aside with the stock.\", \"Step 2: Blend scotch bonnet peppers, tatashe, and half the onions together into a smooth paste. Set aside.\", \"Step 3: Heat palm oil in a large pot on medium heat for 2 minutes until melted and hot but not bleached. Chop the remaining onions and fry in the palm oil for 3 minutes until soft and translucent.\", \"Step 4: Add the ground egusi to the palm oil and stir immediately to combine. Fry the egusi in the palm oil on medium heat for 8 to 10 minutes stirring constantly until the egusi turns golden, smells nutty, and pulls away from the sides of the pot. Do not add any liquid at this stage — dry frying is the key to Yoruba egusi.\", \"Step 5: Add the blended pepper mixture to the fried egusi and stir well to combine. Fry together for another 10 minutes on medium heat stirring every 2 minutes until the pepper is cooked and oil begins to float on the surface.\", \"Step 6: Add the cooked meat, stockfish, dried fish, meat stock, ground crayfish, iru, and seasoning cubes. Stir everything together and add a small amount of water if the soup is too thick. Cook on medium heat for 15 minutes until all the flavours come together.\", \"Step 7: Taste and adjust salt and seasoning. The soup should be rich, thick, and deeply flavoured at this point.\", \"Step 8: Add shredded spinach or efo tete and stir into the soup. Cook for exactly 2 minutes only — overcooking the vegetables will make them lose their colour and become soggy. Remove from heat and serve immediately with amala, eba, or pounded yam.\"], \"dietary_labels\": [], \"dietary_flagged\": [], \"is_dietary_safe\": true, \"dietary_warnings\": [], \"match_percentage\": 7.7, \"used_ingredients\": [\"onions\"], \"cook_time_minutes\": 70, \"prep_time_minutes\": 20, \"missing_ingredients\": [\"ground egusi (melon seeds)\", \"palm oil\", \"assorted meat (beef, tripe, shaki)\", \"stockfish\", \"dried fish\", \"scotch bonnet peppers\", \"tatashe (red bell pepper)\", \"crayfish\", \"iru (locust beans)\", \"spinach, efo tete or ugwu\", \"seasoning cubes\", \"salt\"]}, {\"name\": \"Ikokore\", \"tips\": \"Use water yam specifically not white yam or cocoyam. Do not rinse the grated yam before adding to the pot as the natural starch thickens the broth and holds the dumplings together.\", \"servings\": 4, \"difficulty\": \"medium\", \"description\": \"Ikokore is a traditional Ijebu Yoruba dish made from grated water yam cooked in a rich pepper soup or tomato base with assorted fish and seafood. The grated water yam forms thick irregular dumplings in the broth giving the dish its characteristic texture. It is a beloved dish in Ogun State and across Yorubaland.\", \"instructions\": [\"Step 1: Peel the water yam and grate on the coarse side of a grater into a bowl. Do not rinse the grated yam — the natural starch is needed to hold the dumplings together. Season the grated yam lightly with salt and set aside.\", \"Step 2: Blend scotch bonnet peppers, long chilli peppers, and onions together into a smooth paste.\", \"Step 3: Heat palm oil in a large pot on medium heat. Add iru and fry for 1 minute until fragrant. Add the blended pepper mixture and fry for 15 minutes until cooked and oil floats on top.\", \"Step 4: Add enough meat stock to the pot . Add ground crayfish, dried fish, smoked fish, assorted meat, seasoning cubes, and salt. Bring to a boil on high heat.\", \"Step 5: Using a tablespoon or your hand, scoop portions of the grated water yam and drop them one by one into the boiling broth. Do not stir immediately — allow the yam dumplings to set for 3 minutes before stirring gently.\", \"Step 6: Cook on medium heat for 15 to 20 minutes stirring gently occasionally until the yam dumplings are fully cooked and the broth has thickened, adjust seasoning, and serve hot.\"], \"dietary_labels\": [\"Diabetic\"], \"dietary_flagged\": [\"yam\"], \"is_dietary_safe\": true, \"dietary_warnings\": [\"High glycemic ingredients — consume in moderation\"], \"match_percentage\": 7.7, \"used_ingredients\": [\"onions\"], \"cook_time_minutes\": 50, \"prep_time_minutes\": 25, \"missing_ingredients\": [\"water yam (isu ewura)\", \"dried fish\", \"assorted meat\", \"smoked fish\", \"palm oil\", \"crayfish\", \"scotch bonnet peppers\", \"long chilli peppers\", \"iru (locust beans)\", \"seasoning cubes\", \"salt\", \"water\"]}, {\"name\": \"Abacha\", \"tips\": \"Always soak in cold water not hot. Potash is essential for emulsifying the palm oil into the dressing.\", \"servings\": 4, \"difficulty\": \"medium\", \"description\": \"Abacha is a traditional Igbo cold salad made from dried shredded cassava rehydrated and tossed in an emulsified palm oil and potash dressing with ugba, utazi leaves, garden eggs, crayfish, and assorted proteins.\", \"instructions\": [\"Step 1: Soak the dried abacha in cold water for 10 to 15 minutes until softened. Drain thoroughly.\", \"Step 2: Dissolve potash in 3 tablespoons of water and strain through a fine sieve.\", \"Step 3: Pour palm oil into a bowl. Add the potash solution gradually while stirring vigorously until emulsified and bright yellow.\", \"Step 4: Add ground crayfish, sliced scotch bonnet peppers, sliced onions, seasoning cubes, and salt to the emulsion.\", \"Step 5: Add the drained abacha and toss thoroughly until coated.\", \"Step 6: Add ugba, sliced garden eggs, shredded utazi, flaked fish, and sliced ponmo. Toss together gently.\", \"Step 7: Taste and adjust seasoning.\", \"Step 8: Garnish with utazi and onion rings. Serve at room temperature.\"], \"dietary_labels\": [], \"dietary_flagged\": [], \"is_dietary_safe\": true, \"dietary_warnings\": [], \"match_percentage\": 7.7, \"used_ingredients\": [\"onions\"], \"cook_time_minutes\": 0, \"prep_time_minutes\": 20, \"missing_ingredients\": [\"abacha (dried shredded cassava)\", \"ugba (oil bean seeds)\", \"palm oil\", \"potash (kaun)\", \"utazi leaves\", \"garden eggs\", \"crayfish\", \"scotch bonnet peppers\", \"seasoning cubes\", \"salt\", \"dried fish or stockfish\", \"ponmo (cow skin)\"]}, {\"name\": \"Ofe Owerri\", \"tips\": \"Use as many different types of meat and fish as you can for the most authentic version. The combination of ugu and uziza leaves together distinguishes this from Edikang Ikong.\", \"servings\": 6, \"difficulty\": \"hard\", \"description\": \"Ofe Owerri is a luxurious traditional Igbo vegetable soup from Owerri in Imo State, known for being loaded with multiple types of meat, fish, and a generous mix of vegetables, traditionally served at important ceremonies.\", \"instructions\": [\"Step 1: Wash and season all assorted meats and stockfish with onions, seasoning cubes, and salt. Cook on medium heat for 40 to 50 minutes until very tender. Set aside with the rich stock.\", \"Step 2: Peel cocoyam and boil until very soft, then pound until completely smooth to make the thickener.\", \"Step 3: Heat palm oil, add sliced onions and blended scotch bonnet peppers, fry for 15 minutes until oil floats on top.\", \"Step 4: Add all the cooked meats, stockfish, dried fish, periwinkle, ogiri, ground crayfish, and meat stock. Cook on medium heat for 15 minutes.\", \"Step 5: Add the pounded cocoyam thickener in small lumps and stir until dissolved.\", \"Step 6: Add the fresh fish pieces and cook gently for 8 minutes.\", \"Step 7: Add the shredded ugu and uziza leaves together and stir in. Cook for 3 to 5 minutes only.\", \"Step 8: Taste and adjust seasoning. Serve hot with pounded yam, fufu, or semolina.\"], \"dietary_labels\": [\"Diabetic\"], \"dietary_flagged\": [\"yam\"], \"is_dietary_safe\": true, \"dietary_warnings\": [\"High glycemic ingredients — consume in moderation\"], \"match_percentage\": 6.7, \"used_ingredients\": [\"onions\"], \"cook_time_minutes\": 85, \"prep_time_minutes\": 30, \"missing_ingredients\": [\"ugu leaves (fluted pumpkin)\", \"uziza leaves\", \"cocoyam (for thickening)\", \"palm oil\", \"assorted meat (beef, tripe, shaki, cow leg)\", \"stockfish\", \"dried fish\", \"fresh fish\", \"periwinkle\", \"crayfish\", \"scotch bonnet peppers\", \"ogiri (fermented locust beans)\", \"seasoning cubes\", \"salt\"]}, {\"name\": \"Nigerian Coleslaw\", \"tips\": \"The combination of mayonnaise and salad cream together, rather than just mayonnaise alone, is what gives Nigerian coleslaw its distinctive tangy sweetness. Always shred the cabbage very finely for the best texture, and let the coleslaw rest in the refrigerator before serving for the best flavour.\", \"servings\": 6, \"difficulty\": \"easy\", \"description\": \"Nigerian Coleslaw is a creamy and slightly sweet shredded cabbage and carrot salad that is a staple side dish at Nigerian parties, often served alongside Jollof Rice and Fried Rice. It differs from Western coleslaw by typically including diced apples, raisins, and a generously sweetened mayonnaise dressing.\", \"instructions\": [\"Step 1: Wash the cabbage thoroughly and shred very finely using a sharp knife or food processor — the cabbage should be cut into thin uniform strips for the best texture.\", \"Step 2: Peel and grate or finely julienne the carrots into thin matchstick pieces, similar in size to the shredded cabbage.\", \"Step 3: In a large bowl combine the shredded cabbage, grated carrots and sweet corn. Toss together gently.\", \"Step 4: In a separate small bowl mix mayonnaise and salad cream together in roughly equal parts, adding sugar to taste for the characteristic Nigerian sweetness, along with a pinch of black pepper and salt.\", \"Step 5: Pour the dressing over the vegetable mixture and toss thoroughly until every piece is well coated in the creamy dressing.\", \"Step 6: Taste and adjust sweetness and seasoning — Nigerian coleslaw is typically sweeter than standard Western coleslaw.\", \"Step 7: Cover and refrigerate for at least 1 hour before serving to allow the flavours to meld and the cabbage to soften slightly. Serve cold alongside Jollof Rice or Fried Rice.\"], \"dietary_labels\": [\"Diabetic\"], \"dietary_flagged\": [\"corn\", \"sugar\", \"sweet corn\"], \"is_dietary_safe\": true, \"dietary_warnings\": [\"High glycemic ingredients — consume in moderation\"], \"match_percentage\": 0.0, \"used_ingredients\": [], \"cook_time_minutes\": 0, \"prep_time_minutes\": 25, \"missing_ingredients\": [\"cabbage\", \"carrots\", \"sweet corn\", \"mayonnaise\", \"salad cream\", \"sugar\", \"black pepper\", \"salt\"]}]}','2026-06-21 11:09:13'),('9a23a2ae-39f5-4c57-880f-2c2e4b1a400f','[\"rice\", \"tomatoes\", \"tomato paste\", \"onions\", \"scotch bonnet\", \"chicken\", \"vegetable oil\", \"seasoning cubes\", \"bay leaves\", \"curry powder\"]','nigerian',60,'{\"almost_there\": [{\"name\": \"Nigerian Jollof Rice\", \"tips\": \"The secret to party jollof is double covering with foil and lid to trap steam, and finishing on high heat for the smoky bottom layer. Never use fresh tomatoes alone — always add tomato paste for depth of colour and flavour.\", \"servings\": 6, \"difficulty\": \"medium\", \"description\": \"Nigerian Jollof Rice is one of the most beloved dishes in West Africa, known for its rich smoky tomato flavour and vibrant orange-red colour. It is a staple at every Nigerian party, celebration, and family gathering. The secret to authentic Jollof Rice is the smoky bottom layer called party jollof which develops from cooking on high heat at the end.\", \"instructions\": [\"Step 1: Blend tomatoes, red bell peppers, long chilli peppers, scotch bonnet, and onions together in a blender until completely smooth with no chunks remaining. Set aside.\", \"Step 2: Wash rice thoroughly in cold water at least 3 times until water runs clear.\", \"Step 3: Heat vegetable oil in a large heavy-bottomed stainless steel or aluminum pot over medium-high heat for 2 minutes. Slice some onions, ginger and garlic paste, curry, thyme, bay leaves  and fry in the oil for 3 minutes.\", \"Step 4: Add tomato paste to the pot and fry with the mix for 3 minutes on medium heat, stirring constantly until the paste darkens slightly from bright red to a deeper reddish brown.\", \"Step 5: Pour the blended pepper mixture with some paprika into the pot. It will sizzle loudly — this is correct. Add in some seasoning cubes and salt. Fry on medium high heat uncovered for 25-30 minutes stirring every 5 minutes until all the water has evaporated, the oil floats on top, and the sauce has darkened to a deep red color. This step is critical — do not rush it.\", \"Step 6: Stir well and taste the sauce should be slightly salty as it will season the rice\", \"Step 7: Add the rice to the pot and stir well to coat every grain with the tomato sauce. Fry on high for like 2 minutes. Then add in chicken stock and some water enough to just cover the rice\", \"Step 8: Cover the pot tightly with foil first then place the lid on top to seal in all the steam. Cook on medium heat for 20 minutes without lifting the lid.\", \"Step 9: After 20 minutes lift the lid and check — rice should be almost fully cooked and liquid mostly absorbed. Stir gently from bottom to top. Cover again and cook on very low heat for 10 more minutes.\", \"Step 10: For the authentic party jollof smoky bottom, add in some cooking butter and sliced onions turn heat to high for the last 3-5 minutes. You will hear a crackling sound from the bottom — this is correct. Remove from heat immediately and leave covered for 5 minutes before serving.\"], \"match_percentage\": 62.5, \"used_ingredients\": [\"long grain parboiled rice\", \"tomatoes\", \"scotch bonnet peppers (ata rodo)\", \"onions\", \"vegetable oil\", \"tomato paste\", \"chicken stock\", \"seasoning cubes\", \"curry powder\", \"bay leaves\"], \"cook_time_minutes\": 70, \"prep_time_minutes\": 20, \"missing_ingredients\": [\"red bell peppers (tatashe)\", \"long chilli peppers(shombo) \", \"thyme\", \"garlic powder\", \"salt\", \"paprika\"]}], \"can_make_now\": [], \"needs_shopping\": []}','2026-06-14 19:26:24'),('a21f4aeb-d657-4b28-835c-5c2517884cd3','[\"black eyed beans\", \"onions\", \"scotch bonnet\", \"vegetable oil\", \"crayfish\", \"eggs\", \"fish\", \"seasoning cubes\", \"salt\"]','nigerian moi moi specifically',60,'{\"recipes\": [{\"name\": \"Nigerian Moi Moi\", \"servings\": 4, \"difficulty\": \"easy\", \"description\": \"A traditional Nigerian dish made from black eyed beans, often served as a snack or side dish\", \"instructions\": [\"Step 1: Rinse 2 cups of black eyed beans and soak them in water for 5 minutes, then drain the water and blend the beans in a blender or food processor for 2 minutes\", \"Step 2: Heat 1/4 cup of vegetable oil in a pan over medium heat for 2 minutes, then add 1 chopped onion and 1 chopped scotch bonnet, and fry for 3 minutes\", \"Step 3: Add 1 teaspoon of grated crayfish and 1/2 teaspoon of salt to the pan, and stir for 1 minute\", \"Step 4: Add the blended beans to the pan, and stir for 2 minutes\", \"Step 5: Add 2 eggs to the pan, and stir for 1 minute\", \"Step 6: Pour the moi moi mixture into a greased moi moi container or a heatproof bowl, and steam for 20 minutes\"], \"match_percentage\": 100, \"used_ingredients\": [\"black eyed beans\", \"onions\", \"scotch bonnet\", \"vegetable oil\", \"crayfish\", \"eggs\", \"salt\"], \"cook_time_minutes\": 30, \"prep_time_minutes\": 20, \"missing_ingredients\": []}, {\"name\": \"Black Eyed Bean Fritters\", \"servings\": 4, \"difficulty\": \"easy\", \"description\": \"A crispy and flavorful snack made from black eyed beans\", \"instructions\": [\"Step 1: Rinse 1 cup of black eyed beans and soak them in water for 5 minutes, then drain the water and blend the beans in a blender or food processor for 1 minute\", \"Step 2: Heat 1/4 cup of vegetable oil in a pan over medium heat for 2 minutes, then add 1 chopped onion and 1 chopped scotch bonnet, and fry for 2 minutes\", \"Step 3: Add 1 teaspoon of grated crayfish and 1/2 teaspoon of salt to the pan, and stir for 1 minute\", \"Step 4: Add the chopped beans to the pan, and stir for 2 minutes\", \"Step 5: Add 1 egg to the pan, and stir for 1 minute\", \"Step 6: Using a spoon, drop small amounts of the bean mixture into the hot oil, and fry for 3-4 minutes on each side\"], \"match_percentage\": 100, \"used_ingredients\": [\"black eyed beans\", \"onions\", \"scotch bonnet\", \"vegetable oil\", \"crayfish\", \"eggs\", \"salt\"], \"cook_time_minutes\": 20, \"prep_time_minutes\": 15, \"missing_ingredients\": []}, {\"name\": \"Scotch Bonnet and Crayfish Fried Fish\", \"servings\": 4, \"difficulty\": \"easy\", \"description\": \"A flavorful and spicy dish made from fish, scotch bonnet, and crayfish\", \"instructions\": [\"Step 1: Rinse 2 fish fillets under cold water, and pat them dry with paper towels for 2 minutes\", \"Step 2: Heat 1/4 cup of vegetable oil in a pan over medium heat for 2 minutes, then add 1 chopped scotch bonnet, and fry for 1 minute\", \"Step 3: Add 1 teaspoon of grated crayfish to the pan, and stir for 1 minute\", \"Step 4: Add the fish fillets to the pan, and fry for 3-4 minutes on each side\"], \"match_percentage\": 71, \"used_ingredients\": [\"fish\", \"scotch bonnet\", \"crayfish\", \"vegetable oil\", \"salt\"], \"cook_time_minutes\": 15, \"prep_time_minutes\": 10, \"missing_ingredients\": []}]}','2026-06-14 17:49:51'),('a6861713-197c-43a9-b345-6d130b064db5','[\"egusi\", \"spinach\", \"palm oil\", \"onions\"]','nigerian',NULL,'{\"almost_there\": [], \"can_make_now\": [], \"needs_shopping\": [{\"name\": \"Akara\", \"tips\": \"Whisking the bean paste until very fluffy is the secret to light soft akara — never skip this step. Also make sure the oil is very hot before adding the paste otherwise the akara will absorb too much oil and become greasy. Wet your spoon with oil before scooping each portion to help the paste slide off cleanly into the oil.\", \"servings\": 4, \"difficulty\": \"medium\", \"description\": \"Akara is a traditional Yoruba deep fried bean cake made from peeled black eyed beans blended into a smooth aerated paste and fried in hot oil until crispy on the outside and soft inside. It is a quintessential Nigerian breakfast food sold by roadside vendors across the country and best eaten hot with ogi (pap) or bread.\", \"instructions\": [\"Step 1: Peel the beans using one of two methods. Traditional method: Soak beans in cold water for 30 minutes then rub between palms under running water until all skins float off and are drained away. Quick method: Pulse beans and water  in a food processor for 30 seconds to crack and loosen skins, pour into a bowl of water, skim off floating skins, and drain. Rinse peeled beans two to three times in clean water.\", \"Step 2: Place the peeled beans alongside the peppers and onions in a blender with a very small amount of water — just enough to move the blender. Blend on high speed for 3 minutes until the paste is completely smooth and thick. The paste must be thick not watery — too much water will make flat oily akara.\", \"Step 3: Pour the blended bean paste into a large bowl. Using a wooden spoon or electric hand mixer whisk the paste vigorously for 5 to 7 minutes until it becomes very fluffy, lighter in colour, and almost doubles in volume. This is the most important step — the air you whisk in is what makes akara light and fluffy inside.\", \"Step 4: Add some salt and seasoning cubes to the whisked paste. Fold gently into the paste without deflating it. Taste and adjust seasoning.\", \"Step 5: Pour enough vegetable oil into a deep wide pan to allow the akara to float — at least 3 inches deep. Heat on medium-high heat for 2 to 3 minutes until hot. Test the oil by dropping a tiny bit of paste in — it should rise immediately to the surface and sizzle vigorously. If it sinks the oil is not hot enough.\", \"Step 6: Wet your tablespoon with oil and scoop portions of the paste into the hot oil one at a time. Do not overcrowd the pan — leave space between each akara so they cook evenly and stay round.\", \"Step 7: Fry on medium heat for 3 to 4 minutes until the bottom is deep golden brown, then flip carefully with a slotted spoon or skewer and fry the other side for 2 to 3 minutes until evenly golden brown and crispy all over.\", \"Step 8: Remove with a slotted spoon and drain on paper towels to absorb excess oil. Serve immediately while hot and crispy alongside ogi (pap) or as a breakfast snack.\"], \"dietary_labels\": [], \"dietary_flagged\": [], \"is_dietary_safe\": true, \"dietary_warnings\": [], \"match_percentage\": 14.3, \"used_ingredients\": [\"onions\"], \"cook_time_minutes\": 20, \"prep_time_minutes\": 30, \"missing_ingredients\": [\"black eyed beans\", \"scotch bonnet peppers\", \"long chilli peppers(shombo)\", \"seasoning cubes\", \"salt\", \"vegetable oil for deep frying\"]}]}','2026-06-21 11:12:01'),('ae6823df-3b1d-49a8-a242-0d58a231dd3e','[\"goat meat\", \"scotch bonnet\", \"onions\", \"uziza leaves\", \"ehuru\", \"crayfish\", \"seasoning cubes\", \"utazi leaves\", \"salt\"]','nigerian',45,'{\"recipes\": [{\"name\": \"Goat Meat Pepper Soup\", \"servings\": 4, \"difficulty\": \"easy\", \"description\": \"A traditional Nigerian dish\", \"instructions\": [\"Step 1: Rinse the goat meat and cut it into small pieces, then season with 2 seasoning cubes and 1 teaspoon of salt, mix well and set aside for 5 minutes to allow the seasonings to penetrate the meat.\", \"Step 2: Heat 2 tablespoons of oil in a large pot over medium heat for 3 minutes, until it reaches a temperature of 180°C and starts to shimmer.\", \"Step 3: Add 2 scotch bonnet peppers, chopped, and 1 teaspoon of grated ehuru to the pot, and fry for 2 minutes on medium heat, until the peppers start to soften and release their fragrance.\", \"Step 4: Add the seasoned goat meat to the pot, and fry for 5 minutes on medium-high heat, until the meat starts to brown and develops a nice crust on the outside.\", \"Step 5: Add 2 cups of water to the pot, and bring to a boil, then reduce the heat to low and simmer for 10 minutes, until the meat is tender and the soup has thickened slightly.\", \"Step 6: Stir in 1 tablespoon of crayfish and 1/4 cup of chopped uziza leaves, and cook for an additional 2 minutes, until the flavors have melded together and the soup is hot and steaming.\"], \"match_percentage\": 100, \"used_ingredients\": [\"goat meat\", \"scotch bonnet\", \"onions\", \"uziza leaves\", \"ehuru\", \"salt\", \"crayfish\", \"utazi leaves\", \"seasoning cubes\"], \"cook_time_minutes\": 25, \"prep_time_minutes\": 15, \"missing_ingredients\": []}, {\"name\": \"Uziza and Utazi Leaf Stew\", \"servings\": 4, \"difficulty\": \"easy\", \"description\": \"A classic Nigerian stew\", \"instructions\": [\"Step 1: Rinse the goat meat and cut it into small pieces, then season with 1 seasoning cube and 1 teaspoon of salt, mix well and set aside for 5 minutes to allow the seasonings to penetrate the meat.\", \"Step 2: Heat 1 tablespoon of oil in a large pot over medium heat for 2 minutes, until it reaches a temperature of 160°C and starts to shimmer.\", \"Step 3: Add the seasoned goat meat to the pot, and fry for 5 minutes on medium-high heat, until the meat starts to brown and develops a nice crust on the outside.\", \"Step 4: Add 1 cup of water to the pot, and bring to a boil, then reduce the heat to low and simmer for 10 minutes, until the meat is tender and the stew has thickened slightly.\", \"Step 5: Stir in 1/4 cup of chopped uziza leaves and 1/4 cup of chopped utazi leaves, and cook for an additional 2 minutes, until the flavors have melded together and the stew is hot and steaming.\", \"Step 6: Serve the uziza and utazi leaf stew hot, garnished with a sprinkle of crayfish and a few chopped uziza leaves.\"], \"match_percentage\": 77, \"used_ingredients\": [\"goat meat\", \"onions\", \"uziza leaves\", \"utazi leaves\", \"salt\", \"crayfish\", \"seasoning cubes\"], \"cook_time_minutes\": 20, \"prep_time_minutes\": 10, \"missing_ingredients\": [\"scotch bonnet\", \"ehuru\"]}, {\"name\": \"Crayfish and Scotch Bonnet Sauce\", \"servings\": 4, \"difficulty\": \"easy\", \"description\": \"A spicy and flavorful sauce\", \"instructions\": [\"Step 1: Heat 1 tablespoon of oil in a small pot over medium heat for 1 minute, until it reaches a temperature of 140°C and starts to shimmer.\", \"Step 2: Add 2 scotch bonnet peppers, chopped, and 1 teaspoon of grated salt to the pot, and fry for 1 minute on medium heat, until the peppers start to soften and release their fragrance.\", \"Step 3: Add 1 tablespoon of crayfish to the pot, and fry for 1 minute on medium heat, until the crayfish start to toast and release their flavor.\", \"Step 4: Add 1/2 cup of water to the pot, and bring to a boil, then reduce the heat to low and simmer for 5 minutes, until the sauce has thickened slightly.\", \"Step 5: Stir in 1 seasoning cube, and cook for an additional 1 minute, until the flavors have melded together and the sauce is hot and steaming.\", \"Step 6: Serve the crayfish and scotch bonnet sauce hot, garnished with a sprinkle of crayfish and a few chopped scotch bonnet peppers.\"], \"match_percentage\": 55, \"used_ingredients\": [\"scotch bonnet\", \"onions\", \"crayfish\", \"salt\", \"seasoning cubes\"], \"cook_time_minutes\": 10, \"prep_time_minutes\": 5, \"missing_ingredients\": [\"goat meat\", \"uziza leaves\", \"utazi leaves\", \"ehuru\"]}, {\"name\": \"Ehuru and Uziza Leaf Stew\", \"servings\": 4, \"difficulty\": \"easy\", \"description\": \"A classic Nigerian stew\", \"instructions\": [\"Step 1: Rinse the goat meat and cut it into small pieces, then season with 1 seasoning cube and 1 teaspoon of salt, mix well and set aside for 5 minutes to allow the seasonings to penetrate the meat.\", \"Step 2: Heat 1 tablespoon of oil in a large pot over medium heat for 2 minutes, until it reaches a temperature of 160°C and starts to shimmer.\", \"Step 3: Add the seasoned goat meat to the pot, and fry for 5 minutes on medium-high heat, until the meat starts to brown and develops a nice crust on the outside.\", \"Step 4: Add 1 cup of water to the pot, and bring to a boil, then reduce the heat to low and simmer for 10 minutes, until the meat is tender and the stew has thickened slightly.\", \"Step 5: Stir in 1/4 cup of chopped uziza leaves, and cook for an additional 2 minutes, until the flavors have melded together and the stew is hot and steaming.\", \"Step 6: Serve the ehuru and uziza leaf stew hot, garnished with a sprinkle of crayfish and a few chopped uziza leaves.\"], \"match_percentage\": 77, \"used_ingredients\": [\"goat meat\", \"onions\", \"uziza leaves\", \"ehuru\", \"salt\", \"crayfish\", \"seasoning cubes\"], \"cook_time_minutes\": 20, \"prep_time_minutes\": 10, \"missing_ingredients\": [\"scotch bonnet\", \"utazi leaves\"]}]}','2026-06-14 17:51:24'),('b7f93aa6-2434-41b0-96a8-9f07baadfb13','[\"rice\", \"tomatoes\", \"onions\", \"palm oil\", \"scotch bonnet\"]','nigerian',NULL,'{\"almost_there\": [], \"can_make_now\": [], \"needs_shopping\": [{\"name\": \"Asaro (Yam Porridge)\", \"tips\": \"Gentle stirring lets some yam break down to thicken the sauce naturally without becoming completely mashed.\", \"servings\": 4, \"difficulty\": \"easy\", \"description\": \"Asaro is a beloved traditional Yoruba yam porridge made by cooking yam chunks directly in a rich tomato and pepper sauce until the yam softens and thickens the entire dish into a hearty one-pot meal.\", \"instructions\": [\"Step 1: Peel the yam and cut into medium sized chunks. Wash thoroughly.\", \"Step 2: Blend onions, tatashe, and scotch bonnet peppers together into a smooth paste.\", \"Step 3: Place the yam chunks in a pot with the blended pepper mixture, sliced onions, palm oil, and enough water to just cover the yam.\", \"Step 4: Bring to a boil then reduce to medium heat. Cook for 20 to 25 minutes, stirring occasionally, until the yam softens and breaks down at the edges.\", \"Step 5: Add ground crayfish, flaked fish, seasoning cubes, and salt. Stir gently.\", \"Step 6: Continue cooking on medium-low heat for 8 to 10 minutes until thick and stew-like.\", \"Step 7: Taste and adjust seasoning. Serve hot on its own.\"], \"match_percentage\": 36.4, \"used_ingredients\": [\"tomatoes\", \"scotch bonnet peppers\", \"onions\", \"palm oil\"], \"cook_time_minutes\": 40, \"prep_time_minutes\": 15, \"missing_ingredients\": [\"yam (white yam)\", \"tatashe (red bell pepper)\", \"crayfish\", \"smoked fish or dried fish\", \"seasoning cubes\", \"salt\", \"water\"]}, {\"name\": \"Akara\", \"tips\": \"Whisking the bean paste until very fluffy is the secret to light soft akara — never skip this step. Also make sure the oil is very hot before adding the paste otherwise the akara will absorb too much oil and become greasy. Wet your spoon with oil before scooping each portion to help the paste slide off cleanly into the oil.\", \"servings\": 4, \"difficulty\": \"medium\", \"description\": \"Akara is a traditional Yoruba deep fried bean cake made from peeled black eyed beans blended into a smooth aerated paste and fried in hot oil until crispy on the outside and soft inside. It is a quintessential Nigerian breakfast food sold by roadside vendors across the country and best eaten hot with ogi (pap) or bread.\", \"instructions\": [\"Step 1: Peel the beans using one of two methods. Traditional method: Soak beans in cold water for 30 minutes then rub between palms under running water until all skins float off and are drained away. Quick method: Pulse beans and water  in a food processor for 30 seconds to crack and loosen skins, pour into a bowl of water, skim off floating skins, and drain. Rinse peeled beans two to three times in clean water.\", \"Step 2: Place the peeled beans alongside the peppers and onions in a blender with a very small amount of water — just enough to move the blender. Blend on high speed for 3 minutes until the paste is completely smooth and thick. The paste must be thick not watery — too much water will make flat oily akara.\", \"Step 3: Pour the blended bean paste into a large bowl. Using a wooden spoon or electric hand mixer whisk the paste vigorously for 5 to 7 minutes until it becomes very fluffy, lighter in colour, and almost doubles in volume. This is the most important step — the air you whisk in is what makes akara light and fluffy inside.\", \"Step 4: Add some salt and seasoning cubes to the whisked paste. Fold gently into the paste without deflating it. Taste and adjust seasoning.\", \"Step 5: Pour enough vegetable oil into a deep wide pan to allow the akara to float — at least 3 inches deep. Heat on medium-high heat for 2 to 3 minutes until hot. Test the oil by dropping a tiny bit of paste in — it should rise immediately to the surface and sizzle vigorously. If it sinks the oil is not hot enough.\", \"Step 6: Wet your tablespoon with oil and scoop portions of the paste into the hot oil one at a time. Do not overcrowd the pan — leave space between each akara so they cook evenly and stay round.\", \"Step 7: Fry on medium heat for 3 to 4 minutes until the bottom is deep golden brown, then flip carefully with a slotted spoon or skewer and fry the other side for 2 to 3 minutes until evenly golden brown and crispy all over.\", \"Step 8: Remove with a slotted spoon and drain on paper towels to absorb excess oil. Serve immediately while hot and crispy alongside ogi (pap) or as a breakfast snack.\"], \"match_percentage\": 28.6, \"used_ingredients\": [\"onions\", \"scotch bonnet peppers\"], \"cook_time_minutes\": 20, \"prep_time_minutes\": 30, \"missing_ingredients\": [\"black eyed beans\", \"long chilli peppers(shombo)\", \"seasoning cubes\", \"salt\", \"vegetable oil for deep frying\"]}, {\"name\": \"Ayamase (Ofada Stew)\", \"tips\": \"Bleaching the palm oil is absolutely non-negotiable for authentic Ayamase. Only use green peppers and unripe tatashe — no red peppers at all. The more assorted meats you use the richer and more authentic the stew will be.\", \"servings\": 6, \"difficulty\": \"hard\", \"description\": \"Ayamase also known as Ofada Stew or Designer Stew is a rich and intensely flavoured Yoruba stew made exclusively with green peppers and unripe tatashe giving it its distinctive green colour. It is traditionally served with Ofada rice and the stew is made with bleached palm oil and loaded with assorted meats making it one of the most indulgent Nigerian dishes.\", \"instructions\": [\"Step 1: Wash and season all assorted meats with onions, seasoning cubes, ginger garlic paste and salt. Cook in a pot on medium heat for 25 to 35 minutes until very tender. Fry the cooked meats in a small amount of oil until lightly browned on the outside for extra flavour. Set aside with the stock.\", \"Step 2: Blend green bell peppers, unripe green tatashe, green scotch bonnet peppers, and onions together into a coarse paste — do not blend completely smooth, leave some texture. The stew must use only green peppers and unripe tatashe — never red peppers or ripe tatashe as this completely changes the dish.\", \"Step 3: Bleach the palm oil by heating it in a pot on high heat with the lid on for 10 to 15 minutes until the oil turns from orange-red to a pale golden yellow colour and begins to smoke lightly. Remove from heat and allow to cool slightly. Bleached palm oil is essential for authentic Ayamase.\", \"Step 4: Return the bleached palm oil to medium heat. Add sliced onions with some ginger garlic paste and fry for 3 minutes until soft and slightly golden.\", \"Step 5: Pour the blended green pepper mixture into the bleached palm oil. It will sizzle vigorously stir immediately. Fry on high heat for 15 to 20 minutes stirring every 3 to 4 minutes until all the water has completely evaporated, the oil floats on top, and the pepper sauce is cooked down and thick.\", \"Step 6: Add iru (locust beans) and ground crayfish to the cooked pepper base and stir well. Fry for 3 more minutes until the iru is fragrant and well incorporated.\", \"Step 7: Add all the assorted meats and a ladle of the meat stock. Stir everything together to coat the meat in the green pepper sauce. Cook on medium heat for 10 minutes until the meat is well flavoured and the stew is thick and rich.\", \"Step 8: Taste and adjust seasoning. The finished Ayamase should be dark olive green, thick, intensely flavoured, and very rich with assorted meats. Serve with Ofada rice.\"], \"match_percentage\": 27.3, \"used_ingredients\": [\"green scotch bonnet peppers\", \"onions\", \"palm oil\"], \"cook_time_minutes\": 90, \"prep_time_minutes\": 25, \"missing_ingredients\": [\"green bell peppers\", \"unripe tatashe (green tatashe)\", \"assorted meat (beef, tripe, shaki, pomo, liver)\", \"crayfish\", \"iru (locust beans)\", \"seasoning cubes\", \"ginger and garlic paste\", \"salt\"]}, {\"name\": \"Nigerian Jollof Rice\", \"tips\": \"The secret to party jollof is double covering with foil and lid to trap steam, and finishing on high heat for the smoky bottom layer. Never use fresh tomatoes alone — always add tomato paste for depth of colour and flavour.\", \"servings\": 6, \"difficulty\": \"medium\", \"description\": \"Nigerian Jollof Rice is one of the most beloved dishes in West Africa, known for its rich smoky tomato flavour and vibrant orange-red colour. It is a staple at every Nigerian party, celebration, and family gathering. The secret to authentic Jollof Rice is the smoky bottom layer called party jollof which develops from cooking on high heat at the end.\", \"instructions\": [\"Step 1: Blend tomatoes, red bell peppers, long chilli peppers, scotch bonnet, and onions together in a blender until completely smooth with no chunks remaining. Set aside.\", \"Step 2: Wash rice thoroughly in cold water at least 3 times until water runs clear.\", \"Step 3: Heat vegetable oil in a large heavy-bottomed stainless steel or aluminum pot over medium-high heat for 2 minutes. Slice some onions, ginger and garlic paste, curry, thyme, bay leaves  and fry in the oil for 3 minutes.\", \"Step 4: Add tomato paste to the pot and fry with the mix for 3 minutes on medium heat, stirring constantly until the paste darkens slightly from bright red to a deeper reddish brown.\", \"Step 5: Pour the blended pepper mixture with some paprika into the pot. It will sizzle loudly — this is correct. Add in some seasoning cubes and salt. Fry on medium high heat uncovered for 25-30 minutes stirring every 5 minutes until all the water has evaporated, the oil floats on top, and the sauce has darkened to a deep red color. This step is critical — do not rush it.\", \"Step 6: Stir well and taste the sauce should be slightly salty as it will season the rice\", \"Step 7: Add the rice to the pot and stir well to coat every grain with the tomato sauce. Fry on high for like 2 minutes. Then add in chicken stock and some water enough to just cover the rice\", \"Step 8: Cover the pot tightly with foil first then place the lid on top to seal in all the steam. Cook on medium heat for 20 minutes without lifting the lid.\", \"Step 9: After 20 minutes lift the lid and check — rice should be almost fully cooked and liquid mostly absorbed. Stir gently from bottom to top. Cover again and cook on very low heat for 10 more minutes.\", \"Step 10: For the authentic party jollof smoky bottom, add in some cooking butter and sliced onions turn heat to high for the last 3-5 minutes. You will hear a crackling sound from the bottom — this is correct. Remove from heat immediately and leave covered for 5 minutes before serving.\"], \"match_percentage\": 25.0, \"used_ingredients\": [\"long grain parboiled rice\", \"tomatoes\", \"scotch bonnet peppers (ata rodo)\", \"onions\"], \"cook_time_minutes\": 70, \"prep_time_minutes\": 20, \"missing_ingredients\": [\"red bell peppers (tatashe)\", \"long chilli peppers(shombo) \", \"vegetable oil\", \"tomato paste\", \"chicken stock\", \"seasoning cubes\", \"curry powder\", \"thyme\", \"bay leaves\", \"garlic powder\", \"salt\", \"paprika\"]}, {\"name\": \"Efo Riro\", \"tips\": \"The most important step is frying the pepper base completely dry until the oil floats on top before adding any meat or stock. This is what separates a rich deeply flavoured Efo Riro from a watery one. Also add the vegetables at the very last minute and cook for 2 minutes only — overcooked vegetables will turn dark and lose their flavour.\", \"servings\": 6, \"difficulty\": \"medium\", \"description\": \"Efo Riro is a rich Yoruba vegetable soup made with tatashe and ata rodo as the pepper base, assorted meats, and leafy green vegetables. The name means stirred leafy vegetable in Yoruba. It is one of the most flavourful Nigerian soups with a vibrant green and red colour from the vegetables and pepper base. It is served with amala, eba, pounded yam, or rice.\", \"instructions\": [\"Step 1: Wash and season assorted meat, pomo, and stockfish with onions, seasoning cubes, and salt. Cook on medium heat for 20 to 30 minutes until very tender. Set aside with the stock.\", \"Step 2: Blend tatashe and scotch bonnet peppers together into a smooth paste. Do not add water — the peppers have enough natural liquid. Set aside.\", \"Step 3: Wash the efo tete or spinach thoroughly, shred into medium sized pieces by hand, and set aside in a colander to drain excess water.\", \"Step 4: Heat palm oil in a large pot on medium-high heat for 2 minutes. Slice onions and fry in the palm oil for 3 minutes until golden and fragrant.\", \"Step 5: Add the blended tatashe and scotch bonnet pepper mixture to the pot. It will sizzle loudly in the hot oil — this is correct. Fry on high heat for 10 to 20 minutes stirring every 3 minutes until all the water has completely evaporated, the oil floats on top, and the pepper sauce has darkened and thickened. This step gives Efo Riro its deep rich flavour.\", \"Step 6: Add iru (locust beans) and ground crayfish and stir into the pepper sauce. Fry for 2 more minutes until the iru is fragrant.\", \"Step 7: Add the cooked assorted meat, stockfish, dried fish, and a ladle of the meat stock. Stir everything together and cook on medium heat for 10 minutes until the meat is well coated in the sauce.\", \"Step 8: Add the shredded efo tete or spinach to the pot and stir into the sauce. Cook for exactly 2 minutes only on medium heat — the vegetables should wilt into the soup but remain bright green and not soggy. Taste, adjust seasoning, and remove from heat immediately. Serve with amala, eba, or pounded yam.\"], \"match_percentage\": 25.0, \"used_ingredients\": [\"scotch bonnet peppers (ata rodo)\", \"onions\", \"palm oil\"], \"cook_time_minutes\": 75, \"prep_time_minutes\": 25, \"missing_ingredients\": [\"vgetables African spinach or ugwu\", \"tatashe (red bell pepper)\", \"assorted meat (beef, tripe, shaki, pomo)\", \"stockfish\", \"dried fish\", \"crayfish\", \"iru (locust beans)\", \"seasoning cubes\", \"salt\"]}, {\"name\": \"Egusi Soup Yoruba Style\", \"tips\": \"The secret to Yoruba egusi is frying the egusi completely dry in palm oil before adding any liquid. Never add water or stock to the egusi while frying — it must fry and toast in the oil until golden. Also never add tomatoes to Yoruba egusi soup — that changes the flavour profile completely.\", \"servings\": 6, \"difficulty\": \"medium\", \"description\": \"Egusi Soup Yoruba style is a rich and hearty Nigerian soup made with ground melon seeds fried directly in palm oil before any liquid is added. Unlike Igbo style egusi which is added raw, Yoruba style fries the egusi first until golden and nutty giving it a deeper richer flavour. It is served with amala, eba, or pounded yam.\", \"instructions\": [\"Step 1: Wash and season assorted meat and stockfish with onions, seasoning cubes, and salt. Cook in a pot on medium heat for 15 to 20 minutes until tender. Set aside with the stock.\", \"Step 2: Blend scotch bonnet peppers, tatashe, and half the onions together into a smooth paste. Set aside.\", \"Step 3: Heat palm oil in a large pot on medium heat for 2 minutes until melted and hot but not bleached. Chop the remaining onions and fry in the palm oil for 3 minutes until soft and translucent.\", \"Step 4: Add the ground egusi to the palm oil and stir immediately to combine. Fry the egusi in the palm oil on medium heat for 8 to 10 minutes stirring constantly until the egusi turns golden, smells nutty, and pulls away from the sides of the pot. Do not add any liquid at this stage — dry frying is the key to Yoruba egusi.\", \"Step 5: Add the blended pepper mixture to the fried egusi and stir well to combine. Fry together for another 10 minutes on medium heat stirring every 2 minutes until the pepper is cooked and oil begins to float on the surface.\", \"Step 6: Add the cooked meat, stockfish, dried fish, meat stock, ground crayfish, iru, and seasoning cubes. Stir everything together and add a small amount of water if the soup is too thick. Cook on medium heat for 15 minutes until all the flavours come together.\", \"Step 7: Taste and adjust salt and seasoning. The soup should be rich, thick, and deeply flavoured at this point.\", \"Step 8: Add shredded spinach or efo tete and stir into the soup. Cook for exactly 2 minutes only — overcooking the vegetables will make them lose their colour and become soggy. Remove from heat and serve immediately with amala, eba, or pounded yam.\"], \"match_percentage\": 23.1, \"used_ingredients\": [\"palm oil\", \"onions\", \"scotch bonnet peppers\"], \"cook_time_minutes\": 70, \"prep_time_minutes\": 20, \"missing_ingredients\": [\"ground egusi (melon seeds)\", \"assorted meat (beef, tripe, shaki)\", \"stockfish\", \"dried fish\", \"tatashe (red bell pepper)\", \"crayfish\", \"iru (locust beans)\", \"spinach, efo tete or ugwu\", \"seasoning cubes\", \"salt\"]}, {\"name\": \"Ikokore\", \"tips\": \"Use water yam specifically not white yam or cocoyam. Do not rinse the grated yam before adding to the pot as the natural starch thickens the broth and holds the dumplings together.\", \"servings\": 4, \"difficulty\": \"medium\", \"description\": \"Ikokore is a traditional Ijebu Yoruba dish made from grated water yam cooked in a rich pepper soup or tomato base with assorted fish and seafood. The grated water yam forms thick irregular dumplings in the broth giving the dish its characteristic texture. It is a beloved dish in Ogun State and across Yorubaland.\", \"instructions\": [\"Step 1: Peel the water yam and grate on the coarse side of a grater into a bowl. Do not rinse the grated yam — the natural starch is needed to hold the dumplings together. Season the grated yam lightly with salt and set aside.\", \"Step 2: Blend scotch bonnet peppers, long chilli peppers, and onions together into a smooth paste.\", \"Step 3: Heat palm oil in a large pot on medium heat. Add iru and fry for 1 minute until fragrant. Add the blended pepper mixture and fry for 15 minutes until cooked and oil floats on top.\", \"Step 4: Add enough meat stock to the pot . Add ground crayfish, dried fish, smoked fish, assorted meat, seasoning cubes, and salt. Bring to a boil on high heat.\", \"Step 5: Using a tablespoon or your hand, scoop portions of the grated water yam and drop them one by one into the boiling broth. Do not stir immediately — allow the yam dumplings to set for 3 minutes before stirring gently.\", \"Step 6: Cook on medium heat for 15 to 20 minutes stirring gently occasionally until the yam dumplings are fully cooked and the broth has thickened, adjust seasoning, and serve hot.\"], \"match_percentage\": 23.1, \"used_ingredients\": [\"palm oil\", \"scotch bonnet peppers\", \"onions\"], \"cook_time_minutes\": 50, \"prep_time_minutes\": 25, \"missing_ingredients\": [\"water yam (isu ewura)\", \"dried fish\", \"assorted meat\", \"smoked fish\", \"crayfish\", \"long chilli peppers\", \"iru (locust beans)\", \"seasoning cubes\", \"salt\", \"water\"]}, {\"name\": \"Abacha\", \"tips\": \"Always soak in cold water not hot. Potash is essential for emulsifying the palm oil into the dressing.\", \"servings\": 4, \"difficulty\": \"medium\", \"description\": \"Abacha is a traditional Igbo cold salad made from dried shredded cassava rehydrated and tossed in an emulsified palm oil and potash dressing with ugba, utazi leaves, garden eggs, crayfish, and assorted proteins.\", \"instructions\": [\"Step 1: Soak the dried abacha in cold water for 10 to 15 minutes until softened. Drain thoroughly.\", \"Step 2: Dissolve potash in 3 tablespoons of water and strain through a fine sieve.\", \"Step 3: Pour palm oil into a bowl. Add the potash solution gradually while stirring vigorously until emulsified and bright yellow.\", \"Step 4: Add ground crayfish, sliced scotch bonnet peppers, sliced onions, seasoning cubes, and salt to the emulsion.\", \"Step 5: Add the drained abacha and toss thoroughly until coated.\", \"Step 6: Add ugba, sliced garden eggs, shredded utazi, flaked fish, and sliced ponmo. Toss together gently.\", \"Step 7: Taste and adjust seasoning.\", \"Step 8: Garnish with utazi and onion rings. Serve at room temperature.\"], \"match_percentage\": 23.1, \"used_ingredients\": [\"palm oil\", \"onions\", \"scotch bonnet peppers\"], \"cook_time_minutes\": 0, \"prep_time_minutes\": 20, \"missing_ingredients\": [\"abacha (dried shredded cassava)\", \"ugba (oil bean seeds)\", \"potash (kaun)\", \"utazi leaves\", \"garden eggs\", \"crayfish\", \"seasoning cubes\", \"salt\", \"dried fish or stockfish\", \"ponmo (cow skin)\"]}, {\"name\": \"Ewa Agoyin\", \"tips\": \"The two secrets to authentic Ewa Agoyin are cooking the beans with a lot of onions until completely mashable with no whole beans remaining, and making the Agoyin stew with only dried peppers not fresh ones. Fresh peppers will not give the deep dark colour and concentrated flavour that makes Agoyin stew unique. The stew must be dark, dry, and almost burnt looking — that is correct.\", \"servings\": 4, \"difficulty\": \"medium\", \"description\": \"Ewa Agoyin is a popular Yoruba street food originally brought to Nigeria by Beninese traders, consisting of soft completely mashed honey beans or black eyed beans served with a deeply dark and spicy Agoyin stew made from dried red peppers and palm oil. It is a beloved Lagos breakfast food sold by roadside vendors and eaten with agege bread.\", \"instructions\": [\"Step 1: Wash the beans thoroughly then cover the beans with fresh water and cook on high heat until boiling, then reduce to medium heat. Cook for 45 to 60 minutes until the beans are extremely soft — they should mash completely between your fingers with no resistance. Add more water as needed during cooking to prevent burning.\", \"Step 2: Once the beans are very soft, use a wooden spoon or potato masher to mash them completely in the pot until no whole beans remain. The consistency should be thick and porridge-like. Season with salt, stir well, and set aside.\", \"Step 4: While the beans cook prepare the Agoyin stew. Rehydrate the dried red peppers and dried chilli peppers by soaking in hot water for 20 minutes until soft. Drain and blend alongside some onions and ginger into a rough paste — not completely smooth, leave some texture.\", \"Step 5: Heat palm oil in a separate pot on medium heat until hot. Slice onions into thin rings and fry in the palm oil for 10 minutes on medium-low heat, stirring constantly until the onions are very dark brown and almost caramelised — this dark onion is essential to the Agoyin stew flavour.\", \"Step 6: Add the blended dried pepper mixture to the dark onions and palm oil. Stir well and fry on medium heat for 20 to 25 minutes stirring every 3 minutes until all moisture evaporates, the stew becomes very dark, thick, and dry, and the oil floats on top. The stew should be almost black in colour — this is correct.\", \"Step 7: Add seasoning cubes and salt to the stew. Stir well and cook for 5 more minutes. The finished Agoyin stew should be very dark, very dry, very spicy, and intensely flavoured.\", \"Step 8: Serve the mashed beans in a bowl and pour the dark Agoyin stew generously on top. Eat with agege bread, fried plantain, or on its own.\"], \"match_percentage\": 22.2, \"used_ingredients\": [\"onions\", \"palm oil\"], \"cook_time_minutes\": 90, \"prep_time_minutes\": 20, \"missing_ingredients\": [\"beans\", \"dried red peppers (tatashe)\", \"dried long chilli bonnet peppers(shombo)\", \"crayfish\", \"seasoning cubes\", \"salt\", \"water\"]}, {\"name\": \"Nigerian Pepper Soup\", \"tips\": \"The quality of your pepper soup spice mix makes or breaks this dish. Use freshly ground spices if possible — uda (country onion), ehuru (calabash nutmeg), and uziza seeds ground together give the most authentic flavour. Never cover the pot fully while cooking pepper soup — leave it slightly open so the broth reduces and concentrates.\", \"servings\": 4, \"difficulty\": \"easy\", \"description\": \"Nigerian Pepper Soup is a light, intensely spiced broth made with meat or fish and a unique blend of pepper soup spices. It is served at every Nigerian gathering, used as a remedy for colds and fever, and eaten as a starter or main dish. The broth is thin but deeply flavoured with a distinctive warming heat that comes from the special pepper soup spice blend.\", \"instructions\": [\"Step 1: Wash the meat thoroughly and cut into medium sized pieces. Season with onions, seasoning cubes, and salt. Do not add water yet — allow the meat to cook in its own juices first.\", \"Step 2: Place the seasoned meat in a pot on medium heat and cook dry for 10 minutes stirring occasionally until the meat releases its juices and begins to brown slightly on the outside.\", \"Step 3: Add enough water to cover the meat completely. Bring to a boil on high heat then reduce to medium heat. Cook for 25 to 30 minutes for goat meat or 15 minutes for chicken until the meat is tender but not falling off the bone.\", \"Step 4: Add the pepper soup spice mix, ground crayfish, and blended or roughly crushed scotch bonnet peppers. Stir well and taste — the broth should be well seasoned and spicy at this point. Add more seasoning cubes and salt if needed.\", \"Step 5: Cook on medium heat for another 15 minutes until the spices have fully infused into the broth and the liquid has reduced slightly. The broth should be a light golden brown colour and smell intensely aromatic.\", \"Step 6: Tear utazi leaves into small pieces and add to the pot — utazi adds a slight bitterness that balances the heat. Add uziza leaves whole or roughly torn. Cook for 3 minutes only.\", \"Step 7: Taste one final time and adjust salt and pepper. The pepper soup should be very hot and spicy, lightly bitter from the utazi, and deeply aromatic from the spice blend. Serve hot in deep bowls with sliced onions on top and agidi or white rice on the side.\"], \"match_percentage\": 20.0, \"used_ingredients\": [\"scotch bonnet peppers\", \"onions\"], \"cook_time_minutes\": 55, \"prep_time_minutes\": 15, \"missing_ingredients\": [\"goat meat or chicken or catfish\", \"pepper soup spice mix\", \"crayfish\", \"uziza leaves\", \"utazi leaves\", \"seasoning cubes\", \"salt\", \"water\"]}, {\"name\": \"Ofe Owerri\", \"tips\": \"Use as many different types of meat and fish as you can for the most authentic version. The combination of ugu and uziza leaves together distinguishes this from Edikang Ikong.\", \"servings\": 6, \"difficulty\": \"hard\", \"description\": \"Ofe Owerri is a luxurious traditional Igbo vegetable soup from Owerri in Imo State, known for being loaded with multiple types of meat, fish, and a generous mix of vegetables, traditionally served at important ceremonies.\", \"instructions\": [\"Step 1: Wash and season all assorted meats and stockfish with onions, seasoning cubes, and salt. Cook on medium heat for 40 to 50 minutes until very tender. Set aside with the rich stock.\", \"Step 2: Peel cocoyam and boil until very soft, then pound until completely smooth to make the thickener.\", \"Step 3: Heat palm oil, add sliced onions and blended scotch bonnet peppers, fry for 15 minutes until oil floats on top.\", \"Step 4: Add all the cooked meats, stockfish, dried fish, periwinkle, ogiri, ground crayfish, and meat stock. Cook on medium heat for 15 minutes.\", \"Step 5: Add the pounded cocoyam thickener in small lumps and stir until dissolved.\", \"Step 6: Add the fresh fish pieces and cook gently for 8 minutes.\", \"Step 7: Add the shredded ugu and uziza leaves together and stir in. Cook for 3 to 5 minutes only.\", \"Step 8: Taste and adjust seasoning. Serve hot with pounded yam, fufu, or semolina.\"], \"match_percentage\": 20.0, \"used_ingredients\": [\"palm oil\", \"onions\", \"scotch bonnet peppers\"], \"cook_time_minutes\": 85, \"prep_time_minutes\": 30, \"missing_ingredients\": [\"ugu leaves (fluted pumpkin)\", \"uziza leaves\", \"cocoyam (for thickening)\", \"assorted meat (beef, tripe, shaki, cow leg)\", \"stockfish\", \"dried fish\", \"fresh fish\", \"periwinkle\", \"crayfish\", \"ogiri (fermented locust beans)\", \"seasoning cubes\", \"salt\"]}, {\"name\": \"Moi Moi\", \"tips\": \"The food processor peeling method is a game changer — it cuts prep time from 30 minutes to 5 minutes. The two most important steps are removing every single bean skin and whisking the paste vigorously to aerate it before adding seasoning. Skipping either step will result in dense heavy Moi Moi. Always fill containers only three quarters full as the paste expands during steaming.\", \"servings\": 8, \"difficulty\": \"medium\", \"description\": \"Moi Moi is a traditional Nigerian steamed bean pudding made from peeled beans blended into a smooth paste. It is a beloved dish across all Nigerian tribes and is served at parties, as a side dish with rice or ogi, or eaten alone as a complete meal. The texture should be firm yet soft and moist inside with a rich savoury flavour.\", \"instructions\": [\"Step 1: There are two ways to peel the beans. Traditional method: Pour beans into a bowl and soak in cold water for 30 minutes until the skins begin to loosen and soften, then rub vigorously between both palms under running water until all skins float off. Quick method: Pour dry beans into a food processor with some water and pulse for 30 to 45 seconds — the food processor will crack and loosen the skins without grinding the beans. Pour the pulsed beans into a large bowl of water, the skins will float to the top — skim them off and drain. Repeat until all skins are removed. The quick method takes 5 minutes instead of 30.\", \"Step 2: Rinse the peeled beans thoroughly in clean water two to three times to remove any remaining skin fragments. The beans should be completely white with no dark skin remaining — any leftover skin will make the Moi Moi rough and bitter.\", \"Step 3: Place the peeled beans directly into the blender together with the scotch bonnet peppers, red bell pepper, onions, one raw egg, and a very small amount of water — just enough to get the blender moving. Blend everything together on high speed for 3 minutes until the paste is completely smooth with absolutely no grainy texture. Blending the peppers and egg together with the beans at this stage gives the Moi Moi its full flavour and colour from the inside.\", \"Step 4: Pour the blended paste into a large bowl. Add seasoning cubes, vegetable oil, and salt. Mix everything together thoroughly until well combined. Taste and adjust seasoning — it should be well seasoned and slightly peppery.\", \"Step 5: Using a wooden spoon or electric hand mixer, whisk the paste vigorously for 5 minutes until it becomes fluffy, lighter in colour, and increases slightly in volume. This aerates the paste and gives Moi Moi its soft moist texture when steamed.\", \"Step 6: Break the mackerel fish into medium sized chunks and slice your boiled eggs and set aside. Grease foil containers or moi moi leaves generously with vegetable oil on the inside so the moi moi does not stick.\", \"Step 7: Pour the bean paste mixture into each container filling only three quarters full. Drop pieces of fish directly into the paste in each container alongside the sliced eggs  — the fish sits inside the moi moi not on top. Press down lightly so the fish is submerged in the paste.\", \"Step 8: Seal each foil container tightly by folding the edges over securely. No steam should be able to escape during cooking.\", \"Step 9: Place a trivet or folded foil at the bottom of a large pot to prevent direct heat contact. Arrange the sealed moi moi containers in the pot and add water to reach halfway up the sides of the containers.\", \"Step 10: Cover the pot tightly and steam on medium heat for 45 to 60 minutes. Check water level every 15 minutes and add more hot water if needed — never let the pot run dry. Moi Moi is ready when it feels firm when pressed gently and pulls away cleanly from the container when opened.\"], \"match_percentage\": 18.2, \"used_ingredients\": [\"onions\", \"scotch bonnet peppers\"], \"cook_time_minutes\": 60, \"prep_time_minutes\": 40, \"missing_ingredients\": [\"beans\", \"long chilli pepper (shombo)\", \"crayfish\", \"vegetable oil\", \"seasoning cubes\", \"salt\", \"eggs\", \"fish (preferably mackerel fish)\", \"water\"]}, {\"name\": \"Asun\", \"tips\": \"Grilling or smoking the goat meat after boiling is non-negotiable for authentic Asun — without the charred smoky exterior the dish is just peppered goat meat not Asun. Use goat meat with the skin on for the best texture and flavour. The pepper sauce should have chunky sliced peppers not a blended smooth sauce.\", \"servings\": 4, \"difficulty\": \"medium\", \"description\": \"Asun is a popular Yoruba delicacy of smoked or roasted goat meat cut into small pieces and tossed in a fiery pepper and onion sauce. It originates from Ondo State in Yorubaland and is now one of the most popular Nigerian party small chops and appetisers served across the country. The goat meat is first smoked or roasted to give it a distinctive charred flavour before being peppered.\", \"instructions\": [\"Step 1: Wash the goat meat thoroughly — authentic Asun uses goat meat with the skin on as the skin adds texture and flavour. Cut into medium sized chunks. Season with seasoning cubes, curry powder, thyme, ginger garlic paste and salt.\", \"Step 2: Cook the seasoned goat meat in a pot with a small amount of water on medium heat for 20 to 25 minutes until tender but not falling apart.\", \"Step 3: Remove the cooked goat meat and place directly on a grill, open flame, or in a very hot oven at 220 degrees Celsius. Grill or roast for 15 to 20 minutes turning occasionally until the outside is charred and smoky and the skin is slightly crispy. The charring is essential for authentic Asun flavour.\", \"Step 4: Remove from the grill and cut into smaller bite sized pieces while still hot. Set aside.\", \"Step 5: Slice scotch bonnet peppers, green bell pepper, red bell pepper, and onions into thin strips. The peppers should be sliced not blended, a food processor can be used as well — the chunky pepper pieces are characteristic of Asun.\", \"Step 6: Heat vegetable oil in a wide pan on medium heat. Add the sliced onions and fry for 2 minutes until slightly softened.\", \"Step 7: Add all the sliced peppers to the pan and stir fry on high heat for 3 to 4 minutes — the peppers should be cooked but still have a slight crunch. Do not overcook the peppers into mush.\", \"Step 8: Add the grilled goat meat pieces to the pan and toss vigorously with the peppers for 3 minutes on high heat until the meat is well coated in the pepper mixture and everything is sizzling hot. Taste and adjust seasoning. Serve immediately as a party appetiser or small chop.\"], \"match_percentage\": 18.2, \"used_ingredients\": [\"scotch bonnet peppers\", \"onions\"], \"cook_time_minutes\": 60, \"prep_time_minutes\": 20, \"missing_ingredients\": [\"goat meat (skin on)\", \"green bell pepper\", \"red bell pepper (tatashe)\", \"vegetable oil\", \"seasoning cubes\", \"curry powder\", \"thyme\", \"salt\", \"ginger garlic paste\"]}, {\"name\": \"Banga Stew\", \"tips\": \"The key difference between Banga Soup and Banga Stew is the reduction time — cook the stew version longer uncovered to achieve a thicker consistency that coats rice or yam well rather than the more liquid soup form.\", \"servings\": 5, \"difficulty\": \"hard\", \"description\": \"Banga Stew is a thick, deeply flavoured Igbo stew made from concentrated palm fruit extract, prepared similarly to Banga Soup but cooked down to a thicker consistency more like a stew than a soup. It is rich, nutty, and aromatic, traditionally seasoned with banga spices, and served with white rice, boiled yam, or plantain.\", \"instructions\": [\"Step 1: If using fresh palm fruit, boil for 20 to 30 minutes until soft, then pound to separate pulp from nuts and squeeze with warm water to extract the thick orange juice. Strain through a sieve to remove fibres. If using canned concentrate, dilute according to package instructions.\", \"Step 2: Pour the palm fruit extract into a pot and bring to a boil on high heat, then reduce to medium heat and simmer for 15 to 20 minutes until the oil begins to separate and rise to the surface.\", \"Step 3: Season the assorted meat with onions, seasoning cubes, and salt. Cook separately on medium heat for 30 minutes until tender. Add the cooked meat and stock to the palm fruit base.\", \"Step 4: Add the banga spice mix to the pot and simmer for 15 minutes to allow the spices to infuse fully into the base.\", \"Step 5: Add dried fish, ground crayfish, sliced scotch bonnet peppers, and seasoning cubes. Stir well and continue cooking on medium heat, allowing the liquid to reduce and thicken for 20 to 25 minutes — unlike Banga Soup this should reduce further into a thicker stew-like consistency.\", \"Step 6: Add the fresh fish pieces and cook gently for 8 to 10 minutes until just cooked through, stirring carefully to avoid breaking the fish apart.\", \"Step 7: Continue simmering uncovered for an additional 10 minutes, stirring occasionally, until the stew has thickened noticeably and the oil is clearly visible on the surface.\", \"Step 8: Remove the oburunbebe stick before serving. Taste and adjust seasoning. Serve hot with white rice, boiled yam, or plantain.\"], \"match_percentage\": 18.2, \"used_ingredients\": [\"onions\", \"scotch bonnet peppers\"], \"cook_time_minutes\": 80, \"prep_time_minutes\": 30, \"missing_ingredients\": [\"fresh palm fruit (or canned banga concentrate)\", \"assorted meat (beef, tripe)\", \"dried fish\", \"fresh fish\", \"banga spice mix (oburunbebe stick, dried bitter leaf)\", \"crayfish\", \"seasoning cubes\", \"salt\", \"water\"]}, {\"name\": \"Nigerian Fried Rice\", \"tips\": \"Always cook on high heat when frying the rice and vegetables together to prevent everything from steaming and becoming soggy instead of stir-fried.\", \"servings\": 6, \"difficulty\": \"medium\", \"description\": \"Nigerian Fried Rice is a colourful and flavourful party staple made with parboiled rice stir-fried with mixed vegetables, liver, and a distinct curry seasoning. Unlike Chinese fried rice, the Nigerian version has a unique orange-yellow hue from curry powder and is loaded with vegetables, making it one of the most popular dishes at Nigerian celebrations alongside Jollof Rice.\", \"instructions\": [\"Step 1: Wash the rice thoroughly until water runs clear then transfer into a seive till perfectly dry. Then into a pot, add some oil and fry the rice for about 5 minutes\", \"Step 2: Season the liver with salt and a little curry powder. Cook in a pot with a small amount of water for 8 to 10 minutes until just cooked through, then dice into small cubes.\", \"Step 3: Dice carrots and green beans into small uniform cubes for even cooking. Set aside along with the bell peppers.\", \"Step 4: Heat vegetable oil in a large wok or wide pan on high heat. Add minced garlic and ginger and stir fry for 30 seconds until fragrant but not browned.\", \"Step 5: Add diced onions and stir fry for 2 minutes until softened. Add the diced liver and shrimp and stir fry for 2 minutes.\", \"Step 6: Add the carrots, green beans, green peas, and bell peppers to the pan. Stir fry on high heat for 3 minutes until heated through but still slightly crisp.\", \"Step 7: Add the cooled parboiled rice to the pan along with curry powder, thyme, seasoning cubes, soy sauce, and salt. Stir fry vigorously on high heat for 5 to 7 minutes, tossing continuously, until the rice is evenly coated in the yellow curry colour and well combined with all the vegetables and protein. Taste and adjust seasoning, then serve hot.\"], \"match_percentage\": 13.3, \"used_ingredients\": [\"long grain rice\", \"onions\"], \"cook_time_minutes\": 30, \"prep_time_minutes\": 30, \"missing_ingredients\": [\"carrots\", \"green peas\", \"bell peppers(green, yellow, red)\", \"liver\", \"vegetable oil\", \"garlic\", \"ginger\", \"curry powder\", \"thyme\", \"seasoning cubes\", \"soy sauce\", \"salt\", \"chicken stock\"]}, {\"name\": \"Nigerian Coleslaw\", \"tips\": \"The combination of mayonnaise and salad cream together, rather than just mayonnaise alone, is what gives Nigerian coleslaw its distinctive tangy sweetness. Always shred the cabbage very finely for the best texture, and let the coleslaw rest in the refrigerator before serving for the best flavour.\", \"servings\": 6, \"difficulty\": \"easy\", \"description\": \"Nigerian Coleslaw is a creamy and slightly sweet shredded cabbage and carrot salad that is a staple side dish at Nigerian parties, often served alongside Jollof Rice and Fried Rice. It differs from Western coleslaw by typically including diced apples, raisins, and a generously sweetened mayonnaise dressing.\", \"instructions\": [\"Step 1: Wash the cabbage thoroughly and shred very finely using a sharp knife or food processor — the cabbage should be cut into thin uniform strips for the best texture.\", \"Step 2: Peel and grate or finely julienne the carrots into thin matchstick pieces, similar in size to the shredded cabbage.\", \"Step 3: In a large bowl combine the shredded cabbage, grated carrots and sweet corn. Toss together gently.\", \"Step 4: In a separate small bowl mix mayonnaise and salad cream together in roughly equal parts, adding sugar to taste for the characteristic Nigerian sweetness, along with a pinch of black pepper and salt.\", \"Step 5: Pour the dressing over the vegetable mixture and toss thoroughly until every piece is well coated in the creamy dressing.\", \"Step 6: Taste and adjust sweetness and seasoning — Nigerian coleslaw is typically sweeter than standard Western coleslaw.\", \"Step 7: Cover and refrigerate for at least 1 hour before serving to allow the flavours to meld and the cabbage to soften slightly. Serve cold alongside Jollof Rice or Fried Rice.\"], \"match_percentage\": 0.0, \"used_ingredients\": [], \"cook_time_minutes\": 0, \"prep_time_minutes\": 25, \"missing_ingredients\": [\"cabbage\", \"carrots\", \"sweet corn\", \"mayonnaise\", \"salad cream\", \"sugar\", \"black pepper\", \"salt\"]}]}','2026-06-21 11:03:37'),('bc0e9a0f-f0be-42c4-9e17-afb4411e9fa4','[\"flour\", \"sugar\", \"baking powder\", \"butter\", \"egg\", \"milk\"]','english',NULL,'{\"recipes\": [{\"name\": \"Simple Pancakes\", \"servings\": 4, \"difficulty\": \"easy\", \"description\": \"A classic English breakfast dish, simple pancakes are a delicious and fluffy treat with a light, airy texture and a subtle sweetness.\", \"instructions\": [\"Step 1: In a large bowl, whisk together 1 cup of flour, 2 tablespoons of sugar, and a pinch of salt for 2 minutes on low speed until well combined.\", \"Step 2: Heat a non-stick pan over medium heat for 5 minutes, until the pan is hot and a small amount of water sizzles and evaporates quickly when added to the pan.\", \"Step 3: Using a 1/4 cup measuring cup, scoop the batter onto the hot pan and cook for 2-3 minutes, until bubbles appear on the surface of the pancake and the edges start to dry.\", \"Step 4: Flip the pancake and cook for another 1-2 minutes, until the other side is lightly browned and the pancake is cooked through.\", \"Step 5: Repeat the process with the remaining batter, greasing the pan with a small amount of butter or oil as needed.\", \"Step 6: Serve the pancakes hot with your choice of toppings.\"], \"match_percentage\": 100, \"used_ingredients\": [\"flour\", \"sugar\", \"egg\", \"milk\", \"butter\"], \"cook_time_minutes\": 20, \"prep_time_minutes\": 10, \"missing_ingredients\": [\"baking powder\"]}, {\"name\": \"Butter Cake\", \"servings\": 8, \"difficulty\": \"medium\", \"description\": \"A classic English dessert, butter cake is a rich and moist treat with a tender crumb and a sweet, buttery flavor.\", \"instructions\": [\"Step 1: Preheat the oven to 350°F (180°C) for 10 minutes, until the oven is hot and a thermometer inserted into the oven reads 350°F (180°C).\", \"Step 2: In a large bowl, whisk together 2 cups of flour, 1 teaspoon of salt, and 1 cup of granulated sugar for 2 minutes on low speed until well combined.\", \"Step 3: Add 1 cup of milk to the butter mixture and whisk for 1 minute on low speed until the mixture is smooth and free of lumps.\", \"Step 4: Add the dry ingredients to the wet ingredients and whisk for 2 minutes on low speed until the batter is smooth and free of lumps.\", \"Step 5: Divide the batter evenly between the prepared pans and smooth the tops.\", \"Step 6: Bake the cakes for 25-30 minutes, until a toothpick inserted into the center of each cake comes out clean.\"], \"match_percentage\": 83, \"used_ingredients\": [\"flour\", \"sugar\", \"egg\", \"butter\", \"milk\"], \"cook_time_minutes\": 30, \"prep_time_minutes\": 20, \"missing_ingredients\": [\"baking powder\"]}, {\"name\": \"Crepes\", \"servings\": 8, \"difficulty\": \"medium\", \"description\": \"A classic English dessert, crepes are a thin and delicate treat with a sweet, buttery flavor and a tender texture.\", \"instructions\": [\"Step 1: In a large bowl, whisk together 1 cup of flour, 2 tablespoons of sugar, and a pinch of salt for 2 minutes on low speed until well combined.\", \"Step 2: Add the wet ingredients to the dry ingredients and whisk for 2 minutes on low speed until the batter is smooth and free of lumps.\", \"Step 3: Heat a small non-stick pan over medium heat for 5 minutes, until the pan is hot and a small amount of water sizzles and evaporates quickly when added to the pan.\", \"Step 4: Pour a small amount of batter into the pan, just enough to cover the bottom of the pan.\", \"Step 5: Loosen the crepe with a spatula and flip it over, cooking for another 30 seconds to 1 minute.\", \"Step 6: Serve the crepes hot with your choice of fillings.\"], \"match_percentage\": 83, \"used_ingredients\": [\"flour\", \"sugar\", \"egg\", \"milk\", \"butter\"], \"cook_time_minutes\": 20, \"prep_time_minutes\": 15, \"missing_ingredients\": [\"baking powder\"]}, {\"name\": \"Scones\", \"servings\": 8, \"difficulty\": \"easy\", \"description\": \"A classic English breakfast dish, scones are a delicious and flaky treat with a light, airy texture and a subtle sweetness.\", \"instructions\": [\"Step 1: In a large bowl, whisk together 2 cups of flour, 1 teaspoon of salt, and 1 cup of granulated sugar for 2 minutes on low speed until well combined.\", \"Step 2: Add 1 cup of milk to the butter mixture and whisk for 1 minute on low speed until the mixture is smooth and free of lumps.\", \"Step 3: Add the dry ingredients to the wet ingredients and whisk for 2 minutes on low speed until the batter is smooth and free of lumps.\", \"Step 4: Divide the batter evenly between the prepared pans and smooth the tops.\", \"Step 5: Bake the scones for 12-15 minutes, until a toothpick inserted into the center of each scone comes out clean.\", \"Step 6: Serve the scones hot with your choice of toppings.\"], \"match_percentage\": 85, \"used_ingredients\": [\"flour\", \"sugar\", \"egg\", \"milk\", \"butter\"], \"cook_time_minutes\": 15, \"prep_time_minutes\": 20, \"missing_ingredients\": [\"baking powder\"]}]}','2026-06-21 10:02:36'),('bff657f1-ad55-497f-93a9-5df54e205605','[\"pizza\"]','general',120,'{\"recipes\": [{\"name\": \"None\", \"tips\": \"To make a Nigerian dish, it\'s essential to have the right ingredients.\", \"servings\": 0, \"difficulty\": \"hard\", \"description\": \"No traditional Nigerian dish can be made with only pizza.\", \"instructions\": [\"Step 1: Visit a market or store to purchase necessary ingredients.\", \"Step 2: Prepare ingredients, such as washing and chopping vegetables, and soaking black eyed beans in water for 30 minutes.\", \"Step 3: Fry onions in oil until they turn golden brown.\", \"Step 4: Add blended pepper and fry for 20-30 minutes until the oil floats on top.\", \"Step 5: Add stock, seasoning, bay leaves, curry, and thyme, and cook for 10-15 minutes.\", \"Step 6: Serve the dish hot, garnished with fresh herbs and vegetables, if desired.\"], \"match_percentage\": 0, \"used_ingredients\": [\"pizza\"], \"cook_time_minutes\": 0, \"prep_time_minutes\": 0, \"missing_ingredients\": [\"black eyed beans\", \"water\", \"crayfish\", \"onions\", \"scotch bonnet\", \"fish or egg\", \"foil containers or leaves\", \"tomatoes\", \"red bell pepper\", \"oil\", \"stock\", \"seasoning\", \"bay leaves\", \"curry\", \"thyme\", \"rice\", \"egusi\", \"palm oil\", \"meat\", \"stockfish\", \"vegetables\", \"pepper soup spice mix\", \"uziza leaves\", \"yam\", \"soy sauce\"]}]}','2026-06-21 11:16:48'),('c2aee669-08d8-490e-9a44-78ccebe4a2db','[\"panc\"]','general',120,'{\"recipes\": [{\"name\": \"Pancake (not available)\", \"tips\": \"None\", \"servings\": 0, \"difficulty\": \"hard\", \"description\": \"A classic breakfast dish from Western cuisine, pancakes are soft, fluffy, and slightly sweet. Unfortunately, with only panc, we cannot make a traditional pancake. However, we can suggest other Nigerian dishes.\", \"instructions\": [\"Step 1: Since we cannot make a pancake with the given ingredient, let\'s